(8, 6, 12, 'Which of the following is correct regarding consulting?', 'Consultants must be fresh from college with no experience to be effective.', 'Consultants are better off being specialists.', 'Arrogance is expected out of successful consultants.', 'To show confidence, consultants should bring in all their basic books.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Consultants must NOT be fresh from college with no experience to be effective. Experience matters and very few graduates have the type of experience expected.', 'Consultants are better off being specialists to understand the issues at a depth expected.', 'Arrogance is NOT expected from successful consultants and should be avoided. People usually prefer dealing with others that are easy to communicate with.', 'To show confidence, consultants should NOT bring in all their basic books, showing lack of knowledge.', ''),
(9, 6, 12, 'Which of the following statements is correct regarding a consultant’s behavior?', 'Arrogance is a must to get along with people.', 'The best way to create rapport with a client is to tell confidential details of a competitor.', 'When sharing information, it is better NOT to name names.', 'When sharing information, it is better to name names and addresses.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Arrogance is NOT necessary to get along with people; it’s a deterrent to good relationship building.', 'The best way to create rapport with a client is NOT to tell confidential details of a competitor.  Telling confidential details is a sign that the person cannot be trusted.', 'When sharing information, it is better NOT to name names. Discretion is appreciated in the consulting world.', 'When sharing information, it is NOT better to name names and addresses. It’s better to be discreet and less specific due to confidentiality issues.', ''),
(10, 6, 12, 'Which of the following reflects a beneficial attitude for consultants?', 'Consultants who are gurus in their areas do NOT need to remain current.', 'A good way to start a project is to be very emotional and say how shocked you are.', 'People love a "show off".', 'Consultants should show respect to everyone, not just the boss.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Consultants who are gurus in their areas need to remain current, since things are changing all the time.', 'A good way to start a project is NOT to be very emotional and NOT to say how shocked you are. The less emotional a consultant is, the better off he/she is.', 'People DO NOT love a “show off.” They prefer someone they can relate to.', 'Consultants should show respect to everyone, not just the boss. This includes the secretary and lower level employees.', ''),
(11, 6, 13, 'Which of the following is correct?', 'Consultants should NOT ask questions since they are the experts.', 'Consultants should ask questions as part of the project.', 'Listening is really not that important in the consulting world.', 'Ignore all complaints—that’s the consultant mantra.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Consultants should ask questions, even if they are the experts to obtain proper and complete information.', 'Consultants should ask questions as part of the project to obtain proper and complete information.', 'Listening is important in the consulting world to gather data and evaluate a situation quickly.', 'DO NOT ignore all complaints—that’s the consultant mantra. Complaints may point the consultant into the right direction.', ''),
(12, 6, 13, 'Consultants should present the following behavior:', 'Apologize for any mistakes.', 'Cover-up mistakes.', 'Behave as if they are employees.', 'Gossip to bond with clients', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Consultants should apologize for any mistakes, taking responsibility over their errors.', 'Consultants should NOT cover up mistakes. This type of behavior does NOT foster trust.', 'Consultants should NOT behave as if they are employees; rather, they should be aware that they are outsiders and behave as such.', 'Consultants should NOT gossip to bond with clients. Gossiping is a sign of immaturity and lack of professionalism.', ''),
(13, 6, 13, 'A good attitude for consultants is:', 'NEVER document their work.', 'Listen to complaints to get to the heart of the problem faster.', 'NOT listen to client employees.', 'Interrupt employees all the time to get prompt answers.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Consultants should document their work to show the work they are doing, analysis, and recommendations.', 'Consultants should listen to complaints to get to the heart of the problem faster.', 'Consultants should listen to client employees to understand the issues better and faster.', 'Consultants should NOT interrupt employees all the time to get prompt answers.  Being polite is necessary for the success of a consultant.', ''),
(14, 6, 14, 'Which option is correct regarding consultants’ leadership skills?', 'In order to build trust, consultants must agree with clients in all matters.', 'New, original thinking is valued in consulting engagements.', 'Consultants must make unrealistic promises to win a consulting project.', 'Clients’ expectations are to be ignored.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'In order to build trust, consultants must NOT agree with clients on all matters. Consultants should bring new views and ideas to a business.', 'New, original thinking is valued in consulting engagements.  New ideas and solutions are appreciated in most settings.', 'Consultants must NOT make unrealistic promises to win a consulting project. Once the situation is discovered, the consultants lose the client’s trust.', 'Clients’ expectations are NOT to be ignored; rather, expectations are to be identified and managed.', ''),
(15, 6, 14, 'A good attitude for consultants is:', 'Consultants do NOT need to be leaders because all decisions are made by clients.', 'Strategic thinking is a waste of time for consultants, since each client is different.', 'The first step in strategic thinking is to baseline a situation.', 'Consultants should hide their real goals to earn people’s trust.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Consultants need to be leaders in spite of all decisions being made by clients.  They must guide the client to the best solution to a problem or situation.', 'Strategic thinking is NOT a waste of time for consultants. Strategies can be applied to many different projects, becoming the consultant’s framework.', 'The first step in strategic thinking is to baseline a situation, to figure out what is going on now. Only then, a plan can be devised to arrive at a future destination.', 'Consultants should NOT hide their real goals to earn people’s trust.  Any form of hiding gives the impression of fakeness, not promoting good rapport.', ''),
(16, 6, 14, 'Which option shows characteristic typical of consultants-leaders?', 'Consultants should inspire professionalism and trust.', 'Original thinking is too risky to be used in consulting engagements.', 'Consultants can NOT be flexible because it implies weakness.', 'Strategy is used only in military engagements.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Consultants should inspire professionalism and trust to be successful.', 'Original thinking is NOT too risky to be used in consulting engagements; it’s valued to come up with fresh ideas and solutions.', 'Consultants can be flexible. It does NOT imply weakness; rather, flexibility is a good trait to have in handling different and unexpected situations.', 'Strategy is NOT used only in military engagements. Many professionals employ their own strategies to handle their work and to solve problems.', ''),
(17, 6, 15, 'Which one is correct regarding consulting engagements?', 'Consultants should always strive for excellence in their work.', 'Extensive training is usually given to consultants by clients.', 'Clients should wait at least ten weeks before getting any results from consultants.', 'Consultants do NOT need common sense because they are experts.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Consultants should always strive for excellence in their work.', 'Extensive training is NOT usually given to consultants by clients.  Consultants should hit the ground running.', 'Clients should NOT wait at least ten weeks before getting any results from consultants. The faster the results, the better it is.', 'Consultants do need common sense in spite of them being experts. Theories alone don’t work well in a consulting environment.', ''),
(18, 6, 15, 'Which of the following is correct regarding problem solving skills?', 'Consultants are often engaged to solve problems and give recommendations.', 'Good judgment is also known as common sense.', 'Good judgment is also known as theory X.', 'Consultants should perform below par when a client is difficult.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Consultants are often engaged to solve problems and give recommendations.', 'Good judgment is also known as common sense. It’s the ability to make good decisions.', 'Good judgment is NOT known as theory X.  Good judgment may be known as common sense.', 'Consultants should NOT perform below par when a client is difficult.  The reasons for the difficulties should be identified and resolved.', ''),
(19, 6, 15, 'Consultants must have certain attributes to be able to succeed in an engagement. Which of the following statements is correct regarding these attributes?', 'Expecting consultants to learn fast is unrealistic.', 'Consultants should work very slowly at first to gain the client’s trust.', 'The Internet should be avoided in learning more about the client.', 'Consultants should learn fast and give some results fast as well.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Expecting consultants to learn fast is realistic and is a trait required.', 'Consultants should NOT work very slowly at first to gain the client’s trust. They should work fast and efficiently to gain the client’s trust.', 'Internet should be used in learning more about the client since it contains a lot of pertinent information.', 'Consultants should learn fast and give some results fast as well. Giving the client a report or some valuable data fast builds trust and confidence.', ''),
(20, 6, 16, 'Which option is correct regarding integrity and the consultant?', 'All consultants should B.S. to gain clients’ trust.', 'Consultants should be transparent and honest.', 'Transparency in consulting is an obsolete concept.', 'Consultants must pad timesheets to earn respect.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Consultants should NOT B.S. to gain clients’ trust. B.S. only goes so far.  It doesn’t work long-term.', 'Consultants should be transparent and honest to build trust long term.', 'Transparency in consulting is NOT an obsolete concept. It should be used to create mutual trust and respect.', 'Consultants must NOT pad time-sheets to earn respect. Padding time-sheets shows that the consultant may be dishonest.', ''),
(21, 6, 16, 'Which one is correct as related to gaining trust from clients?', 'Consultants should NOT pad time-sheets. Doing so, it shows dishonesty.', 'B.S., flash and theatrics without substance works very well for consultants.', 'Consultants should act as if they have a hidden agenda to create better rapport with clients.', 'Bad-mouthing past clients creates rapport with clients.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Consultants should NOT pad time-sheets. Doing so, it shows dishonesty.', 'B.S, flash and theatrics without substance DO NOT work well for consultants. All show and no substance may works on the short-term basis.', 'Consultants should NOT act as if they have a hidden agenda to create better rapport with clients. The act of hiding anything creates the sense that the consultant cannot be trusted.', 'Bad-mouthing past clients DOES NOT create rapport with clients; bad-mouthing creates a negative environment and it shows that the consultant doesn’t respect confidentiality.', ''),
(22, 6, 16, 'Which of these statements presents correct information regarding the value of communication and attitude?', 'Communications is a prime tenet of transparency.', 'Consultants should appear to know more than they actually do to build respect.', 'Sharing information poses a conflict of interest situation.', 'Communication in the consulting world is overrated.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Communications is a prime tenet of transparency. Consultants should communicate with a focus on transparency.', 'Consultants should NOT appear to know more than they actually do to build respect. Lies are eventually uncovered with the consultant losing credibility.', 'Sharing information DOES NOT pose a conflict of interest situation in most cases, especially when the consultant is independent of client.', 'Communication in the consulting world is NOT overrated. Communication is important in any consulting engagement.', ''),
(23, 7, 22, 'Which of the following statements is TRUE?', 'In order to eliminate most of the risk, just invest in CDs or Treasury Bills.', 'Since the client has over a million dollars in land and a fairly steady job, his ability to ride out a recession is very high.', 'As the time frame gets larger, the client''s stock market risk gets smaller.', 'Since you have over twenty-five years experience in financial planning, you can breeze through the data-gathering phase and go right to the plan itself.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'CDs and Treasury Bills are subject to purchasing power risk, which can be devastating in periods like the late 1970s and early 1980s', 'Land in a recession time may be impossible to sell and if something happens to the client''s job he may be forced to sell any bonds or stocks at a very disadvantageous time.', 'A twenty-year time frame in the stock market has much less risk of loss than the one-year risk.', 'This is the client''s financial plan and not yours. Make sure you know what they want.', ''),
(24, 7, 22, 'If the client has a large lump sum to invest, a recommended method of investing this sum is:', 'All of it immediately so that it can grow as fast as possible.', 'Dollar cost averaging.', 'Put it in a money market account since you have a lot of money.', 'Half in a money market account and half in bonds.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'This may be done, but it risks the market making a correction right after the investment is made.', 'This smoothes out the costs of shares as they are invested in each part of the swings in the market.', 'The amount should be invested in a diversified portfolio, regardless of how much it is.', 'The amount should be invested in a diversified portfolio.', ''),
(25, 7, 22, 'Which of the following is FALSE about an advantage of a variable annuity?', 'Tax-deferred growth and returns on "tax deferred" portion.', 'Many variable annuities have highly visible mutual fund managers.', 'There are normally higher expenses.', 'Since outflow of funds in variable annuities is very small, the managers can invest fully without keeping cash for the outflows.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'The ability to invest the “tax-deferred” portion gives the policy greater returns.', 'Many Variable Annuities have fund managers that also manage money for Mutual Funds giving them more name recognition.', 'The higher expense ratio is one of the main disadvantages to a variable annuity. However, this should be offset by the opportunities given the portfolio managers to manage in a different tax environment.', 'The ability of Variable Fund Managers to closely know their cash flow allows them to maximize their investment portfolio since they do not have to keep larger cash reserves than mutual funds due to the selling and buying of mutual funds.', ''),
(26, 7, 22, 'Asset allocation is a key method of obtaining:', 'Maximum Returns on the Portfolio with high risks.', 'A fairly stable rate of return.', 'A Portfolio that has NO risks.', 'Investing in all of the best mutual funds.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'High risks and returns are not the results of an Asset Allocation plan since some asset classes would not be included in the plan.', 'Asset Allocation does provide a fairly stable rate of return since the different classes provide differing returns and risks.', 'NO portfolio can be devised that has NO risks – impossible.', 'Asset allocation involves some asset classes that are not in mutual funds.', ''),
(27, 7, 21, 'When determining the amount of life insurance needed to adequately provide for beneficiaries, which of the following is TRUE?', 'Past salary increases.', 'The current budget.', 'The client has an incapacitated dependent.', 'The client does not have sufficient disability insurance.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Past salary increases have already been considered in the current financial statements.', 'The current is part of the financial plan for taking care of the client, not the heirs.', 'This is a big problem which greatly pertains to the amount of life insurance needed.', 'The risk of lack of disability insurance should be taken care of in the life financial plan, not the insurance for heirs', ''),
(28, 7, 21, 'With annual renewable term insurance:', 'The interest rate is important since it assists in determining the amount of the premium.', 'The pure insurance premium is all you pay, not for investment income', 'You have a cut-off date when no more premiums will have to be paid, since you will have sufficient paid-up life insurance.', 'The savings feature is important.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Annual renewal term insurance does not have an interest factor.', 'With the annual renewable term insurance, the only factor in the premium is the pure insurance needed for the client.', 'Annual renewal insurance never builds up paid-up insurance since the premium is all for the current insurance.', 'There are no saving feature in the annual renewable insurance policy.', ''),
(29, 7, 21, 'Which of the following is FALSE?', 'Whole life policies utilize bond investments to build up cash value.', 'Variable life may utilize bond investments and/or stocks.', 'Universal life policies utilize bond investments to build up cash value.', 'Variable life only utilizes stock investments.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'The portfolio of Whole Life policies will consist of bond investments only.', 'The portfolio of a Variable Life policy may utilize stocks and/ or bonds which gives it the variable name since stocks vary in value.', 'Universal Life policies’ portfolio will include bonds only.  Stocks are not available in these policies.', 'A Variable Life portfolio may include bonds as well as stocks.  The portfolio depends on the economic environment and its impact on bonds.', ''),
(30, 7, 21, 'Which of the following statements is TRUE?  With variable life', 'The funds generated by investments from within the policy belong to the Insured', 'The funds generated by investments from within the policy belong to the Insurance Company.', 'The funds generated by the investments from within the policy belong to the creditors of the failed insurance company.', 'The investment returns cannot be transferred with the policy to another insurance company.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'This is one of the big advantages of the variable life over the regular whole life or universal life policies.', 'The investment returns do not belong to the company as they are returns on the insured’s policy, not the company’s investment portfolio.', 'The investment returns do not belong to the company as they are returns on the insured’s policy, not the company’s investment portfolio which would make them available to creditors.', 'Since the returns belong to the insured’s policy they can be transferred to another insurance company.', ''),
(31, 7, 20, 'After the data gathering session, there should be a written financial plan established which includes the:', 'Client''s personal goals.', 'Client’s confidential information obtained.', 'Assumptions made.', 'Detailed data used to prepare the plan.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'The client’s personal goals were used to prepare the plan, but should not be stated as a part of the financial plan.', 'The financial plan is for many people to use, so it should not have confidential information included.', 'The assumptions made are vital to understanding the financial plan and should be included.', 'The financial plan should include only the conclusions, not the details in getting to them.', ''),
(32, 7, 20, 'Which of the following situations should be dealt with first after the data-gathering phase?', 'The client has not started savings yet, but has been paying off current credit card debt fairly rapidly.', 'The client has not prepared a formal budget yet.', 'The client has sufficient life insurance, but it is all in term insurance.', 'The client does not have a will.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Paying off the credit card debt is a concern, but it is not of primary interest.', 'Not doing a budget is a concern, but it is not of primary interest.', 'This may or may not be a concern, but it is not of primary interest.', 'This should be the first priority to address with the client for immediate action.', ''),
(33, 7, 20, 'If your client is 40 years old and you are planning her investment portfolio, who is your client?', 'The 40 year old with whom you have been dealing.', 'The 55 year old who is over half-way to retirement.', 'The 65 year old who is looking at retirement.', 'The 90 year old who is losing her health.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'The 40 year old is not the one that you can assist with their financial plan.  It is too late to change the way they are at 40.', 'The financial plan is made to take care of retirement, not while she is still working.', 'This is where the financial plan is focused, retirement when the steady income is gone and the plan starts in the process of giving rather than receiving.', 'The financial plan should have protected the person until the age of 90, but that is not focal point of the plan.', ''),
(34, 7, 19, 'Stocks have a very high volatility risk factor over:', 'A one-year time frame', 'A five-year time frame', 'Over a ten-year time frame', 'Over  a 25-year time frame.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'The risk defined is over a period of one year, not five years.', 'The 5 year time frame has risk, but not a high volatility risk factor.', 'A 10 year time frame has less risk than a shorter time-frame.', 'Stocks have less volatility over a 25-year time frame than bonds have.', ''),
(35, 7, 19, 'Which of the following statements is false?', 'The stock market as a whole, for the intermediate term investment, has less risk (due to less volatility) than in the short-term market and more risk than in the long-term.', 'The stock market as a whole, for the intermediate term investment, has more risk (due to less volatility) than in the short-term market and less risk than in the long-term.', 'The long-term market (10 years or more) has less risk than the intermediate market and lesser risk the longer the term.', 'When investment length gets to the 25-year period, stocks have historically outperformed all other types of investment in every 25-year period.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'This is a true statement since the intermediate-term investment has less volatility, therefore less risk than the short-term market.', 'The intermediate-term market has less risk than the short-term market and less risk than the longer the term.', 'This is a true statement since the longer the time frame has less risk than the intermediate market.', 'This is a true statement for a 25-year period of time.  Stocks outperform all other investment types.', ''),
(36, 7, 19, 'Which of the following questions is FALSE concerning insurance information needed?', 'How much and what kind of life insurance does the client have?', 'Does the employer have a 401(k) plan?', 'How much does the client have in the bank account now?', 'Is the client renting or owns their home.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'This is a good question to ask about insurance matters.', 'This is a good question to ask, but it only indirectly pertains to insurance.', 'This is not very important concerning insurance matters.', 'This is a personal choice for the present time, not in determining insurance matter', ''),
(37, 7, 19, 'Which of the following statements is TRUE?', 'Since the rate of inflation has been effectively curbed, inflation is not really a big factor in financial planning now.', 'The interest rate risk is the risk that the interest on the bonds will not be paid.', 'Comments like "do you have any hot tips for me to make a lot of money" usually expresses the client''s true feelings about investing.', 'Business risk is the risk that the business whose stock is in the client''s portfolio will run into financial difficulties.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'There has been no period in our history when inflation should not be considered unless the time-frame is very short-term.', 'The interest rate risk is that as bond rates change the value of bonds will decline and you may be forced to sell them', 'This may be a fantasy desire, but it may not reflect their true risk taking tolerance. Without the increased risk they usually will not "make a lot of money."', 'Business risk is the risk that the business will have financial problems or fail.', ''),
(38, 7, 18, '<p><strong>Which of the following describes what the <em>bond interest rate</em> is?&nbsp;</strong></p>', 'The risk that business may not be able to live up to expectations', 'The risk that the market interest rate will change', 'That the value of the bond will remain unchanged', 'The risk that the market interest rate will NOT change', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'The interest rate risk is not the risk that the business will not follow expectations.', 'The value of the bond is directly impacted by the market interest rate, which changes the value of the bond.', 'The value of the bond staying the same is a positive, not a risk.', 'The bond rate staying the same is a positive, not a risk.', ''),
(39, 7, 18, '<p><strong>Business or financial risk arises when:</strong></p>', 'The market interest rate changes.', 'The business owned may run into financial difficulties.', 'The value of the business remains unchanged.', 'The value of real estate has dropped around the business.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'The interest rate changing may impact the business, but it may be favorable or unfavorable.', 'The fact that the business may run into difficulties creates risk', 'It may be desirable for the business to grow, but the value of a business may not change, but still be very profitable since earnings may be taken out instead of leaving in the business for it to grow.', 'The value of real estate surrounding the business does not impact a going-concern business since their basic real estate is not for sale.', ''),
(40, 7, 18, '<p><strong>Which of the following may be a recommended investment to hedge against short-term inflation?</strong></p>', 'Common Stocks.', '30-day Treasury Bills.', 'Real Estate.', 'Hedge Funds.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'It is an inflation hedge, but not in the short-term.', 'T-Bills are not a good inflation hedge in the long-term, but short-term it does keep up with inflation as the rates change quickly.', 'Real Estate is a very good inflation hedge in the long run, but very definitely not in the short-term due to illiquidity.', 'Hedge Funds main purpose is to beat inflation in the long-run, not necessarily in the short-term.', ''),
(41, 7, 18, '<p><strong>The longer the life of a U.S. Government bond is:</strong></p>', 'Generally the rate will be better than shorter-term bonds.', 'The safer the principal will be.', 'The interest rate will keep increasing.', 'The less volatility there will be in the market value.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'This is true since longer that bond is the more interest rate risk will be.', 'The principal will always be safe as far as collecting the principle amount when the bonds mature.', 'The interest rate of a bond is set when the bond is initially sold, so it cannot be changed.  The market rate may change, but the bond rate will not.', 'The longer the life of the bond is the greater the volatility due to market interest rate changes that occur.', ''),
(42, 7, 18, '<p><strong>What is&nbsp;<em>alpha?</em></strong></p>', 'Measures the portfolio volatility.', 'Measures the part of the return on investments that is attributable to the investment skill of the manager of a mutual fund.', 'Measures the reliability of the measurements used in explaining the return of an investment manager.', '', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Beta measures the portfolio volatility.', 'This is the definition of Alpha.', 'This is the definition of R-squared.', '', ''),
(43, 7, 17, '<p><strong>A CPA firm would likely want to work with a prospective client on a complete financial plan if the client:&nbsp;</strong></p>', 'Unsure about what he would like  to invest in.', 'Is heavily invested and really does not want to change much.', 'Cannot save any funds for several years due to present obligations.', 'Is very aggressive in investing.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'This is what you want to do to assist the client by determining the investment portfolio.', 'This type of client does not give you much latitude in getting a well-rounded portfolio which the firm prefers.', 'If the potential client has no prospects for being able to implement a financial plan, you probably cannot help him with a full plan.', 'The person who is very aggressive normally would not fit into a good financial plan which limits your effectiveness.', ''),
(44, 7, 17, '<p><strong>If a female client is&nbsp;sixty-five years old and does not have any serious health issues, what is the ideal time frame for her financial plan?&nbsp;</strong></p>', 'Ten years.', 'Fifteen years.', 'Twenty years.', 'More than twenty years.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Ten years is too short a time frame.', 'Fifteen years is too short a time frame.', 'Twenty years is too short a time frame.', 'The chance of her living to age ninety is 40 percent; therefore her plan should reflect this.', ''),
(45, 7, 17, '<p><strong>What should occur during the <u>first session</u> with a&nbsp;potential new client for Personal Financial Planning (PFP):</strong></p>', 'The various levels of Personal Financial Planning available at the firm should be presented and discussed.', 'The potential client''s preferred group of mutual funds and insurance company.', 'The type of portfolio the potential client would like should be discussed.', 'It should be discussed and determined if the potential client is going to want the firm to also do his or her taxes.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct.  The first session should explain the firm’s available services for PFP.', 'Incorrect.  The potential client may, or may not have a preferred mutual fund group and insurance company; however, this information should not be discussed during the first sessions.', 'Incorrect.  There are more pressing discussions to be had during the important first session.  The potential client''s portfolio should not be discussed until after the first session has been completed and he or she has become a client.', 'Incorrect.  The first session should be informative enough for the potential client to determine if the firm is a good fit for his or her Personal Financial Planning.  The first session should not be used to discuss and determine if the firm will complete the potential client''s tax returns.  The discussion should definitely take place, as it is an ultimate objective, but not a first one.', ''),
(46, 7, 17, '<p><strong>Which of the following is generally&nbsp;required in the basic data collection for a new PFP client?</strong></p>', 'Copy of portfolio plan you have constructed for the client.', 'Copy of Audit report for the firm for which the client works.', 'Tax returns for at least the last 2 years.', 'Report from the investment firm you have chosen for at least part of the portfolio.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'The portfolio plan is not made until much later in the process.', 'The audit report of the firm for which the client works would not give any vital personal information.', 'Tax returns contain income information for jobs as well as details of investment income.', 'The investment firms are not selected until much later in the process.', ''),
(47, 7, 17, '<p><strong>It is better to make cash flow projections for healthy spouses, <em>until and unless</em>:</strong></p>', 'Retirement age since all funds need to be liquid at that time.', 'Age 75 since the average person will not live to be past this age.', 'Age 80 since it is probable that both spouses will not have survived.', 'Age 90 since it is probable that one of the spouses will live close to this age.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'All funds should not be in liquid form at retirement age as most people will live considerably longer and liquid funds do not protect against inflation.', 'One of the spouses will live, on average, longer than age 75.', 'One of the spouses will live, on average, longer than age 80.', 'Age 90 is correct since it is now probable that one of the spouses will live to this age and that age in growing due to the longer longevity of people.', ''),
(48, 7, 17, '<p><strong>The client&#39;s ability to evaluate the merits and risks of an investment is assumed to be good if the client is which of the following:</strong></p>', 'A very successful physician.', 'The controller of a medium sized company.', 'Chairman of the science research department.', 'A CRIMINAL Attorney.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'The physician may or may not be knowledgeable about investments, but you cannot assume that he is.', 'You may assume that the controller is knowledgeable about investments since he works with financial statements.', 'A research scientist is obviously very smart, but not necessarily in investments.', 'A criminal attorney is smart, but his field does not necessarily mean smart in investments.', ''),
(49, 7, 17, '<p><strong>One of the overall phenomena currently facing many baby boomers is:</strong></p>', 'Their children are staying home longer.', 'They have to get help from their parents.', 'Their children are staying home a shorter time, but are more expensive.', 'They have to support their children and their parents as well.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'This is part of the problem, but not all of it.', 'More have to help their parents.', 'Children are staying home longer on the average.', 'Many in this generation have to take care of their children and their parents.', ''),
(50, 7, 17, '<p><strong>The young, fast-track Client&#39;s Main PFP time frame Goals should be:</strong></p>', 'Immediate (0 - 2 years).', 'Intermediate (2 - 5 years).', 'Mid to Long-term (5 – 15 years).', 'Long-term (15 – 50 years).', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'The immediate time frame would be studied only as it impacts their main goal.', 'The intermediate time frame would be studied only as it impacts their main goal.', 'The Mid to Long-term time frame would be studied only as it impacts their main goal.', 'The long-term (15 to 50 years) time frame would be studied intensely as this is their primary planning period.', ''),
(51, 7, 17, '<p><strong>Personal goals and financial goals:</strong></p>', 'Are only somewhat inter-related.', 'Should not clash or planning may be futile.', 'Are not important to each other.', 'Should be accomplished by different planning individuals with different expertise.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'They are more than just somewhat related.', 'If they clash planning may be completely useless.', 'They are more important to each other.', 'PFP may be accomplished using different people, but all should be focused on accomplishing both goals.', ''),
(52, 7, 17, '<p><strong>The client&#39;s financial objectives should be determined:</strong></p>', 'After the planning process is complete.', 'By the firm’s experts in PFP.', 'By the client’s heirs.', 'By the client’s wishes – it is their money and future.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'The planning cannot be accomplished without the client’s financial objectives.', 'No one in the firm can determine what the client wants.', 'The heirs would not necessarily have the same objectives as the client.', 'The client is the only one that can determine what they want.', ''),
(53, 9, 26, 'Warranty obligations:', 'only occur when the warranty is sold separate from the related product per ASC 605-20-25.', 'meet the definition of a contingency under ASC 405-20-25-2.', 'should be disclosed but not recognized according to ASC 405-20-25-2.', 'are not specifically covered in the FASB Accounting Standards Codification.', '', '2', '', '', 'Deleted', 'Incorrect because warranty liabilities occur whether it is included in the sale price or sold separately.', 'Correct because of the uncertain nature of warranties.', 'Incorrect because ASC 405-20-25-2 requires warranty obligation to be recognized..', 'Incorrect because warranty accounting is addressed in the ASC 405-20-25-2 and ASC 605-20-25..', ''),
(54, 9, 23, 'Warranty obligations:', 'only occur when the warranty is sold separate from the related product per ASC 605-20-25.', 'meet the definition of a contingency under ASC 405-20-25-2.', 'should be disclosed but not recognized according to ASC 405-20-25-2.', 'are not specifically covered in the FASB Accounting Standards Codification.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect because warranty liabilities occur whether it is included in the sale price or sold separately.', 'Correct because of the uncertain nature of warranties.', 'Incorrect because ASC 405-20-25-2 requires warranty obligation to be recognized.', 'Incorrect because warranty accounting is addressed in the ASC 405-20-25-2 and ASC 605-20-25.', ''),
(55, 9, 24, 'Firms are commonly sued:', 'by their shareholders for losses related to stock price declines.', 'by customers for patent infringement on key ingredients.', 'by customers for stock price declines.', 'when the warranty length is not sufficient.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct because shareholder class action lawsuits are common.', 'Incorrect because generally competitors, not customers sue for patent infringement.', 'Incorrect because shareholders, not customers, may sue for stock price declines.', 'Incorrect because warranty suits are generally based on the firm’s unwillingness to comply with the warranty terms.', ''),
(56, 9, 24, 'Merck discloses potential liabilities related to hazardous waste based on which federal law?', 'Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation and Liability Act', 'Consolidated States Class-Action Lawsuit Act', 'Occupational Health and Safety Act (OSHA) – standards and practices', 'Securities and Exchange Act of 1933', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct because Merck disclosed potential lawsuits related to the Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation and Liability Act.', 'Incorrect because Merck did not disclose potential lawsuits related to the Class-Action Lawsuit Act.', 'Incorrect because Merck did not disclose potential lawsuits related to OSHA.', 'Incorrect because Merck did not disclose potential lawsuits related to the Securities and Exchange Act of 1933.', ''),
(57, 9, 25, 'Which of the following is an example of a customer loyalty program obligation?', 'One year, limited product warranty.', 'A free coffee drink for every ten cups of coffee purchased.', 'A 20% off coupon sent out to every resident in a certain city.', 'Senior citizen discount offered at the local movie theater.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect because warranties are separate from customer loyalty programs.', 'Correct because the coffee seller incurs an obligation to supply a certain amount of free coffee each time the customer buys a cup.', 'Incorrect because no customer loyalty obligation is created by make this discount offer.', 'Incorrect because no customer loyalty obligation is created by make this discount offer.', ''),
(58, 9, 26, 'This term is used to describe the fact that not all gift certificates purchased will be redeemed.', 'Disclosure', 'Adjustment', 'Breakage', 'Unearned', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect because disclosure refers to including financial statement footnotes.', 'Incorrect because “adjustment” is a general term for all changes in amounts. It does not specifically relate to gift cards.', 'Correct because “breakage” describes the fact that not all gift certificates purchased will be redeemed.', 'Incorrect because “unearned” refers to assets received for services or products that have not yet been earned.', ''),
(59, 9, 27, 'Per U.S. GAAP, ASC 420-10, asset retirement obligation footnote disclosure should include material adjustments related to:', 'Liabilities incurred in the current period.', 'Gains from an asset sale.', 'The depreciation method used to allocate the retirement liability.', 'Liabilities incurred in future periods.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct because ASC 420-10 requires disclosure of significant changes related to liabilities incurred in the current period.', 'Incorrect because ASC 420-10 does not require disclosure of significant changes related to gains from asset sale.', 'Incorrect because depreciation is not used to determine the retirement liability.', 'Incorrect because ASC 420-10 does not require disclosure of significant changes related to future liabilities. The code refers only to current and past liabilities.', ''),
(60, 9, 28, 'Financial statement footnotes should show the _____ of beginning and ending pension obligation:', 'Cost basis', 'Fair value', 'Historical trend', 'Average', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect because fair value not historical cost of the beginning and ending pension obligation should be used.', 'Correct because fair value of the beginning and ending pension obligation should be used.', 'Incorrect because a trend report of the beginning and ending pension obligation is not specifically required.', 'Incorrect because the average of the beginning and ending pension obligation is not required to be disclosed.', ''),
(61, 9, 28, 'During 2012, how much did Proctor & Gamble’s pension benefit obligation increase?', 'Between 5 and 6 Billion Dollars', 'Between 1 and 2 Billion Dollars', 'Less than 1 Billion Dollars', 'More than 6 Billion Dollars', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect because this was the amount of total pension obligation at the end of 2012.', 'Correct because the total pension obligation increased from $12.2 Billion to $13.6 Billion.', 'Incorrect because the total pension obligation increased by approximately $1.4 Billion.', 'Incorrect because the total pension obligation was more than $6 Billion but it increased by approximately $1.4 Billion.', ''),
(62, 9, 29, 'A convertible debt issuer incurs liability for the:', 'conversion ratio of the bonds.', 'amount owed to the bondholder.', 'premium paid for the conversion feature.', 'detachable warrant .', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect because the conversion ratio refers to the exchange ratio of stock shares to bonds.', 'Correct because the term “owes” suggests an obligation to the bondholder.', 'Incorrect because this is not a loan to the issuing company.', 'Incorrect because the premium paid for the conversion feature is the amount in addition to the amount paid for the bond. This additional amount is paid for the option to buy shares.', ''),
(63, 9, 30, 'A debt cosigner incurs a related liability:', 'When the debt is extinguished.', 'If the debt will not be repaid by the primary borrower.', 'When the lender seeks payment from the cosigner following loan default.', 'If the primary lender refinances the loan.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct because, ASC 460-10-55-4 provides that the guarantor firm record a liability equal to the fair value of a payment necessary for the guaranteed firm to obtain such a guarantee.', 'Incorrect because the debt has not yet been issued at this point.', 'A debt would have already been recorded at debt issuance.', 'The cosigner’s debt would be removed (not added) when the debt is extinguished.', ''),
(64, 10, 31, 'How often should the policy and procedures manual be updated? (Please select the best response).', 'Every five years', 'Whenever there is a change or annually, if no changes were made', 'Never', 'When there is a new hire', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. If you wait five years to review and update a manual, it will be hopelessly out of date.', 'Correct. Whenever there is a change or annually, if no changes were made is a recommended best practice for all organizations.', 'Never. A policy and procedures manual that is never updated is one that is not worth the paper it is written on.', 'While all new hires in the accounts payable department should be given a copy of the policy and procedures manual, their hiring does not trigger an update of the manual.', ''),
(65, 10, 31, 'Who should have access to the policy and procedures manual?', 'Only managers', 'Only Processors', 'Anyone who might need to see it', 'Only upper management', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. By limiting the manual to mangers, your processors will not have a reference guide should they need to check on a rarely used procedure.', 'Incorrect. By limiting the manual to processors, others in the organization who might need to see it will not have that opportunity and as a result may make mistakes.', 'Correct. Anyone who might need to see the manual should have access to it. That is the best way to insure maximum value given the time and effort that go into preparing one.', 'Incorrect. If upper management is the only group to have access to the manual, it will be of little use at all.', ''),
(66, 10, 32, 'When you have finally finished a new manual, the manager should do which of the following? (Please select the best response).', 'Publish it', 'Publicize it', 'Both of the above', 'Neither of the above', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. While publishing the manual is important, it is not the only tactic the manager needs to use when it is complete.', 'Incorrect. While publicizing the manual is important, it is not the only tactic the manager needs to use when it is complete.', 'Correct. To be effective, the new manual must be both publicized and published.', 'Incorrect. To be effective, the new manual must be both publicized and published.', ''),
(67, 10, 32, 'Which of the following is recommended as a technique for creating an effective accounts payable policy and procedures manual?', 'Use long detailed explanations', 'Use bulleted lists', 'Both of the above', 'Neither of the above', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. If you use long detailed explanations in your manual, people are apt to lose interest and then forget what was said.', 'Correct Using bulleted lists makes it easier for employees to follow what is being said and integrate the various tasks into their day-to-day processes.', 'Incorrect. While it is important to include bulleted lists to make it easy for employees, long detailed explanations are apt to lose their attention.', 'Incorrect. Neither of the above', ''),
(68, 10, 33, 'To ensure everyone follows the new policy and procedures manual, it should do which of the following? (Please select the best choice).', 'Spell out the new policy', 'Set an effective date for any changes', 'Be signed by a high level executive', 'All of the above', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. While spelling out the new policy is important, it is only part of the process any organization needs to undertake to make their new manual successful.', 'Incorrect. While spelling out an effective date for any changes is important, , it is only part of the process any organization needs to undertake to make their new manual successful.', 'Incorrect. While having a high level executive a high level executive sign the policy to signify its importance, , it is only part of the process any organization needs to undertake to make their new manual successful.', 'Correct. All of the items discussed above are important when it comes to having a successful manual.', '');
INSERT INTO `chapter_review_questions` (`rev_ques_id`, `course_id`, `chapter_id`, `rev_ques_title`, `rev_ques_ans_1`, `rev_ques_ans_2`, `rev_ques_ans_3`, `rev_ques_ans_4`, `rev_ques_ans_5`, `rev_correct_ans_id`, `rev_correct_ans_text`, `rev_wronge_ans_text`, `rev_ques_status`, `ans1_text`, `ans2_text`, `ans3_text`, `ans4_text`, `ans5_text`) VALUES
(69, 10, 33, 'Which of the following is not a tactic that will get a policy and procedures manual started quickly, when there is no existing one to update?', 'Download one from the Internet to use for revisions.', 'Purchasing a manual for use for revisions.', 'Taking another department’s manual and revising it.', 'Copy someone else’s manual and revise it.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Download a manual from the Internet to use for revisions that match what your organization does is one way to get started.', 'Incorrect. Purchasing a manual for use for revisions that match what your organization does is one way to get started.', 'Correct. Taking another department’s manual and revising it will not help. It will have no procedures related to accounts payable and will be a complete waste of time.', 'Incorrect. Copy someone else’s manual and revising it so it matches what your organization does is one way to get started.', ''),
(70, 10, 34, 'The person responsible for the master vendor file, should have be able to do which of the following? (Please select the best response.)', 'Be an authorized signer', 'Approve invoices', 'Handle unclaimed property matters', 'All of the above', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. While those with access to the master vendor file shouldn’t be authorized signers, that’s not their only limitation.', 'Incorrect. While those access to the master vendor file shouldn’t approve invoices, that’s not their only limitation.', 'Incorrect. While those access to the master vendor Handle shouldn’t handle unclaimed property matters, that’s not their only limitation.', 'Correct. To achieve appropriate segregation of duties, all of the tasks mentioned above should be off limits to the professional responsible for the master vendor file.', ''),
(71, 10, 34, 'To ensure no segregation of duties issues crop up, which of the following should you do? (Please select the best response)', 'Run a report showing who has what system access to identify conflicts.', 'Ask managers if they know of any segregation of duties conflicts.', 'Ask the staff if they are aware of any segregation of duties conflicts.', 'All of the above', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. Running a report showing who has what system access is a great way to identify conflicts related to appropriate segregation of duties.', 'Incorrect. While asking managers if they know of any segregation of duties conflicts may help you identify some problem areas, it is unlikely to result in an identification of all problems.', 'Incorrect. While asking the staff if they are aware of any segregation of duties conflicts may help you identify some problem areas, it is unlikely to result in an identification of all problems.', 'Incorrect. Only the running of a report showing who has what system access will definitively identify all problem areas. The other responses, while they might provide some information, in all likelihood will be lacking.', ''),
(72, 10, 35, 'How can you make sure your current accounts payable policy and procedures manual matches your current practices?', 'Ask your employees if they are doing exactly what is in the manual.', 'Email processors reminding them to use the practices outlined in the manual', 'Watch each processor for some time to determine if what they are doing matches the manual', 'All of the above', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. If you ask your employees if they are doing exactly what is in the manual, they are likely to respond positively – regardless of what they are actually doing.', 'Incorrect. Email processors reminding them to use the practices outlined in the manual is not a bad idea but it does not guarantee they are following the manual completely.', 'Correct. By watching each processor for some time, you will be able to determine if what they are doing matches the manual.', 'Incorrect. While the ideas presented above are not bad, they will not provide you with the information you need to verify that the manual is being followed.', ''),
(73, 10, 35, 'Why is it problematic if you play favorites when it comes to honoring requests for Rush checks? (Please select the best response)', 'Resentment will build with those who are not treated equally.', 'Departments will send your favorites down with requests to get around accounts payable.', 'It really is not fair.', 'All of the above', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. While resentment will build with those who are not treated equally, that is not the only problem you’ll have.', 'Incorrect. While departments will send your favorites down with requests to get around accounts payable, that is not the only problem you’ll have.', 'Incorrect. While this tactic is really is not fair, what’s worse are the problems it will create.', 'Correct. Playing favorites is clearly not a good practice for all of the reasons discussed above.', ''),
(74, 8, 36, 'The history of accountants goes back to:', '1494', '1458', '1887', 'The beginning of civilization', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  As early 1494, a man, often referred to as the “father of accounting,” wrote the first accounting textbook.', 'Incorrect.  Benedetto Cotrugli wrote Delia Mercatura et del Mercante Perfetto (Of Trading and the Perfect Trader) in 1458, that included a brief chapter which described many of the features of double entry accounting as we know it today.', 'Incorrect.  In 1887, the American Association of Public Accountants (AAPA) was formed and it was described as the leader in public accounting.', 'Correct.  As a matter of fact, it is accountants who over five thousand years ago are believed to have developed the first forms of writing as we know writing to be today, in order to keep track of the wealth, trade and tribute payments.', ''),
(75, 8, 36, 'As early 1494, a man by the name of ___________ wrote the first accounting textbook.', 'Luca Bartolomes Paciolli', 'Benedetto Cotrugli', 'Major Jerome Lee Nicholson', '', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct.  As early 1494, a man, often referred to as the “father of accounting,” by the name of Luca Bartolomes Paciolli wrote the first accounting textbook.', 'Incorrect.  Benedetto Cotrugli wrote Delia Mercatura et del Mercante Perfetto (Of Trading and the Perfect Trader) in 1458, that included a brief chapter which described many of the features of double entry accounting as we know it today.', 'Incorrect.  Major Jerome Lee Nicholson became known for the process of “cost accounting.”', '', ''),
(76, 8, 36, 'With the creation of the ____________in the early 1800’s, there suddenly became a huge demand for refined operational reports to assist management, investors and emerging larger corporations in their decision making activities.', 'Wheel', 'Railroad', 'Securities and Exchange Commission', 'Which of the following was created in 2002 to oversee the activities of the auditing profession?', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The wheel was created prior to the 1800’s.', 'Correct. With the creation of the railroads in the early 1800’s, there suddenly became a huge demand for refined operational reports to assist management, investors and emerging larger corporations in their decision making activities.', 'Incorrect. The SEC was created by Section 4 of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 (now codified as 15 U.S.C. § 78d and commonly referred to as the 1934 Act).', 'Incorrect. According to archaeologists, the wheel was probably invented in around 8,000 B.C. in Asia.', ''),
(77, 8, 36, 'Which of the following was created in 2002 to oversee the activities of the auditing profession?', 'American Institute of Certified Public Accountants', 'Financial Accounting Standards Board', 'Public Company Accounting Oversight Board', '', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The AICPA was one of the original accounting standard setters.', 'Incorrect. The FASB issues accounting standards updates.', 'Correct. The PCAOB was created through the Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002, to oversee the activities of the auditing profession.', '', ''),
(78, 8, 37, 'According to the DOL, which of the following will drive faster-than-average growth of accountants and auditors?', 'A decrease in the number of businesses', 'A decrease in financial laws and regulations', 'Greater scrutiny of company finances', '', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  An increase (not a decrease) in the number of business is one factor which will lead to the increase in demand, according to the DOL.', 'Incorrect.  Changing financial laws and regulations is one factor which will lead to the increase in demand.  More and more laws and regulations are being written to provide transparency and reduce the risk of fraud.', 'Correct. Both greater scrutiny of company finances and changing financial laws and regulations are factors which will lead to the increase in demand.', '', ''),
(79, 8, 37, 'In addition to openings resulting from growth, the need to replace _________ accountants is expected to produce numerous job openings in the accounting occupation.', 'Staff level', 'Management level', 'Baby-boomer', 'Public', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  The staff level accountant generally is responsible for maintaining the company''s general ledger and subsidiary ledger accounts, including posting and preparing opening, adjusting, and closing journal entries', 'Incorrect.  Management level accountants normally supervise the activities of other accountants.', 'Correct. In addition to openings resulting from growth, the need to replace baby-boomer accountants and auditors who retire or transfer to other occupations is expected to produce numerous job openings in the accounting occupation.', 'Incorrect.  A public accountant is an accountant whose services are available to the public at large, in contrast to one employed on a full-time basis by a company.', ''),
(80, 8, 37, 'As a result of recent accounting scandals at several large corporate companies, Congress passed which of the following legislation?', 'The AICPA Code of Professional Conduct', 'The Sarbanes Oxley Act', 'The Financial Accounting Standards Board Act', '', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  The AICPA Code of Professional Conduct is a collection of codified statements issued by the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants that outline a CPA''s ethical and professional responsibilities.', 'Correct.  As a result of recent accounting scandals at several large corporate companies, Congress passed legislation, in particular the Sarbanes Oxley Act, in an effort to curb corporate accounting fraud.', 'Incorrect.  The FASB has been in existence since before the recent accounting scandals. The FASB is not a governmental body.', '', ''),
(81, 8, 37, 'If an accounting firm audits a client’s financial statements, that same firm may also provide advice on which of the following?', 'Human resources', 'Investment banking', 'Technology', 'Tax issues', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  If an accounting firm audits a client’s financial statements, that same firm cannot provide advice on human resources such as making a referral for a replacement CFO.', 'Incorrect.  If an accounting firm audits a client’s financial statements, that same firm cannot provide advice on investment banking, such a recommending an equity transaction.', 'Incorrect.  If an accounting firm audits a client’s financial statements, that same firm cannot provide advice on technology or legal matters.', 'Correct.  If an accounting firm audits a client’s financial statements, that same firm cannot provide advice on human resources, technology, investment banking, or legal matters, although accountants may still advise on tax issues, such as establishing a tax shelter.', ''),
(82, 8, 38, 'Most accounting firms have an average growth rate of  _____% per year.', '9', '17', '27', '53', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  The number of Bachelor’s degree recipients (40,400) increased 9%.', 'Incorrect.  In 2004, there was a 17% increase in the number of new accounting graduate hires by the firms compared to 2003.', 'Correct.  Most firms see an average of about 27 % growth each year, according to the Department of Labor.', 'Incorrect.  Females accounted for 53% of accounting graduates hired by the firms surveyed.', ''),
(83, 8, 39, 'To respect an employee with a technical/functional competence according to the career anchors you would do which of the following?', 'Give them a raise', 'Give them a promotion', 'Encourage them to work alone', 'Recognize them for what they know', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The entrepreneurial creativity anchor wants a raise.', 'Incorrect. The general managerial anchor wants a promotion.', 'Incorrect. The autonomy/independence anchor wants to work alone.', 'Correct. This career anchor wants to be recognized for what they know.', ''),
(84, 8, 39, 'Which of the following career anchors is most interested in climbing the corporate ladder as their main objective?', 'Entrepreneurial creativity', 'General managerial', 'Autonomy/independence', 'Technical/functional', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The entrepreneurial creativity is more interested in getting a raise than in a promotion.', 'Correct. The general managerial anchor is most interested in getting a promotion.', 'Incorrect. The autonomy/independence anchor wants to work alone.', 'Incorrect. The technical/functional career anchor wants to be recognized for what they know.  More important than a promotion is an opportunity to learn more about what they are currently working on and increasing their performance level.', ''),
(85, 8, 39, 'Which of the following career anchors is most interested in as much time as possible away from work?', 'Lifestyle', 'General managerial', 'Autonomy/independence', 'Technical/functional', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct.  The best way to show appreciation to an employee with a lifestyle anchor is to give them as much time as possible away from work. Their lifestyle is much more important to them than making a lot of money.', 'Incorrect.  The general managerial anchor is most interested in getting a promotion.', 'Incorrect.  The autonomy/independence anchor wants to work alone.', 'Incorrect.  The technical/functional career anchor wants to be recognized for what they know.  More important than time away from work is an opportunity to learn more about what they are currently working on and increasing their performance level.', ''),
(86, 12, 40, 'Assets can equal shareholders’ equity if', 'no liabilities are present.', 'shareholder equity is less than total liabilities.', 'liabilities are positive and equal to shareholders’ equity.', 'only current assets are owned by the company.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Assets = Liabilities + Shareholders’ Equity. Hence, “Assets = $0 (Liabilities) + Shareholders’ Equity” is equivalent to “Assets = Shareholders’ Equity”.', 'If total liabilities are greater than shareholder equity then liabilities are not equal to $0. If liabilities are not equal to $0, then assets cannot equal shareholder equity per the accounting equation: Assets = Liabilities + Shareholders’ Equity.', 'If liabilities are not equal to $0, then assets cannot equal shareholder equity per the accounting equation: Assets = Liabilities + Shareholders’ Equity. Assets = Liabilities + Shareholders’ Equity so if Liabilities = 0, the Assets = Shareholders’ Equity.', 'Assets = $0 (Liabilities) + Shareholders’ Equity” is equivalent to “Assets = Shareholders’ Equity”. The firm could own current assets and/or noncurrent assets', ''),
(87, 12, 41, 'Examples of GAAP-based expenses that are commonly subject to estimation include', 'cash.', 'warranty expense.', 'gain on publicly-traded securities available for sale.', 'cash dividends payable.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Cash is valued at its face amount by definition.', 'Expenses related to warranty offers should be recognized in the same period that the related product or service is sold. Hence, an estimate of future warranty cost is necessary.', 'This is a gain not an expense.', 'This is a liability previously determined by the board of directors – it is not subject to estimation.', ''),
(88, 12, 41, 'Income from continuing operations', 'excludes amortization expense.', 'is not included on GAAP-based income statements', 'can be used as a proxy for economic earnings (cash-flow).', 'excludes all adjustments for voluntary accounting method changes.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'This method includes amortization expense.', 'This line item is included on GAAP-based income statements.', 'Income from continuing operations can be used as a proxy for economic earnings (cash-flow) because it excludes certain “non-continuing” items.', 'Voluntary accounting method changes are accounted for retroactively.', ''),
(89, 12, 41, 'Before calculating an asset value using the DCF method, the single period cash-flow estimate should be', 'multiplied by two.', 'combined with other data to determine future cash-flows adjusted for probable economic changes.', 'multiplied by the risk-adjusted discount rate-of-return.', 'adjusted for the tax benefit associated with future depreciation charges.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'No specific cash-flow multiple is an assumed part of the DCF method.', 'The initial cash-flow estimate may need to be adjusted for probable future economic changes.', 'Once the future cash-flows are determined then they are divided by the discount rate.', 'Tax-related cash-flows are already considered in the initial calculation of cash-flows.', ''),
(90, 12, 42, 'When referring to the DCF model, risk refers to the uncertainty of the _____ of projected cash-flows used in the numerator of the discounted cash-flow projection.', 'Accuracy and Liquidity', 'Amount and Solvency', 'Pros and Cons', 'Amount and Timing', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Uncertainty and level of accuracy are synonymous – liquidity is a risk factor but it is not related to the amount and timing of future cash flows.', 'Amount is correct but solvency is a term referring to a firm’s ability to pay debt.', 'Risk relates to uncertainty of the amount and timing of project cash flows not the pros and cons.', 'Risk relates to uncertainty of the amount and timing of project cash flows, not the pros and cons.', ''),
(91, 12, 42, 'A significant limitation associated with CAPM is that a stock beta cannot be determined unless', 'a legitimate and efficient market for the asset exists.', 'the risk-free rate is known.', 'the MRP is known.', 'future price changes are known.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'A legitimate/efficient market for the asset needs to exist in order to calculate the stock’s beta coefficient.', 'The risk-free rate does not determine beta.', 'The MRP does not determine beta. It is a risk premium related to the market as a whole.', 'Future price changes are never known – they can only be predicted or estimated.', ''),
(92, 12, 42, 'The CAPM differs from the APM in that the CAPM includes a specific parameter that represents', 'inflation.', 'interest rates.', 'stock beta.', 'factor loading.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'The CAPM does not include a separate parameter that represents inflation.', 'The CAPM does not include a separate parameter that represents interest.', 'The CAPM includes a separate parameter that represents beta. The APM does not include this parameter.', 'The CAPM does not include a separate parameter that represents factor loading since only one factor (beta) is considered.', ''),
(93, 12, 43, 'A financial analyst could estimate an asset’s value with a DCF model by', 'using EBITDA to calculate future cash-flow proxy and CAPM to calculate the risk-adjusted discount rate.', 'using EBITDA as a risk-adjusted discount rate proxy and APT to calculate the estimated future cash-flow.', 'using Income from Operations as a cash-flow proxy and EBITDA to calculate the risk-adjusted discount rate.', 'using APT as a cash-flow proxy and CAPM to calculate the risk-adjusted discount rate.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'An asset’s valuation can be calculated using EBITDA to calculate future cash-flow proxy and CAPM to calculate the risk-adjusted discount rate.', 'An asset’s valuation cannot be calculated using EBITDA as a risk-adjusted discount rate proxy and APT to calculate the estimated future cash-flow because EBITDA is a cash-flow estimate and APT is a discount rate estimate.', 'An asset’s valuation cannot be calculated using Income from Operations as a cash-flow proxy and EBITDA to calculate the risk-adjusted discount rate because EBITDA is a cash-flow estimate not a discount rate estimate.', 'An asset’s valuation cannot be calculated using APT as a cash-flow proxy and CAPM to calculate the risk-adjusted discount rate because APT is used to calculate the risk-adjusted discount rate, not the cash-flow estimate.', ''),
(94, 12, 43, 'One could calculate expected future cash-flows by', 'using the CAPM.', 'using a figure calculated as an average of APT and CAPM.', 'observing the Security Market Line.', 'using a figure calculated as an average of income from continuing operations and EBITDA.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'One could NOT calculate expected future cash-flows by using the CAPM because the CAPM is used to calculate the discount rate, not the expected cash-flow amount.', 'One could NOT calculate expected future cash-flows by using a figure calculated using an average of APT and CAPM because the CAPM and APT are used to calculate the discount rate not the expected cash-flow amount.', 'One could NOT calculate expected future cash-flows by observing the Security Market Line (SML) because the SML displays the relationship between risk and reward. The SML does is not used to calculate expected future cash-flows.', 'One could calculate expected future cash-flows by using a figure calculated using an average of income from continuing operations and EBITDA.', ''),
(95, 14, 44, 'When best practices are ignored, which of the following is likely to happen?', 'The AP manager will be promoted', 'Duplicate payments are more apt to occur', 'The opportunity for fraud decreases', 'Financial statements are apt to be more accurate', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. In all likelihood the AP manager will not be promoted as there will be numerous problems.', 'Correct. Poor practices frequently result in a second invoice being sent and occasionally those second invoices get paid.', 'Incorrect. In fact, poor practices are likely to make fraud easier to commit.', 'Incorrect. When best practices are ignored, financial data tends to be less accurate and so financial statements are apt to be less accurate.', ''),
(96, 14, 44, 'When best practices are not followed which of the following is likely to occur?', 'Regulatory problems increase', 'Regulatory problems decrease', 'There is no effect on regulatory issues', 'Regulatory pressures disappear', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. Regulatory problems are likely to increase as the needed information is often not collected.', 'Incorrect. Regulatory problems are unlikely to decrease as organizations that ignore best practices are likely to ignore some of their regulatory requirements.', 'Incorrect. Unfortunately, not using best practices tends to make regulatory compliance more difficult and thus the impact is negative.', 'Incorrect. Unfortunately, not using best practices tends to make regulatory compliance more difficult and thus the impact is negative rather than the opposite.', ''),
(97, 14, 44, 'Which of the following is a best practice when it comes to establishing a best practice policy for the accounts payable function?', 'Update the policy whenever a change is made', 'Review the policy once a year and update it for all changes made during the year', 'Never review the policy; once it’s set it’s good for life', 'You don’t need a policy', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. Updating the policy whenever a change is made is the recommended approach to having the most accurate manual all the time.', 'Incorrect. While reviewing the policy once a year and updating it for all changes made during the year is a good idea, it will not result in an accurate manual for most of the year.', 'Incorrect. Never reviewing the policy; believing once it’s set it’s good for life is an absolute worst practice.', 'Incorrect. You don’t need a policy is another worst practice.', ''),
(98, 14, 44, 'Who should have a copy of the policy and procedures manual?', 'Only the AP manager', 'Only supervisors and managers', 'Only invoice processors', 'Anyone who needs to see it', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. By only giving the AP manager a copy of the manual, you don’t get the full benefit of it.', 'Incorrect. By only giving supervisors and managers the manual, you don’t get the full benefit of having a manual.', 'Incorrect. While invoice processors certainly need a copy of the manual, others do as well.', 'Correct. Anyone who needs to see the manual should have a copy of it or access to it.', ''),
(99, 14, 44, 'Which of the following is a reasonable approach when there is little budget training?', 'Forget about staff training and hope there will be budget next year', 'Make staff training the responsible for their own staff training', 'Bring in an expert and charge each staff member for a portion of their fees', 'Assign topics and encourage each staff to find information on the Internet and then share their intelligence with the rest of the staff', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Forgetting about staff training and hoping there will be budget for training next year is likely to result in a staff that is not fully trained. What’s more, once an organization removes funding for training, it usually takes several years before it is restored.', 'Incorrect. Making staff training the responsibility of each member of the staff will result in little or no training and a staff that is not prepared to institute best practices on an ongoing basis.', 'Incorrect. Bringing in an expert and charging each staff member for a portion of their fees is likely to result in chaos and complaining and is a really bad idea.', 'Correct. Assign topics and encourage each staff to find information on the Internet and then share their intelligence with the rest of the staff is a great approach, even if there is funding for training. Developing in-house subject matter experts is great not only for the department but to build staff morale.', ''),
(100, 14, 44, 'Which of the following is a good source for process improvement recommendations?', 'The staff who handle the process each day', 'Top management', 'The sales manager', 'The board of directors', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. The staff who handles the process each day is in the best position to know where changes can be made.', 'Incorrect. Top management rarely gets involved in the nitty gritty of the operation and so is not in a great position to make process improvement recommendations although they can certainly suggest policy changes.', 'Incorrect. The sales manager rarely understands the way the accounts payable process works and as such is not in a good position to make process improvement recommendations.', 'Incorrect. The board of directors rarely understands the way the accounts payable process works and as such is not in a good position to make process improvement recommendations.', ''),
(101, 14, 44, 'Which of the following is not a benefit of a third party payment audit?', 'Control weaknesses are identified', 'Funds are recovered for the organization', 'Control weaknesses can be corrected', 'Relations with other departments improve', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Identifying control weaknesses is one of the main benefits of an audit', 'Incorrect. Funds being recovered for the organization is clearly a benefit', 'Incorrect. Being able to correct control weaknesses after they are identified in an audit is a clear plus.', 'Correct. Audits do little to affect relations with other departments and hence it is unlikely they will improve.', ''),
(102, 14, 45, 'Who should have the ability to add new vendors to the master vendor file?', 'Anyone in the accounting department', 'Anyone in purchasing', 'Only the few people whose job it is to handle master vendor file data', 'Anyone in accounts payable', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Letting anyone in the accounting department update the master vendor file can lead to problems.', 'Incorrect. Letting anyone in purchasing update the master vendor file can lead to problems.', 'Correct. Letting only the few people whose job it is to handle master vendor file data is the best way to prevent collusion and have appropriate segregation of duties.', 'Incorrect. Letting anyone in accounts payable update the master vendor file can lead to problems.', ''),
(103, 14, 45, 'When should a new vendor be set up in the master vendor file?', 'Whenever the vendor data has been collected', 'Before the first purchase order is written', 'It doesn’t matter', 'Before 1099s have to be issued in January', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. By not having a firm policy regarding when the vendor should be set up, controls are weakened, the demand for Rush checks increases and other problems ensue.', 'Correct. By setting up the vendor in the master vendor file before the first purchase order is written, it is possible to ascertain that the vendor is someone you want to do business with and all the controls are in place.', 'Incorrect. By not having a firm policy regarding when the vendor should be set up, controls are weakened, the demand for Rush checks increases and other problems ensue.', 'Incorrect. By waiting until January to set up vendors, all controls are lost and the likelihood is that many duplicate payments will have been made.', ''),
(104, 14, 45, 'Which of the following is not a worst practice when it comes to developing a naming convention?', 'Ignoring the issue and having no standards', 'Allowing creativity when it comes to data entry', 'Using a rigid naming convention', 'Not communicating the standard to all affected parties', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Ignoring the naming convention issue and having no standards will result in duplicate vendors in the master vendor file.', 'Incorrect. Allowing creativity when it comes to data entry will result in duplicate vendors in the master vendor file.', 'Correct. Using a rigid naming convention is the recommended best practice.', 'Incorrect. Not communicating the standard to all affected parties will result in duplicate vendors in the master vendor file.', ''),
(105, 14, 45, 'Updates to information in the master vendor file should be reviewed using which of the following approaches?', 'Updates don’t need to be reviewed', 'A regular report showing changes given to senior management for review', 'Updates should be reviewed by the person who requested them', 'A clerk in accounts payable can review the updates', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. If updates aren’t reviewed, the chances of catching a fraudulent vendor set up by an employee decrease', 'Correct. A regular report showing changes given to senior management for review so employees realize someone is watching. This practice serves primarily as a deterrent.', 'Incorrect. Having updates reviewed by the person who requested them does nothing to prevent phony vendors from being set up.', 'Incorrect. While having a clerk in accounts payable review the updates is better than nothing, it does not provide the same force as a senior management review.', ''),
(106, 14, 45, 'How frequently should the master vendor file be cleansed?', 'Never', 'Every two or three years', 'Annually', 'Whenever someone in AP has the time', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Vendor files that are never cleansed make it easier for an employee trying to get a phony invoice paid.', 'Incorrect. While cleansing every two or three years is certainly better than never, it still is not frequent enough.', 'Correct. Cleansing annually is the recommended approach, although some best-practice organizations do it quarterly.', 'Incorrect. If you want for someone in AP to have the time to devote to a cleansing project, you are likely to fall into the never category.', ''),
(107, 14, 45, 'Self-service vendor portals offer all the following benefits except which one?', 'Vendors input the data', 'Relations with purchasing are improved', 'The opportunity for certain types of fraud is reduced', 'It is easier to update vendor contact information', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Vendors inputting the data is a definite benefit', 'Correct. Relations with purchasing are not likely to be improved or will they deteriorate.', 'Incorrect. The opportunity for certain types of fraud is reduced with self-service vendor portals.', 'Incorrect. It is easier to update vendor contact information as vendors can be sent a mass e-mail reminding them to update their information.', ''),
(108, 14, 46, 'Which of the following describes the recommended best practice for the receipt of invoices?', 'Invoices should go wherever the supplier chooses to send them', 'Invoice receipt should be centralized with one postal address, one e-mail address and one fax number', 'Invoices should only be received by postal mail', 'Invoices should only be received by e-mail', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. By letting invoices go wherever the supplier chooses to send them, you guarantee they will not always get to accounts payable in a timely manner. Early payment discounts will be lost.', 'Correct.   By centralizing the receipt of invoices to one postal address, one e-mail address and one fax number you stand the best chance of earning as many early payment discounts as possible and making accounts payable more efficient.', 'Incorrect. If you insist invoices are received only by postal mail you will aggravate suppliers and possibly lose a few key ones.', 'Incorrect. If you insist invoices are received only by e-mail you will aggravate suppliers and possibly lose a few key ones.', ''),
(109, 14, 46, 'The ability to approve invoices should be guided by which of the following?', 'Delegations of authority from the board of directors', 'Practices that evolved', 'What was always done in the past', 'Directives from the AP manager', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. A delegation of authority from the board of directors for the right to approve invoices is the correct way to do things.', 'Incorrect. By relying on practices that evolved for the right to approve invoices, you are setting the organization up for a potential problem.', 'Incorrect. By relying on what was always done in the past, you are setting the organization up for a potential problem.', 'Incorrect. In just about every organization the AP manager does not have the authority to decide who can approve invoices for payment and who cannot.', ''),
(110, 14, 46, 'Invoices should be returned to the supplier if they do not contain which of the following pieces of information?', 'The headquarters address', 'The website address', 'A PO number or name of the purchaser', 'A tax ID number', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The headquarters address is not needed to process or pay an invoice.', 'Incorrect. The website address is not needed to process or pay an invoice.', 'Correct. Without either a PO number or name of the purchaser, accounts payable wastes valuable time trying to figure out who ordered goods and who should approve the invoice.', 'Incorrect. A tax ID number is not needed to process or pay an invoice.', ''),
(111, 14, 46, 'The three-way match involves matching all of the following documents except which one?', 'Receiving document', 'W-9', 'Purchase Order', 'Invoice', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The receiving document is needed for the three-way match.', 'Correct. While a W-9 should be collected from all vendors, it is not used in the three-way match.', 'Incorrect. The purchase Order is needed for the three-way match.', 'Incorrect. The invoice is needed for the three-way match.', ''),
(112, 14, 46, 'When entering invoice data, processors should be instructed to do it which of the following ways?', 'However they can get the data entered the fastest', 'The way they always did it in the past', 'The way they did it at their former company', 'Using the standards set by the organization', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. While entering data quickly is desired, it should not be the primary mission of those handling invoices.', 'Incorrect. The way they always did it in the past may or may not be a best practice method of handling data entry and should not be the guiding principle.', 'Incorrect. The way they did it at their former company is not relevant in your organization.', 'Correct. Using the standards set by the organization is the best way to ensure everyone is handling workflow in the same way. This will help weed out duplicates.', ''),
(113, 14, 47, 'Which of the following is not a legitimate reason for short-paying an invoice?', 'Taking an early payment discount', 'Take a deduction for problems on another invoice', 'Taking an advertising allowance', 'Using an open credit from an earlier transaction', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Taking an early payment discount is a legitimate reason for paying less than the total amount shown on an invoice.', 'Correct. Take a deduction for problems on another invoice is likely to lead to confusion and further complications with the vendor.', 'Incorrect. Taking an advertising allowance is a legitimate reason for paying less than the total amount shown on an invoice.', 'Incorrect. Using an open credit from an earlier transaction is a legitimate reason for paying less than the total amount shown on an invoice.', ''),
(114, 14, 47, 'Paying small dollar invoices without knowing who ordered the items included on the invoice is a poor practice for all of the following reasons except which one?', 'The invoice could be fraudulent and no one placed the order', 'It is efficient', 'If you pay a fraudulent invoice you are likely to get more', 'Your financial statements will be negatively affected if you pay for something never ordered', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The invoice could be fraudulent and no one placed the order and without someone reviewing the invoice you will never know.', 'Correct. While paying small dollar invoices without knowing who ordered the goods might save time, it is a terrible practice.', 'Incorrect. If you pay a fraudulent invoice you are likely to get more as crooks learn you don’t have good review processes.', 'Incorrect. Your financial statements will be negatively affected if you pay for something never ordered as this money comes right off the bottom line.', ''),
(115, 14, 47, 'Which of the following is not a worst practice when it comes to creating invoice numbers?', 'Using the date as an invoice number', 'Using a social security number as part of the invoice number', 'Processing the invoice without an invoice number', 'Insist that all invoices have invoice numbers', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Using the date as an invoice number can result in numerous invoices with the same invoice number. What’s more if a second invoice is submitted, it will be assigned a different invoice number and be more likely to be paid.', 'Incorrect. Using a social security number as part of the invoice number is a really poor practice given all the problems with identity theft.', 'Incorrect. Processing the invoice without an invoice number makes it extremely difficult to identify potential duplicate invoices.', 'Correct. Insisting that all invoices have invoice numbers is a recommended best practice.', ''),
(116, 14, 47, 'When analyzing discrepant invoice data to see if you can identify root causes, you should categorize invoices by all of the following except which issue?', 'Invoice number', 'Purchaser', 'Vendor', 'Processor', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. The invoice number will be of little help when categorizing discrepant invoices to determine the root of possible problems.', 'Incorrect. Categorizing by purchaser will help you evaluate whether the problem is in purchasing.', 'Incorrect. Categorizing by vendor will help you evaluate whether the problem is in something your vendors are doing.', 'Incorrect. Categorizing by processor will help you evaluate whether the problem is with a particular processor.', ''),
(117, 14, 48, 'When it comes to making payments, which of the following is a best practice approach?', 'Pay everything by check', 'Encourage vendors to accept electronic payments', 'Always pay by check unless requested otherwise', 'Refuse to pay by check', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Paying everything by check is an inefficient way to run the accounts payable function.', 'Correct. Encouraging vendors to accept electronic payments is the wave of the future and a recommended best practice.', 'Incorrect. Always paying by check unless requested otherwise will result in mostly paper checks. More aggressive action is usually called for when it comes to the move to an electronic payment environment.', 'Incorrect. Refusing to pay by check might be nice in theory but in reality will not work as some vendors will refuse to work with your organization if you take this stance.', ''),
(118, 14, 48, 'Which of the following practices should when using pre-printed check stock?', 'A log should be kept comparing the number of checks printed with the check numbers used', 'Check stock should be kept near the printer for ease of use', 'Damaged checks should be thrown away', 'Checks should be signed as they are printed by the person printing the checks', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. A log should be kept comparing the number of checks printed with the check numbers used as a control and safeguard.', 'Incorrect. Check stock should NOT be kept near the printer despite the fact that is facilitates work. It also facilitates fraud.', 'Incorrect. Damaged checks should not be thrown away, but kept to prove to auditors they were not used.', 'Incorrect. Having checks signed as they are printed by the person printing the checks is a direct violation of appropriate segregation of duties.', ''),
(119, 14, 48, 'Who should authorize check signers in the organization?', 'The accounts payable manager', 'The Treasurer', 'The Board of the Directors', 'No one', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The accounts payable manager does not have the authority to grant this responsibility.', 'Incorrect. The Treasurer does not have the authority to grant this responsibility in most organizations.', 'Correct. The Board of the Directors is where the authority to sign should come from.', 'Incorrect. With no one in charge, not only will there be no controls, fraud is likely to increase.', ''),
(120, 14, 48, 'When it comes to check storage which of the following is not a best practice?', 'Storing checks in a secure locked location', 'Keeping a few emergency checks in a desk drawer', 'Limiting access to check stock', 'Using a strong lock on the door to the closet where checks are stored', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Storing checks in a secure locked location is a recommended best practice.', 'Correct. Keeping a few emergency checks in a desk drawer.', 'Incorrect. Limiting access to check stock is a recommended best practice.', 'Incorrect. Using a strong lock on the door to the closet where checks are stored is a recommended best practice.', ''),
(121, 14, 48, 'What is the best time to take checks to the mailroom for final delivery to the post office?', 'Whenever they are ready to go', 'First thing in the morning', 'Right before mail is taken to the post office', 'It really doesn’t matter', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Whenever they are ready to go will result in the checks being in the mailroom longer than they need to be increasing the chances that someone will walk off with a few.', 'Incorrect. First thing in the morning will result in the checks being in the mailroom longer than they need to be increasing the chances that someone will walk off with a few.', 'Correct. Right before mail is taken to the post office is the best time to take the checks to the mailroom as it will result in them being there for the shortest amount of time.', 'Incorrect. Unfortunately, it does really matter.', ''),
(122, 14, 48, 'When it comes to responsibility for check fraud losses, who is responsible?', 'The bank', 'The check issuer', 'The entity in the best position to prevent the fraud', 'The feds', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The bank no longer is always responsible for check losses due to changes in the UCC.', 'Incorrect. The check issuer in not always responsible for check fraud losses.', 'Correct. The UCC has been changes so the entity in the best position to prevent the fraud is now held responsible for the loss.', 'Incorrect. The feds play no part in this discussion.', ''),
(123, 14, 48, 'When it comes to the use of positive pay, what is the worst practice?', 'Using reverse positive pay', 'Not using positive pay at all', 'Using positive pay', 'Using payee name positive pay', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Using reverse positive pay is a good practice when an organization can’t produce a positive pay tape to give to the bank.', 'Correct. Not using positive pay at all is a worst practice, as positive pay has been shown to be the best defense against check fraud.', 'Incorrect. Using positive pay has been shown to be the best defense against check fraud.', 'Incorrect. Using payee name positive pay, where available, pay has been shown to be the best defense against check fraud.', ''),
