(160, 11, 84, 'Check alteration schemes include which of the following?', 'Forged signer', 'Altered returns', 'Forged accounts', 'Altered routing number', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Forged signer is a type of check alteration scheme.', 'Altered returns are not a type of check alteration scheme.', 'Forged accounts is not a type of check alteration scheme.', 'Altered routing numbers is not a check alteration scheme mentioned in the course.', ''),
(161, 11, 84, 'One way to mitigate check alteration fraud is to:', 'secure checks in the accounting department.', 'secured checks in a locked safe.', 'prohibit treasury department personnel from access to checks.', 'allow only one authorized signature on high-dollar checks.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Accounting personnel should not have access to checks.', 'To mitigate check fraud, checks should be placed in a safe.', 'The treasury department is responsible for processing checks.', 'Multiple signatures should be required for high-dollar checks.', ''),
(162, 11, 84, 'Paying a non-existent employee is referred to as a:', 'ghost employee scheme.', 'falsified hours fraud.', 'fraudulent return scheme.', 'lapping fraud.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'A ghost employee scheme involved payment to a non-existent employee.', 'A falsified hours scheme involves paying a current employee for more hours than they worked.', 'A Fraudulent return scheme does not relate to non-existent employees.', 'Lapping is a receivable fraud scheme. It does not relate to non-existent employees.', ''),
(163, 11, 85, 'One common type of receivables fraud is:', 'kiting.', 'lapping.', 'flying.', 'leaking.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Kiting is a checking account related fraud.', 'Lapping is a type of receivables fraud.', 'Flying is not a type of receivables fraud.', 'Leaking is not a type of receivables fraud.', ''),
(164, 11, 85, 'A scheme in which an employee steals a payment on account received from one customer, then uses collection of future receivable from other customers to cover the theft is known as:', 'bid rigging', 'lapping', 'larceny', 'skimming', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Bid rigging refers to contract fraud not receivables fraud.', 'Lapping is a scheme in which an employee steals a payment on an account received from one customer, then uses the collections of future receivables from other customers to cover the theft.', 'The unlawful taking of the personal property of another person or business.', 'Skimming involves misappropriation of funds before the funds are associated with any accounting transaction.', ''),
(165, 11, 85, 'Trend analysis of which figure would be most useful in detecting receivables fraud?', 'Days sales outstanding', 'Debt ratio', 'Times interest earned', 'Asset ratio', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Days sales outstanding would increase if lapping were to occur.', 'The debt ratio would not likely provide useful information related to receivables fraud.', 'The times-interest earned figure would not likely provide useful information related to receivables fraud.', 'The asset ratio would not likely provide useful information related to receivables fraud.', ''),
(166, 11, 86, 'Warehouse employees may try to cover inventory theft by:', 'Lapping payments from one customer to cover another customer''s payment.', 'Emptying the contents out of the box and returning the empty, sealed box to the warehouse shelf.', 'Altering the quantity ordered amount written on the purchase order.', 'Selling the pilfered inventory to other company employees.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Lapping is a receivables fraud not an inventory fraud.', 'Warehouse employees may try to cover inventory theft by emptying the contents out of the box and returning the empty, sealed box to the warehouse shelf.', 'Warehouse employees would not generally have access to POs.', 'Selling the inventory to other employees would not hide the theft.', ''),
(167, 11, 86, 'Merchandise inventory theft by employees generally occurs in the retail store, and', 'warehouse.', 'accounting department.', 'post office.', 'administrative offices.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Merchandise inventory theft by employees generally occurs in the retail store and warehouse.', 'Merchandise inventory is generally not located in the accounting department.', 'Merchandise inventory is generally not located in the post office.', 'Merchandise inventory is generally not located in the administrative offices.', ''),
(168, 11, 87, 'From the items listed below, which company PP&E is most likely to be stolen by employees?', 'Truck', 'Desk', 'Tablet computer', 'Accounts receivable', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Vehicles are often misused but are rarely stolen.', 'A desk is often too large to steal.', 'Tablet computers are small and mobile. An employee would be most likely to steal this item.', 'Accounts receivable is not considered in the category of property, plant, and equipment.', ''),
(169, 11, 87, 'Which of the following methods would most discourage employees from stealing company equipment located in the warehouse?', 'Proper depreciation accounting for all capital assets purchased over a certain dollar amount.', 'Video cameras located in the treasury departments.', 'Permanently label equipment with company name and unique identifying number.', 'Capital asset turnover analysis.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Depreciation accounting is important but not overly effective at preventing theft.', 'Surveillance of treasury department would discourage treasury employees from stealing equipment but would not affect other employees.', 'Labeling all equipment with name and identification number would make employees reconsider theft.', 'Trend analysis of fixed asset to total debt would not be an effective way to mitigate equipment theft.', ''),
(170, 11, 87, 'Which of the following methods would most effectively detect equipment fraud?', 'Accurate depreciation accounting for all fixed assets.', 'Surveillance of treasury department.', 'Labeling all equipment with name and identification number.', 'Surprise physical inventory checks.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Accurate depreciation accounting is important but physical inventory checks would be more likely to detect equipment theft.', 'Surveillance equipment located in the treasury department would be more likely to detect cash fraud as opposed to equipment theft.', 'Labeling equipment is more likely to prevent that detect equipment fraud.', 'Surprise physical inventory checks would be most effective at detecting equipment theft.', ''),
(171, 11, 88, 'Sales personnel would most likely attempt to acquire a favorable position with a new employer by promising to bring a ____________ from their previous employer.', 'trademark', 'research and development report', 'customer list', 'delivery truck', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Trademarks are publicly available information. So, the new employer would already be aware of these trademarks.', 'Sales personnel would likely not have detailed access to research and development information.', 'Customer lists are likely available to sales staff.', 'A delivery truck would be difficult to transfer without notice.', ''),
(172, 15, 89, 'Which of the following describes the recommended best practice for the receipt of invoices?', 'Invoices should go wherever the supplier chooses to send them.', 'Invoice receipt should be centralized with one postal address, one e-mail address and one fax number.', 'Invoices should only be received by postal mail.', 'Invoices should only be received by e-mail.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. By letting invoices go wherever the supplier chooses to send them, you guarantee they will not always get to accounts payable in a timely manner. Early payment discounts will be lost.', 'Correct.   By centralizing the receipt of invoices to one postal address, one e-mail address and one fax number you stand the best chance of earning as many early payment discounts as possible and making accounts payable more efficient.', 'Incorrect. If you insist invoices are received only by postal mail you will aggravate suppliers and possibly lose a few key ones.', 'Incorrect. If you insist invoices are received only by e-mail you will aggravate suppliers and possibly lose a few key ones.', ''),
(173, 15, 89, 'The ability to approve invoices should be guided by which of the following?', 'Delegations of authority from the board of directors.', 'Practices that evolved.', 'What was always done in the past.', 'Directives from the AP manager.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. A delegation of authority from the board of directors for the right to approve invoices is the correct way to do things.', 'Incorrect. By relying on practices that evolved for the right to approve invoices, you are setting the organization up for a potential problem.', 'Incorrect. By relying on what was always done in the past, you are setting the organization up for a potential problem.', 'Incorrect. In just about every organization the AP manager does not have the authority to decide who can approve invoices for payment and who cannot.', ''),
(174, 15, 89, 'Invoices should be returned to the supplier if they DO NOT contain which of the following pieces of information?', 'The headquarters address', 'The website address', 'A PO number or name of the purchaser', 'A tax ID number', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The headquarters address is not needed to process or pay an invoice.', 'Incorrect. The website address is not needed to process or pay an invoice.', 'Correct. Without either a PO number or name of the purchaser, accounts payable wastes valuable time trying to figure out who ordered goods and who should approve the invoice.', 'Incorrect. A tax ID number is not needed to process or pay an invoice.', ''),
(175, 15, 89, 'The three-way match involves matching all of the following documents except which one?', 'Receiving document', 'W-9', 'Purchase Order', 'Invoice', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The receiving document is needed for the three-way match.', 'Correct. While a W-9 should be collected from all vendors, it is not used in the three-way match.', 'Incorrect. The purchase Order is needed for the three-way match.', 'Incorrect. The invoice is needed for the three-way match.', ''),
(176, 15, 89, 'When entering invoice data, processors should be instructed to do it which of the following ways?', 'However they can get the data entered the fastest.', 'The way they always did it in the past.', 'The way they did it at their former company.', 'Using the standards set by the organization.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. While entering data quickly is desired, it should not be the primary mission of those handling invoices.', 'Incorrect. The way they always did it in the past may or may not be a best practice method of handling data entry and should not be the guiding principle.', 'Incorrect. The way they did it at their former company is not relevant in your organization.', 'Correct. Using the standards set by the organization is the best way to ensure everyone is handling workflow in the same way. This will help weed out duplicates.', ''),
(177, 15, 89, 'Which of the following is NOT a legitimate reason for short-paying an invoice?', 'Taking an early payment discount.', 'Take a deduction for problems on another invoice.', 'Taking an advertising allowance.', 'Using an open credit from an earlier transaction.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Taking an early payment discount is a legitimate reason for paying less than the total amount shown on an invoice.', 'Correct. Take a deduction for problems on another invoice is likely to lead to confusion and further complications with the vendor.', 'Incorrect. Taking an advertising allowance is a legitimate reason for paying less than the total amount shown on an invoice.', 'Incorrect. Using an open credit from an earlier transaction is a legitimate reason for paying less than the total amount shown on an invoice.', ''),
(178, 15, 89, 'Paying small dollar invoices without knowing who ordered the items included on the invoice is a poor practice for all of the following reasons EXCEPT which one?', 'The invoice could be fraudulent and no one placed the order.', 'It is efficient.', 'If you pay a fraudulent invoice you are likely to get more.', 'Your financial statements will be negatively affected if you pay for something never ordered.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The invoice could be fraudulent and no one placed the order and without someone reviewing the invoice you will never know.', 'Correct. While paying small dollar invoices without knowing who ordered the goods might save time, it is a terrible practice.', 'Incorrect. If you pay a fraudulent invoice you are likely to get more as crooks learn you don’t have good review processes.', 'Incorrect. Your financial statements will be negatively affected if you pay for something never ordered as this money comes right off the bottom line.', ''),
(179, 15, 89, 'Which of the following is NOT a worst practice when it comes to creating invoice numbers?', 'Using the date as an invoice number.', 'Using a social security number as part of the invoice number.', 'Processing the invoice without an invoice number.', 'Insist that all invoices have invoice numbers', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Using the date as an invoice number can result in numerous invoices with the same invoice number.  Additionally, if a second invoice is submitted, it will be assigned a different invoice number and be more likely to be paid.', 'Incorrect. Using a social security number as part of the invoice number is a really poor practice given all the problems with identity theft.', 'Incorrect. Processing the invoice without an invoice number makes it extremely difficult to identify potential duplicate invoices.', 'Correct. Insisting that all invoices have invoice numbers is a recommended best practice.', ''),
(180, 15, 89, 'When analyzing discrepant invoice data to see if you can identify root causes, you should categorize invoices by all of the following except which issue?', 'Invoice number', 'Purchaser', 'Vendor', 'Processor', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. The invoice number will be of little help when categorizing discrepant invoices to determine the root of possible problems.', 'Incorrect. Categorizing by purchaser will help you evaluate whether the problem is in purchasing.', 'Incorrect. Categorizing by vendor will help you evaluate whether the problem is in something your vendors are doing.', 'Incorrect. Categorizing by processor will help you evaluate whether the problem is with a particular processor.', ''),
(181, 16, 90, 'Which of the following scenarios involves the assumption of the greatest amount of speculative risk?', 'Company A invests heavily in U.S. treasury notes.', 'Company B’s headquarters may be attacked by terrorists.', 'Company C’s systems may be corrupted by a computer virus.', 'Company D invests most of its capital in small business stocks.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Investing in the stock market carries a greater degree of speculative risk than investing in U.S. treasury notes, as financial instruments issued by the U.S. government are generally considered risk-free.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Pure risk is a category of risk in which loss is the only possible outcome. The likelihood that a company’s headquarters may be attacked by terrorists would be considered a pure risk (not a speculative risk), as there can be no beneficial result from this event.', 'Answer C is incorrect. There can be no beneficial result from a company’s systems being corrupted by a computer virus. Therefore this risk would be considered a pure risk, not a speculative risk.', 'Answer D is correct. Speculative risk is a category of risk that results in an uncertain degree of gain or loss. Investing in the stock market is a conscious choice that carries a certain amount of speculative risk, as the investor can either gain or lose money on the investment.', ''),
(182, 16, 90, 'Joker Corp. has made an investment in a small construction company that employs several union workers. The likelihood that the company’s earnings will be negatively impacted by a union strike would be considered _________; the likelihood that the company’s earnings will be negatively impacted by a downturn in the U.S. economy would be considered _________.', 'An unsystematic risk; an unsystematic risk.', 'An unsystematic risk; a systematic risk.', 'A systematic risk; an unsystematic risk.', 'A systematic risk; a systematic risk.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The likelihood that the company’s earnings will be negatively impacted by a downturn in the U.S. economy would not be considered an unsystematic (company-specific) risk. Rather, it would be considered a systematic risk, which is a risk that is inherent to the entire market.', 'Answer B is correct. The likelihood that the company’s earnings will be negatively impacted by a union strike would be considered an unsystematic risk, as it is a company-specific risk. The likelihood that the company’s earnings will be negatively impacted by a downturn in the U.S. economy would be considered a systematic risk, as it is inherent to the entire market.', 'Answer C is incorrect. The likelihood that the company’s earnings will be negatively impacted by a downturn in the U.S. economy would not be considered an unsystematic (company-specific) risk. Also, the likelihood that the company’s earnings will be negatively impacted by a union strike would not be considered a systematic risk, as such an event would likely affect only this company.', 'Answer D is incorrect. The likelihood that the company’s earnings will be negatively impacted by a union strike would not be considered a systematic risk, as such an event would likely affect only this company.', ''),
(183, 16, 90, 'Companies A, B, C & D are U.S.-based reporting entities. Their customers exclusively reside in the United States.  The highest amount of interest rate risk would most likely be associated with which of the following assets?', 'Company A’s fixed rate securities portfolio.', 'Company B’s land held for sale.', 'Company C’s trade receivables.', 'Company D’s USD cash balances.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. Interest rate risk would have the most impact  on the value of fixed rate securities, which are interest-bearing financial instruments. As interest rates rise, security prices fall and vice versa.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Interest rate risk is not normally associated with land, as the value of land is not directly correlated with the value of interest rates.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Trade receivables are not normally interest-bearing instruments. Therefore interest rate risk affects the value of debt securities more than receivables.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Cash accounts earn very little (if any) interest. Therefore these assets are less likely to be subject to interest rate risk than debt securities.', ''),
(184, 16, 90, 'The highest amount of credit risk would most likely be associated with which of the following assets?', 'Company A’s U.S. Treasuries portfolio.', 'Company B’s factory.', 'Company C’s past due accounts receivable.', 'Company D’s office equipment.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. U.S. Treasuries are generally considered credit risk-free because they are backed by the “full faith and credit of the U.S. Government”.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Credit risk is associated with financial assets, such as receivables, debt securities, etc. It is not normally associated with physical assets.', 'Answer C is correct. Credit risk exists when there is a probability that a loss will be incurred from the customer’s failure to meet their contractual obligation. In the examples given, the highest amount of credit risk would most likely be associated with the past due accounts receivable.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Credit risk is not normally associated with equipment.', ''),
(185, 16, 90, 'The highest amount of foreign exchange risk would most likely be associated with which of the following assets?', 'Company A’s USD securities portfolio.', 'Company B’s property & plant.', 'Company C’s cost of goods sold.', 'Company D’s Euro-denominated money markets account.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Company A is a U.S. based company, and their securities are denominated in USD. Therefore, there would be no FX risk associated with these instruments.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Company B’s physical assets are located in the U.S. and are denominated in USD. Therefore, the value of these assets would not have exposure to movements in foreign exchange rates.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Company C’s cost of goods sold are denominated in USD. Therefore, there would be no FX risk associated with them. Furthermore, the cost of goods sold is an expense, not an asset.', 'Answer D is correct. Foreign currency risk would be associated with the Euro-denominated money market accounts. The company would be subject to adverse changes in the value of these accounts should the USD/EUR exchange rate move unfavorably.', ''),
(186, 16, 90, 'Riddler, Inc. currently own an equity investment that is not traded in an active market. The risk that Riddler would not be able to sell this investment in a timely manner (should they require excess cash at some point in the future) is knows as:', 'Political Risk.', 'Credit Risk.', 'Inflation Risk.', 'Liquidity Risk.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The risk that Riddler would not be able to sell its investment in a timely manner is referred to as liquidity risk, not political risk. Political risk is the risk that an investment’s returns could suffer as a result of changes or instability in a country.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Credit risk is the risk that a borrower will default on a loan or otherwise fail to meet a contractual obligation.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Inflation risk reflects the possibility that the value of assets or income will decrease as inflation shrinks the purchasing power of a currency.', 'Answer D is correct. The risk that an investment cannot be bought or sold quickly enough to prevent or minimize losses is referred to as liquidity risk.', ''),
(187, 16, 90, 'Which of the following would likely be considered the most appropriate action for an entity to take to effectively manage financial risk?', 'Company A allows its individual business line managers to decide whether their organization should reduce its exposure to various risks.', 'Company B continues monitoring its exposures even after it has implemented a risk management strategy.', 'Company C limits its risk management practices to monitoring systematic risks only.', 'Company D addresses financial risks after losses have been incurred.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Company A’s senior management (not business line managers) should decide whether the organization as a whole is in a position to tolerate certain risks.', 'Answer B is correct. Company B effectively manages its financial risk by periodically monitoring each financial exposure as well as the effectiveness of each risk management strategy it has employed to reduce the risk associated with that exposure.', 'Answer C is incorrect. In order to manage financial risk effectively, Company C should monitor both systematic and unsystematic risks.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Company D should address financial risks proactively in order to effectively manage its financial exposures.', ''),
(188, 16, 90, 'Which of the following actions would a U.S. based entity most likely take in order to “hedge” its exposure to movements in foreign currency rates?', 'Company A purchases a foreign currency derivative.', 'Company B ceases doing business with non-U.S. entities.', 'Company C establishes a subsidiary in a foreign country.', 'Company D maintains close political ties with several foreign governments.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. The purchase of a foreign currency derivative would be the best method for hedging FX risk in this case. Derivative instruments are tools commonly used to hedge such risk.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Although this might reduce exposure to FX risk, it is not likely that an entity would take such a drastic action simply to reduce its exposure to movements in foreign currencies.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Establishing a subsidiary in a foreign country would not reduce exposure to FX risk (in fact, it would likely increase exposure).', 'Answer D is incorrect. Maintaining close political ties with several foreign governments might reduce a company’s exposure to political risk; however, it would have no effect on the company’s exposure to FX risk.', ''),
(189, 16, 90, 'Which of the following contracts represents an example of a derivative instrument?', 'Company A’s floating rate debt security.', 'Company B’s lease agreement.', 'Company C’s pork belly futures contract.', 'Company D’s Treasury note.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. A debt security is an example of an investment, not a derivative instrument.', 'Answer B is incorrect. A lease agreement is a contract that generally pertains to the rental of equipment, office space or other property. It is not an example of a derivative instrument.', 'Answer C is correct. A futures contract is a type of derivative instrument, as it is a financial product that derives its value from an underlying asset or liability.', 'Answer D is incorrect. A Treasury note is an example of an investment, not a derivative instrument. Its value is not derived from another (underlying) asset.', ''),
(190, 16, 90, 'The Penguin Group is a London-based public company that issued a number of stock options to its employees as compensation. Which of the following would most likely cause the value of these options to increase?', 'Decreases in the level of interest rates.', 'Decreases in employee turnover at Penguin.', 'Increases in Penguin’s stock price.', 'Increases in the EUR/USD exchange rate.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The value of interest rate options (not stock options) would fluctuate with movements in interest rates.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Decreases in employee turnover at Penguin would have no effect on the value of their stock options.', 'Answer C is correct. The underlying item associated with these stock options would be Penguin’s equity shares. The value of the stock options would, therefore, increase as Penguin’s stock price increases.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Movements in foreign currency rates would not directly cause changes in the value of Penguin’s stock options. Such movements would instead cause the value of FX options to fluctuate.', ''),
(191, 16, 91, 'The following set of facts apply to questions 1-5.  <br /> Luthor, Inc. has entered into two agreements for the purchase of foreign currency and the sale of wheat. Under contract A, Luthor will purchase 1 million euros today at $1.49 per euro. Under contract B, Luthor will sell 500,000 bushels of wheat to a customer one year from now at $10.00 per bushel.  The market price of wheat on the agreement date was $10.20 per bushel. The market price of wheat on the delivery date is $9.90 per bushel.  <br /><br /> Contract A is an example of which type of financial instrument?', 'A long FX forward contract.', 'A short FX forward contract.', 'A long FX spot contract.', 'A short FX spot contract.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Contract A is not a forward contract, as the exchange will occur today (not in the future).', 'Answer B is incorrect. Contract A is not a forward contract, as the exchange will not occur in the future. Also, contract A is not a short transaction as Luthor Inc. will be purchasing (not selling) the foreign currency.', 'Answer C is correct. Contract A is an example of a long FX spot contract. It involves the purchase of foreign currency today at the current market price.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Contract A is not a short transaction as Luthor Inc. will be purchasing (not selling) the foreign currency.', ''),
(192, 16, 91, 'Contract B is an example of which type of financial instrument?', 'A long FX forward contract.', 'A short FX forward contract.', 'A long FX spot contract.', 'A short FX spot contract.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Contract B is not a long transaction as Luthor Inc. will be selling (not purchasing) the bushels of wheat.', 'Answer B is correct. Contract B is an example of a short forward contract. It involves the sale of wheat in the future at a price agreed upon today.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Contract B is not a spot contract, as the exchange will occur in the future (not today). Also, contract B is not a long transaction as Luthor Inc. will be selling (not purchasing) the bushels of wheat.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Spot contracts involve the purchase or sale of an asset today (not in the future). Contract B is not a spot contract.', ''),
(193, 16, 91, 'Contract B is an example of which type of financial instrument?', 'A long FX forward contract.', 'A short FX forward contract.', 'A long FX spot contract.', 'A short FX spot contract.', '', '2', '', '', 'Deleted', 'Answer A is incorrect. Contract B is not a long transaction as Luthor Inc. will be selling (not purchasing) the bushels of wheat.', 'Answer B is correct. Contract B is an example of a short forward contract. It involves the sale of wheat in the future at a price agreed upon today.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Contract B is not a spot contract, as the exchange will occur in the future (not today). Also, contract B is not a long transaction as Luthor Inc. will be selling (not purchasing) the bushels of wheat.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Spot contracts involve the purchase or sale of an asset today (not in the future). Contract B is not a spot contract.', ''),
(194, 16, 91, 'Which of the following equals the “forward price” under the terms of Luthor’s wheat contract?', '$9.90 per bushel.', '$10.00 per bushel.', '$10.20 per bushel.', '$11.49 per bushel.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. $9.90 represents the market price of wheat on the delivery date (not the forward price).', 'Answer B is correct. The forward price (or delivery price) associated with this contract equals $10. This represents the guaranteed price at which the future exchange will take place.', 'Answer C is incorrect. $10.20 represents the market price of wheat on the agreement date. The forward price ($10) is the guaranteed price at which the future exchange will take place.', 'Answer D is incorrect. The amount incorrectly represents the sum of the forward prices for contracts A & B.', ''),
(195, 16, 91, 'Under the terms of contract B, the payoff to Luthor, Inc. equals a:', '$100,000 loss.', '$50,000 loss.', '$50,000 gain.', '$100,000 gain.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. This amount incorrectly equals 500,000 bushels * ($10.00 forward price - $10.20 market price on the agreement date).', 'Answer B is incorrect. This amount represents the loss to Luthor’s counterparty (who is long in the forward contract).', 'Answer C is correct. Contract B results in a $50,000 gain to Luthor Inc. This amount equals 500,000 bushels * ($10.00 forward price - $9.90 market price on the delivery date).', 'Answer D is incorrect. This amount incorrectly equals 500,000 bushels * ($10.20 market price on the agreement date – $10.00 forward price).', ''),
(196, 16, 91, 'Regarding contract B, which of the following will occur as the spot price of wheat increases over time?', 'Luthor’s payoff value will increase.', 'The forward price will increase.', 'The forward price will decrease.', 'Luthor’s payoff value will decrease.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Luthor’s payoff value will decrease (not increase) as the spot (market) price of wheat increases over time because Luthor is in a short position.', 'Answer B is incorrect. The forward price is locked in at the beginning of a forward contract. This price does not fluctuate over time.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Under the terms of most forward contracts, the forward price is locked in for the duration of the contract.', 'Answer D is correct. Luthor’s payoff value will decrease as the spot (market) price of wheat increases over time. This is because Luthor is short in the contract and has agreed to sell wheat at a fixed price in the future.', ''),
(197, 16, 91, 'Bizarro Corp. has entered into an agreement to create a front office system for an investment management firm located in Japan. The project is expected to last 2 years, at which point a payment of 10 million Japanese yen (JPY) will be made to Bizarro. Bizarro expects the value of the yen to fall over the next two years (relative to the U.S. dollar). Which of the following actions would Bizarro most likely take today to hedge the foreign currency risk associated with this construction contract?', 'Purchase JPY in the market today.', 'Sell JPY in the market today.', 'Enter into a long forward contract to purchase JPY in the future.', 'Enter into a short forward contract to sell JPY in the future.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Purchasing JPY today would increase (not decrease) Bizarro’s exposure to foreign currency risk.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Bizarro will not receive the JPY payment until the contract has been fulfilled. Therefore the company would not sell JPY today.', 'Answer C is incorrect. A forward contract to purchase JPY in the future would increase (not decrease) Bizarro’s exposure to foreign currency risk.', 'Answer D is correct. Bizarro Corp. would most likely enter into a short FX forward to hedge its exposure to foreign currency risk. Bizarro knows that it will receive JPY in the future, and by using an FX forward, it can lock in the exchange rate at which it will sell those JPY for USD.', '');
INSERT INTO `chapter_review_questions` (`rev_ques_id`, `course_id`, `chapter_id`, `rev_ques_title`, `rev_ques_ans_1`, `rev_ques_ans_2`, `rev_ques_ans_3`, `rev_ques_ans_4`, `rev_ques_ans_5`, `rev_correct_ans_id`, `rev_correct_ans_text`, `rev_wronge_ans_text`, `rev_ques_status`, `ans1_text`, `ans2_text`, `ans3_text`, `ans4_text`, `ans5_text`) VALUES
(198, 16, 91, 'Zod Co. has sold an oil forward contract to a counterparty.  Under the terms of the agreement, Zod has agreed to charge a specified price for 100,000 gallons of oil in one year. The current market price of oil equals $70 per gallon. Zod has incurred a $4 per gallon opportunity cost by entering into this forward contract. The future value of the contract’s benefits equals $3 per gallon.  <br /> Given the above information, the implied forward price of oil equals:', '$69.', '$71.', '$73.', '$74.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. This amount reflects an incorrect subtraction of the future value of the opportunity costs and addition of the future value of the contract’s benefits.', 'Answer B is correct. The implied forward price equals the spot price ($70) plus the future value of the opportunity costs ($4) minus the future value of the contract’s benefits ($3).', 'Answer C is incorrect. This amount reflects an incorrect addition of the future value of the contract’s benefits and ignores the future value of the opportunity costs.', 'Answer D is incorrect. This amount does not correctly incorporate the future value of the contract’s benefits.', ''),
(199, 16, 91, 'Which of the following scenarios would most likely occur if Zod has established a forward price that is lower than the implied forward price calculated in the question above?', 'Counterparty A makes an arbitrage profit at the expense of Zod.', 'Counterparty B incurs arbitrage expenses.', 'Counterparty C opts out of the forward contract without penalty.', 'Counterparty D sues Zod Co. for damages.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. Arbitrage is the practice of taking advantage of a price differential between two or more markets. A counterparty would most likely be able to make an arbitrage profit (at the expense of Zod) if Zod were to establish a forward price lower than $71.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Arbitrage is the result of voluntary trading activities that are executed in order to take advantage of a pricing differential between various markets. If such a strategy were to result in net losses, the counterparty would simply not execute the additional trades.', 'Answer C is incorrect. A counterparty would not be able to opt out of a forward contract in this manner, as it is a binding agreement between counterparties.', 'Answer D is incorrect. There would be no basis for a counterparty to sue Zod Co. in this situation.', ''),
(200, 16, 91, 'Brainiac, Inc. has entered into a one year forward rate agreement in which it will pay an interest settlement based on a 5% fixed rate and receive an interest settlement based on the 1 year Treasury index (which is observed as 4%). The notional principal of the FRA equals $1,000,000. Which of the following represents the cash exchange that will occur at the settlement date?', 'The counterparty will pay $10,000 to Brainiac.', 'The counterparty will pay $1,010,000 to Brainiac.', 'Brainiac will pay $10,000 to the counterparty.', 'Brainiac will pay $1,010,000 to the counterparty.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Brainiac is paying a higher rate (5%) on the FRA than it is receiving (4%). Therefore the result is a net cash outflow (not inflow) of $10,000 on the settlement date.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Brainiac is paying a higher rate (5%) on the FRA than it is receiving (4%). Therefore the result is a net cash outflow (not inflow) of $10,000 on the settlement date. Also, the FRA notional principal would not be exchanged between the two counterparties.', 'Answer C is correct. Brainiac will pay its counterparty a net $10,000 on the FRA settlement date. This amount equals $1,000,000 * (4% receive - 5% pay).', 'Answer D is incorrect. The FRA notional principal would not be exchanged between the two counterparties.', ''),
(201, 16, 92, 'Goblin, Corp. has determined that it will require 65,400 gallons of natural gas 186 days from now. Goblin, Corp. would like to purchase a contract today that would allow them to lock in the price that they pay for this gas in the future. Goblin has very specific terms that they would like included in this contract, including the number of gallons to be delivered and the delivery date. Which of the following derivative instruments would most likely meet the needs of Goblin, Corp.?', 'A long forward contract.', 'A long futures contract.', 'A short forward contract.', 'A short futures contract.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. A long forward contract would most likely need the hedging needs to Goblin Corp. as such a contract would (1) involve the purchase of gas in the future and (2) allow for customized terms', 'Answer B is incorrect. Future contracts have standardized terms that would not likely fit the very specific needs of Goblin Corp.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Goblin Corp. would require a long (not short) contract as they are looking to buy (not sell) natural gas.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Goblin Corp. would require a long (not short) contract as they are looking to buy (not sell) natural gas. Also, future contracts have standardized terms that would not likely fit the very specific needs of Goblin Corp.', ''),
(202, 16, 92, 'Which of the following scenarios would a new participant in the futures market most likely observe?', 'Company A experiences high barriers to entry.', 'Company B discovers unreliable price information.', 'Company C benefits from the simplified trading mechanisms.', 'Company D incurs high transaction costs.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Standardized delivery grades mean virtually anyone with sufficient capital can enter the market easily to hedge or speculate. Therefore, there are relatively lower barriers to enter the futures market.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Futures markets often offer buyers and sellers more reliable price information than cash and forward markets.', 'Answer C is correct. Trading futures is made relatively simple by the standardization of the key characteristics of a commodity or product to be delivered.', 'Answer D is incorrect. The futures markets are highly liquid, and increased liquidity often means lower transaction costs.', ''),
(203, 16, 92, 'Which of the following futures transactions is an example of a limit order?', 'Company A places a short order that will be executed whenever the market price falls below a specified threshold.', 'Company B places a long order to be carried out immediately at the best price available.', 'Company C places a long order than can only be executed at a specific price (or a price more favorable to the company).', 'Company D places a short order to be carried out during off-market hours.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. This is an example of a stop order, which is a futures order executed at the best available price once a bid or offer is made at that specific price or a less-favorable price. It is also referred to as a stop-loss order.', 'Answer B is incorrect. This is an example of a market order, which is a futures trade that will be executed immediately at the best available price.', 'Answer C is correct. A limit order specifies a particular price. This order can be executed only at this price or at one more favorable to the investor.', 'Answer D is incorrect. This is not an example of a valid futures order.', ''),
(204, 16, 92, 'Which of the following practices effectively minimizes the credit risk associated with futures contracts?', 'Company A strictly places only stop-limit orders.', 'Company B maintains its margin account on a daily basis.', 'Company C matches the purchase and sale dates of their assets with the delivery dates of their futures contracts.', 'Company D purchases futures contracts for speculative purposes.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The type of futures order placed generally does not have an impact on the credit risk associated with the contract.', 'Answer B is correct. The margin requirement associated with futures contracts minimizes the credit risk associated with these instruments, as traders are required by the exchange to deposit funds in a margin account on a daily basis to prevent contract defaults.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Matching dates in this manner would minimize the basis risk associated with the hedge, not the credit risk associated with the futures contract.', 'Answer D is incorrect. The specific usage of a futures contract (hedging vs. speculating) generally does not affect the credit risk associated with the instrument.', ''),
(205, 16, 92, 'For the following 3 questions, please refer to the facts below: <br /> Venom Inc. purchased 1,000 commodity futures contracts on Day 1 at $100 per contract.  The futures price moved to $101 on Day 2, and then down to $95 on Day 3. The maintenance margin on Venom’s account is $98,000.  <br /><br /> The initial margin that Venom, Inc. will be required to deposit into their account on Day 1 equals:', '$0.', '$95,000.', '$98,000.', '$100,000.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Initial margin is required for new futures contracts purchased. Therefore the initial margin amount would not equal $0.', 'Answer B is incorrect. The initial margin amount is based on the total value of the futures contract(s) at the time of purchase ($100 per contract).', 'Answer C is incorrect. The initial margin is based on the total value of the futures contract(s) at the time of purchase ($100 per contract), not the maintenance margin (i.e. the minimum balance to be held in the margin account going forward).', 'Answer D is correct. The initial margin required equals the total value of the futures contract(s) at the time of purchase. In this case, the initial margin equals 1,000 contracts * $100 per contract ($100,000).', ''),
(206, 16, 92, 'The variation margin that Venom, Inc. will be required to deposit into their account as a result of Day 2 pricing adjustments equals:', '$0.', '$1,000.', '$2,000.', '$5,000.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. Venom Inc. would not be required to deposit any variation margin (i.e. additional funds) into their margin account as the value of their futures position increased on Day 2 (from 100 to 101).', 'Answer B is incorrect. Venom would not be required to deposit an additional $1,000 into their margin account as the value of their futures position increased on Day 2 (from 100 to 101).', 'Answer C is incorrect. Venom would be required to deposit an additional as variation margin only if the market price decreased. In this example, the market priced increased to 101.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Venom would not be required to deposit an additional $5,000 into their margin account as the value of their futures position increased.', ''),
(207, 16, 92, 'The variation margin that Venom, Inc. will be required to deposit into their account as a result of Day 3 pricing adjustments equals:', '$0.', '$1,000.', '$3,000.', '$5,000.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Variation margin totaling $5,000 would be required in this case as the market price of futures dropped below the maintenance margin threshold.', 'Answer B is incorrect. The correct variation margin amount equals the difference between the maintenance initial margin level ($100 per contract) and the current market price ($95 per contract).', 'Answer C is incorrect. When a margin call takes place, the account owner must deposit enough funds to bring the balance back up to the initial margin level. Therefore, the correct variation margin amount does not equal the difference between the variation margin threshold ($98 per contract) and the current market price ($95 per contract).', 'Answer D is correct. Venom Inc. would be required to deposit $5,000 variation margin (i.e. additional funds) into their margin account as the value of their futures position dropped to $95, which is $5 per contract below the $100 initial margin level.  ', ''),
(208, 16, 92, 'For the following 3 questions, please refer to facts below: <br /> Sandman Co. uses futures contracts to hedge its exposure to widget price movements. Sandman expects to sell 100,000 “grade B” widgets in 3 months. Sandman would like to lock in the sales price that it receives for its widgets by entering into futures contracts, however such contracts are not offered for grade B widgets. Sandman therefore enters into 100,000 short “grade A” widget futures contracts at a delivery price of $50 per widget. Upon maturity of the futures contract, the market prices of a grade A and B widgets equal $45 and $40 respectively.  <br /><br /> Assuming that the company does not close out its futures position prior to maturity, the payoff to Sandman Oil. would equal a:', '$1,000,000 loss.', '$1,000,000 gain.', '$500,000 loss.', '$500,000 gain.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. This payoff amount incorrectly uses the “grade B” widget market price in the calculation. Also, the payoff amount would represent a gain to Sandman Co., as they would be able to sell 100,000 grade A widgets for $50 each even though the current market price for such a widget equals $45.', 'Answer B is incorrect. This payoff amount incorrectly uses the “grade B” widget market price in the calculation.', 'Answer C is incorrect. The payoff amount would represent a gain to Sandman Co., as they would be able to sell 100,000 grade A widgets for $50 each even though the current market price for such a widget equals $45.', 'Answer D is correct. This “grade A” futures position results in a $500,000 gain to Sandman Co., which equals ($50 delivery price - $45 market price) * 100,000 contracts.', ''),
(209, 16, 92, 'Had Sandman Co. been able to purchase “grade B” futures contracts for the same delivery price ($50 per widget), their payoff would have equaled a:', '$1,000,000 loss.', '$1,000,000 gain.', '$500,000 loss.', '$500,000 gain.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The payoff amount would have represented a gain to Sandman Co., as they would have been able to sell 100,000 grade A widgets for $50 each even though the current market price for such a widget equals $40.', 'Answer B is correct. A “grade B” futures position would have resulted in a $1,000,000 gain to Sandman Co., which equals ($50 delivery price - $40 market price) * 100,000 contracts.', 'Answer C is incorrect. This payoff amount incorrectly uses the “grade A” widget market price in the calculation. Also, the payoff amount would have represented a gain to Sandman Co., as they would have been able to sell 100,000 grade A widgets for $50 each even though the current market price for such a widget equals $40.', 'Answer D is incorrect. This payoff amount incorrectly uses the “grade A” widget market price in the calculation.', ''),
(210, 16, 92, 'The imperfect hedging relationship that exists between the “grade B” widgets and the “grade A” futures contract results in which of the following risks?', 'Credit risk.', 'Commodities risk.', 'Basis risk.', 'Grade risk.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Such a risk is not referred to as credit risk. In terms of futures, credit risk would refer to the risk of loss resulting from a counterparty’s failure to deliver in accordance with the contract. Such risk is mitigated through margin requirements.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Commodities risk is not a risk normally associated with futures contracts.', 'Answer C is correct. The imperfect correlation between the “grade B” widgets held for sale and the “grade A” futures contract created the potential for excess gains or losses in Sandman’s hedging strategy. Such exposure is referred to as basis risk. The value of Sandman’s “grade B” widgets declined by $1,000,000 over 3 months in our example. Sandman was able to offset some (but not all) of these losses with the $500,000 gain on their “grade A” futures contracts. Therefore, the basis risk associated with this hedge resulted in $500,000 losses that could have been eliminated had Sandman been able to properly hedge their exposure using “grade B” futures contracts.', 'Answer D is incorrect. “Grade risk” is not a commonly used term in the world of derivatives.', ''),
(211, 16, 93, 'For the first 3 questions, please refer to facts below: <br /> Magneto Investments is a European-based hedge fund that frequently invests in countries all over the world. Magneto’s financial statements are reported in euros. Magneto recently entered into a swap agreement to pay ABC Bank a stream of U.S. dollar cash flows based on a 5% fixed rate in exchange for another stream of U.S. dollar cash flows based on 1 year LIBOR. The annual swap settlements are based on a $10 million notional principal.  <br /><br /> The swap agreement between Magneto and its counterparty is considered _____________.', 'A currency swap.', 'An interest rate swap.', 'An equity swap.', 'A credit default swap.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. This swap agreement is not a currency swap. A currency swap involves exchanging principal and interest payments in one currency for principal and interest payments in another. Unlike an interest rate swap, the parties to a currency swap will exchange principal amounts at the beginning and end of the swap.', 'Answer B is correct. The swap agreement between Magneto and its counterparty is an interest rate swap. The transaction is an agreement to exchange one set of cash flows based on a fixed (5%) rate for another set based on a floating index (1 year LIBOR).', 'Answer C is incorrect. This contract is not an equity swap. An equity swap is an agreement to exchange the total return (dividends and capital gains) on an equity index for either a fixed or floating rate of return.', 'Answer D is incorrect. This contract is not a credit default swap. A credit default swap is a contract that provides the buyer with protection against default, a credit rating downgrade, or another credit event.', ''),
(212, 16, 93, 'If the value of 1 year LIBOR equals 3.5% on the first observation date, a net settlement amount would be remitted by __________ in the amount of ___________ (in accordance with the swap agreement).', 'Magneto Investments; $10,150,000.', 'ABC Bank; $10,150,000.', 'Magneto Investments; $150,000.', 'ABC Bank; $150,000.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The $10mm notional principal in an interest rate swap agreement is not exchanged between counterparties.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Magneto would owe ABC Bank for the difference in interest rates, as the fixed rate it is paying under the contract (5%) is higher than the floating rate it is receiving (3.5%). Also, the $10mm notional principal in an interest rate swap agreement is not exchanged between counterparties.', 'Answer C is correct. A net settlement amount of $150,000 would be paid by Magneto Investments; this amount equals $10,000,000 notional principal * (3.5% receive rate – 5% pay rate). The $10mm notional principal in an interest rate swap agreement is not exchanged between counterparties.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Magneto would owe ABC Bank for the difference in interest rates, as the fixed rate it is paying under the contract (5%) is higher than the floating rate it is receiving (3.5%).', ''),
(213, 16, 93, 'During the third year of the swap agreement, Magneto and ABC Bank notice a discrepancy in their calculations for the current year’s settlement amount. Which of the following sources would the two companies most likely review to resolve this discrepancy?', 'ISDA guidelines.', 'The credit support annex.', 'European legal code.', 'The swap confirmation.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. ISDA guidelines consist of clauses defining in some detail the terminology used in swap agreements. These guidelines would not contain specific information about the swap agreement between Magneto and ABC Bank.', 'Answer B is incorrect. The rules governing the mutual posting of collateral between Magneto and ABC Bank would be included in the credit support annex. This document would not contain information about the calculation of interest settlements.', 'Answer C is incorrect. The two companies would not likely review European legal code to resolve their discrepancy.', 'Answer D is correct. The swap confirmation would contain all of the details regarding the calculation of the instrument’s settlement amounts. The two companies would most likely review this document to resolve their discrepancy.', ''),
(214, 16, 93, 'Phoenix, Inc. has issued $10,000,000 of floating rate debt. The interest that Phoenix pays on this debt is based on the London Inter-bank Offer Rate. Which of the following actions would Phoenix most likely take in order to hedge its exposure to future increases in LIBOR?', 'Enter into a receive LIBOR, pay fixed interest rate swap to create a synthetic fixed rate liability.', 'Enter into a receive USD, pay EUR currency swap to create a synthetic USD liability.', 'Enter into a receive EUR, pay USD currency swap to create a synthetic EUR liability.', 'Enter into a pay LIBOR, receive fixed interest rate swap to create a synthetic fixed rate liability.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. Phoenix is currently paying floating rate (LIBOR) interest on their debt. A receive LIBOR, pay fixed interest rate swap would effectively transform the debt into a “synthetic” fixed rate liability by offsetting the LIBOR-based interest payment associated with the debt with the LIBOR-based interest receipt associated with the receive leg of the interest rate swap. The only remaining cash flow would be the fixed rate settlement associated with the pay leg of the interest rate swap.', 'Answer B is incorrect. A currency swap would not effectively hedge the interest rate risk associated with Phoenix’s floating rate liability. Rather, a currency swap would instead be used to hedge any the foreign exchange risk associated with this transaction (if any exists).', 'Answer C is incorrect. A currency swap would not effectively hedge the interest rate risk associated with Phoenix’s floating rate liability. Rather, a currency swap would instead be used to hedge any the foreign exchange risk associated with this transaction (if any exists).', 'Answer D is incorrect. A pay LIBOR, receive fixed interest rate swap would increase (not decrease) Phoenix’s interest rate risk because Phoenix is already paying a floating rate of interest (LIBOR) on its debt.', ''),
(215, 16, 93, 'For the following 3 questions, please refer to the facts below: <br /> On 12/31/X1, Mystique, Corp. entered into a 5 year USD/CAD currency swap with XYZ Bank. Mystique is using this swap to convert a 5,000,000 U.S. dollar (USD) liability to Canadian dollars (CAD). Under the terms of the agreement, the USD interest rate equals 6% and the CAD interest rate equals 4.5%. Interest settlements are exchanged annually (up to and including 12/31/X6, the maturity date of the swap). On 12/31/X1, 1 USD is worth $1.10 CAD. On 12/31/X6, 1 USD is worth $1.18 CAD.  <br /><br /> Which of the following best illustrates the (gross) currency exchange that will take place between Mystique Corp. and XYZ Bank on 12/31/X1?', 'No currency exchange will take place on this date.', 'Mystique will send 5,000,000 USD to XYZ Bank in exchange for $5,000,000 CAD.', 'Mystique will send 5,000,000 USD to XYZ Bank in exchange for $5,500,000 CAD.', 'Mystique will send 5,000,000 CAD to XYZ Bank in exchange for $5,500,000 USD.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Under currency swap agreements, counterparties exchange principals to satisfy each other’s need for funds denominated in another currency.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Mystique would receive 5,500,000 CAD (i.e $5,000,000 USD * the $1.10 USD/CAD exchange rate) as part of the currency swap agreement.', 'Answer C is correct. Under currency swap agreements, counterparties exchange principals to satisfy each other’s need for funds denominated in another currency. In this case, Mystique would transfer $5,000,000 USD to XYZ Bank in exchange for 5,500,000 CAD (i.e. $5,000,000 USD * the $1.10 USD/CAD exchange rate).', 'Answer D is incorrect. Mystique would transfer $5,000,000 USD to XYZ Bank in exchange for 5,500,000 CAD under the terms of the agreement.', ''),
(216, 16, 93, 'Which of the following best illustrates the (gross) currency exchange that will take place between Mystique, Corp. and XYZ Bank on 12/31/X2?', 'Mystique will send 247,500 CAD to XYZ Bank in exchange for $300,000 USD.', 'Mystique will send 247,500 USD to XYZ Bank in exchange for $300,000 CAD.', 'Mystique will send 330,000 CAD to XYZ Bank in exchange for $225,000 USD.', 'Mystique will send 330,000 USD to XYZ Bank in exchange for $225,000 CAD.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. Under the currency swap agreement, Mystique’s 12/31/X2 currency payment to XYZ Bank equals 5,500,000 CAD principal * 4.5% = 247,500 CAD. XYZ Bank’s 12/31/X2 currency payment to Mystique $5,000,000 USD principal * 6% = $300,000 USD.', 'Answer B is incorrect. This answer incorrectly switches the currency payments being transferred between the counterparties. Under the currency swap agreement, Mystique will receive USD, while XYZ Bank will receive CAD.', 'Answer C is incorrect. This answer incorrectly switches the USD & CAD interest rates paid in accordance with the currency swap agreement. Under the currency swap agreement, Mystique will receive a payment based on a 6% interest rate, while XYZ Bank will receive a payment based on a 4.5% interest rate.', 'Answer D is incorrect. This answer incorrectly switches the currencies and USD & CAD interest rates paid in accordance with the currency swap agreement. Under this agreement, Mystique will receive a principal amount denominated in USD and an interest payment based on a 6% interest rate. XYZ Bank will receive principal amount denominated in CAD and an interest payment based on a 4.5% interest rate.', ''),
(217, 16, 93, 'Which of the following best illustrates the (gross) currency exchange that will take place between Mystique Corp. and XYZ Bank on 12/31/X6?', 'Mystique will send 6,165,500 CAD to XYZ Bank in exchange for $5,300,000 USD.', 'Mystique will send 6,165,500 USD to XYZ Bank in exchange for $5,300,000 CAD.', 'Mystique will send 5,747,500 CAD to XYZ Bank in exchange for $5,300,000 USD.', 'Mystique will send $5,747,500 USD to XYZ Bank in exchange for 5,300,000 CAD.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The CAD currency payment is incorrectly adjusted for changes in the USD/CAD exchange rate that occurred during the life of the currency swap agreement.', 'Answer B is incorrect. The USD and CAD currency payments are incorrectly reversed. Also, the currency payments should not be adjusted for changes in the USD/CAD exchange rate that occurred during the life of the currency swap agreement.', 'Answer C is correct. Under the currency swap agreement, Mystique’s 12/31/X6 currency payment to XYZ Bank equals the 5,500,000 CAD principal plus the final interest payment of 247,500 CAD (total payment equals 5,747,500 CAD). XYZ Bank’s 12/31/X6 currency payment to Mystique equals the $5,000,000 USD principal plus the final interest payment of $300,000 USD (total payment equals $5,300,000 USD). The principal payments included in the above calculations are not adjusted for changes in exchange rates that occurred during the life of the currency swap agreement.', 'Answer D is incorrect. The USD and CAD currency payments are incorrectly reversed. Under the currency swap agreement, Mystique will receive USD, while XYZ Bank will receive CAD.', ''),
(218, 16, 93, 'For the following 3 questions, please refer to the facts below: <br /> Sentinel, Inc. currently holds a LIBOR-based corporate bond (denominated in USD) that has been issued by Microsoft. The company wishes to purchase a derivative from NYC Bank that would protect them from losses resulting from the Microsoft’s failure to meet its obligation under the terms of the debt agreement. NYC offers such a product for an annual fee of 1% (100bps) of the total notional principal.  <br /><br /> The derivative product that would most likely meets the hedging needs of Sentinel is a ____________.', 'Equity swap.', 'Credit default swap.', 'Interest rate swap.', 'Currency swap.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. An equity swap is an agreement to exchange the total return (dividends and capital gains) on an equity index for either a fixed or floating rate of return. This type of instrument would most likely not meet the credit risk hedging needs of Sentinel.', 'Answer B is correct. A credit default swap would most likely meet the hedging needs to Sentinel. A credit default swap is a contract that provides the buyer with protection against default, a credit rating downgrade, or another credit event.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Interest rate swaps involve the exchange of cash flows based on fixed and floating interest rates. This type of instrument would most likely not meet the credit risk hedging needs of Sentinel.', 'Answer D is incorrect. A currency swap involves exchanging principal and interest payments in one currency for principal and interest payments in another. This type of instrument would most likely not meet the credit risk hedging needs of Sentinel.', ''),
(219, 16, 93, 'Under the terms of the derivative contract, the “reference entity” is:', 'Sentinel, Inc.', 'NYC Bank.', 'LIBOR.', 'Microsoft.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Sentinel Inc. is the buyer of the CDS, not the reference entity. It is hedging its credit exposure to Microsoft (the reference entity).', 'Answer B is incorrect. NYC Bank is the seller of the CDS, not the reference entity. It is assuming the credit risk associated with Sentinel’s bond, which was issued by Microsoft (the reference entity).', 'Answer C is incorrect. LIBOR is the benchmark interest rate from which the interest payments on the debt instrument are based. It is not the reference entity, which is the issuer of the debt instrument (Microsoft).', 'Answer D is correct. Microsoft is the reference entity, as it is the issuer of the debt instrument that is being hedged. In the event that Microsoft defaults on its debt, NYC Bank will reimburse Sentinel Bank under the terms of its credit default swap.', ''),
(220, 16, 93, 'Under the terms of the derivative contract, NYC Bank would be required to pay Sentinel for losses incurred as a result of:', 'An increase in Microsoft’s stock price.', 'An increase in inflation.', 'A Microsoft credit event.', 'A decrease in LIBOR.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Increases in Microsoft’s stock price would have no direct impact on NYC Bank’s obligation under a credit default swap. Rather, NYC Bank would be required to reimburse Sentinel for losses incurred as a result of a Microsoft’s bankruptcy, ratings downgrade, or other credit event.', 'Answer B is incorrect. NYC Bank’s obligation to pay under the terms of a credit default swap would not be directly impacted by an increase in macroeconomic measures such as inflation. The terms of credit default swaps are normally linked directly to the ability of the reference entity (Microsoft) to pay its debts.', 'Answer C is correct. Under the terms of a credit default swap, NYC Bank would be required to pay Sentinel for losses incurred as a result of a Microsoft credit event (such as a bankruptcy or ratings downgrade).', 'Answer D is incorrect. Movements in interest rates would have no direct impact on NYC Bank’s obligation under a credit default swap.', ''),
(221, 16, 94, 'Which of the following agreements is the most consistent with the terms of a typical option contract?', 'Company A will pay 6% fixed interest to ABC Bank in exchange for interest based on a floating index.', 'Company B is obligated to purchase $5 million of corporate bonds at a specified price in 3 years.', 'Company C will receive payment from NYC Bank in the event of default by its primary bond issuer.', 'Company D has paid a fee for the right to buy 1,000 shares of Proctor & Gamble stock for a specified price.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Company A’s contract is consistent with the terms of an interest rate swap, as it involves the exchange of cash flows based on interest rates.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Company B’s contract is consistent with the terms of a forward contract. A forward contract obliges one party to buy a specific asset for a specified price, while an option contract grants a party the right to do so.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Company’s C contract is consistent with the terms of a credit default swap, which is a derivative contract that allows the transfer of third party credit risk from one party to the other.', 'Answer D is correct. In an option contract, one party grants to the other the right to buy or sell an asset at a specific price at some point in the future. Company D’s contract would be considered an option.', ''),
(222, 16, 94, 'For the following 2 questions, please refer to the facts below: <br />  Vader Inc. currently owns a fixed income security that it anticipates selling in the near future. Vader sells the right for a counterparty to purchase this security from them for a predetermined price at any time over the next 6 months.  <br /><br /> From the perspective of Vader Inc., this contract is considered a:', 'Long call option contract.', 'Long put option contract.', 'Short call option contract.', 'Short put option contract.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Vader’s contract would be a long call option if it were purchasing the right to buy an underlying instrument at a specified price until the expiration date.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Vader’s contract would be a long put option if it were purchasing the right to sell an underlying instrument at a specified price until the expiration date.', 'Answer C is correct. Vader’s contract is a short call option, in which they are selling the right for their counterparty to buy the underlying fixed income security at a specified price until the expiration date (6 months from now).', 'Answer D is incorrect. Vader’s contract would be a short put option if it were selling the right to sell an underlying instrument at a specified price until the expiration date.', ''),
(223, 16, 94, 'Assuming the option sold by Vader is exercised, the value that the counterparty would pay for the underlying security is based on:', 'The strike price.', 'The option price.', 'The original cost basis.', 'The market price.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. The price specified in an option contract is known as the strike price. In this example, the counterparty would be able to purchase the fixed income security from Vader Inc. for the strike price that is specified in the contract.', 'Answer B is incorrect. The option price refers to the premium paid by the counterparty for the right to purchase the underlying security from Vader.', 'Answer C is incorrect. The short call option contract would allow the counterparty to purchase the underlying security from Vader at the strike price (not the original cost basis).', 'Answer D is incorrect. The short call option contract would allow the counterparty to purchase the underlying security from Vader at the strike price (not the current market price). If the counterparty wanted to purchase the security at its current market price, it could simply do so in the open market (without entering into an option contract).', ''),
(224, 16, 94, 'For the following 6 questions, please refer to the facts below:  <br />  Jabba, Corp. is an active market maker for option contracts.  Jabba pays a $1 per share premium for its purchased option contracts and earns a $2 per share premium for the option contracts that they sell.  Jabba currently has four outstanding stock option contracts with ABC Bank that are nearing expiration, including: <br />  Outstanding option contracts (from the perspective of Jabba, Corp.) <br />  Contract #1: Long call option on Microsoft; strike price = $25.00 per share <br /> Contract #2: Short put option on Pfizer; strike price = $20.00 per share <br />  Contract #3:	Long put option on Exxon Mobil; strike price = $70.00 per share <br /> Contract #4: Short call option on Wal-Mart; strike price = $50.00 per share  <br /><br /> Regarding contract #1, which of the following actions would most likely occur if Microsoft’s stock price were to rise to $30.00 per share?', 'Jabba, Corp. would exercise the option and realize a $6 per share loss.', 'ABC Bank would exercise the option and realize a $4 per share net gain.', 'ABC Bank would exercise the option and realize a $6 per share loss.', 'Jabba, Corp. would exercise the option and realize a $4 per share net gain.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Jabba would not incur a loss on the long call option because the option is in-the-money. Furthermore, Jabba would not exercise any option that is out-of-the-money.', 'Answer B is incorrect. ABC Bank has sold the call option to Jabba and therefore does not hold the right to exercise it. Also, the Bank would not exercise any option contract that is out-of-the-money.', 'Answer C is incorrect. ABC Bank has sold the call option to Jabba and therefore does not hold the right to exercise it.', 'Answer D is correct. Jabba, Corp., as the holder of the long call option, would have the right to exercise the option for a net $4 per share gain ($5 capital gains less the $1 option premium).', ''),
(225, 16, 94, 'Regarding contract #2, how much profit would Jabba, Corp. earn if Pfizer’s stock price were to rise to $30.00 per share?', '$0 per share.', '$2 per share.', '$8 per share.', '$12 per share.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Jabba, Corp. would earn a $2 profit on the premiums received on the short put option.', 'Answer B is correct.   Jabba, Corp. has sold this put option to ABC Bank for a $2 per share premium. ABC Bank would not exercise the option if the underlying stock price were to rise above the $20 strike price as the contract would then be out-of-the-money. Therefore, ABC Bank would simply allow the option to expire worthless, leaving Jabba Corp. with a $2 per share profit on the trade.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Jabba, Corp. is the seller of this option contract (not the buyer); therefore, they would not earn a $8 profit on any increases or decreases in the underlying stock’s value. Their profit is limited to the $2 per share premium received.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Jabba, Corp. is the seller of this option contract (not the buyer); therefore, they would not earn a $10 profit on any increases or decreases in the underlying stock’s value. Their profit is limited to the $2 per share premium received.', ''),
(226, 16, 94, 'Regarding contract #3, which of the following actions would most likely occur if Exxon Mobil’s stock price were to rise to $80.00 per share?', 'ABC Bank would allow the option to expire worthless.', 'ABC Bank would exercise the option and realize a $12 per share net gain.', 'Jabba, Corp. would allow the option to expire worthless.', 'Jabba, Corp. would exercise the option and realize a $9 per share net gain.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.   Jabba, Corp. is long the option position (i.e. they have purchased the option) and therefore Jabba (not ABC Bank) owns the right to exercise the option or allow it to expire.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Jabba, Corp. is long the option position (i.e. they have purchased the option) and therefore Jabba (not ABC Bank) owns the right to exercise the option or allow it to expire.', 'Answer C is correct.  When the current value of an option contract is negative, the option is considered “out-of-the-money”.  Jabba, Corp. would allow the contract to expire worthless, as the option is out-of-the-money.', 'Answer D is incorrect. The long put option is out-of-the-money as the current stock price is greater than the strike price of the contract.', ''),
(227, 16, 94, 'If contract #4 is exercised when the market value of Wal-Mart’s stock equals $57.00, the net economic impact of the option on ABC Bank would equal a:', '($8) per share loss.', '($2) per share loss.', '$1 per share gain.', '$5 per share gain.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. This contract would not result in a net expense greater than the $2 option premium paid, as ABC Bank could simply not exercise the out-of-the-money option.', 'Answer B is incorrect. This contract would not result in a net loss of $2 (i.e. the value of the option premium paid), as the option is in-the-money by $7 per share.', 'Answer C is incorrect. ABC Bank has paid a $2 per share premium for the right to purchase the underlying stock from Jabba; it did not receive a $1 per share premium under this contract.', 'Answer D is correct. This contract is a long call option from ABC Bank’s perspective, as they have purchased the right to buy shares of Wal-Mart stock from Jabba, Corp. for $50 per share. ABC Bank’s total net profit on their long call option would, therefore equal ($57 ST – $50 K) - $2 premium paid = $5 per share profit.', ''),
(228, 16, 94, 'Under contract #4, the maximum profit that Jabba, Corp. can earn is __________, while the maximum loss that Jabba Corp. can incur is ___________.', 'Equal to the value of the premium received; unlimited.', 'Unlimited; equal to the value of the premium paid.', 'Limited to the value of the underlying stock; unlimited.', 'Unlimited; limited to the value of the underlying stock.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. Under contract #4, the maximum profit that Jabba Corp. can earn is equal to the value of the premium received, while the maximum loss that they can incur is unlimited.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  The maximum profit is limited to the value of the premium received, as ABC Bank would simply allow the option to expire if the contract is out-of-the-money from their perspective. The maximum loss is unlimited as the price of the underlying stock could increase infinitely.', 'Answer C is incorrect. The maximum profit is limited to the value of the premium received, as ABC Bank would simply allow the option to expire if the contract is out-of-the-money from their perspective.', 'Answer D is incorrect. The maximum profit is limited to the value of the premium received, as ABC Bank would simply allow the option to expire if the contract is out-of-the-money from their perspective. The maximum loss is not limited to the value of the underlying stock, as the price of the underlying stock could increase infinitely.', ''),
(229, 16, 94, 'Regarding Jabba, Corp.’s short call option (see contract #4, Review Questions 5.2), which of the following actions could Jabba, Corp. take to protect themselves from potential losses resulting from sharp increases in Wal-Mart’s stock price?', 'Sell a call option to a different counterparty.', 'Purchase a call option on Wal-Mart stock.', 'Sell any holdings in Wal-Mart stock that the company may own.', 'Purchase a put option on Wal-Mart stock.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Selling a call option to a different counterparty would increase (not decrease) Jabba’s exposure to rising Wal-Mart stock prices.', 'Answer B is correct.  By purchasing a call option on Wal-Mart stock, Jabba, Corp. would effectively create a “covered call” position that would protect them from a potentially large payoff on the ABC Bank short call option contract.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Selling their holdings in Wal-Mart stock would increase Jabba’s total losses as they would forgo any of their own capital gains resulting from the rise in Wal-Mart’s stock price.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Purchasing a put option would not effectively protect them from these losses as put options decline in value as the underlying stock value increases.', ''),
(230, 16, 94, 'Which of the following option strategies would benefit the most from increases in the price of the underlying asset?', 'Company A enters into a bear spread.', 'Company B enters into a short call option.', 'Company C enters into a bull spread.', 'Company D enters into a long put option.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  An investor who enters a “bear spread” strategy will profit from decreases in the underlying asset’s price.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  A short call option decreases in value as stock prices increase.', 'Answer C is correct. An investor who enters a “bull spread” strategy will profit from increases in the underlying asset’s price.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  A long put option increases in value as stock prices decline.', ''),
(231, 21, 95, 'For Questions 1-4, please refer to the following facts. <br />  Cersei is an economist that is reviewing reports published by the NBER on the economic activity that occurred during the previous decade. She has observed that during the year 20X1, the economy experienced several consecutive quarters of negative GDP measures, higher unemployment, and increasingly severe declines in economic activity. During the year 20X3, Cersei observed that the economy “bottomed out”, with economic activity no longer declining and consumer purchasing activity slightly increasing due to low interest rates. During the year 20X4, the economy begins to grow rapidly and unemployment rates decrease. After several years of strong growth, the Federal Reserve Bank raises interest rates in 20X7 based on fears of rising inflation.  This action slows the growth rate of the economy.  <br /><br /> The economist would most likely conclude that which of the following phases of the business cycle occurred during 20X1?', 'Peak.', 'Recession.', 'Trough.', 'Expansion.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The peak in a business cycle is the last month in which the economy is growing overall. In 20X1 the economy is in severe decline, which is indicative of a recession.', 'Answer B is correct. A recession is an extended period of significant of economic decline. Common indicators of a recession include negative Gross Domestic Product and higher unemployment rates. Based on these observations, the economist would likely conclude that the economy was in the recession phase of the business cycle.', 'Answer C is incorrect. The trough of a business cycle is the last month that economic activity declines. In 20X1, the economist has observed increasingly severe declines in economic activity. Therefore, the economist would likely conclude that the economy remained in recession.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Economic expansions occur when economic activity increases following the trough of recession. In 20X1, the economist has observed declining (not increasing) economic activity.', ''),
(232, 21, 95, 'The economist would most likely conclude that which of the following phases of the business cycle occurred during 20X3?', 'Peak.', 'Recession.', 'Trough.', 'Expansion.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The peak in a business cycle is the last month in which the economy is growing overall. In 20X3 the economy in nearing the end of a recession (not an expansion), which is indicative of a trough.', 'Answer B is incorrect. A recession is a period of significant and extended period of economic decline. A trough occurs when such declines end and the economy “bottoms out”. The economist would therefore likely conclude that the economy was in a trough during 20X3, as the economic activity is no longer declining.', 'Answer C is correct.  A trough occurs when a recession ends and the economy “bottoms out”.  A common event that occurs during a trough is a decrease in interest rates, which results in an increase in consumer purchasing.  Based on these observations, the economist would likely conclude that the economy was in the trough phase of the business cycle.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Economic expansions occur when economic activity increases following the trough of recession.  During 20X3, the economy remained relatively flat following a period of recession.  Such a condition is inactive of a trough, not an expansion.', '');
INSERT INTO `chapter_review_questions` (`rev_ques_id`, `course_id`, `chapter_id`, `rev_ques_title`, `rev_ques_ans_1`, `rev_ques_ans_2`, `rev_ques_ans_3`, `rev_ques_ans_4`, `rev_ques_ans_5`, `rev_correct_ans_id`, `rev_correct_ans_text`, `rev_wronge_ans_text`, `rev_ques_status`, `ans1_text`, `ans2_text`, `ans3_text`, `ans4_text`, `ans5_text`) VALUES
(233, 21, 95, 'The economist would most likely conclude that which of the following phases of the business cycle begins in 20X4?', 'Peak.', 'Recession.', 'Trough.', 'Expansion.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  The peak in a business cycle is the last month in which the economy is growing overall.  In 20X4 the economy is growing and there are no indications that this growth will end soon.  Therefore, the economist would likely conclude that the economy was in expansion at this time.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  A recession is a period of significant and extended period of economic decline. In 20X4 the economy is growing (not declining) and therefore the economist would not conclude that the economy was in a recession.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  A trough occurs when a recession ends and the economy “bottoms out”.  In 20X4 the economy is growing rapidly and therefore the economist would not conclude that the economy was in a trough.', 'Answer D is correct.  Economic expansions occur when economic activity increases following the trough of recession.  During 20X4, the economy is growing after “bottoming out” in 20X3.  Based on these observations, the economist would likely conclude that the economy was in the expansion phase of the business cycle.', ''),
(234, 21, 95, 'The economist would most likely conclude that which of the following phases of the business cycle occurred during 20X7?', 'Peak.', 'Recession.', 'Trough.', 'Expansion.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct.  The peak in a business cycle is the last month in which the economy is growing overall.  The Federal Reserve is known to raise interest rates at this point to slow the rate of inflation.  The economist observes such activity in 20X7, and therefore, she would likely conclude that the economy was at its peak.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  A recession is a period of significant and extended period of economic decline.  In 20X4 the economy is still growing (but at a slower pace).  Therefore, the economist would not conclude that the economy was in a recession.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  A trough occurs when a recession ends and the economy “bottoms out”.  In 20X7 the economy is nearing the end of an expansion (not recession), and therefore the economist would not conclude that the economy was in a trough.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Economic expansions occur when economic activity increases following the trough of recession.  Although the economy is still growing in 20X7, this growth is occurring at a slow pace as a result of the Federal Reserve’s raising of interest rates.  This is indicative of an economy’s peak.', ''),
(235, 21, 95, 'Which of the following economic conditions would most likely be observed immediately prior to the beginning of a recession?', 'Economist A observes an increase in exports to foreign countries.', 'Economist B observes business increasing production due to inventory shortages.', 'Economist C observes lower oil prices and higher consumer spending power.', 'Economist D observes a sharp drop in home prices following years of high demand.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Decreases (not increases) in exports are a sign that a recession is imminent.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Excess inventories (not inventory shortages) are a cause of recession. When this occurs, businesses slow production and unemployment often increases.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Higher (not lower) oil prices are a cause of recession, as businesses’ production costs increase and consumers spending power decreases.', 'Answer D is correct.  When very high demand drives up prices of particular assets (e.g. homes), an “asset bubble” often occurs. When this bubble bursts, the values of these assets normally declines severely, which often results in a decline in overall economic activity (i.e. a recession).', ''),
(236, 21, 95, 'For the following 5 questions, please refer to the facts below. <br /> Three institutional investors (in varying economic scenarios) are reviewing economic indicators prior to making investment decisions. Investor A is reviewing his country’s unemployment rate, which has increased following the beginning of a recession. Investor B is reviewing the performance of the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE), which has recently experienced declines even though a recession has not been officially declared. Investor C is reviewing GDP measures, which are growing as economic activity continues an expansion. <br /><br /> The unemployment rate would most like be considered an example of a:', 'Lagging indicator.', 'Composite indicator.', 'Leading indicator.', 'Coincident indicator.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct.  The unemployment rate is an example of a lagging indicator.  The rate tends to change 2-3 quarters after an upturn or downturn in the general economy has occurred.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  The unemployment rate is not considered a “composite”, as it is a single economic indicator and not an average of other indicators.', 'Answer C is incorrect.   A leading indicator is one that indicates changes in the business cycle before they happen.  The unemployment rate tends to change after an upturn or downturn in the general economy has occurred, and therefore it is not considered a leading indicator.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Changes in strength and weakness of coincident indicators typically occur in conjunction with changes in the business cycle.  The unemployment rate tends to change after an upturn or downturn in the general economy has occurred, and therefore it is not considered a coincident indicator.', ''),
(237, 21, 95, 'The performance of the NYSE would most like be considered an example of a:', 'Lagging indicator.', 'Composite indicator.', 'Leading indicator.', 'Coincident indicator.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Lagging indicators are those that move after changes in the business cycle have already occurred.  Changes in stock market (e.g. the NYSE) performance tend to occur ahead of changes in the overall economy, and therefore it is considered a leading (not lagging) indicator.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Changes in the NYSE are not considered a “composite”, as it is a single economic indicator and not an average of other indicators.', 'Answer C is correct.  A leading indicator is one that indicates changes in the business cycle before they happen.  The performance of the NYSE is an example of such an indicator, as it usually declines before the economy as a whole, declines.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Changes in strength and weakness of coincident indicators typically occur in conjunction with changes in the business cycle.  Changes in stock market (e.g. the NYSE) performance tend to occur ahead of changes in the overall economy, and therefore it is considered a leading (not coincident) indicator.', ''),
(238, 21, 95, 'Gross Domestic Product (GDP) would most like be considered an example of a:', 'Lagging indicator.', 'Composite indicator.', 'Leading indicator.', 'Coincident indicator.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Lagging indicators are those that move after changes in the business cycle have already occurred.  Changes in GDP tend to occur concurrently with changes in the overall economy, and therefore it is considered a coincident (not lagging) indicator.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  GDP is not considered a “composite”, as it is a single economic indicator and not an average of other indicators.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  A leading indicator is one that indicates changes in the business cycle before they happen.  Changes in GDP tend to occur concurrently with changes in the overall economy, and therefore it is considered a coincident (not leading) indicator.', 'Answer D is correct.  Changes in strength and weakness of coincident indicators typically occur in conjunction with changes in the business cycle.  Changes in GDP tend to occur concurrently with changes in the overall economy, and therefore it is considered a coincident indicator.', ''),
(239, 21, 95, 'Investor A notes is his research report that the unemployment rate increases as economic activity declines. Based on this observation, the unemployment rate would most likely be referred to as a _____________ in the investor’s report.', 'Countercyclical indicator.', 'Leading indicator.', 'Procyclical indicator.', 'Coincident indicator.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct.  A countercyclical indicator is one that moves in the opposite direction as the economy.  The unemployment rate is a countercyclical indicator, as it increases as the economy worsens.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  A leading indicator is one that indicates changes in the business cycle before they happen.  The unemployment rate tends to change after an upturn or downturn in the general economy has occurred, and therefore it is not considered a leading indicator.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  A procyclical indicator is one that moves in the same direction as the economy.  The unemployment rate is a countercyclical (not procyclical) indicator, as it increases as the economy worsens.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Changes in strength and weakness of coincident indicators typically occur in conjunction with changes in the business cycle.  The unemployment rate tends to change after an upturn or downturn in the general economy has occurred, and therefore it is not considered a coincident indicator.', ''),
(240, 21, 95, 'Investor C notes in her research report that GDP increases as economic activity increases. Based on this observation, GDP would most likely be referred to as a _____________ in the investor’s report.', 'Countercyclical indicator.', 'Leading indicator.', 'Procyclical indicator.', 'Lagging indicator.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  A countercyclical indicator is one that moves in the opposite direction as the economy.  GDP is an example of a procyclical (not countercyclical) indicator, as it increases when the economy strengthens and decreases when the economy weakens.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  A leading indicator is one that indicates changes in the business cycle before they happen.  Changes in GDP tend to occur concurrently with changes in the overall economy, and therefore it is considered a coincident (not leading) indicator.', 'Answer C is correct.  A procyclical indicator is one that moves in the same direction as the economy.  GDP is an example of a procyclical indicator, as it increases when the economy strengthens and decreases when the economy weakens.', 'Answer D is correct.  Lagging indicators are those that move after changes in the business cycle have already occurred.  Changes in GDP tend to occur concurrently with changes in the overall economy, and therefore, it is considered a coincident (not lagging) indicator.', ''),
(241, 21, 95, 'Stannis would like to become a day trader in the stock market and needs to have access to updated economic indicators as soon as they become available. The tool that Stannis would most likely use to determine when such economic indicators are updated is referred to as:', 'A composite index.', 'A consensus forecast.', 'A production report.', 'An economic calendar.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  A composite index is a grouping of economic indicators that is combined in a standardized way, providing a useful statistical measure of overall market or sector performance over time.  Stannis would not be able to use a composite index to determine when various economic indicators are updated. Rather, an economic calendar would be used for such a purpose.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Consensus forecasts are reports that combine separate economic forecasts that are made using different methodologies.  Such reports do not provide information on when various economic indicators will be updated.', 'Answer C is correct.  A production report is an example of an economic indicator.  It would not likely provide information on when other economic indicators would be published.', 'Answer D is correct.  An economic calendar is the schedule that indicates when various economic indicators will be made available to the public through news releases.  Stannis would use an economic calendar to stay abreast on the most recently issued indicators.', ''),
(242, 21, 96, 'Arya is drafting an article on the role of financial markets in the global economy. Which of the following statements would she include in this article to best describe the primary purpose of financial markets:', 'Financial markets provide the means for governments to levy taxes to pay for public services.', 'Financial markets provide a mechanism for households, businesses and governments to obtain financing.', 'Financial markets provide a consistent set of accounting principles used by businesses when preparing financial statements.', 'Financial markets protect depositors from risky or improper investing by banks and other financial institutions.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  The primary purpose of the tax system (not financial markets) is to provide the means for governments to levy taxes to pay for public services.', 'Answer B is correct.  The primary purpose of financial markets is to provide a mechanism for participants to obtain financing (such as home mortgages, automobile loans, and other forms of short- and long-term financing).', 'Answer C is incorrect.  The primary purpose of Generally Accepted Accounting Principles (not financial markets)  is to provide a consistent set of accounting principles used by businesses when preparing financial statements.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  The primary purpose of the bank regulatory system (not financial markets) is to protect depositors from risky or improper investing by banks and other financial institutions.', ''),
(243, 21, 96, 'Which of the following financial market participants would most likely be considered an example of a deficit unit?', 'Company A has a $2 million cash balance in a money market account.', 'Company B is seeking a $2 million loan from ABC Bank.', 'Company C reported $2 million positive cash flow from operations last year.', 'Company D is seeking to purchase $2 million of fixed rate bonds.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Company A would be considered a ‘surplus unit’ because it has $2 million excess funds that are currently in a money market account.', 'Answer B is correct.  Company B is considered a ‘deficit unit’ because it has entered the financial market to obtain funds (i.e. the $2 million loan).', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Company C would most likely be considered a ‘surplus unit’ because it recently realized $2 million of positive cash flow from operations.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Company D would be considered a ‘surplus unit’ because it has $2 million of excess funds that it is looking to invest in the bond market.', ''),
(244, 21, 96, 'For the next Two questions, please refer to the facts below:  <br /> Winterfell Corp. has issued a financial instrument by which it will remit principal and 5% interest payments to the holder until a stated maturity date (10 years from the issue date).  <br /><br /> Winterfell Corp.’s financial instrument is most likely an example of:', 'A short-term equity instrument.', 'A long-term equity instrument.', 'A short-term debt instrument.', 'A long-term debt instrument.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Equity instruments represent a percentage ownership of the company.  The features of Winterfell Corp.’s instrument are not consistent with those of an equity instrument.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Winterfell Corp.’s financial instrument is not an equity instrument because it does not represent a percentage ownership of the company.  (Note – equity instruments are not delineated between short-term and long-term).', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Winterfell Corp.’s financial instrument is a not short-term debt instrument because its maturity period is greater than one year’s time.', 'Answer D is correct.  Winterfell Corp.’s financial instrument is a long-term debt instrument because it is a contractual agreement by Winterfell to pay the holder fixed dollar amounts at regular intervals (interest and principal payments) over 10 years.', ''),
(245, 21, 96, 'Winterfell Corp. most likely sold their financial instrument to an investor in a:', 'Over-the-counter market.', 'Money market.', 'Primary market.', 'Secondary exchange.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  The over-the-counter market is a secondary market; new debt issuances (such as this example) are sold to investors in the primary market.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  The money market is a financial market for short-term debt instruments; Winterfell Corp.’s financial instrument is a long-term debt instrument.', 'Answer C is correct. Winterfell Corp’s financial instrument is a new debt issuance, which are sold to investors in the primary market.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  An exchange is an example of a secondary market; new debt issuances (such as this example) are sold to investors in the primary market.', ''),
(246, 21, 96, 'Which of the following financial transactions would most likely take place in a money market?', 'Company A purchases U.S. Government Treasury bills.', 'Company B issues long-term corporate debt.', 'Company C purchases shares of Wal-Mart stock.', 'Company D obtains a second mortgage on its manufacturing plant.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct.  The money market is a financial market in which only short-term debt instruments are traded.  A U.S. Government Treasury bill is an example of such an instrument that is traded in the money market.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Only short-term debt instruments are traded in the money market.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Equity shares are traded in equity (i.e. stock) markets, not the money market.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Such mortgages are normally obtained in the capital market.', ''),
(247, 21, 96, 'Which of the following financial market instruments represents a percentage ownership in the issuing company?', 'Company A’s commodity.', 'Company B’s common stock.', 'Company C’s corporate bond.', 'Company D’s Treasury note.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Commodities are homogeneous goods that are supplied to buyers without any qualitative differentiation, such as oil and gold.  Commodities do not represent a percentage ownership in a company.', 'Answer B is correct.  Common stock is a financial instrument that represents a percentage ownership in the issuing company.  A stockholder owns a percentage interest in the firm, consistent with the percentage of outstanding stock held.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  A bond represents debt (i.e. an obligation) of the issuing entity; it does not represent a percentage ownership.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  A Treasury note is a debt instrument issued by the United States government.  Common stocks are instruments issued by companies in the private sector.', ''),
(248, 21, 96, 'Which of the following transactions would most likely occur in the bond market?', 'Company A has purchased equity shares for its investment portfolio.', 'Company B has purchased gold as an investment.', 'Company C has issued debt to finance a long-term construction project.', 'Company D has issued 30-day instrument to finance current expenses.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Equity shares are generally exchanged in the stock market.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Gold and other commodities are purchased in the commodities market.', 'Answer C is correct.  Bonds are long-term debt instruments that are generally issued to finance a variety of projects and activities.  The primary bond market is where new issues of bonds are introduced.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Short-term financial instruments issued to finance current expenses (such as commercial paper) are generally traded in the money markets.', ''),
(249, 21, 96, 'Which of the following transactions would most likely occur in the commodities market?', 'Company A has purchased equity shares for its investment portfolio.', 'Company B has purchased gold as an investment.', 'Company C has issued debt to finance a long-term construction project.', 'Company D has issued 30-day instrument to finance current expenses.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Equity shares are generally exchanged in the stock market.', 'Answer B is correct. Gold and other commodities are purchased in the commodities market.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Bonds are long-term debt instruments that are generally issued to finance a variety of projects and activities.  The primary bond market is where new issues of bonds are introduced.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Short-term financial instruments issued to finance current expenses (such as commercial paper) are generally traded in the money markets.', ''),
(250, 21, 96, 'Catelyn, a trader for Stark Financial, has been asked to research the possibility of investing the company’s capital in the foreign exchange market. Which of the following statements would most likely appear in Catelyn’s report to accurately describe the characteristics of the FX market?', '“The FX market features thousands of different currencies.”', '“The FX market is open only during standard European business hours.”', '“The FX market is highly liquid.”', '“The FX market is comprised strictly of domestic and international governmental entities.”', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  There are only eight currencies in the FX market that are commonly traded, including the U.S. Dollar, Euro, Japanese Yen, British Pound Sterling, Swiss Franc, Canadian Dollar, and others.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  The FX market is a global market that is generally open 24 hours a day.', 'Answer C is correct. The foreign exchange market is one of the largest and most liquid financial markets in the world.  It is several times larger than the U.S. Government securities market (the second largest market in the world).', 'Answer D is incorrect.  The FX market consists of a limited number of major dealer institutions that are particularly active in foreign exchange, trading with customers and (more often) with each other. Most, but not all, are commercial banks and investment banks.', ''),
(251, 21, 96, 'For the next 4 Questions, please refer to the facts below: <br /> Lannister Corp. has issued two debt instruments in order to raise funds. Bond #1 accrues 6% simple interest based on a $3,000,000 principal amount with a three-year maturity. Bond #2 accrues 3% compound interest based on a $10,000,000 principal amount with a five-year maturity. Both instruments accrue interest on an annual basis. <br /><br /> 10.	What is the amount of the annual interest that will accrue on Bond #1 during its second year?', '$0.', '$180,000.', '360,000.', '$540,000.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The bond has a stated interest rate of 6% (not 0%).', 'Answer B is correct. The bond will accrue $180,000 simple interest during its second year. This equals the $3,000,000 principal amount multiplied by the 6% interest rate.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  This amount equals the cumulative interest accrued on the bond for years 1 and 2 (i.e. $3,000,000 principal amount X 6% X 2).', 'Answer D is incorrect.  This amount equals the cumulative interest accrued on the bond throughout its 3- year term (i.e. $3,000,000 principal amount X 6% X 3).', ''),
(252, 21, 96, '<p>Assuming that no debt extinguishments take place, what is the principal balance of Bond #2 at the end of its second year?</p>', '$10,000,000.', '$10,300,000.', '$10,600,000.', '$10,609,000.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  This amount is the original principal balance of the instrument. The compounded interest amounts from years 1 & 2 are not correctly added to the balance.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  This amount is the principal balance of the instrument at the end of year 1.  The compounded interest amount from year 2 is not correctly added to the balance.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  This amount incorrectly doubles the interest amount from year 1 and adds it to the original principal balance.  The correct calculation is illustrated below.', 'Answer D is correct.  The bond accrues interest on a compound basis, which means that the interest accrued for a particular compounding period is added to the principal balance of the instrument. In this case, the principal balance of the bond at the end of year 2 would be calculated as follows:\r\n\r\nYear      Beg. Principal      Interest (3%)       End Principal \r\n1            10,000,000          300,000                 10,300,000\r\n2            10,300,000          309,000                 10,609,000', ''),
(253, 21, 96, 'Which of the following bonds was most likely purchased at a discount?', 'Bond A has an 8% stated coupon (paid semi-annually) and an 8% YTM.', 'Bond B has a 5% stated coupon (paid annually) and a 7% YTM.', 'Bond C has a 6% stated coupon (paid semi-annually) and a 5% YTM.', 'Bond D has a 6% stated coupon (paid annually) and a 6% YTM.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Bond A would be traded at par because its stated coupon rate (8%) equals its yield-to-maturity (8%).', 'Answer B is correct.  The comparison of a bond’s YTM with its stated coupon rate determines the price at which the instrument is traded.  Bond B would be traded at a discount because its stated coupon rate (5%) is less than its yield-to-maturity (7%).', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Bond C would trade at a premium because the stated coupon rate (6%) is more than its yield-to-maturity (5%).', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Bond D would be traded at par because its stated coupon rate (6%) equals its yield-to-maturity (6%).', ''),
(254, 21, 96, 'Which of the following bonds was most likely purchased at a premium?', 'Bond A has a 4% stated coupon (paid semi-annually) and a 5% YTM.', 'Bond B has a 3% stated coupon (paid annually) and a 3% YTM.', 'Bond C has a 5% stated coupon (paid semi-annually) and a 5% YTM.', 'Bond D has a 9% stated coupon (paid annually) and a 7% YTM.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Bond A would be traded at a discount because its stated coupon rate (4%) is less than its yield-to-maturity (5%).', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Bond B would be traded at par because its stated coupon rate (3%) equals its yield-to-maturity (3%).', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Bond B would be traded at par because its stated coupon rate (5%) equals its yield-to-maturity 5%).', 'Answer D is correct.  The comparison of a bond’s YTM with its stated coupon rate determines the price at which the instrument is traded. Bond D would be traded at a premium because its stated coupon rate (9%) is more than its yield-to-maturity (7%).', ''),
(255, 21, 96, 'Theon, a market analyst, is attempting to predict market interest rate movements. Which of the following economic indicators would most likely be necessary in order for Theon to make this prediction using the concepts of the loanable funds theory?', 'Changes in the money supply.', 'The Dow Jones Industrial Average.', 'Foreign currency exchange rates.', 'The unemployment rate.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct.  The supply and demand for money (or ‘loanable funds’) are the key components to determining interest rates under the loanable funds theory.  The ability to predict changes in the money supply would be necessary in order to predict changes in interest rates under this theory.  ', 'Answer B is incorrect.  The DJIA is a price-weighted average of 30 significant stocks traded on the New York Stock Exchange and the Nasdaq.  It is not a component for determining interest rates under the loanable funds theory.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  A foreign exchange (FX) rate is the price of one country''s currency expressed in another country''s currency.  The loanable funds theory explain interest rate movements, not FX rate movements.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  The unemployment rate is not a component for determining interest rates under the loanable funds theory.', ''),
(256, 21, 96, 'Castle Black, Corp. recently issued debt instruments to finance an expansion of their northern operations. The company has reported material net losses in their income statements for the past three years. Under the risk structure of interest rates, which of the following interest rate characteristics would be most likely be adjusted to compensate Castle Black’s bond investors for the increased risk of loss?', 'Liquidity risk premium.', 'Interest rate risk premium.', 'Default risk premium.', 'Foreign exchange risk premium.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  The liquidity risk premium compensates bond holders if the debt instrument cannot be quickly converted to cash in a secondary market.  Such risk does not apply in this example.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  While interest rates are often associated with bonds, the yields on these instruments are not adjusted for interest rate risk under the risk structure of interest rates.', 'Answer C is correct.  Under the risk structure of interest rates, the primary characteristics that affect the yields on debt instruments are default risk, liquidity risk and income taxes. Premiums are added to a bond’s yield when such risks exist.  The interest rate on Castle Black’s debt instrument would likely include a default risk premium to compensate investors for assuming the default risk associated with the instrument.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Bond yields are not adjusted for foreign exchange risk under the risk structure of interest rates.', ''),
(257, 21, 96, 'On 5/1/201X, bonds A, B & C are being offered in the market under the following terms: Bond A pays 3% interest with a 5-year term-to-maturity; Bond B pays 5.5% interest with an 8-year term-to-maturity; Bond C pays 8.5% interest with a 12 year term-to-maturity. The risk, liquidity and tax profiles of the three bonds are identical. Under this scenario, the bond yield curve on 5/1/201X is most likely:', 'Downward sloping.', 'Flat.', 'Upward sloping.', 'Inverted.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  The yield curve would slope downward if interest rates on longer-term bonds were lower than interest rates on shorter-term bonds.  However, in this scenario, the longer-term bonds have higher yields than the shorter-term bonds, and therefore the yield curve is upward sloping.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  The yield curve would be flat if interest rates on longer-term bonds were the same as interest rates on shorter-term bonds. However, this is not true in this scenario.', 'Answer C is correct.  A yield curve is a graphical depiction of bond yields based on their terms-to-maturity.  A yield curve slopes upward when interest rates on longer-term bonds are higher than interest rates on shorter-term bonds (as is the case in this scenario).', 'Answer D is incorrect.  The yield curve would be inverted (i.e. slope downward) if interest rates on longer-term bonds were lower than interest rates on shorter-term bonds.', ''),
(258, 21, 97, 'Tyrion is a financial analyst who wishes to examine growth in the U.S. economy as a whole (including all of its components) using a single economic metric. Which of the following measures would best serve this purpose?', 'Government expenditures.', 'Gross domestic product.', 'Trade deficits.', 'Personal consumption expenditures.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  While government expenditures are part of the overall economy and should be considered, this measure would not provide Tyrion with information on the U.S. economy as a whole.  Rather, gross domestic product measures (which include government expenditures and other components of the economy) would best serve this purpose.', 'Answer B is correct.  The size of a nation’s overall economy is measured by gross domestic product (GDP). By analyzing GDP, Tyrion would be able to examine the growth in all goods and services produced in the U.S. (including all of the economy’s components).', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Foreign trade information (including trade deficit or surplus data) represents only a fraction of the entire economy.  GDP measures would serve as the best source of information on the economy as a whole.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Personal consumption expenditures are a component of the overall economy and should be considered. However, PCE data would not provide Tyrion with information on the U.S. economy as a whole.  Rather, gross domestic product measures would best serve this purpose.', ''),
(259, 21, 97, 'For the following 5 questions, please refer to the facts below: <br />  Sansa, an economist at Westeros Corp., is reviewing economic data that has been compiled for the previous calendar year (20X4) by the U.S. Commerce Department.  Sansa plans to use this data to calculate gross domestic product under the expenditure approach. <br />  This data includes the following: <br /><br />  Consumption of durable goods: $5.0 trillion <br /> Consumption of nondurable goods: $4.0 trillion <br /> Consumption of services: $2.0 trillion <br /> Investments in capital goods: $3.0 trillion <br /> Investments in stocks and bonds: $2.5 trillion <br /> Government transfer payments: $0.5 trillion Government expenditures (other): $3.5 trillion <br /> Net imports: $1.0 trillion  <br />  <br /> Based on the data provided above, the amount of consumption expenditures (C) that should be included in Sansa’s calculation of GDP equals:', '$6 trillion.', '$7 trillion.', '$9 trillion.', '$11 trillion.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  This amount ($6T) incorrectly excludes the consumption of durable goods, which should be included in the calculation of GDP.', 'Answer B is incorrect.   This amount ($7T) incorrectly excludes the consumption of nondurable goods, which should be included in the calculation of GDP.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Amounts paid by consumers for services are a component of GDP.  This amount ($9T) incorrectly excludes such expenditures.', 'Answer D is correct.  Consumption expenditures (C) include amounts spent on durable goods ($5T), nondurable goods ($4T) and services ($2T).   Therefore, the amount of consumer expenditures that Sansa should include in her calculation of GDP equals the sum of these three amounts ($11T).', ''),
(260, 21, 97, 'Based on the data provided above, the amount of investment expenditures (I) that should be included in Sansa’s calculation of GDP equals:', '$0.5 trillion.', '$2.5 trillion.', '$3.0 trillion.', '$5.5 trillion.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  This amount ($0.5T) incorrectly subtracts investments in stocks and bonds ($2.5T) from investments in capital goods ($3.0T).  While investments in stocks and bonds should not be included when calculating GDP, such amounts should not be subtracted from investments in capital goods.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  This amount ($2.5T) equals investments in stocks and bonds, which should be excluded from Sansa’s calculation of GDP.  Rather, the amounts invested in capital goods ($3.0T) should be included.', 'Answer C is correct.  When calculating GDP, the amount of investment expenditures to be included is limited to those related to investments in capital goods. This includes purchases of property, plant, equipment, and other similar items.  Investment expenditures DO NOT include investments in stocks, bonds, and other financial instruments. Therefore, Sansa should include only $3.0 trillion when calculating GDP.', 'Answer D is incorrect.   This amount ($5.5T) incorrectly sums investments in stocks and bonds with investments in capital goods.  Sansa should include only $3.0 trillion when calculating GDP.', ''),
(261, 21, 97, 'Based on the data provided above, the amount of government expenditures (G) that should be included in Sansa’s calculation of GDP equals:', '$0.5 trillion.', '$3.0 trillion.', '$3.5 trillion.', '$4.0 trillion.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  This amount ($0.5T) equals transfer payments (such as Social Security and unemployment benefits), which should be excluded from Sansa’s calculation of GDP.  Rather, the other amounts spent on government expenditures ($3.5T) should be included.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  This amount ($3.0T) incorrectly subtracts transfer payments ($0.5T) from other government expenditures ($3.5T).  While transfer should not be included when calculating GDP, such amounts should not be subtracted from the other government expenditures.', 'Answer C is correct.  When calculating GDP, the amount of government expenditures should not include transfer payments (such as Social Security and unemployment benefits). Therefore, Sana should include only $3.5 trillion when calculating GDP, which reflects the other government expenditures.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  This amount ($5.5T) incorrectly sums transfer payments with the other government expenditures. Sansa should exclude only the $0.5T transfer payments when calculating GDP.', ''),
(262, 21, 97, 'When reviewing the net import data that she collected for 20X4, Sansa would most likely conclude that:', 'The United States had a trade deficit.', 'Net imports understate the measure of GDP.', 'The United States had a trade surplus.', 'Net imports should be excluded when calculating GDP.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct.  In this example, Sansa has observed that the United States is in a net import position. If a country’s imports exceed its exports (as in this case), the country is said to have a trade deficit.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Net imports overstate (not understate) the measure of U.S. GDP, as these goods are not produced in the country and therefore should not be considered part of U.S. output. This is why net imports are subtracted from other expenditures when calculating GDP.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Sansa has observed that the United States is in a net import position.  When this occurs, the country is said to have a trade deficit (not a trade surplus, which exists when a country’s exports exceed its imports).', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Net imports should not be excluded from the calculation of GDP.  Rather, such amounts should be subtracted from other expenditures when performing the calculation.', ''),
(263, 21, 97, 'Based on the data provided above, the measure of gross domestic product for 20X4 equals:', '$16.5 trillion.', '$17.0 trillion.', '$17.5 trillion.', '$18.5 trillion.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct.  In this example, gross domestic product equals ($11.0T Consumption + $3.0T Investment + $3.5T Government – $1.0T Net Imports) = $16.5 trillion.  Investments in stocks and bonds and government transfer payments are excluded from the calculation.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  The answer ($17.0T) incorrectly adds government transfer payments to the other GDP components.  Such amounts are excluded when calculating GDP.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  The answer ($17.5T) incorrectly ignores the impact of net imports on the measure of GDP.  Such amounts are subtracted from the other components when calculating GDP.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  The answer ($18.5T) incorrectly adds net imports to the sum of the other expenditures when calculating GDP.  Such amounts should be subtracted.', ''),
(264, 21, 97, 'Edmure prepares a report on economic activity that includes separate measures of GDP that have been prepared under the expenditure approach and the income approach. Assuming that his calculations were performed correctly, Edmure should observe that his GDP measure under the expenditure approach _________ his GDP measure under the income approach.', 'Is less than.', 'Is equal to.', 'Has no correlation to.', 'Is greater than.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  GDP measures under the expenditure approach would not be less than those performed under the income approach if they were done correctly.  Rather, these two measures should equal one another.', 'Answer B is correct.  When performed correctly, the expenditure approach or the income approach should result in identical measures of GDP.  Therefore, Edmure’s calculations should be equal.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  When performed correctly, the expenditure approach or the income approach should result in identical measures of GDP.  Therefore, this implies the perfect correlation between the two measures.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  GDP measures under the expenditure approach would not be greater than those performed under the income approach if they were done correctly. Rather, these two measures should equal one another.', ''),
(265, 21, 97, 'Bran is a policymaker that is attempting to explain the difference between measures of “nominal” GDP and “real” GDP to his constituents. Bran concludes that real GDP represents a measure of gross domestic product that is adjusted for changes in:', 'Foreign exchange rates.', 'Inflation.', 'Interest rates.', 'The business cycle.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  The “real” value of GDP refers to a measure that has been adjusted for inflation (not FX rates).', 'Answer B is correct.  The “real” value of any economic statistic refers to one that has been adjusted for inflation.  Real GDP is a measure of GDP that is adjusted for changes in the price level (i.e. inflation).', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Real GDP represents a measure of GDP that has been adjusted for inflation (not changes in interest rates).', 'Answer D is incorrect.  GDP measures can be analyzed to predictor or observe changes in the business cycle.  However, the relationship between nominal and real GDP is not related to the business cycle.', ''),
(266, 21, 97, 'Robb is an economist that is attempting to calculate real GDP for the previous year (20X5). He notes that nominal GDP was $4.5 trillion and the price index (i.e. GDP deflator) was 30.0. Based on this information, real GDP for 20X5 equals:', '$1.4 trillion.', '$4.5 trillion.', '$6.7 trillion.', '$15.0 trillion.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  This calculation incorrectly divides nominal GDP by (100 / 30.0 GDP deflator). Rather, real GDP equals ($4.5 trillion nominal GDP / (30.0 GDP deflator / 100) = $15.0 trillion.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  This amount represents nominal GDP (not real GDP), which has not been adjusted for inflation using the GDP deflator.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  This calculation incorrectly divides the 30.0 GDP deflator by $4.5 nominal GDP.  The correct calculation of real GDP equals ($4.5 trillion nominal GDP / (30.0 GDP deflator / 100) = $15.0 trillion.', 'Answer D is correct.  In this example, real GDP equals ($4.5 trillion nominal GDP / (30.0 GDP deflator / 100) = $15.0 trillion.  This amount represents a measure of GDP after being adjusted for inflation.', ''),
(267, 21, 97, 'Eddard is preparing a report that highlights the economic significance of the GDP Report. Which of the following statements would Eddard least likely include in his report?', '“The GDP Report provides data that can be used by policymakers to frame U.S. monetary policy.”', '“The GDP Report provides information to businesses that can be used for forecasting and financial planning purposes.”', '“The GDP Report provides traders with early access to important financial data.”', '“The GDP Report provides data to investors regarding the current state of the economy as it relates to the business cycle.”', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  The GDP Report provides data that can be used by policymakers to frame U.S. monetary policy. Therefore, Eddard might include such a statement in his report.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Businesses can use the information included in the GDP report to forecast earnings, plan capital expenditures, and for other purposes.', 'Answer C is correct.  From a trader’s perspective, the GDP Report is often old news. The information included is normally available (through other sources) before it is presented in the GDP Report.  Therefore, Eddard would not likely include such a statement in his report.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  The GDP Report does provide data regarding the current state of the economy as it relates to the business cycle.  The GDP Report is commonly used to identify when the economy has entered a recession.', ''),
(268, 21, 97, 'For the last two Questions, please refer to the facts below. <br /> The treasurer at Tyrell Corp. is analyzing the various components of GDP by reviewing certain key economic indicators. Tyrell Corp. is currently considering plans to expand its production capacity by financing the construction of new factories. <br /><br /> Which of the following economic indicators would likely provide the most useful information to the treasurer regarding consumer spending?', 'The unemployment rate.', 'Defense spending levels.', 'Inventory-to-sales ratios.', 'Capacity utilization rates.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct.  One of the most important factors of consumer spending is job growth, which is commonly measured by the unemployment rate.  Consumers tend to save more and spend less in periods of higher unemployment.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Defense spending levels do not directly impact consumer spending levels.  However, it would provide the treasurer with useful information regarding the government expenditure component of GDP.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Inventory-to-sales ratios allow businesses to gauge whether or not they have sufficient inventories to meet current demand.  This metric does not directly impact consumer spending levels.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Capacity utilization rates allow businesses to gauge whether or not their current production facilities are being properly utilized.  This metric does not directly impact consumer spending levels.', ''),
(269, 21, 97, 'Which of the following economic observations would prove the most beneficial to Tyrell Corp. as they plan to expand their production capacity?', 'Declining inventory-to-sales ratios.', 'Declining housing prices.', 'Declining GDP in foreign countries.', 'Declining interest rates.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Declining inventory-to-sales ratios is indicative of excess inventories and decreasing consumer demand for Tyrell’s products.  This would suggest that Tyrell should abandon its plans to increase production capacity.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Declining house prices often decreases consumer spending, which would likely decrease consumer demand for Tyrell’s products.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Declining GDP in foreign countries would likely decrease the exports of Tyrell’s products.  Increasing production in such an environment would result in excess inventories for which there is decreasing demand.', 'Answer D is correct.  Lower interest rates would allow Tyrell Corp. a cheaper way to finance the construction of new factories. This would allow them to construct more new factories that they would be able to build if interest rates were high.', ''),
(270, 21, 98, 'Davos, a market analyst, is researching U.S. central banking practices and their impact on interest rates. Which of the following institutions would likely have the greatest impact on market interest rates in the United States?', 'The Internal Revenue Service.', 'The Securities and Exchange Commission.', 'The Federal Reserve System.', 'The Financial Accounting Standards Board.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  The Internal Revenue Service is the United States federal government agency that collects taxes and enforces the internal revenue laws. Its actions do not directly impact interest rates.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  The Securities and Exchange Commission is an independent agency of the United States government which holds primary responsibility for enforcing the federal securities laws and regulating the securities industry.  Its actions do not directly impact interest rates.', 'Answer C is correct.  The Federal Reserve System is the central bank of the United States. Its monetary policies significantly influence interest rates.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  The Financial Accounting Standards Board is a private, not-for-profit organization whose primary purpose is to develop generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP) within the United States in the public''s interest.   Its actions do not directly impact interest rates.', '');
INSERT INTO `chapter_review_questions` (`rev_ques_id`, `course_id`, `chapter_id`, `rev_ques_title`, `rev_ques_ans_1`, `rev_ques_ans_2`, `rev_ques_ans_3`, `rev_ques_ans_4`, `rev_ques_ans_5`, `rev_correct_ans_id`, `rev_correct_ans_text`, `rev_wronge_ans_text`, `rev_ques_status`, `ans1_text`, `ans2_text`, `ans3_text`, `ans4_text`, `ans5_text`) VALUES
(271, 21, 98, 'Which of the following scenarios most accurately depicts a central banking practice in the United States?', 'The Board of Governors votes to raise tax rates on capital gains.', 'The Federal Reserve Bank reviews and approves a proposed merger between two commercial banks.', 'The Securities and Exchange Commission raises the discount rate charged for primary credit.', 'The Comptroller of the Currency establishes reserve requirements.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  The Federal Reserve Board of Governors does not have the ability to modify tax rates.', 'Answer B is correct.  The evaluation of proposed bank mergers is a function performed by the 12 Federal Reserve banks.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  The Federal Reserve Board of Governors authorizes changes in the discount rate for primary credit (not the SEC).', 'Answer D is incorrect.  The Federal Reserve Board of Governors establishes reserve requirements (not the Comptroller of the Currency).', ''),
(272, 21, 98, 'For the following 2 Questions, please refer to the facts below: <br /> On 12/31/1X, the Federal Reserve reports having the following asset & liability balances: Securities $1.2 trillion; Currency in circulation $1.5 trillion; Discount loans $0.8 trillion. <br /><br /> Given the information above, the balance of Reserves reported on the Fed’s 12/31/1X balance sheet must have equaled:', '$0 trillion.', '$0.5 trillion.', '$1.1 trillion.', '$1.9 trillion.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  The Federal Reserve’s balance sheet must balance, and in this example, the total reserves must equal $0.5 trillion in order for this to be true.', 'Answer B is correct. The Federal Reserve’s total assets (i.e. securities + discount loans) equals $2.0 trillion in this scenario; therefore, their total reserves must equal $0.5 trillion ($2.0 trillion total assets – $1.5 trillion currency liability) in order to balance.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  This answer incorrectly assumes that the Fed’s reserves are an asset and their discount loans are a liability. The opposite is true.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Government securities represent an asset on the Federal Reserve’s balance sheet.  Bank reserves represent a liability on the Fed’s balance sheet. Therefore, The Federal Reserve’s total assets (i.e. securities + discount loans) equals $2.0 trillion in this scenario; therefore, their total reserves must equal $0.5 trillion ($2.0 trillion total assets – $1.5 trillion currency liability) in order to balance.', ''),
(273, 21, 98, 'Given the information above, the total assets reported on the Fed’s 12/31/1X balance sheet must have equaled:', '$0.8 trillion.', '$1.2 trillion.', '$1.5 trillion.', '$2.0 trillion.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  A calculation of $0.8 trillion incorrectly includes only discount loans and excludes the $1.2 trillion of government securities (assets).', 'Answer B is incorrect.  $1.2 trillion represents the securities, which are assets of the Federal Reserve. However, this answer incorrectly excludes the $0.8 trillion of discount loans (assets) from the calculation of Total Assets.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  This answer incorrectly excludes the $1.2 trillion of government securities and $0.8 trillion of discount loans (assets) from the calculation and incorrectly includes the $1.5 trillion of currency in circulation (liability) in the calculation.', 'Answer D is correct.  The Federal Reserve’s total assets (i.e. $1.2 securities + $0.8 discount loans) equals $2.0 trillion in this scenario.', ''),
(274, 21, 98, 'Which of the following actions would most likely increase the U.S. money supply?', 'The Fed purchases government securities in the open market.', 'The Fed sells government securities in the open market.', 'Commercial Bank 1 purchases corporate bonds in the open market.', 'Commercial Bank 2 sells corporate bonds in the open market.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct.  The Federal Reserve increases the U.S. money supply when it purchases U.S. government securities in the open market.  Funds previously held by the Fed are placed into circulation when they are transferred to the securities’ sellers.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  The Fed reduces (not increases) the U.S. money supply when it sells U.S. government securities in the open market.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  The U.S. money supply is not affected when commercial banks purchase corporate bonds.  The funds are still considered in circulation when securities transactions are conducted by private parties.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  The U.S. money supply is only affected when the Federal Reserve buys or sells its securities in the open market. Securities transactions conducted by private parties have no effect on the money supply.', ''),
(275, 21, 98, 'Tarly Bank currently has insufficient reserves in their Federal Reserve account. Which of the following actions would the Bank most likely take in order to increase their reserves balance?', 'Borrow funds directly from the Federal Reserve.', 'Purchase government securities in the open market.', 'Decrease their reserve requirement ratio.', 'Purchase funds in the federal funds market.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  While borrowing funds directly from a Federal Reserve Bank would increase Tarly Bank’s reserves, such an action would normally be taken only as a last resort.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Purchasing government securities in the open market would lower Tarly Bank’s reserves (not increase them).', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Tarly Bank would not have the ability to lower their reserve requirement ratio (this ratio is established by the Federal Reserve).', 'Answer D is correct.  The federal funds market is the most commonly used outlet for purchasing funds to eliminate reserve deficiencies.  Tarly Bank would most likely purchase federal funds to increase their reserves balance.', ''),
(276, 21, 98, 'Which of the following represents the most likely scenario in which the U.S. money supply is decreased?', 'A Federal Reserve Bank replaces damaged currency with new currency.', 'The FOMC purchases government securities in the open market.', 'The Fed Board of Governors increases the primary credit rate.', 'A Member Bank increases its reserve requirement ratio.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The money supply would not increase or decrease if the Fed were to replace damaged currency with new currency.', 'Answer B is incorrect. The money supply would increase (not decrease) if the FOMC were to purchase government securities in the open market.', 'Answer C is correct. The discount rate is the interest rate charged to commercial banks and other depository institutions on loans they receive from their regional Federal Reserve Bank’s discount window. To decrease money supply, the Fed could authorize an increase in the discount rate for primary credit.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  A member bank would not be able to modify its own reserve requirement ratio (this ratio is established by the Federal Reserve).', ''),
(277, 21, 98, 'Which of the following represents the most likely scenario in which the U.S. money supply is increased?', 'The Federal Reserve increases the reserve requirement ratio.', 'The Federal Reserve increases the foreign exchange rate for the U.S. dollar.', 'The Federal Reserve increases the discount rate.', 'The Federal Reserve increases its outright purchases of government securities in the market.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The money supply would decrease (not increase) if the Fed were  to increase the reserve requirement ratio, as banks would be required to hold higher levels of reserves (rather than circulating that money in the market through lending activity).', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Foreign exchange rates are market driven and cannot be directly increased or decreased by the Federal Reserve Bank.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Increasing the discount rate would decrease the money supply, as depository institutions would be discouraged from borrowing money directly from the Fed.', 'Answer D is correct.  To increase money supply, the Fed could authorize an increase in the outright purchases of government securities in the market.  The money paid for these securities would be placed into circulation upon purchase by the Fed.', ''),
(278, 21, 98, 'For the following 3 Questions, please refer to the facts below. <br /> Brienne, an analyst at the Federal Reserve Bank, calculated the following balances of U.S. money supply as of 12/31/1X: <br />  <br /> Currency in circulation: $4.2 trillion <br /> Demand deposits: $1.7 trillion <br /> Money market funds (retail): $0.2 trillion <br /> Savings accounts: $2.2 trillion <br /> Short-term repos: $1.6 trillion <br /> Traveler’s checks: $0.6 trillion <br /> <br /> Based on the above balances, M1 equals:', '$2.3 trillion.', '$4.2 trillion.', '$6.5 trillion.', '$8.9 trillion.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. A calculation of $2.3 trillion incorrectly excludes the $4.2 trillion currency in circulation from the M1 calculation.', 'Answer B is incorrect. A calculation of $4.2 trillion incorrectly excludes the $1.7 trillion demand deposits and $0.6 trillion travelers’ checks from the M1 calculation.', 'Answer C is correct. The M1 money measure is restricted to the most liquid form of money; it consists of currency in the hands of the public, travelers’ checks, demand deposits and other checkable deposits. In this example, M1 would equal $6.5 trillion, or the sum of the $4.2 trillion currency in circulation, $1.7 trillion demand deposits and $0.6 trillion travelers’ checks.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  A calculation of $8.9 trillion incorrectly includes the $0.2 trillion money market funds and $2.2 trillion savings accounts in the M1 calculation. These amounts would be included in the calculation of M2, but not M1.', ''),
(279, 21, 98, 'Based on the above balances, M2 equals:', '$6.5 trillion.', '$8.7 trillion.', '$8.9 trillion.', '$10.5 trillion.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  A calculation of $6.5 trillion equals the M1 money measure (not M2).  It incorrectly excludes the $0.2 trillion money market funds and $2.2 trillion savings accounts in the calculation.  ', 'Answer B is incorrect.  A calculation of $8.7 trillion incorrectly excludes the $0.2 trillion money market funds, which is included in the definition of M2.', 'Answer C is correct.  The M2 money measure includes M1 plus savings accounts, time deposits under $100,000 and retail money market mutual funds.  In this example, M2 would equal $8.9 trillion, or the sum of M1 ($6.5 trillion), the $0.2 trillion money market funds and the $2.2 trillion savings accounts.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  A calculation of $10.5 trillion incorrectly includes $1.6 trillion short-term repos, which is not included in definitions of either M1 or M2.', ''),
(280, 21, 98, 'Which of the following actions would most likely result in a theoretical reduction of the M2 money measure?', 'Consumer A purchases a government security from the Fed using money from a checking account.', 'Consumer B transfers money from a savings account to a checking account.', 'Consumer C purchases travelers’ checks using money from a checking account.', 'Consumer B transfers money from a checking account to a retail money market mutual fund.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct.  This transaction would theoretically reduce the M2 money measure because the proceeds used to purchase the security would be transferred from a checking account (included in M2) to a Federal Reserve account (effectively taking the funds out of circulation).', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Such a transfer would have no net impact on M2, as both checking and saving accounts are included in the calculation.  ', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Both checking accounts and travelers’ checks are included in the calculation of M2.  Therefore, transferring money between the two would have no net impact on M2.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Transfers of money between checking accounts and retail money market mutual funds would have no net impact on the measure of M2, as both are included in the definition.', ''),
(281, 21, 98, 'Bronn is a stock market analyst for a European investment bank that is reviewing various U.S. economic reports, including those issued by the Federal Reserve.  <br />  Which of the following reports being reviewed by Bronn is issued by the Federal Reserve and includes announcements regarding changes in the federal funds rate?', 'The Beige Book.', 'The GDP Report.', 'The FOMC Statement.', 'Monetary Report to the Congress.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  The Beige Book is an economic report issued by the Federal Reserve, but it is not used to announce changes in the federal funds rate.  Rather, this report describes business conditions in each of the Fed’s 12 districts.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  The GDP Report is not issued by the Federal Reserve, and does not announce changes in the federal funds rate. Rather, it is an economic report issued by the U.S. Commerce Dept. on gross domestic product.  ', 'Answer C is correct.  The FOMC Statement is an economic report issued by the Federal Reserve. It is used by the Fed for setting monetary policy and includes announcements of changes in the federal funds rate.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  The Monetary Report to the Congress is a report issued by the Federal Reserve, but it used to announce fed funds rate changes. Rather, it provides a general economic update to the members of the U.S. Congress.', ''),
(282, 21, 99, 'For Questions 1-4, please refer to the facts below:  <br /> Gregor is a government economist that is drafting a report that will include a calculation of the latest unemployment rate. The unemployment survey data that he has collected indicate that 150 million people have been classified as employed, 10 million people have been classified as unemployed, and 75 million people are out of the labor force. <br /><br />  When calculating the unemployment rate, which of the following jobless people would most likely be classified as ‘unemployed’?', 'A full-time college student.', 'A retired postal worker.', 'A construction worker actively seeking employment.', 'A stay-at-home parent.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  The ‘unemployed’ classification generally excludes full-time college students, as they are considered ‘out of the labor force.’', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Retired workers are not classified as ‘unemployed,’ but rather as ‘out of the labor force.’', 'Answer C is correct.  When calculating the unemployment rate, those people who are out of work and actively looking for a job are classified as ‘unemployed.’  A construction worker who is jobless and actively seeking employment would meet that definition.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Stay-at-home parents are classified ‘out of the labor force’ and not ‘unemployed’ as the assumption is that such people are not actively seeking employment.', ''),
(283, 21, 99, 'Based on the data collected, what percentage of people would be considered part of the ‘labor force’?', '36%.', '68%.', '96%.', '100%.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  This calculation incorrectly reflects the percentage of the total adult-age population (235 million) who are either unemployed (10 million) or are out of the labor force (75 million). The labor force includes those who are classified as ‘employed’ and ‘unemployed’, and excludes those who are ‘out of the labor force.''', 'Answer B is correct.  The term ‘labor force’ refers to the number of employed people plus the unemployed people. In this example, the percentage of people in the labor force would be approximately 68%, which equals the total labor force (150 million employed + 10 million unemployed) divided by the 235 million total adult-age population.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  This calculation incorrectly reflects the percentage of the total adult-age population (235 million) who are either employed (150 million) or are out of the labor force (75 million). The labor force includes those who are classified as ‘employed’ and ‘unemployed’, and excludes those who are ‘out of the labor force.’', 'Answer D is incorrect. This value incorrectly represents the entire adult-age population (235 million, or 100%). Those who are considered ‘out of the labor force’ should be excluded from the calculation of the labor force, as noted above.', ''),
(284, 21, 99, 'Based on the data collected, the unemployment rate equals approximately:', '4.3%.', '6.3%.', '6.7%.', '13.3%.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  This calculation incorrectly divides the number of unemployed people (10 million) by the total adult-age population (235 million). When calculation the unemployment rate, the denominator should exclude those who are out of the labor force.  ', 'Answer B is correct.  To calculate the unemployment rate, divide the number of unemployed people (10 million) by the total labor force (160 million).  The result of this calculation is 6.3%.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  This calculation incorrectly divides the number of unemployed people (10 million) by the number of employed people (150 million). The denominator in this calculation should include all workers who are considered to be part of the labor force.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  This calculation incorrectly divides the number of unemployed people (10 million) by the number of people who are out of the labor force.  The denominator in this calculation should include all workers who are considered to be part of the labor force.', ''),
(285, 21, 99, 'Which of the following footnotes included in Gregor’s report would accurately highlight an inherent limitation of unemployment measures?', '“Unemployed workers data includes those who have stopped looking for work.”', '“Employed workers data excludes those with part-time jobs who are seeking full-time employment.”', '“Unemployed workers data excludes those who are out of work and are currently looking for a job.”', '“Employed workers data includes those who are underemployed.”', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct.  The household survey presents unemployment data from a worker’s perspective.  This data includes household employment, the number of unemployed, and other data necessary to calculate the unemployment rate.  The establishment survey is a survey of businesses that represents a job count from the employer’s perspective.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  The establishment survey provides unemployment data from the employer’s perspective.  It does not include household survey data.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  The household survey includes unemployment data from the worker’s perspective (not the employer’s perspective).  Also, the establishment survey includes unemployment data from the employer’s perspective (not the worker’s perspective).', 'Answer D is incorrect.  The household survey presents survey results from approximately 60,000 households.  It presents unemployment data from the worker’s perspective.', ''),
(286, 21, 99, 'Which of the following statements most accurately describes a key difference between the household survey and the establishment survey?', 'The household survey data is taken from a larger sample size than the establishment survey.', 'The establishment survey includes data on farm sectors, while the household survey does not.', 'The household survey includes data on sole proprietors, while the establishment survey does not.', 'The establishment survey is released on a weekly basis, while the household survey is released on a monthly basis.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  The household survey presents survey results from a smaller (not larger) sample size.  Its sample size is approximately 60,000 households, while the establishment survey’s sample size is approximately 390,000 businesses.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  The establishment survey excludes data from farm sectors, while the household survey included such data.', 'Answer C is correct.  Several differences exist between the household and establishment surveys.  One of the biggest differences is that the household survey data includes the self-employed and sole proprietors, while the establishment survey data does not.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Both surveys are released in the same report (i.e. the Employment Situation Report) on a monthly basis.', ''),
(287, 21, 99, 'While analyzing the impact of unemployment indicators on financial markets, Myrcella observes that investors in the stock market react favorably when unemployment ________ while investors in the bond market react favorably when unemployment ________.', 'Rises; rises.', 'Rises; falls.', 'Falls; falls.', 'Falls; rises.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Stock market investors do not react favorably to rises in unemployment, as it is commonly an indicator of declining economic output.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Stock market investors react favorably when unemployment falls (not rises). Bond markets often react favorably when unemployment rises (not falls).', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Bond markets often react favorably to increases in unemployment (not decreases).', 'Answer D is correct.  Stock market investors react favorably when unemployment falls and production grows.  Conversely, bond markets often react favorably when unemployment rises. This is generally because bond investors often anticipate the Federal Reserve to lower interest rates to stimulate economic activity.', ''),
(288, 21, 99, 'Which of the following economic indicators would provide market analysts with information on how consumers feel about the current state of the economy and their current financial situation?', 'Analyst A reviews the Monster Employment Index.', 'Analyst B reviews the Current Conditions Index.', 'Analyst C reviews the Employment Situation Index.', 'Analyst D reviews the Consumer Expectations Index.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  The Monster Employment Index is a measure of employer online recruitment activity.  It is an unemployment indicator that does not measure consumer sentiment.', 'Answer B is correct.  The Current Conditions Index is a consumer sentiment indicator that provides information on consumers’ current financial situation and purchasing plans. The CCI is published by the University of Michigan in conjunction with the Consumer Sentiment Index.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  The Employment Situation Report is a monthly employment report published by the U.S. Department of Labor.  It is not a consumer sentiment indicator (and it is also not an index).', 'Answer D is incorrect.  The Current Expectations Index is a consumer sentiment indicator that provides information on consumers’ expectations for the future of the economy.  It does not provide information on consumers’ attitudes towards the current state of the economy.  Rather, the Current Conditions Index provides this information.', ''),
(289, 21, 99, 'For the following 2 questions, please refer to the facts below: <br /> Tommen is reviewing data on consumers’ saving and spending activities, as presented on the Personal Income and Outlays report. He is particularly interested in analyzing changes in disposable personal income over the past few years.  <br /> <br /> Which of the following sources of income is excluded from the calculation “personal income” on the report?', 'Profits from sale of common stock.', 'Interest income earned on corporate bonds.', 'Rental income received from an apartment complex.', 'Cash dividends received from preferred stock.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct.  Proceeds or profits from any asset sales are not included in the personal income calculation.  This includes the sale of real estate, binds, or stocks.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Interest income paid to consumers on financial assets (such as corporate bonds) in included in the calculation of personal income on the report.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Income on rental properties is not excluded from the calculation of personal income on the report.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Dividend income, including all dividends paid to consumers by corporations, is included in the calculation of personal income on the report.', ''),
(290, 21, 99, 'Which of the following amounts is subtracted from “total personal income” to calculate “disposable personal income” on the report?', 'Royalties income.', 'Income taxes.', 'Personal outlays.', 'Employee benefits.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Royalties received from patents, copyrights, etc. is included in total personal income and is not subtracted when calculating DPI.', 'Answer B is correct.  Disposable personal income (DPI) refers to money that people have available to spend on goods and services.  When calculating this measure, the report subtracts amounts paid for income and property taxes from “total personal income.”', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Personal outlays are not subtracted when calculating DPI. Rather, such amounts are subtracted from personal income on to calculate “personal savings” on the report.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Employee benefits (e.g. pension contributions, healthcare insurance, etc.) are included in total personal income on the report and is not subtracted when calculating DPI.', ''),
(291, 21, 100, '<p>For Questions 1-4, please refer to the facts below.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Loras is analyzing price increases that he has observed for items that he most commonly purchases. In any given month, Loras spends money on 10 pounds of chicken, 25 bottles of beer, and 30 gallons of gasoline.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src="https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-GI8wyr6UDL04cYUAVQyz3qMKMWHcWDCR3jrIO4HVSptVxLqKqpM_2BzPPTIE3uhhYj6gdU-F7hATYatCYocILt5TRUgkY3oEIZR5rAN3WsWkApiEYu2v50UoDBc0sVz0f1fz9Gz" style="height:357px; width:396px" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Based on the information provided, the inflation rate from period 1 to period 2 equals approximately:</p>', '0.0%.', '3.3%.', '4.0%.', '5.0%.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Inflation is a term used to describe a general and ongoing rise in the level of prices in the economy. In this example, the price levels of the items purchased by Loras increases from period 1 to 2. Therefore, the inflation rate would not be 0.0%.', 'Answer B is correct.  From period 1 to 2, the total cost of purchasing the basket of goods increases from $144.25 to $149.00. Therefore, the inflation rate equals ($149.00 – $144.25)/$144.25 = 3.3%.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  This rate represents the relative price increase for beer from period 1 to 2, not the overall inflation rate. Inflation represents price increases of the entire economy (as represented by a basket of goods), not individual items.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Inflation represents price increases of the entire economy (as represented by a basket of goods), not individual items. This rate represents the relative price increase for gasoline from period 1 to 2.', ''),
(292, 21, 100, 'Based on the information provided, the inflation rate from period 2 to period 3 equals approximately:', '1.5%.', '2.0%.', '3.3%.', '5.4%.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  This rate represents the relative price increase for beer from period 2 to 3, not the overall inflation rate.  Inflation represents price increases of the entire economy (as represented by a basket of goods), not individual items.', 'Answer B is correct. From period 2 to 3, the total cost of purchasing the basket of goods increases from $149.00 to $152.00.  Therefore, the inflation rate equals ($152.00 – $149.00)/$149.00 = 2.0%.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  This rate equals the inflation rate for periods 1 to 2, not periods 2 to 3.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  This rate incorrectly equals the cumulative increase in price levels that occurred from period 1 to 3.  The periodic inflation rate for period 2 to 3 equals 2.0%.', ''),
(293, 21, 100, 'Based on the information provided, the inflation rate from period 3 to period 4 equals approximately:', '0.5%.', '2.0%.', '2.5%.', '5.9%.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct.  From period 3 to 4, the total cost of purchasing the basket of goods increases from $152.00 to $152.75.  Therefore, the inflation rate equals ($152.75 – $152.00)/$152.00 = 0.5%.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  This rate equals the inflation rate for periods 2 to 3, not periods 3 to 4.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  This rate incorrectly equals the cumulative increase in price levels that occurred from period 2 to period 4.  The periodic inflation rate for period 3 to 4 equals 0.5%.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  The periodic inflation rate for period 3 to 4 equals 0.5%.  5.9% represents the aggregate increase in price levels that occurred from period 1 to 4.', ''),
(294, 21, 100, 'Based on the periodic inflation rates calculated previously, Loras would most likely conclude that the economy was in a state of ________ during the periods analyzed.', 'Hyperinflation.', 'Deflation.', 'Accelerating inflation.', 'Disinflation.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Hyperinflation occurs when very high and usually accelerating rates of inflation are experienced. Loras has observed decreasing rates of inflation over the periods observed, which is not consistent with hyperinflation.  ', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Deflation is a general decline in prices (or ‘negative inflation’).  The rates of inflation that Loras has observed were declining, but not negative.  Such an observance is referred to as disinflation.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Loras has observed decreasing (not accelerating) rates of inflation over the periods observed.', 'Answer D is correct. Disinflation is a term used to describe instances when the inflation rate has reduced marginally (but has remained positive).  In this example, Loras has observed that the inflation rate has remained positive, but has decreased from 3.3% to 2.0% to 0.5% over time.  Therefore, he would most likely conclude that the economy was in a state of disinflation during periods 1 through 4.', ''),
(295, 21, 100, 'For the following 3 Questions, please refer to the facts below: <br /> A financial planning and analysis (FP&A) team at Braavos Bank is reviewing various measures of inflation when updating its five year earnings forecast. The city of Braavos had recently experienced a natural disaster that resulted in a temporary spike in oil prices. <br /><br />  An inflation measure that excludes volatile economic variables (such as oil prices) would be best described as a:', 'Noncore index.', 'Consumer index.', 'Core index.', 'Monthly index.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  A noncore index (such as CPI or PPI) would not exclude volatile economic variables such as energy and food prices.  ', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Not all consumer indexes exclude volatile economic variables.  Only those identified as “core” indexes exclude such variables.', 'Answer C is correct.  A core inflation index is calculated by taking CPI or PPI and excluding volatile economic variables. In Braavos, a measure of core CPI would not be skewed by its recent temporary spike in oil prices.  Many economists prefer core inflation indexes for this reason.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Not all monthly indexes exclude volatile economic variables.  Only those identified as “core” indexes exclude such variables.', ''),
(296, 21, 100, 'Which of the following inflation measures reviewed by the FP&A team is least likely measured at the wholesale level?', 'Commodity index.', 'Stage-of-processing index.', 'Crude goods index.', 'Consumer price index.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  A commodity index is an example of a PPI and therefore is measured at the wholesale/producer level.  ', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Stage-of-processing indexes measure price levels for the various components of the processing cycle, including crude goods, intermediate goods, and finished goods.  These indexes are accordingly measured at the wholesale level.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  The crude goods index is an example of a stage-of-processing index, which is measured at the wholesale level.  This index includes raw materials that have not been processed.', 'Answer D is correct.  The CPI measures prices at the household level, not the wholesale level.  Conversely, a producer price index (PPI) is a weighted index of prices at the wholesale (or “producer”) level.  ', ''),
(297, 21, 100, 'Assuming that all other economic indicators remain constant, the FP&A team would most likely expect increases in short-term interest rates if which of the following inflation-related conditions is observed?', 'Core CPI has increased significantly.', 'Significant deflation has occurred.', 'Core PPI has decreased significantly.', 'Price levels have remained constant.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct.  The Federal Reserve Bank pays close attention to inflation measures when setting interest rate levels.  If significant increases occur in CPI and PPI, the Fed would most likely raise short-term interest rates to “cool off” the economy in this example.  ', 'Answer B is incorrect.  In this scenario, the Fed would most likely decrease (not increase) interest levels to stimulate the economy if it observed significant deflation occurring.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Significant decreases in core PPI is indicative of deflation. In this scenario, the Fed would most likely decrease (not increase) interest levels to stimulate the economy.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  The Fed would not likely change interest rate levels if inflation remains unchanged.  ', ''),
(298, 21, 100, '<p>Which of the following transactions would most likely occur in a commodity exchange?</p>', 'Investor A purchases foreign currency.', 'Investor B executes an oil futures contract.', 'Investor C purchases shares of Wal-Mart stock.', 'Investor D purchases a long-term corporate bond.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Foreign currency transactions occur in FX markets, not commodity exchanges.  ', 'Answer B is correct.  A commodity exchange is a market where trading in commodities (such as oil, gold, and agriculture products) takes place.  Commodity futures contracts are traded in commodities exchanges.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Shares of Wal-Mart stock are traded in the stock market, not in commodity exchanges.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Corporate bonds are purchased in bond markets, not in commodity exchanges.  ', ''),
(299, 21, 100, '<p>Shireen is drafting a report on improvements that have been made in labor productivity in a number of developing countries. She notes that the country of Riverrun has reduced its per-unit fixed costs by producing higher quantities of its goods, which has increased its economic growth at a higher rate than the other countries. This labor productivity factor is referred to as:</p>', 'Accumulated knowledge.', 'Economies of scale.', 'Human capital.', 'Technological change.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Accumulated knowledge is a component of human capital, not economies of scale.  It is unrelated to reducing per-unit costs by producing higher quantities', 'Answer B is correct.  The term ‘economies of scale’ refers to the cost advantage that arises with increased output of a product. It arises from the inverse relationship between the quantity produced and per-unit fixed costs.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Human capital refers to accumulated knowledge, skills, and expertise that the average worker in an economy possesses.  Although this concept is a labor productivity factor, it is unrelated to reducing per-unit costs by producing higher quantities.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Technological change improves labor productivity through invention (i.e. advances in knowledge) and innovation (i.e. using new inventions to improve productivity). It is unrelated to the cost advantage that arises with increased output of a product.', ''),
(300, 21, 100, '<p>Earlier this morning, financial news networks announced the release of the Productivity and Costs Report. The networks noted that the report indicated that per-unit labor costs had significantly increased, which resulted in higher inflation levels. Based solely on this information, bond yields would most likely ________ and stock prices would most likely ________.</p>', 'Decrease; increase.', 'Decrease; decrease.', 'Increase; increase.', 'Increase; decrease.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Higher inflation levels normally increase (not decrease) bond yields and decrease (not increase) stock prices.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Higher inflation levels normally increase (not decrease) bond yields, as the Federal Reserve will often increase interest rates to “cool off” the economy.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Higher inflation levels normally decrease (not increase) stock prices. This is because high inflation often results in higher interest rates and lower economic growth, both of which negatively impact stock prices.', 'Answer D is correct.  Inflationary increases in labor costs such as those noted in this example would likely result in higher bond yields and lower stock prices.  When inflation levels are elevated, the Federal Reserve will often increase interest rates to “cool off” the economy.', ''),
(301, 21, 101, '<p>For Questions 1-4, please refer to the facts below:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An economist at Pentos, Inc. is drafting how white paper on industrial production and its impact on the overall economy. &nbsp;While performing her research, the economist reviewed the most prevalent economic indicators related to industrial production, including the Fed&rsquo;s Industrial Production and Capacity Utilization report.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Which of the following measures would the economist most likely find in the Fed&rsquo;s industrial production data series?</strong></p>', 'Volume of consumer goods produced.', 'Standard industry operating hours.', 'Investments in new production equipment.', 'Prices of business goods produced.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. The industrial production (IP) series differs from most other economic indicators in one important respect. It measures only changes in the volume of goods produced, without taking into account the prices of these products and the distorting effects of inflation.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Standard industry operating hours are not reported in the industrial production data series presented by the Fed.  Rather, this information is used to define “full capacity” when calculating the capacity utilization rate.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  The industrial production series measures changes in the volume of goods produced.  It does not present data on business investment.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  The industrial production series measures changes in the volume of goods produced, not changes in the prices of those goods.', ''),
(302, 21, 101, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements would the economist least likely include in her white paper regarding the usefulness of the capacity utilization rate?</strong></p>', 'The rate is a leading economic indicator of business spending.', 'The rate can be used to identify underutilized industries.', 'The rate reflects the strength and elasticity of the industrial sector.', 'The rate is a precise measurement that is simple to calculate.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  The capacity utilization rate is a leading economic indicator, as it can predict future business investment based on how well utilized the industrial sector is today.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  The capacity utilization rate is useful to understand how underutilized manufacturers, utilities, and the mining sectors are in the event that more output is needed in the future.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  The capacity utilization rate is a good indicator of the strength and flexibility of the industrial sector.', 'Answer D is correct.  The capacity utilization rate is a complex measurement that is impossible to calculate precisely.  This complexity results from the difficulty in defining “full capacity”, as well as other factors such as foreign production, mergers and acquisitions, and new business investment.', ''),
(303, 21, 101, '<p><strong>The new orders data included in the Durable Goods Orders report is an example of a _________ indicator, while the shipments data is an example of a _________ indicator.</strong></p>', 'Lagging; leading.', 'Leading; coincident.', 'Lagging; coincident.', 'Coincident; leading.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  The new orders data is not a lagging indicator, as it provides an indication of future (not past) factory production.  Also, the shipments data is considered a coincident (not leading) indicator.', 'Answer B is correct.  The new orders data is considered a good leading indicator, as increases in new orders indicate that factories will be productive in the future.  Shipments data are considered a coincident indicator, as they provide an indication of current goods production by measuring the quantity of goods being shipped to customers at a specific point in time.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  The new orders data is not a lagging indicator, as it provides an indication of future (not past) factory production.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  New orders data indicates how busy factories will be in the future, and therefore is considered a leading (not coincident) economic indicator.  On the other hand, shipments data indicate current factory production and is therefore considered a coincident indicator.', ''),
(304, 21, 101, '<p><strong>Which of the following economic indicators reviewed by the economist generally has the most impact on the U.S. economy when released?</strong></p>', 'Durable goods orders.', 'Industrial production.', 'Factory orders.', 'Capacity utilization.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct.  The advance report on durable goods is the earliest and most prevalent indicator of industrial production.  Its release will often impact financial markets more than any other industrial production and manufacturer.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Although the Fed’s report on industrial production is an important indicator, it does not often impact financial markets significantly.  This is because market participants can often anticipate changes in production using other data.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  The Factory Orders report is released behind the Durable Goods Order report and presents similar data.  Therefore, financial markets rarely react significantly to this report.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  As with industrial production, the Fed’s capacity utilization data are an important economic indicator. However, these measurements are viewed as imprecise and therefore do not impact financial markets as significantly as durable goods orders.', ''),
(305, 21, 101, '<p>For the following 6 Questions, please refer to the facts below:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Tormund is a financial analyst preparing a report on the state of the housing market. While performing his research, he notes that consensus forecasts indicate that interest rate levels will be volatile in the future as the Federal Reserve moves to fight inflation. Tormund reviews a number of prominent economic releases on the housing market while preparing his report.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Which of the following statements would Tormund most likely include in his report regarding a potential increase in interest rates?</strong></p>', 'Changes in interest rate levels have no impact on the housing market.', 'An increase in interest rates would result in driving the demand for housing downward.', 'An increase in interest rates would result in lower unemployment in the construction industry.', 'An increase in interest rates would reduce borrowing costs for home builders.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  The housing market is very sensitive to changes in interest rates, which is why it is considered a very effective economic indicator.', 'Answer B is correct.  The housing market is very sensitive to changes in interest rates. An increase in interest rates normally results in lower demand for housing, as the cost of borrowing to purchase a home increases.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Increases in interest rates would likely result in higher (not lower) unemployment in the construction industry, as the lower demand for houses would reduce the need for skilled construction workers.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  An increase in interest rates would increase (not decrease) borrowing costs for both home builders and home purchasers.', ''),
(306, 21, 101, '<p><strong>An increase in which of the following would most likely result in stronger demand in the housing market?</strong></p>', 'Unemployment rates.', 'Interest rates.', 'Divorce rates.', 'Income tax rates.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Higher unemployment rates are indicative of weak economic growth, which normally results in weaker demand for housing.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  An increase in interest rates normally results in lower demand for housing, as the cost of borrowing to purchase a home increases.', 'Answer C is correct.  Higher divorce rates often result in higher demand in the housing market.  Marriage, divorce, and other life events create new households, which in turn increase the demand for new housing.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Higher income tax rates reduce the spending power of consumers, which hurts economic growth and the demand for housing.', ''),
(307, 21, 101, '<p><strong>A decrease in which of the following would most likely result in stronger demand in the housing market?</strong></p>', 'Mortgage interest deduction limits.', 'Economic growth rates.', 'Natural disasters.', 'Unemployment rates.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Any change in U.S. tax policy that reduces the deductibility of mortgage interest would likely reduce residential construction.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Weak economic growth normally results in weaker demand for housing, as consumers become reluctant to make large purchases and/or borrow.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Natural disasters often increase the demand for new housing as older houses are summarily destroyed.', 'Answer D is correct.  Lower unemployment rates are indicative of stronger economic growth.  This normally results in stronger demand for housing, as consumers become less wary of taking on new (or larger) mortgages.', ''),
(308, 21, 101, '<p><strong>Which of the following observations noted by Tormund would least likely impact the demand for wood through the so-called &lsquo;multiplier effect&rsquo;?</strong></p>', 'An increase in existing home sales.', 'A decrease in housing starts.', 'An increase in housing permits.', 'A decrease in new residential construction projects.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. The multiplier effect is a term used to describe the impact that the housing market has on the rest of the economy.  Existing home sales do not involve the construction of new homes; and therefore, would likely have the least effect on the demand for wood.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Decreases in housing starts have a negative impact on the wood industry and other areas of the economy, which is why it closely monitored by economists and analysts.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Increases in housing permits are indicative of new construction, which would likely increase the demand for wood.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  A decrease in new residential construction projects would decrease the demand for wood and other construction projects.', ''),
(309, 21, 101, '<p><strong>Which of the following housing projects would most likely be classified by the Census Bureau as a &ldquo;housing start&quot;?</strong></p>', 'Project A involves replacing the roof of an existing residence.', 'Project B involves the construction of a new mobile home.', 'Project C involves building a new home on an existing foundation.', 'Project D involves building a new dormitory for a local university.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Replacing a roof on an existing residence would not be reported as a ‘housing start’ in the Census Bureau’s report.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Housing start figures do not include construction of mobile homes.', 'Answer C is correct.  The Census Bureau’s housing starts report presents how much new groundbreaking occurred for residential real estate in a given month. All new homes built on an existing foundation would be included in this data as a ‘housing start’.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Housing start figures do not include construction of dormitories.', '');
INSERT INTO `chapter_review_questions` (`rev_ques_id`, `course_id`, `chapter_id`, `rev_ques_title`, `rev_ques_ans_1`, `rev_ques_ans_2`, `rev_ques_ans_3`, `rev_ques_ans_4`, `rev_ques_ans_5`, `rev_correct_ans_id`, `rev_correct_ans_text`, `rev_wronge_ans_text`, `rev_ques_status`, `ans1_text`, `ans2_text`, `ans3_text`, `ans4_text`, `ans5_text`) VALUES
(310, 21, 101, '<p><strong>Which of the following events would most likely provide the earliest indication of new residential construction activity?</strong></p>', 'Builder A sets the foundation for a new single family home.', 'Builder B completes the construction of a housing unit.', 'Builder C files for a building permit with a local government agency.', 'Builder D finalizes the sale of a newly constructed home.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  A housing start generally occurs when excavation begins to set a new foundation for a residence.  However, housing permits must often be obtained before the construction begins, which makes them the earliest indicator of construction activity.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Filing for a building permit generally occurs well before construction has been completed.', 'Answer C is correct.  Housing permits represent written authorization to begin construction.  Home builders must file for permits in advance, and therefore housing permits data often provide the earliest indications of strength or weakness in the housing market.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  The sale of a newly constructed home is generally the final (not earliest) indication of new residential construction activity.', ''),
(311, 21, 102, '<p>For the following 2 Questions, please refer to the facts below:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An economist is preparing a report on two countries (Winterfell and Highgarden) that heavily engage in international trade. The following import and export data for the two countries have been collected for the year ending December 31, 201X: ($ in billions)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Country &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Exports &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Imports &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Difference</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Winterfell &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$750 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$650 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $100</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Highgarden &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;$585 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $710 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; ($125)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The difference between each country&rsquo;s exports and imports is commonly referred to as:</strong></p>', 'Comparative advantage.', 'International trade.', 'Absolute advantage.', 'Balance of trade.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Comparative advantage is not a term that refers to the difference between a country’s exports and its imports. Rather, it applies when a country can produce one good at a lower opportunity cost than another good.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  International trade includes both the exporting and importing of goods in the global market. The difference between exports and imports is referred to as the balance of trade.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  A country has an absolute advantage in a product if it can produce that good using fewer resources than another country.  The term does not refer to the difference between a country’s exports and its imports.', 'Answer D is correct.  An export is any product that is sold to the global market, while an import is any product that is purchased from the global market.  The balance of trade represents the difference between a country’s exports and imports.', ''),
(312, 21, 102, '<p><strong>Based on the information provided above, the economist would most likely report that Winterfell&rsquo;s economy has a __________, while Highgarden&rsquo;s economy has a __________.</strong></p>', 'Trade deficit; trade surplus.', 'Trade deficit; trade deficit.', 'Trade surplus; trade surplus.', 'Trade surplus; trade deficit.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Winterfell’s economy has a trade surplus (not a trade deficit) because its exports exceed its imports. Highgarden’s economy has a trade deficit (not a trade surplus) because its imports exceed its exports.', 'Answer B is incorrect.  Winterfell’s economy has a trade surplus (not a trade deficit) because its exports exceed its imports by $100 billion.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Highgarden’s economy has a trade deficit (not a trade surplus) because its imports exceed its exports by $125 billion.', 'Answer D is correct.  If a country’s exports exceed its imports, the economy is said to have a trade surplus.  If imports exceed exports, the economy is said to have a trade deficit.  Winterfell’s economy has a trade surplus because its exports exceed its imports by $100 billion.  Highgarden’s economy has a trade deficit because its imports exceed its exports by $125 billion.', ''),
(313, 21, 102, '<p>Assume that Winterfell and Highgarden each produce two homogeneous products (oil and wheat). The only resource available in both countries to produce these products is labor hours. The hours required to produce these goods are presented below:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u><strong>Country &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Oil (per barrel) &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Wheat (per bushel)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Winterfell &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2 hours &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;4 hours</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Highgarden &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;1 hour &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;3 hours</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Based on the information provided above, _________ has an absolute advantage in the production of oil, while __________ has an absolute advantage in the production of wheat.</strong></p>', 'Winterfell; Winterfell.', 'Highgarden; Highgarden.', 'Winterfell; Highgarden.', 'Highgarden; Winterfell.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Highgarden (not Winterfell) has an absolute advantage in producing oil because it can produce a barrel in less time.', 'Answer B is correct.  A country has an absolute advantage in producing a good over another country if it uses fewer resources to produce that good.  In this example, Highgarden has an absolute advantage in producing oil because it can produce a barrel in less time than Winterfell (1 hour vs. 2 hours).  Highgarden also has an absolute advantage in producing wheat because it can produce a bushel in less time than Winterfell (3 hours vs. 4 hours).', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Winterfell does not have an absolute advantage in the production of oil because they require more resources to produce a barrel than Highgarden.  Similarly, Highgarden does not have an absolute advantage in the production of wheat because they require more resources to produce a bushel than Winterfell.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Highgarden does not have an absolute advantage in the production of wheat because they require 2 more labor hours to produce a bushel than Winterfell.', ''),
(314, 21, 102, '<p>Based on the information provided above, _________ has a comparative advantage in the production of oil, while _________ has a comparative advantage in the production of wheat.</p>', 'Winterfell; Winterfell.', 'Highgarden; Winterfell.', 'Winterfell; Highgarden.', 'Highgarden; Highgarden.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Winterfell does not have a comparative advantage in the production of oil, as its opportunity cost for producing one barrel (1/2 a bushel of wheat) is higher than that of Highgarden (1/3 a bushel).', 'Answer B is correct.  Highgarden has a comparative advantage in the production of oil because its opportunity cost for producing one barrel equals 1/3 a bushel of wheat, which is lower than Winterfell’s opportunity cost (1/2 a bushel).  Winterfell has a comparative advantage in the production of wheat because its opportunity cost for producing one bushel equals 2 barrels of oil, which is lower than Highgarden’s opportunity cost (3 barrels).', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Winterfell does not have a comparative advantage in the production of oil, as its opportunity cost for producing one barrel (1/2 a bushel of wheat) is higher than that of Highgarden (1/3 a bushel).  Highgarden does not have a comparative advantage in the production of wheat.  This is because its opportunity cost for producing one bushel (3 barrels of oil) is higher than that of Winterfell (2 barrels of oil).', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Although Highgarden has the absolute advantage in producing wheat, it does not have a comparative advantage.  This is because its opportunity cost for producing one bushel (3 barrels of oil) is higher than that of Winterfell (2 barrels of oil).', ''),
(315, 21, 102, '<p><strong>Which of the following economic policies would least likely result in gains from trade?</strong></p>', 'Country A decreases tariffs on imported goods.', 'Country B specializes in the production of electronic consumer goods.', 'Country C utilizes its abundant farmland to produce food.', 'Country D restricts the sale of foreign-produced goods.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  Tariffs are used to restrict trade, and therefore decreasing tariffs would likely result in gains from trade.', 'Answer B is correct.  Specialization occurs when countries shift their resources to focus on producing a good that offers a comparative advantage.  Country B would likely experience gains from trade by specializing in the production of electronic consumer goods then trading these goods in the foreign market.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Specialization and gains from trade occur when countries utilize their unique natural resources to produce goods and trade those goods in the global market. Therefore, Country C would likely experience gains from trade by using their abundant farm land to produce food and trade the food in the global market.', 'Answer D is correct. “Gains from trade” is an economic concept that refers to the net benefits that countries experience as a result of facilitating foreign trade.  Country D would not experience gains from trade if it restricted the sale of foreign-produced goods through tariffs or other means.', ''),
(316, 21, 102, '<p><strong>An economist at Lannister Corp. is drafting a white paper on international trade. While performing his research, the economist reviewed the most prevalent economic indicators related to international trade. The economist would most likely review the International Trade in Goods and Services for data on which of the following?</strong></p>', 'Imports and exports.', 'Foreign exchange rates.', 'Foreign GDP measures.', 'Tariffs.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct.  The International Trade in Goods and Services report tracks the value of all imports and exports.  This report is produced by the Bureau of Economic Analysis on a monthly basis.', 'Answer B is correct.  A foreign exchange rate is price for a country’s currency in terms of another currency.  The International Trade in Goods and Services report provides information on imports and exports, not foreign exchange rates.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  The International Trade in Goods and Services report presents information on imports and exports.  It does not report on gross domestic product measures for foreign countries.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Tariffs represent taxes on imported goods and services.  Tariffs are not reported in the International Trade in Goods and Services report.', ''),
(317, 21, 102, '<p>The following is a summary of imports and exports for King&rsquo;s Landing: (amounts in billion)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src="https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/cB4J72olu_9_Of9p4w81u1rwb4O7N42rpxW2TXAdXlBzS1a3_LkWsefqwu6UHutRSRNSZW5AjU0vb0OAPefjak6xw2WXvpt2M2GC86hH4vFTSygdzpNu1fHLrFI6bAfzm9lFwMgc" style="height:155px; width:343px" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Based on the information provided, the merchandise trade balance for King&rsquo;s Landing equals:</strong></p>', '($150).', '($30).', '$60.', '$85.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct.  The merchandise trade balance represents the difference between imports and exports of physical goods. The merchandise trade balance for King’s Landing equals its $450 exports minus its $600 imports = ($150).', 'Answer B is incorrect.  ($30) incorrectly represents the difference between all imports and exports for King’s Landing. The merchandise trade balance is limited to imports and exports of goods.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  This amount represents the net export of income payments (not the merchandise trade balance).', '', ''),
(318, 21, 102, '<p><strong>Based on the information provided, the current account balance for King&rsquo;s Landing equals?</strong></p>', '($150).', '($30).', '$60.', '$85.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect.  This amount represents the merchandise trade balance, which is limited to the difference between imports and exports of physical goods.  The current account balance includes all imports and exports.', 'Answer B is correct.  The current account balance is the difference between all imports and exports.  The current account balance for King’s Landing equals $785 exports minus $815 imports = ($30).', 'Answer C is incorrect.  This amount represents the net export of income payments (not the current account balance).', 'Answer D is incorrect.  This amount represents the net export of services from King’s Landing. The current account balance represents the difference between all imports and all exports.', ''),
(319, 21, 102, '<p><strong>Which of the following cash transfers would most likely be classified as a unilateral transfer on the Summary of International Transactions report?</strong></p>', 'A U.S. accounting firm receives payment from a European client.', 'The U.S. government provides foreign aid to Haiti following a natural disaster.', 'A U.S. retailer purchases video game consoles from Japan.', 'A U.S. investor receives a dividend payment from a Canadian company.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. International payments received for accounting services performed would be reported as part of the Services Trade Account, not as a unilateral transfer.', 'Answer B is correct.  Unilateral transfers represent one-way transfers of foreign aid, government grants, and similar transfers to foreign countries.  Foreign aid provided to Haiti following a natural disaster would be reported as a unilateral transfer in the Summary of International Transactions Report.', 'Answer C is incorrect.  Payments to foreign countries for goods would be reported in the Merchandise Trade Account, not as a unilateral transfer.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Dividend payments and other similar investment cash flows from foreign countries would be reported in the Income Account, not as a unilateral transfer.', ''),
(320, 32, 103, '<p><strong>Which of the following is a synonym for &ldquo;ethics&rdquo;?</strong></p>', 'Moral practice', 'Social values', 'Decency', 'All of the above', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Moral practice is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. Social values is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. Decency is not the best answer.', 'Correct. All of the above answers are synonyms for “ethics.”', ''),
(321, 32, 103, '<p><strong>Which of the following best completes the sentence? A member who departs from Rulings in similar circumstances:</strong></p>', 'Will be requested to justify the departure.', 'Is still ethical since these are not principles, but only rulings.', 'Is not considered ethical, but because of the circumstances does not have to justify it.', 'Is still ethical since rulings are only guidelines.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct.  A member that departs from a “Ruling” has to defend that position or be found guilty of violating the Code of Professional Ethics.', 'Incorrect.  Rulings are an official part of the Code of Professional Ethics.', 'Incorrect. Rulings summarize the application of Rules of Conduct', 'Incorrect Interpretations to a particular set of factual circumstances.', ''),
(322, 32, 103, '<p><strong>A member of the AICPA is responsible to which of the following groups?</strong></p>', 'The state society to which the member belongs.', 'The appropriate state board of accountancy.', 'The AICPA ethics division.', 'All of the above.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The state society to which the member belongs is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. The appropriate state board of accountancy is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. The AICPA ethics division is not the best answer.', 'Correct. All of the answers above are appropriate.', ''),
(323, 32, 103, '<p><strong>Which of the following words is NOT a synonym of &ldquo;ethical&rdquo;?</strong></p>', 'Honest', 'Conscientious', 'Moral', 'Humane', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Honest is being ethical.', 'Incorrect. Being Conscientious is being ethical.', 'Correct. Moral may be ethical or not.  The Mafia has their “moral code” which society does not consider ethical.', 'Incorrect. Being Humane is being ethical.', ''),
(324, 32, 103, '<p><strong>&nbsp;The sections of the Code consist of _________ and _________:</strong></p>', 'Principles and Standards.', 'Rules and Standards.', 'Principles and Rules.', 'Rules, Principles and Standards.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Standards are not one of the sections.', 'Incorrect.  Principles must be one of the sections.', 'Correct. The two sections are Principles and Rules.', 'Incorrect. Standards are a subset of the Rules, not one of the sections.', ''),
(325, 32, 103, '<p><strong>&nbsp;A Covered Member is:</strong></p>', 'An individual on the attest engagement team.', 'A Partner in an office in the same state.', 'An individual in a position to influence the attest engagement.', 'The firm, including the firm&#039;s employee benefit plans.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. An individual on the attest engagement team is a Covered Member.', 'Correct. A Partner in an office in the same state is not necessarily a covered member.  Other attributes must be present.', 'Incorrect. An individual in a position to influence the attest engagement is a Covered Member.', 'Incorrect. The firm, including the firm''s employee benefit plans, is a Covered Member.', ''),
(326, 32, 103, '<p><strong>A member should consult, in addition to the Code of Professional Ethics, if applicable, the ethical standards of:</strong></p>', 'The state society to which the member belongs.', 'The appropriate state board of accountancy.', 'The AICPA ethics division.', 'All of the above.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The state society to which the member belongs is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. The appropriate state board of accountancy is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. The AICPA ethics division is not the best answer.', 'Correct. All of the above answers are appropriate.', ''),
(327, 32, 104, '<p><strong>Which one of the following definitions is NOT correct?</strong></p>', 'Council: the Council of the AICPA.', 'Member: a member, associate member, or international associate of the AICPA.', 'Professional services: all services performed by a member while performing public accounting services.', 'Institute: the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Council is properly defined as  “The Council of the AICPA.”', 'Incorrect.  Member is properly defined as “A member, associate member, or international associate of the AICPA.”', 'Correct. Professional services include all services performed by a member while holding out as a CPA, not just while performing public accounting services.', 'Institute is properly defined as “The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants.”', ''),
(328, 32, 104, '<p><strong>&nbsp;Which of the following items completes the following sentence? Independence in Fact:</strong></p>', 'involves impartiality.', 'indicates that the member has abstained from relationships that appear to prevent objectivity.', 'is a state of mind.', 'involves freedom from conflicts of interest.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Impartiality is connected with objectivity.', 'Incorrect. Independence in appearance, not fact, involves actions such as abstaining from relationships.', 'Correct.  Independence, in fact is attitudinal, that is, a state of mind. Independence in  appearance involves actions.', 'Incorrect. Objectivity involves actions such as freedom from conflicts of interest.', ''),
(329, 32, 104, '<p><strong>The unique characteristics of the accounting profession that set it apart from the rest of society is its acceptance of its responsibility to:</strong></p>', 'Its clients.', 'The government and its agencies.', 'The public.', 'Investors.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. A profession is responsible to its clients, but this is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. A profession is responsible to certain government agencies at times, but this is not the best answer.', 'Correct.  A profession is responsible to its public, which is unique.', 'Incorrect. A profession is responsible to investors sometimes, but this is not the best answer.', ''),
(330, 32, 104, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements is</strong><strong> NOT </strong><strong>correct?&nbsp; A Key position is a position in which an individual:&nbsp;</strong></p>', 'Has primary responsibility for significant accounting functions that support material components of the financial statements.', 'Has responsibility for the sales force.', 'Has primary responsibility for the preparation of the financial statements.', 'Has the ability to exercise influence over the contents of the financial statements, including when the individual is a member of the board of directors.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Having primary responsibility for significant accounting functions that support material components of the financial statements gives the possibility of adversely affecting the financial statements and they are therefore in a key position.', 'Correct. Having responsibility for the sales force does NOT allow the person to impact adversely the financial statements.', 'Incorrect.  Primary responsibility for the preparation of the financial statements allows the individual to adversely impact the financial statements and makes them in a key position.', 'Incorrect. The ability to exercise influence over the contents of the financial statements in any capacity is a key position.', ''),
(331, 32, 104, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements is the BEST answer?&nbsp; &ldquo;All sections of society are recipients &hellip; of the work of the profession. Society includes:</strong></p>', 'Clients & credit grantors', 'Governments', 'Employers & investors', 'All of the above', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Clients & credit grantors are most definitely a part of society; however, this is not the BEST answer.', 'Incorrect.  Governments are most definitely a part of society; however, this is not the BEST answer.', 'Incorrect. Employers & investors are most definitely a part of society; however, this is not the BEST answer.', 'Correct. All of the above are a part of Society', ''),
(332, 32, 105, '<p><strong>&nbsp;In which of the following situations would a CPA be considered independent?</strong></p>', 'The CPA was the temporary staff training instructor during the initial portion 		of the period.', 'The CPA had or was committed to acquire a small direct interest in the client.', 'The CPA had or was committed to acquire a large but indirect interest in the client.', 'The CPA was the controller for the firm during the initial portion of the period.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. The position of staff training instructor does not require decision making or indicate financial interest, which would cause the CPA to not be independent.', 'Incorrect. Acquisition of a small direct interest is specifically stated as one of the situations where the CPA is not considered to be independent.', 'Incorrect. Acquisition of a large but indirect interest in the client is specifically stated as one of the situations where the CPA is not considered to be independent.', 'Incorrect. The position of controller involves decision-making, which is specifically prohibited and affects independence.', ''),
(333, 32, 105, '<p><strong>A member who performs auditing, review, compilation, consulting, tax, or other professional services shall comply with only:</strong></p>', 'All applicable standards promulgated by bodies designated by Council.', 'The Code of Professional Ethics.', 'Generally Accepted Accounting Principles.', 'Internal Auditing Standards.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. Members have to comply with the standards set for the particular service performed.', 'Incorrect. Members have to comply with more than the Code.', 'Incorrect. Members have to comply with more than Generally Accepted Accounting Principles.', 'Incorrect. Internal Auditors are the only ones required to comply with Internal Auditing Standards.', ''),
(334, 32, 105, '<p><strong>Which one of the following professionals does not have a privileged information status with their client?&nbsp;</strong></p>', 'Medical doctors.', 'Certified public accountants.', 'Attorneys.', 'Religious ministers.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. A medical doctor has the privilege under our laws so that they may treat patients psychologically as well as physically.', 'Correct. For the most part, CPAs cannot disclose confidential information, but they are not protected by law or given privileged information status exempting them from being required to do so.', 'Incorrect. In order to be an advocate for their client, attorneys have the right to not disclose communications with them.', 'Incorrect. In order to  minister adequately and appropriately to members or parishioners, ministers of religious orders have privilege.', ''),
(335, 32, 105, '<p><strong>What kind of working papers may a client request, and have a right to receive from its auditor?</strong></p>', 'Analysis and comments on management’s strengths and weaknesses.', 'Papers that contain support for a client’s journal entries and that the client does not have a copy of.', 'Auditor’s comments and conclusions concerning materiality.', 'Both a & c.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Analyses of and comments on management’s strengths and weaknesses are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client.', 'Correct. Sole support for any part of the financial statements is the basis for the client having a right to the auditor’s working papers.', 'Incorrect. Auditor’s comments and conclusions concerning materiality are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client.', 'Incorrect. Analyses of and comments on management’s strengths and weaknesses are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client and auditor’s comments and conclusions concerning materiality are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client.', ''),
(336, 32, 105, '<p><strong>Which one of the following groups does NOT require disclosure of commissions or anticipated commissions?</strong></p>', 'To the AICPA Ethics Division.', 'To those members in public practice who do not perform an audit or review, examination of prospective statements, or compilation when independent.', 'To the client.', 'The State Board of the state in which the professional is practicing in.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. No disclosure is required to the AICPA.', 'Incorrect.  A member in public practice who do not perform an audit or review, examination of prospective statements, or compilation when independent is required and is not an exception to the rules.', 'Incorrect.  A professional is always required to disclose to their client.', 'Incorrect. A professional is not required to disclose commissions or anticipated commissions to the Board of the State in which they practice.', ''),
(337, 32, 105, '<p><strong>Which of the following is NOT an Exception to client confidentiality rules:</strong></p>', 'A member must comply with a valid subpoena of a court.', 'A member must allow review by an appropriate AICPA or state CPA society.', 'A member may initiate a complaint or respond to one of a recognized investigative body.', 'A clients name is considered non-confidential information and therefore may be revealed.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  A CPA must comply to a valid court subpoena since they do not have privileged information protection.', 'Incorrect. In order for appropriate bodies to fulfill their functions, the CPA must allow them access to files.', 'Incorrect. Initiating a complaint is a right of the member and they must respond to any proper investigative body.', 'Correct. A client’s name IS confidential and may not be revealed without their consent.', ''),
(338, 32, 106, '<p><strong>A CPA borrows $12,000 from a client for the purchase of a car and makes a $4,000 down payment. The rate and terms are the same as those that other car buyers in a similar situation would receive. A loan from the client to the CPA would:</strong></p>', 'Produce a permitted loan.', 'Affect independence.', 'Not produce a permitted loan since the CPA would be independent.', 'Not produce a permitted loan since the CPA would not be independent.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. This loan meets all the criteria for a permitted loan.', 'Incorrect. This loan would not affect independence since the terms are the same as those for other car buyers.', 'Incorrect. This loan has the same criteria applicable to the public.', 'Incorrect. Since the terms are the same as those for other car buyers, independence would not be impaired.', ''),
(339, 32, 106, '<p><strong>The attest engagement team includes all of the following except:</strong></p>', 'The proprietor who participates in the acceptance or performance of the attest engagement.', 'The partners who participate in the acceptance or performance of the attest engagement.', 'Full- or part-time professional staff in another office of the same firm in the same state who did not participate in the attest engagement.', 'The shareholders who participate in the acceptance or performance of the attest engagement.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The proprietor has to remain independent in order to participate in the performance of the attest engagement.', 'Incorrect. The partners have to remain independent in order to participate in the performance of the attest engagement.', 'Correct. These staff members would not be required to be independent since they had nothing to do with the attest engagement and were not in the same office.', 'Incorrect. The shareholders have to remain independent in order to participate in the performance of the attest engagement.', ''),
(340, 32, 106, '<p><strong>Upon determining that a supervisor&rsquo;s recommendation for treatment of financial information could result in a material misstatement, the first step in the CPA&rsquo;s ethical obligation is to:</strong></p>', 'Quit to avoid ethical violations.', 'Communicate concerns to the external accountant and all regulatory agencies that may be involved.', 'Report the disagreement to the supervisor’s supervisor.', 'Do sufficient research and consultation to determine if the supervisor is correct.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. This is the third step.', 'Incorrect. This is the fourth step.', 'Incorrect. This is the second step.', 'Correct. Determining if the supervisor is correct is the first step of a CPA’s ethical obligation in a matter of disagreement with a supervisor.', ''),
(341, 32, 106, '<p><strong>&nbsp;When is a contingent fee or commission deemed to be received?</strong></p>', 'When money for services is first received.', 'When services have been performed and the fee or commission is determined.', 'When a client agrees to have a member perform a service for the client.', 'When an initial sales contact is made with a client.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The receipt of money for the first time is not the first time the fee could be deemed received.', 'Correct. When the fee or commission can be determined is the time it is deemed received.', 'Incorrect. This is not the best time to consider a fee to be received.', 'Incorrect. A fee has not yet been earned.', ''),
(342, 32, 106, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements is FALSE?&nbsp; When an Attest Function CPA performs &ldquo;Other Services&rdquo; the client must be in a position to have an informed judgment on the results of the other services and that the client understands its responsibility to:</strong></p>', 'Designate a staff member to be responsible for overseeing the services being provided.', 'Evaluate the adequacy of the services performed and any findings that result.', 'Make management decisions, including accepting responsibility for the results of the other services.', 'Establish and maintain internal controls, including monitoring ongoing activities.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. The company must designate a Management-level individual to be responsible for overseeing the services being provided, not a staff person.', 'Incorrect. The client is responsible for evaluating the adequacy of the services performed and any findings that result.', 'Incorrect. The client is responsible for making management decisions, including accepting responsibility for the results of the other services.', 'Incorrect. The client is responsible for establishing and maintaining internal controls, including monitoring ongoing activities.', ''),
(343, 32, 106, '<p><strong>Which of the following new loans to be obtained from a financial institution client where independence is required is NOT an &ldquo;Other Permitted Loan&rdquo;?</strong></p>', 'Automobile loans and leases collateralized by the automobile.', 'Loans fully collateralized by the cash surrender value of an insurance policy.', 'Loans partially collateralized by cash deposits at the same financial institution.', 'Credit cards where the aggregate outstanding balance on the current statement is reduced to $5,000 or less by the payment due date.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Collateralized automobile loans are permitted.', 'Incorrect. Fully collateralized loans by an insurance policy are permitted.', 'Correct. Partially collateralized loans are not permitted, no matter the collateral.', 'Incorrect. Credit cards of $5,000 or less are permitted.', ''),
(344, 32, 107, '<p><strong>A member shall be considered to have Properly represented facts according to rule 102 when she knowingly:</strong></p>', 'Makes materially misleading entries in an entity''s financial statements.', 'Fails to correct an entity''s financial statements or records that are materially false when she has the authority to record an entry.', 'Determines that the information presented is not materially misleading.', 'Permits another to sign a document containing materially misleading information.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Material misleading entries, when known violate the Integrity and Objectivity rules.', 'Incorrect. Failing to correct material false statements, when known, violate the Integrity and Objectivity rules.', 'Correct. If the information presented is not materially misstated then no rules have been violated.', 'Incorrect. Permitting another to sign a materially misleading document is the same as if you had signed the document.', ''),
(345, 32, 107, '<p><strong>A member shall be considered to have Properly represented facts according to rule 102 when she knowingly:</strong></p>', 'Makes materially misleading entries in an entity''s financial statements.', 'Fails to correct an entity''s financial statements or records that are materially false when she has the authority to record an entry.', 'Determines that the information presented is not materially misleading.', 'Permits another to sign a document containing materially misleading information.', '', '3', '', '', 'Deleted', 'Incorrect. Material misleading entries, when known violate the Integrity and Objectivity rules.', 'Incorrect. Failing to correct material false statements, when known, violate the Integrity and Objectivity rules.', 'Correct. If the information presented is not materially misstated then no rules have been violated.', 'Incorrect. Permitting another to sign a materially misleading document is the same as if you had signed the document.', ''),
(346, 32, 107, '<p><strong>Which of the following members must remain objective and avoid any aspects of conflicts of interest?</strong></p>', 'Those who prepare financial statements.', 'Those who perform audits.', 'Those who prepare tax returns.', 'All of the above.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Those who prepare financial statements must avoid conflicts of interest, but this is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. Those who perform audits must avoid conflicts of interest, but this is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. Those who prepare tax returns must avoid conflicts of interest, but this is not the best answer.', 'Correct.  All of the above answers are appropriate.', ''),
(347, 32, 107, '<p><strong>Concerning Corporate Finance&mdash;consulting or advisory services &ndash; Independence Would be impaired if the CPA:</strong></p>', 'Commits the client to the terms of a transaction on behalf of the client.', 'Assists in developing corporate strategies.', 'Assists in identifying possible sources of capital that meet the client''s specifications or criteria.', 'Assists in drafting an offering document or memorandum.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct.  Any managerial decisions made for a company by the CPA would impair the Independence of the CPA.', 'Incorrect. The CPA may assist in developing corporate strategies as long as he does not make the decisions.', 'Incorrect. The CPA may assist in identifying possible sources of capital as long as she does not make any decisions.', 'Incorrect. The CPA may assist in drafting an offering document or memorandum as long as he does not make any decisions.', ''),
(348, 32, 107, '<p><strong>Which of the following is NOT an obligation of a member to her employer&#39;s external accountant?</strong></p>', 'Must be candid.', 'Not knowingly misrepresent facts.', 'Respond to questions from the CPA about the integrity of the CFO.', 'Not knowingly fail to disclose material facts.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The internal CPA must be candid with the external accountant.', 'Incorrect. The internal CPA must not knowingly misrepresent facts to the external accountant.', 'Correct. The internal CPA has NO obligation to answer questions of this nature from the external accountant.', 'Incorrect. The internal CPA must not knowingly fail to disclose material facts to the external accountant.', ''),
(349, 32, 108, '<p><strong>&nbsp;A member refers computer products of wholesalers to clients of the firm through distributors and agents. The wholesaler pays the member a fee if a client purchases the computer products. Which of the following statements is true about this situation?</strong></p>', 'The member is not concerned about commissions or referral rules since the fee does not come directly from the client.', 'The member is concerned about commissions or referral rules even though the fee does not come directly from the client.', 'In this case the member is concerned only with commission or referral rules to determine if it is ethical.', 'The member does not need to consider the actions of anyone but the client.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. There is a transaction that produces a fee so the member must be concerned with commission or fee rules.', 'Correct. The member must be concerned about commissions or referral rules since there is a fee involved.', 'Incorrect. The member has to consider all rules that may pertain to a particular case, not just one of the parts of a case.', 'Incorrect. Section 91.03 of the Code of Professional Conduct provides that a member shall not permit others to perform acts on behalf of the member that, if carried out by the member, would place the member in violation of the rules. Therefore, the member would be held responsible for the actions of the distributors and agents.', ''),
(350, 32, 108, '<p><strong>&nbsp;An accountant withdrew from an engagement upon discovering irregularities in his client&rsquo;s tax return. May he reveal to the successor accountant why the relationship was terminated?</strong></p>', 'Yes, in any event.', 'Yes, in certain  circumstances.', 'No. not in any event.', 'Only if the successor requests the information.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. No, this is not an absolute.  There are certain circumstances that it is not permitted.', 'Correct. The rule on confidential client information is not intended to help an unscrupulous client cover up illegal acts or otherwise hide information by changing CPAs. If the member is contacted by the successor he should, at a minimum, suggest that the successor asks the client to permit the member to discuss all matters freely with the successor.  The successor is then on notice of some conflict. Because of the serious legal implication, the member should seek legal advice as to his status and obligations in the matter.', 'Incorrect.  This information may be revealed in some circumstances.', 'Incorrect, there are circumstances in which the previous accountant can inform the successor without the successor probing.', ''),
(351, 32, 108, '<p><strong>&nbsp;A CPA who is also admitted to their state Bar as an attorney :</strong></p>', 'May represent him/herself on his letterhead as both an attorney and a CPA.', 'Must use separate letterheads if the Bar allows the practice of both.', 'May not represent him/herself as an attorney in any form if he is practicing as a CPA, even though the Bar allows it.', 'Both b&c', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. The Code does not prohibit the simultaneous practice of accounting and law by a member licensed in both professions.   Both may be on the same letterhead.', 'Incorrect. May use separate letterheads if the rules of the applicable Bar Association allows.', 'Incorrect. The Code does not prohibit the simultaneous practice of accounting and law by a member licensed in both professions.', 'Incorrect. A member who is also admitted to the Bar may use separate letterheads if the rules of the applicable Bar Association allows, and the Code does not prohibit the simultaneous practice of accounting and law by a member licensed in both professions.', ''),
(352, 32, 108, '<p><strong>A member in the practice of public accounting may have an unlimited investment in an organization that provides accounting services:</strong></p>', 'As long as the practice of public accounting through that form of organization is permitted by state law and the organization’s characteristics conform to resolutions of Council.', 'Even though the practice of public accounting through that form of organization is not permitted by that state’s law.', 'If the practice of public accounting through a corporate form is not permitted by state law or regulation, the member may invest in the corporation and serve as Controller.', 'If the practice of public accounting through a corporate form is not permitted by state law or regulation, the member may invest in the corporation and serve on the Board of Directors.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. These are the requirements for permission.', 'Incorrect.  A member in the practice of public accounting may have an unlimited investment in an organization that provides accounting services.', 'Incorrect. Significant influence over the corporation may not exist and being a controller would allow this.', 'Incorrect. Significant influence over the corporation may not exist and being on the Board would allow this.', ''),
(353, 32, 108, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements is <u>TRUE</u>?&nbsp; A member provides for a contingent fee services to a non-attest client</strong></p>', 'The member would be considered to be in violation of only rule 302, Contingent Fees.', 'The member would be considered to be in violation of only rule 503, Commissions and Referral of Fees.', 'The member would be considered to be in violation of BOTH rule 302 or rule 503.', 'The member would be considered to be in violation of NEITHER rule 302 or rule 503.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. A member receiving contingent fees would NOT be in violation with a non-attest client.', 'Incorrect. A member receiving commissions would NOT be in violation with a non-attest client.', 'Incorrect. A member contingent fees or commissions would NOT be in violation with a non-attest client.', 'Correct. Since it is a non-attest client, Neither rule would be violated.', ''),
(354, 32, 108, '<p><strong>Which of the following examples of circumstances where a contingent fee would<u> NOT</u> be permitted.</strong></p>', 'Representing a client in an examination by a revenue agent of the client''s state income tax return.', 'The preparation of very complex original state tax returns.', 'Filing an amended federal income tax return claiming a tax refund based on a tax issue that is the subject of a test case (involving a different taxpayer) to which the taxing authority is developing a position.', 'Filing an amended state income tax return claiming a tax refund in an amount greater than the threshold for review by the Joint Committee on Internal Revenue Taxation.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. A client has the right to have his CPA at his side in an examination by a revenue agent.', 'Correct. No original tax return can be paid with a contingent fee.  This creates a conflict of interest as to the refund.', 'Incorrect. This situation is all right for the CPA to have a contingent fee.', 'Incorrect. When beyond the threshold, a contingent fee is permitted.', ''),
(355, 32, 109, '<p><strong>Complete the following statement: As an advocate:</strong></p>', 'A lawyer provides a client with an enlightened comprehension of the client’s legal rights and obligations.', 'A lawyer tries to obtain an advantageous result for a client.', 'A lawyer vigorously asserts a client’s position within the rules of the adversary system.', 'A lawyer shall have the competence to represent a client or have attorney(s) who are competent in the matter associated in the case.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. This is how a lawyer represents a client as an advisor.', 'Incorrect. This is how a lawyer represents a client as a negotiator.', 'Correct. This is the correct definition of how a lawyer represents a client as an advocate.', 'Incorrect. This is how a lawyer should always be in representing all aspects of their many duties for a client.', ''),
(356, 32, 109, '<p><strong>Attorney fees may be contingent:</strong></p>', 'When prohibited by law.', 'On the basis of an oral agreement.', 'And it may be determined after a matter has been resolved.', 'On the outcome of the matter, except when law prohibits a contingent fee.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  A lawyer may not charge contingent fees when prohibited by law.', 'Incorrect. A contingent fee agreement must be made in writing.', 'Incorrect. A contingent fee must be determined prior to resolution of the matter, not after.', 'Correct.  An attorney may work on a contingency basis at the outcome of the matter; unless it is a situation in which it is prohibited by law.', ''),
(357, 32, 109, '<p><strong>Internal auditors under the IIA code are NOT required to demonstrate loyalty:</strong></p>', 'When concerned with matters that are unlawful or inappropriate.', 'In all dealings concerning their organization.', 'To whomever they may be performing a service.', 'Both b & c', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. Loyalty does not extend to illegal or inappropriate matters.', 'Incorrect. The IIA Code requires internal auditors to demonstrate loyalty in all dealings concerning their organization.', 'Incorrect. The IIA Code requires internal auditors to demonstrate loyalty to whomever they may be providing a service.', 'Incorrect. The IIA Code requires internal auditors to demonstrate loyalty in all dealings concerning their organization and to whoever they may be providing a service.', ''),
(358, 32, 109, '<p><strong>An internal auditor shall not accept from an employee, client, customer, supplier, or business colleague of their employer anything of:</strong></p>', '$100 or more in value.', 'Material value.', 'Sufficient value to cause bias.', 'Any gift of any amount.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. No dollar amount for gifts is mentioned in the IIA Code.', 'Incorrect. Material is not the proper term to use in determining the value of an acceptable gift.', 'Correct. No gift of any value that might cause bias can be accepted.', 'Incorrect. This is not the best answer.  An internal auditor may not take a gift of value that has the possibility to cause bias.  For example, if a client brings a cup of coffee to their internal auditor, he/she may accept the cup of coffee without it causing an issue because there is little value to the gift from the client.', '');
INSERT INTO `chapter_review_questions` (`rev_ques_id`, `course_id`, `chapter_id`, `rev_ques_title`, `rev_ques_ans_1`, `rev_ques_ans_2`, `rev_ques_ans_3`, `rev_ques_ans_4`, `rev_ques_ans_5`, `rev_correct_ans_id`, `rev_correct_ans_text`, `rev_wronge_ans_text`, `rev_ques_status`, `ans1_text`, `ans2_text`, `ans3_text`, `ans4_text`, `ans5_text`) VALUES
(359, 33, 110, '<p><strong>Intangible assets play a vital role in the valuation of a company, which statement represents what an intangible asset is?</strong></p>', 'An asset that has physical form, such as machinery, buildings, and land.', 'An asset with a life-span of one year or less that can be converted easily into cash.', 'An asset that does not have physical form, but is valuable for a firm and can be critical to its long-term success or failure.', 'An asset that is current and consists of the short-term obligations owed to the company by its clients.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect; a tangible asset is an asset that has a physical form. Tangible assets include both fixed assets, such as machinery, buildings, and land, and current assets, such as inventory. The opposite of a tangible asset is an intangible asset.  Tangible assets keep the company operating and cannot be sold to customers separately from the business as a whole.  Whereas, intangible assets can be sold individually.', 'Incorrect; an asset with a life-span of one year or less that can be converted easily into cash into cash is a current asset.  These assets are current and fixed, which is the opposite of intangible assets, which have future economic benefits and a degree of uncertainty.  ', ' Correct; an intangible asset is one to which an arbitrary dollar value is attached because it has no intrinsic market value but represents financial value.  The characteristics of intangible assets are: they do not make up a physical substance, present future economic benefits and have a degree of uncertainty.', 'Incorrect; a current asset that consists of the short-term obligations owed to the company by its clients is considered accounts receivable and matures in less than one year.  Accounts receivable are dollars due from customers, making it a physical, fixed asset.  ', ''),
(360, 33, 110, '<p><strong>The current United States economy is in an <em>information era</em>, which directly correlates with the need for companies to adequately recognize and value their intangible assets; however, doing so is becoming increasingly difficult for companies complying with U.S. GAAP.&nbsp; Why?</strong></p>', ' Intangible assets are impossible to attach a dollar value to.', 'Companies financial reports do not properly account for intangible assets.', 'U.S. GAAP compliant balance sheets do not permit public companies to account for more than 5 intangible assets.', ' Intangible assets are not uniformly amortized.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect; even though there is no intrinsic market value assessed to intangible assets, they are given an arbitrary dollar value due to the high financial value they provide to a company.', 'Correct; GAAP compliant intangible asset recognition and valuation guidance is not sufficient to provide consistently accurate information to end-users, subsequently resulting in company financial reports that do not accurately reflect intangible assets. The GAAP-compliant model is outmoded and becoming more antiquated each day.  ', 'Incorrect; although not all intangible assets appear on public and private company balance sheets, all companies are permitted and should recognize and value all of their intangible assets.', 'Incorrect; a recognized intangible asset shall be amortized over its useful life to the reporting entity unless that life is determined to be indefinite.  If an intangible asset has a finite useful life, but the precise length of that life is not known, that intangible asset shall be amortized over the best estimate of its useful life.  The method of amortization shall reflect the pattern in which the economic benefits of the intangible asset are consumed or otherwise used up.', ''),
(361, 33, 110, '<p><strong>Currently, why do the new &ldquo;technology-age&rdquo; publicly traded companies have higher price-to-book ratios than their older counterparts?</strong></p>', ' Publicly traded companies have higher price-to-book ratios because they are not properly recognizing and valuing their intangible assets.', 'Publicly traded companies have higher price-to-book ratios because their intangible assets are valued higher than their tangible assets.', ' Publicly traded companies have higher price-to-book ratios because they have unrecognized tangible assets.  ', 'Publicly traded companies have higher price-to-book ratios because their stock prices per share are higher today than they were 50 years ago.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', ' Correct; research has shown that the difference between price and book value is mostly the result of unrecognized intangible asset value.  The price-to-book ratio of publicly traded companies has increased considerably over the last 30 years.  Newer “information age” companies have higher price-to-book ratios because they have a greater number of intangible assets, many of which go unrecognized.', 'Incorrect; despite the fact that intangible assets have become an increasingly significant portion of a company’s overall corporate value, the price-to-book ratio is not determined by the value of the intangible assets alone, it is the total market value of the company divided by the net assets, which include all intangible and tangible assets combined less the company’s total liabilities.', 'Incorrect; currently, new “information age” publicly traded companies have higher price-to-book ratios than their older counterparts because of unrecognized intangible assets not tangible assets.  Tangible assets have physical form and include fixed assets and current assets, which are given a definitive value and accounted for on a GAAP compliant balance sheet.  They are properly accounted for and included in the price-to-book net assets value.   ', ' Incorrect; although the stock price per share is included in a company’s price-to-book calculation, the stock price per share of a company is specific to each company, and the determination that all stock prices have increased in the last 50 years is not a factor that researchers have determined is the cause of higher price-to-book ratios.  The price per share is included in the calculation of the total market value, which is the number of outstanding shares multiplied by the stock price per share.  ', ''),
(362, 33, 117, '<p><strong>U.S. GAAP compliant balance sheets reflect certain intangible assets; if Company X is preparing a balance sheet, when would the company include its intangible assets, according to U.S. GAAP and FASB?&nbsp;</strong></p>', 'Upon the sale of one of Company X’s intangible assets.', 'Upon the acquisition of an interest in a subsidiary.', 'When Company X accounts for its research and development costs.', 'Upon the acquisition of a contingent liability.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect; selling an asset would remove it from the balance sheet.', 'Correct; According to FASB ASC Topic 350 and Topic 805, there are two distinct conditions that must be met in order for intangible assets to be recognized on a U.S. GAAP compliant balance sheet: (1) the purchase of an individual intangible asset or group of intangible assets from an external entity or the acquisition of an interest in a subsidiary; and (2) internally developed, maintained, or restored intangible assets that are specifically identifiable, that have determinable lives, and that are extrinsic to continuing operations.  ', 'Incorrect; Research and Development costs are generally not recognized as assets but expensed as incurred because they do not fall into one of the two distinct categories that allow intangible assets to be recognized on a balance sheet.  They are internally developed, maintained, and/or restored, but they do not have identifiable, determinable lives.', 'Incorrect; an “acquisition” of a contingent liability would be recorded as a liability on the balance sheet or discussed in the notes to the financial statements.', ''),
(363, 33, 117, '<p><strong>According to U.S. GAAP guidance, costs of internally developed intangible assets that are not specifically identifiable, have indeterminate lives, or that are inherent in a continuing business shall be recognized as a(n) ________.</strong></p>', 'Expense when incurred.', 'Asset when incurred.', 'Asset that is expensed over time.', 'Revenue.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct; according to ASC 350-30-25-3 states that costs of internally developing, maintaining, or restoring intangible assets [including goodwill] that are not specifically identifiable, that have indeterminate lives, or that are inherent in a continuing business or nonprofit activity and related to an entity as a whole, shall be recognized as an expense when incurred, and thus not included on a company’s balance sheet because they do not meet the requirements to be valued and recognized as an intangible asset on a balance sheet.', 'Incorrect; They are not considered an asset when incurred because costs of internally developed intangible assets that are not specifically identifiable, have indeterminate lives, or that are inherent in a continuing business do not meet the U.S. GAAP definition of an asset.   Intangibles that are internally-developed are not recognized as assets because they are not specifically identifiable; have indeterminate lives, or are inherent in a continuing business.  Therefore, the costs to develop and maintain these assets are expensed as incurred.', 'Incorrect; They are not considered an asset that is expensed (or amortized) over time because costs of internally developed intangible assets that are not specifically identifiable, have indeterminate lives, or that are inherent in a continuing business do not meet the U.S. GAAP definition of an asset. Intangibles that are internally-developed are not recognized as assets because they are not specifically identifiable; have indeterminate lives, or are inherent in a continuing business.   Therefore, the costs to develop and maintain these assets are expensed as incurred.  If an intangible asset does have a finite useful life, then it should be amortized over its useful life.', 'Incorrect; Revenue is generally the sales or fees earned and will increase a corporation’s stockholder’s equity in its assets.  Revenue will increase the retained earning section of stockholders’ equity.  The assets that usually increase are cash or accounts receivable, not the costs of internally developed intangible assets that are not specifically identifiable, have indeterminate lives, or that are inherent in a continuing business.', ''),
(364, 33, 117, '<p><strong>A U.S. GAAP compliant balance sheet does not adequately reflect a company&rsquo;s&nbsp; true intangible asset value because ________.&nbsp;</strong></p>', 'It accounts for all intangible assets, including those that are internally developed and unidentifiable.', 'It does not permit intangible assets to be recognized on a company’s balance sheet unless they were acquired during a purchase of another company.', 'It does not account for the intangible assets that do not meet the U.S. GAAP definition of an asset or the intangible assets are not represented at fair value.', 'The company’s intangible asset valuation cannot be sufficiently evaluated without including the valuation of a company’s tangible assets.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect, it does not account for all intangible assets, specifically not 		those that are internally developed and unidentifiable.  If an intangible asset is internally developed, it must be identifiable, have a determinable life, and be extrinsic to continuing operations.', 'Incorrect, a company’s balance sheet is permitted to recognize 		intangible assets other than those acquired during a purchase of 			another company, as long as they are specifically identifiable, have 		determinable lives, and that are extrinsic to continuing operations.', 'Correct, an intangible asset must fall into one of the two categories in order to be recognized on a company’s balance sheet.  Certain intangible assets are never found on a company’s balance sheet because they do not meet the U.S. GAAP definition of an asset or they are recognized, but may not be represented at fair value.  Rather, these intangible assets may be recognized at cost or fair value only if  the asset value was impaired subsequent to initial recognition.  U.S.  GAAP requires a variety of intangibles to be recognized on the face of the balance sheet and to be discussed in the financial statement notes.  This results in a lack of adequate information to properly evaluate a company’s true intangible asset value.', 'Incorrect, a company’s tangible assets are recognized separately on their balance sheet, thus do not have an impact on the value of the company’s intangible assets.', ''),
(365, 33, 118, '<p><strong>A <em>copyright</em> is a legally protected artistic-related intangible asset, which entitles the owner to exclusive rights and profits from which type of work?&nbsp;</strong></p>', 'An oil-painting created by an artist who copied an original photograph by Ansel Adams.', 'An entrepreneur’s method of operation for a new business.', 'An original song that is played for audiences via different media outlets around the nation, written and recorded by one artist.  ', 'The facts about a technology company’s new patent tweeted by a writer on Twitter.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect; copyrightable work must be original.  It must not be copied from someone else and must contain a minimal level of creativity on the part of the creator.', 'Incorrect; If an entrepreneur has a method of operation for a new business, that method is not protected, but if she writes down the method in the form of a business plan, the business plan document itself would be protected.', 'Correct; the song was written by the artist, making it an original piece of work, it is a recording, which fulfills the requirement that it be fixed in a tangible form of expression, therefore, the song is protected by copyright, granting exclusive rights and profits to the artist.', 'Incorrect; Although specific expressions of facts are copyrightable, the facts themselves are not copyrightable because they are facts.  Although print, video and online expressions of news are copyrightable, the news itself is not.  This limits censorship allows discussion and debate on blogs and promotes public access to and the free exchange of information.  ', ''),
(366, 33, 118, '<p><strong>Intangible assets can generally be classified into one of six major categories; if Company Z has a database that includes the contact information, order history, and demographic information of their clients around the world, which category would these intangible assets fall under?&nbsp;</strong></p>', 'Goodwill', 'Technology-Related', 'Marketing-Related', 'Customer-Related', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect; goodwill is the category of non-physical, non-identifiable intangible assets that are classified separately from the other five categories. Although, there are certain non-contractual client relationships that fall under goodwill, this is not one of them.  ', 'Incorrect; technology-related intangible assets are related to innovations or technological advances.  In this example, even though the client information is included in a database, it does not fall under the technology-related category because the intangible asset in this  case is the specific and identifiable client information.  ', 'Incorrect; marketing-related intangible assets are the assets a company 	uses to promote a product or business.  Although, in this example the client information is required in order to reach the client and promote or maintain a business, it is the products that are used to do so, most 		commonly a trademark.', 'Correct; this is an example of a customer-related intangible asset. The order history, contact information, and demographic information 		make up the assets that are the result of the company’s business and interactions with outside parties, their clients.  Each asset is specifically related to the company’s business with their clients, making them quantifiable, specific, and identifiable customer-related intangible assets.', ''),
(367, 33, 118, '<p><strong>Which of the following intangible assets should be included separately on Company X&rsquo;s U.S. GAAP compliant balance sheet?&nbsp;</strong></p>', 'Company X’s high-performing management team that the company CFO spent a great deal of corporate funds on to recruit, interview, and train.', 'State-of-the-art machinery, newly purchased from a company that 	went out of business.', 'The novel trademark that Company X just purchased from another company.', 'The cost Company X is spending to develop a new client analytics technology.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect; employees are not tangible, nor intangible assets; therefore, they do not ever appear on a company’s balance sheet.  It is widely accepted that employees, if properly cultivated, are priceless.  ', 'Incorrect; state-of-the-art manufacturing equipment is a tangible asset, classified under Property, Plant, and Equipment on a GAAP compliant balance sheet.', 'Correct; A purchased trademark should be reported on the balance sheet as an intangible asset.  The cost principle prevents the reported amount from being more than the cost of acquiring and defending the trademark. A trademark that was developed internally, rather than purchased, might have a cost of $0, and therefore it would not be listed on the balance sheet.  The costs incurred with developing a trademark are expensed as incurred; however, in this case the trademark was purchased by Company X from another company; therefore, it should be included on Company X’s balance sheet for the purchased price.', 'Incorrect; The cost for company X to develop new technology is considered in-process research and development.  These costs are related to the development of the product, process, or idea must be expensed as incurred, not included on a balance sheet.', ''),
(368, 33, 119, '<p><strong>A company can employ many different approaches to measure and value intangible assets and each one has its own advantages and disadvantages, but which one is said to result in the least accurate economic value? &nbsp;</strong></p>', 'The Replacement Cost method.', 'The Historical Cost method.', 'The Market Comparison method.', 'The Relief-from-Royalty method.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect; the Replacement Cost method and Historical Cost method 		are independent.  The replacement cost method values an asset based 	on the asset’s current price of replacement.  Replacement cost is a 		viable valuation method for several different types of intangibles.', 'Correct; the Historical Cost method is used to value certain intangible assets, such as internally-developed patents and trademarks.  The costs are those economic sacrifices directly related to asset acquisition, and then amortized over the intangible asset’s useful life. This method is consistent with the long-established, yet mostly outmoded GAAP principle of conservatism, eliminating undesired 	capitalization of expenses, but the end-result is often an intangible asset value that rarely resembles the actual economic value.', 'Incorrect; the Market Comparison method used to assess aggregate firm value and specific intangible asset value by comparing specific intangibles with similar assets that are regularly traded or that have been involved in recent transactions. A private firm would be compared to a similar publicly-traded firm.  This method is not the most efficient 		method for a company to use to value their intangible assets, but the end-result resembles the actual economic value more accurately than 		the historical cost method.', 'Incorrect; the Relief-from-Royalty method is an Income-based method and has been used for many years.  A company can employ the relief-from royalty method to analyze many of its intangibles. The company assumes that the technology has been licensed to other organizations. 100% of the “what-if” royalty payments are accumulated over the expected useful life of the intangible and then discounted back to present dollars. The discounted amount is a reasonable estimate of the asset’s value.', ''),
(369, 33, 119, '<p><strong>As it relates to the Net Present Value model, what does <em>cash flow</em> refer to?&nbsp;</strong></p>', 'The incremental cash flows specific to the intangible asset being analyzed.', 'The cash flow is specific to the tangible liability being analyzed.', 'The rate used to adjust future cash flows to a present dollar amount.', 'Only the expenses associated with a specific intangible asset.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct; NPV appraises an investment by comparing total additional revenues to total incremental costs as adjusted for relative risk. In 		other words, NPV is calculated as the difference between the present value of all cash inflows and all cash outflows.  The cash flow is a critical part of the equation and it refers to the marginal net cash flows specific to the intangible asset being analyzed.', 'Incorrect; as is relates to the NPV model, cash flow refers to the incremental cash flows specific to the intangible asset being analyzed. Assets are being analyzed as opposed to liabilities.  ', 'Incorrect; the tangible liability being realized is the discount rate, or 	“cost-of-capital” and it is the risk-adjusted rate used to adjust future cash-flows to present dollars. The cost-of-capital is generally based on the firm’s weighted average cost of capital adjusted for specific risk characteristics associated with the intangibles unique characteristics.', 'Incorrect; as it relates to the NPV model, cash flow refers to the incremental cash flows specific to the intangible asset being analyzed. Cash flow includes both revenue and expenses.', ''),
(370, 33, 119, '<p><strong>There are three major valuation methods used to measure intangible assets, and there are additional novel methods including, <em>Game Theory</em>; when is <em>Game Theory </em>the most beneficial?&nbsp;</strong></p>', 'When a company is seeking to determine the value of their intangible assets individually, rather than as a whole.', 'When a company is seeking to eliminate the undesired capitalization of expenses.', 'When a company needs to determine the value of their intangible assets and the future is indeterminable.  ', 'When a company must determine the value of an intangible asset for an ongoing court case.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect; When a company is seeking to probe the aggregate price-to-book difference and isolate the individual, specifically identifiable, intangible assets, they should use the Intangible Assets Monitor 			method.  It is one of the novel methods used to value intangible assets, and the developer, Karl-Erik Sveiby developed it in order to expand on the price-to-book method.  It is employed by many global, high-technology firms.', 'Incorrect; This method is the Historical Cost Method.  The historical cost method is consistent with the long-established, yet mostly outmoded 		GAAP principle of conservatism.  As such, this method eliminates the undesired capitalization of expenses, but the end-result is often intangible asset value that rarely resembles the actual economic value.', 'Correct; Game theory is a mathematical tool used to analyze various potential outcomes based on intermittent decisions.  Game theory helps one select the best strategy when one is facing an uncertain future.  This  tool is particularly useful when the analyst is choosing between competing, mutually exclusive options.  Therefore, Game 		theory is the best choice for a company seeking to determine the value of their intangible assets when facing an unknown future.', 'Incorrect; The Relief-from-Royalty method is most commonly used in litigation.  The method is used to calculate damages related to patent, trademark, and copyright infringement litigation.  Therefore, during an ongoing court case, a company should employ the Relief-from-Royalty method to determine the value of the intangible asset because it calculates the value of the intangible based on a “what-if” analysis.  Specifically, the asset’s worth is determined as the total amount of  royalties available to a firm that would have licensed its product to a third party instead of using the intangible asset itself.', ''),
(371, 13, 120, '<p><strong>Who initiates an&nbsp;ACH credit transaction?</strong></p>', 'Payor initiates the transaction', 'Payee initiates the transaction', 'Bank initiates the transaction', 'Either the payor or the payee initiates the transaction', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. Payor initiates the transaction.', 'Incorrect. The payee does not initiate the transaction when a credit is involved.', 'Incorrect. The bank must wait for instructions in order to process any ACH transaction', 'Incorrect. Only the payor can initiate the transaction.', ''),
(372, 13, 120, '<p><strong>How should a company get banking information from a vendor to set them up for ACH payments?</strong></p>', 'It doesn’t really matter as long as you get the information', 'Verbally over the phone', 'From a canceled or voided check', 'In a handwritten note', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. It most definitely matters and if standardized practices are not followed, errors will creep in.', 'Incorrect. Getting information verbally over the phone is likely to result in errors, transpositions and misunderstandings.', 'Correct. By getting the information from a canceled or voided check, there is no chance for misinterpretation.', 'Incorrect. Getting the information in a handwritten note is asking for trouble, especially if the handwriting is not perfect.', ''),
(373, 13, 121, '<p><strong>Which of the following is a benefit of paying electronically through the ACH?</strong></p>', 'Mailing costs are increased', 'Less unclaimed property reporting and remitting', 'Exception handling increased', 'Staff in purchasing can be reduced', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Mailing costs are not increased, they are decreased.', 'Correct. Less unclaimed property reporting and remitting is one of the benefits as there are no un-cashed checks to chase and report.', 'Incorrect. Exception handling is not affected by a move to ACH.', 'Incorrect. Staff in purchasing is also not affected by a move to ACH.', ''),
(374, 13, 121, '<p><strong>When you start an ACH program, which of the following steps should you take?</strong></p>', 'Wait until the next annual update, to include information in your policy and procedures manual', 'Wait until you have all the kinks worked out before training any processors', 'Document every step in the procedure so everyone knows what to do', 'Identify early participants based on how long they’ve been doing business with the company', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. By waiting until the next annual update, to include information in your policy and procedures manual, you are almost guaranteeing there will be mistakes in that time period.', 'Incorrect. By waiting until you have all the kinks worked out before training any processors, your processors will have no guidelines and will inevitably make more mistakes than if they had a reference guide to check.', 'Correct. By documenting every step in the procedure so everyone knows what to do, you minimize the opportunities for the staff to make mistakes.', 'Incorrect. Identifying early participants based on how long they’ve been doing business with the company is a terrible way to select participants in your early ACH programs. You want to focus on those who understand ACH and will be sympathetic if something goes wrong. These parties may or may not be those who you’ve done business with for some time.', ''),
(375, 13, 122, '<p><strong>When starting an ACH program, which is the best approach?</strong></p>', 'Roll it out to your entire supplier base at once', 'Only offer it to the suppliers you do the most regular business with', 'Offer it only to the suppliers who don’t send problematic invoices', 'Start small with a test group', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. By rolling it out to your entire supplier base at once, you’ll have a nightmare on your hands if there is a problem or your program needs tweaking.', 'Incorrect. By only offering it to the suppliers you do the most regular business with, you’ll miss out on many good vendors who would accept electronic payments.', 'Incorrect. By offering it only to the suppliers who don’t send problematic invoices, you will antagonize those who wish to receive electronic payments and will miss the opportunity to grow your program.', 'Correct. By starting with a small with a test group, you’ll have the opportunity to refine the program if you discover any hiccups or problematic approaches.', ''),
(376, 13, 122, '<p><strong>Which of the following approaches can be used to entice vendors to accept ACH payments?</strong></p>', 'Pay electronically more frequently than by paper checks', 'Pay electronically less frequently than by paper checks', 'Pay electronically at the same frequency as by paper checks', 'Run paper checks only once a week', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. By paying electronically more frequently than by paper checks, those suppliers who want their payments quickly will readily sign up.', 'Incorrect. By paying electronically less frequently than by paper checks, you will discourage suppliers from signing up.', 'Incorrect. Paying electronically at the same frequency as by paper checks does nothing to encourage suppliers to switch.', 'Incorrect. Running paper checks only once a week is not infrequent enough to encourage suppliers who might be reluctant to switch.', ''),
(377, 13, 123, '<p><strong>Which of the following is NOT a type of ACH fraud?</strong></p>', 'Account hijacking', 'Representing positive pay rejects as ACH credits', 'Representing positive pay rejects as ACH debits', 'Reverse phishing', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Account hijacking is a type of ACH fraud whereby the crook takes over an account and initiates ACH credits in the company’s name.', 'Correct. Representing positive pay rejects as ACH credits is not an approach used by crooks.', 'Incorrect. Representing positive pay rejects as ACH debits was the first type of ACH fraud seen in any great numbers.', 'Incorrect. Reverse phishing is a type of ACH fraud where the crook attempts to get the information it needs to defraud the company.', ''),
(378, 13, 123, '<p><strong>What does an ACH filter do?</strong></p>', 'Stops all ACH activity', 'Allows ACH activity from pre-approved parties', 'Checks the dollar amount of transactions coming through', 'Checks on the frequency of allowable transactions', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. A filter does not stop all ACH activity; only certain types.', 'Correct. A filter allows ACH activity from pre-approved parties.', 'Incorrect. A filter does not check the dollar amount of transactions coming through.', 'Incorrect. A filter does not check on the frequency of allowable transactions, only allowable parties.', ''),
(379, 13, 124, '<p><strong>How frequently should bank reconciliations be done to ensure recovery of any unauthorized transactions?</strong></p>', 'Weekly', 'Monthly', 'Daily', 'Never', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Weekly bank reconciliations are not frequent enough to notify the bank within the 24-hour window required for recovery of funds.', 'Incorrect. Monthly bank reconciliations are certainly not frequent enough.', 'Correct. Daily reconciliations are what’s required if you are to notify the bank within 24 hours of an unauthorized transaction.', 'Incorrect. Never reconciling your bank accounts is a horrid idea on many levels including the fact that you’ll never identify unauthorized transactions.', ''),
(380, 13, 124, '<p><strong>Why is getting remittance detail for ACH payments to the supplier so important?</strong></p>', 'It is required by law', 'It is required by GAAP', 'It means more ‘where’s my money'' calls from suppliers', 'It facilitates cash application of the funds', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. There is no reference in the law regarding the supplying of remittance information.', 'Incorrect. GAAP also makes no reference to the necessity of providing remittance detail related to ACH payments.', 'Incorrect. Supplying remittance information means less, not more ‘where’s my money calls from suppliers', 'Correct. Remittance information facilitates cash application of the funds.', ''),
(381, 17, 125, '<p><strong>According to the University of Minnesota, the average company, which was put out of business for at least four and a half days, will experience what percentage of loss in capacity to operate?</strong></p>', '40%', '50%', '60%', '100%', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect answer.  Only 40% will ever open their doors again.', 'Correct answer.  According to Kit Tuveson, chairman of the International Facility Management Association and worldwide facility operations manager for Hewlett-Packard in San Francisco, only 40% of the companies that experience a disastrous event at their place of business will ever open their doors again. In addition, a study developed by the University of Minnesota found that the average company which was put out of business for as little as four and a half days experienced up to a 50% loss in its capacity to operate.', 'Incorrect answer.  60% will never open their doors again.', 'Incorrect answer.  Although many companies that experience a disaster will never open their doors again, this number can be significantly reduced with the help of disaster plans.', ''),
(382, 17, 125, '<p><strong>One of the most difficult steps in the process of developing a disaster plan is which of the following?</strong></p>', 'Assembling a recovery team', 'Obtaining upper-management support', 'Getting emergency personnel to participate', 'Communicating the plan', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect answer.  Assembling the recovery team would take place after management approval and is usually a fairly simple process.', 'Correct answer.  Obtaining upper-management support is often the most difficult step in the process. Disaster plan development can be costly due to the human resources and assets which are required.', 'Incorrect answer.  Emergency personnel are usually eager to get involved in the process.', 'Incorrect answer.  Communicating the plan is an extremely important step but is normally done throughout the process and is fairly easy to accomplish.', ''),
(383, 17, 125, '<p><strong>Once management approval has been obtained and a team has been developed, the next step in developing a disaster plan is which of the following? </strong></p>', 'Testing', 'Identifying risks', 'Communicating the plan', 'Implementing the plan', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect answer.  Testing would occur after the plan was developed.', 'Correct answer.  Once management approval has been obtained and a team is developed, the next step is to identify risks. For example, a company located in California may identify earthquake exposure as a risk.', 'Incorrect answer.  Communicating the plan to employees is extremely important, but this takes place throughout development and periodically after the implementation.', 'Incorrect answer.  Implementing the plan will take place throughout the process of development, but it is not the first step.', ''),
(384, 17, 125, '<p><strong>The final step of developing a disaster plan should be which of the following? </strong></p>', 'Notifying emergency services such as the police of the specific details of your disaster plan', 'Describing in detail what conditions must be met for the planned recovery to be considered successful', 'Communicating the plan', 'Implementing the plan', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect answer.  Ideally, the police and/or other emergency personnel would be involved throughout the process of development.  They may offer plenty of advice that will help the development of the plan.', 'Correct answer.  Once developed, the entire plan should be flow charted indicating each step of the recovery plan and each process and procedure which is to take place.  Criteria should be detailed at the end of the plan which would determine whether the planned recovery was successful.', 'Incorrect answer.  Communicating the plan should take place throughout the process as well as periodic testing.', 'Incorrect answer.  Throughout the process of developing your disaster plan, discussions should take place to identify the key business personnel, operations, business goals and objectives to ensure that everything possible is considered to protect them from interruption at any point and under any circumstances.', ''),
(385, 17, 125, '<p><strong>All employees within a company should receive a copy of the disaster plan:</strong></p>', 'On their first day of employment', 'Bi-annually', 'Annually', 'If it is not otherwise posted in the building', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct answer.  New employees should receive a copy on their first day of employment. It is also important to adjust the plan as needed when employees leave the company.', 'Incorrect answer.  Training should take place on at least a bi-annual basis.', 'Incorrect answer. It is important that all employees received an updated copy of the plan at least annually.', 'Incorrect answer.  Even if the disaster plan is otherwise posted in the building, all employees should be given a copy of the plan.  Many employees may not take the time to stop and read the posting.', ''),
(386, 17, 125, '<p><strong>A minimum of how many information system backups should be required to be kept offsite?</strong></p>', 'One', 'Two', 'Three', 'Five', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect answer.  One backup is not sufficient as it may be corrupt.', 'Incorrect answer.  Two backups should be kept onsite.', 'Correct answer.  A minimum of three backups should be required to be kept offsite and two should be kept onsite.  Ideally, the three that are kept offsite should be located at three different locations which are not located near your company or each other.', 'Incorrect answer.  Five backups in total should be required, but not all need to be kept offsite.', ''),
(387, 17, 125, '<p><strong>Which of the following best describes the area that all employees have agreed is the designated area where they will meet in the event that an evacuation is necessary?</strong></p>', 'Assembly', 'Call tree', 'Checklist exercise', 'Exposure', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct answer.  The assembly area is where all employees agree to meet.', 'Incorrect answer.  The call tree is a graphical document which illustrates the order in which individuals or external agencies will be notified in the event a disaster should occur.', 'Incorrect answer.  A checklist exercise is a method by which a completed disaster plan is audited to verify that strategies and information such as current contacts and phone numbers are accurate.', 'Incorrect answer.  Exposure is the level at which something or someone is susceptible to potential loss (i.e., risk).', ''),
(388, 17, 125, '<p><strong>A disaster plan can only be successful if it:</strong></p>', 'Maximizes the duration of critical business process interruption', 'Is communicated and re-communicated to all personnel', 'Is supported by an all risk insurance policy', 'Includes at least one information systems backup', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect answer.  Minimizing the duration of critical business process interruption should be the goal of a disaster plan.', 'Correct answer.  A successful disaster plan is one which is communicated and re-communicated to all personnel. The communication should begin on an employee''s first day of employment.', 'Incorrect answer.  An all risk insurance policy is preferred but is not a requirement in order for a disaster plan to be successful.', 'Incorrect answer.  A disaster plan should include a minimum of three consecutive information systems backups.', ''),
(389, 17, 125, '<p><strong>Which of the following best describes a graphical document which illustrates the order in which individuals or external agencies will be notified in the event a disaster should occur?</strong></p>', 'Call tree', 'Checklist', 'Assembly area', 'Business continuity', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct answer.  A call tree is a graphical document which illustrates the order in which individuals or external agencies will be notified in the event a disaster should occur. This should be updated any time new employees are hired and when they leave the company.', 'Incorrect answer.  A checklist exercise is a method by which a completed disaster plan is audited to verify that strategies and information such as current contacts and phone numbers are accurate.', 'Incorrect answer. The assembly area is where all employees agree to meet.', 'Incorrect answer.  Business continuity is the ability of an organization to continue normal business operations before, during and after an unforeseen event should occur.', ''),
(390, 17, 125, '<p><strong>An insurance policy which is triggered on the date of the occurrence which gave rise to a claim being filed is which of the following?</strong></p>', 'Claims-made policy', 'Occurrence policy', 'Exposure', 'All risk policy', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect answer.  A claims-made policy is triggered on the date that the claim is filed.', 'Correct answer.  An occurrence policy is triggered on the date of the occurrence. This means that if a claim is filed outside of the active policy period, the timing of the event which gave rise to the claim if within the active policy period is considered relevant.', 'Incorrect answer.  Exposure is the level at which something or someone is susceptible to potential loss (i.e., risk).', 'Incorrect answer.  An all risk policy is insurance which covers all perils except those which may be specifically excluded such as flood damage, which may be covered by the national flood insurance programs.', ''),
(391, 17, 125, '<p><strong>Any unforeseen event which would cause a significant interruption in the ability to continue operating critical ongoing functions within an organization is known as which of the following?</strong></p>', 'A disaster', 'An exposure', 'A call tree', 'A checklist exercise', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct answer.  Any unforeseen event which would cause a significant interruption in the ability to continue operating critical ongoing functions within an organization is known as a disaster.', 'Incorrect answer.  Exposure is the level at which something or someone is susceptible to potential loss (i.e., risk).', 'Incorrect answer.  The call tree is a graphical document which illustrates the order in which individuals or external agencies will be notified in the event a disaster should occur.', 'Incorrect answer.  A checklist exercise is a method by which a completed disaster plan is audited to verify that strategies and information such as current contacts and phone numbers are accurate.', ''),
(392, 17, 125, '<p><strong>A disaster plan may also be commonly referred to as which of the following?</strong></p>', 'Occurrence policy', 'Business continuity plan', 'Evacuation', 'Recoverable loss', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect answer.  An occurrence policy is an insurance policy which is triggered on the date of the occurrence which gave rise to a claim being filed.', 'Correct answer.  A disaster plan is also sometimes referred to as a business continuity plan. Continuity means the state or quality of being continuous.', 'Incorrect answer.  An evacuation is the exiting of individuals to another safer location (assembly area) in the event of an emergency.', 'Incorrect answer.  A recoverable loss is a financial loss which may be reclaimed through means such as insurance claims or litigation.', ''),
(393, 17, 125, '<p><strong>Once developed, the entire disaster plan should be:</strong></p>', 'Flow charted', 'Filed', 'Kept offsite', 'Practiced at least annually', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct answer. Once developed, the plan should be flow charted.  It is also very important to communicate the plan to all employees.', 'Incorrect answer.  The plan should never be filed as it will always be undergoing updates and need to be communicated.', 'Incorrect answer.  Although a copy of the plan may be kept offsite, the entire plan should be kept onsite.', 'Incorrect answer.  The plan should be practiced at least bi-annually.', ''),
(394, 17, 126, '<p><strong>The first step that insurance companies normally take when settling claims is which of the following?</strong></p>', 'Investigate what happened', 'Develop a claim for damages', 'Establish damages', 'Remove the evidence', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct answer.  Investigating what happened is typically the first step that insurance companies will take. The circumstances which caused the disaster may determine whether or not the damages will be covered.', 'Incorrect answer.  Developing a claim for damages is typically the second step that insurance companies will take.', 'Incorrect answer.  This is normally the third and final step that insurance companies will take.', 'Incorrect answer.  The recovery team within the organization will usually remove the evidence to a secure location.', ''),
(395, 17, 126, '<p><strong>Gerber and Feldman recommend taking which of the following steps to preserve evidence?</strong></p>', 'Carefully tag or otherwise identify evidence', 'Remove the evidence to a secure location and then photograph it', 'Wait for the insurance company representatives to secure the evidence', 'Hire an external recovery team', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct answer.  The evidence should be carefully tagged or otherwise identified.   It is imperative that a recovery team within the organization itself preserve evidence even prior to the insurance investigation and that it be completed as soon as possible so that critical evidence is not destroyed or removed.', 'Incorrect answer.  The evidence should be photographed in place and then removed to a secure place.', 'Incorrect answer.  The recovery team within the organization will usually remove the evidence to a secure location.', 'Incorrect answer.  A recovery team is recommended to be made up of internal personnel within the organization, although external sources may be relied on for some specific steps.', ''),
(396, 17, 126, '<p><strong>Insurance companies are typically interested in which of the following?</strong></p>', 'Establishing damages', 'The tax impact of the damage assessment', 'Developing a recovery team', 'Developing a disaster plan', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct answer.  Insurance companies are very interested in establishing damages. However, it is your responsibility to safeguard the assets.', 'Incorrect answer.  Insurance companies are not typically interested in the tax impact of the damage assessment. However, a tax specialist should be consulted by an entity''s management anytime a loss is experienced due to a disaster.', 'Incorrect answer.  Developing a recovery team is typically performed within the organization, although the insurance company may be consulted through the process.', 'Incorrect answer.  Although insurance companies may offer tips and tools to assist, developing a disaster plan is typically done within the organization.', ''),
(397, 17, 126, '<p><strong>The part of a disaster plan which deals with the recovery of software programs once the initial platforms that this data runs on has been recovered is known as which of the following?</strong></p>', 'Business continuity', 'Backlog', 'Application recovery', 'Subrogation', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect answer.  Business continuity is the ability of an organization to continue normal business operations.', 'Incorrect answer.  Backlog is the amount of work which accumulates.', 'Correct answer.  Application recovery is the part of a disaster plan which deals with the recovery of software programs, applications and files once the initial platforms that this data runs on has been recovered.', 'Incorrect answer.  Subrogation is the substitution of one party (the insurer) for another (the insured) to pursue any legal rights the latter may have against a third party liable for an insurance-reimbursed loss the insured suffered.', ''),
(398, 17, 126, '<p><strong>The disaster plan you implement should do which of the following?</strong></p>', 'Minimize the duration of critical business process interruption', 'Maximize the duration of critical business process interruption', 'Not focus on geographically obvious specific types of risk', 'Be communicated only to key management personnel', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct answer.  The disaster plan should limit the amount of loss by minimizing the duration of critical business process interruption, which could be very costly for the organization and its customers, vendors, etc.', 'Incorrect answer.  Business process interruption should be minimized.', 'Incorrect answer.  The disaster plan should focus on geographically obvious specific types of potential risk.', 'Incorrect answer.  The disaster plan should be communicated to all personnel.', '');
INSERT INTO `chapter_review_questions` (`rev_ques_id`, `course_id`, `chapter_id`, `rev_ques_title`, `rev_ques_ans_1`, `rev_ques_ans_2`, `rev_ques_ans_3`, `rev_ques_ans_4`, `rev_ques_ans_5`, `rev_correct_ans_id`, `rev_correct_ans_text`, `rev_wronge_ans_text`, `rev_ques_status`, `ans1_text`, `ans2_text`, `ans3_text`, `ans4_text`, `ans5_text`) VALUES
(399, 34, 127, '<p><strong>Which of the following is a synonym for &ldquo;ethics&rdquo;?</strong></p>', 'Moral practice.', 'Social values.', 'Decency.', 'All of the above.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Moral practice is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. Social values is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect.  Decency is not the best answer.', 'Correct. All of the above answers are synonyms for “ethics.”', ''),
(400, 34, 127, '<p><strong>Which of the following best completes the sentence? A member who departs from Rulings in similar circumstances:</strong></p>', 'Will be requested to justify the departure.', 'Is still ethical since these are not principles, but only rulings.', 'Is still ethical since these are not principles, but only rulings.', 'Is still ethical since rulings are only guidelines.', '', '1', '', '', 'Deleted', 'Correct.  A member that departs from a “Ruling” has to defend that position or be found guilty of violating the Code of Professional Ethics.', 'Incorrect.  Rulings are an official part of the Code of Professional Ethics.', 'Incorrect. Rulings summarize the application of Rules of Conduct.', 'Incorrect Interpretations to a particular set of factual circumstances.', ''),
(401, 34, 127, '<p><strong>A member of the AICPA is responsible to which of the following groups?</strong></p>', 'The state society to which the member belongs.', 'The appropriate state board of accountancy.', 'The AICPA ethics division.', 'All of the above.', '', '4', '', '', 'Deleted', 'Incorrect. The state society to which the member belongs is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. The appropriate state board of accountancy is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. The AICPA ethics division is not the best answer.', 'Correct. All of the answers above are appropriate.', ''),
(402, 34, 127, '<p><strong>Which of the following words is NOT a synonym of &ldquo;ethical&rdquo;?</strong></p>', 'Honest', 'Conscientious', 'Moral', 'Humane', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Honest is being ethical.', 'Incorrect. Being Conscientious is being ethical.', 'Correct. Moral may be ethical or not.  The Mafia has their “moral code” which society does not consider ethical.', 'Incorrect.  Being Humane is being ethical.', ''),
(403, 34, 127, '<p><strong>The sections of the Code consist of _________ and _________:</strong></p>', 'Principles and Standards.', 'Rules and Standards.', 'Principles and Rules.', 'Rules, Principles, and Standards.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Standards are not one of the sections.', 'Incorrect.  Principles must be one of the sections.', 'Correct. The two sections are Principles and Rules.', 'Incorrect. Standards are a subset of the Rules, not one of the sections.', ''),
(404, 34, 127, '<p><strong>A Covered Member is:</strong></p>', 'An individual on the attest engagement team.', 'A Partner in an office in the same state.', 'An individual in a position to influence the attest engagement.', 'The firm, including the firm''s employee benefit plans.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. An individual on the attest engagement team is a Covered Member.', 'Correct. A Partner in an office in the same state is not necessarily a covered member.  Other attributes must be present.', 'Incorrect. An individual in a position to influence the attest engagement is a Covered Member.', 'Incorrect. The firm, including the firm''s employee benefit plans, is a Covered Member.', ''),
(405, 34, 127, '<p><strong>A member should consult, in addition to the Code of Professional Ethics, if applicable, the ethical standards of:</strong></p>', 'The state society to which the member belongs.', 'The appropriate state board of accountancy.', 'The AICPA ethics division.', 'All of the above.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The state society to which the member belongs is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. The appropriate state board of accountancy is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. The AICPA ethics division is not the best answer.', 'Correct. All of the above answers are appropriate.', ''),
(406, 34, 128, '<p><strong>Which one of the following definitions is NOT correct?</strong></p>', 'Council: the Council of the AICPA.', 'Member: a member, associate member, or international associate of the AICPA.', 'Professional services: all services performed by a member while performing public accounting services.', 'Institute: the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Council is properly defined as “The Council of the AICPA.” The Council is the governing body of the AICPA and is comprised of approximately 265 members and representatives from every state and U.S. Territory. Council meets twice a year, in May and October, and Regional Council meetings are held every year in March.', 'Incorrect.  Member is properly defined as “A member, associate member, or international associate of the AICPA.”', 'Correct. Professional services include all services performed by a member while holding out as a CPA, not just while performing public accounting services.', 'Incorrect. Institute is properly defined as “The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants.”', ''),
(407, 34, 128, '<p><strong>Which of the following items completes the following sentence? Independence in Fact:</strong></p>', 'involves impartiality.', 'indicates that the member has abstained from relationships that appear to prevent objectivity.', 'is a state of mind.', 'involves freedom from conflicts of interest.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Impartiality is connected with objectivity.', 'Incorrect. Independence in appearance, not fact, involves actions such as abstaining from relationships.', 'Correct. Independence, in fact, is attitudinal, that is, a state of mind. Independence in  appearance involves actions.', 'Incorrect. Objectivity involves actions such as freedom from conflicts of interest.', ''),
(408, 34, 128, '<p><strong>The unique characteristics of the accounting profession that set it apart from the rest of society is its acceptance of its responsibility to:</strong></p>', 'Its clients.', 'The government and its agencies.', 'The public.', 'Investors.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. A profession is responsible to its clients, but this is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. A profession is responsible to certain government agencies at times, but this is not the best answer.', 'Correct.  A profession is responsible to its public, which is unique.', 'Incorrect. A profession is responsible to investors sometimes, but this is not the best answer.', ''),
(409, 34, 128, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements is NOT correct? &nbsp;A Key position is a position in which an individual: </strong></p>', 'Has primary responsibility for significant accounting functions that support material components of the financial statements.', 'Has responsibility for the sales force.', 'Has primary responsibility for the preparation of the financial statements.', 'Has the ability to exercise influence over the contents of the financial statements, including when the individual is a member of the board of directors.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Having primary responsibility for significant accounting functions that support material components of the financial statements gives the possibility of adversely affecting the financial statements and they are therefore in a key position.', 'Correct. Having responsibility for the sales force does NOT allow the person to impact adversely the financial statements.', 'Incorrect.  Primary responsibility for the preparation of the financial statements allows the individual to adversely impact the financial statements and makes them in a key position.', 'Incorrect. The ability to exercise influence over the contents of the financial statements in any capacity is a key position.', ''),
(410, 34, 128, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements is the BEST answer?&nbsp; &ldquo;All groups of society are recipients of the work of the accounting profession.&nbsp; Society includes which of the following _____.</strong></p>', 'Clients & credit grantors', 'Governments', 'Employers & investors', 'All of the above', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Clients & credit grantors are most definitely a part of society; however, this is not the BEST answer.', 'Incorrect.  Governments are most definitely a part of society; however, this is not the BEST answer.', 'Incorrect. Employers & investors are most definitely a part of society; however, this is not the BEST answer.', 'Correct. All of the above are a part of Society.', ''),
(411, 34, 129, '<p><strong>In which of the following situations would a CPA be considered independent?</strong></p>', 'The CPA was the temporary staff training instructor during the initial portion of the period.', 'The CPA had or was committed to acquire a small direct interest in the client.', 'The CPA had or was committed to acquire a large but indirect interest in the client.', 'The CPA was the controller for the firm during the initial portion of the period.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct.  The position of staff training instructor does not require decision making or indicate financial interest, which would cause the CPA to not be independent.', 'Incorrect. Acquisition of a small direct interest is specifically stated as one of the situations where the CPA is not considered to be independent.', 'Incorrect. Acquisition of a large but indirect interest in the client is specifically stated as one of the situations where the CPA is not considered to be independent.', 'Incorrect. The position of controller involves decision-making, which is specifically prohibited and affects independence.', ''),
(412, 34, 129, '<p><strong>A member who performs auditing, review, compilation, consulting, tax, or other professional services shall comply with only:</strong></p>', 'All applicable standards promulgated by bodies designated by Council.', 'The Code of Professional Ethics.', 'Generally Accepted Accounting Principles.', 'Internal Auditing Standards.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. Members have to comply with the standards set for the particular service performed.', 'Incorrect. Members have to comply with more than the Code.', 'Incorrect. Members have to comply with more than Generally Accepted Accounting Principles.', 'Incorrect. Internal Auditors are the only ones required to comply with Internal Auditing Standards.', ''),
(413, 34, 129, '<p><strong>Which one of the following professionals does not have a privileged information status with their client? </strong></p>', 'Medical doctors.', 'Certified public accountants.', 'Attorneys.', 'Religious ministers.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. A medical doctor has the privilege under our laws so that they may treat patients psychologically as well as physically.', 'Correct. For the most part, CPAs cannot disclose confidential information, but they are not protected by law or given privileged information status exempting them from being required to do so.', 'Incorrect. In order to be an advocate for their client, attorneys have the right to not disclose communications with them.', 'Incorrect. In order to  minister adequately and appropriately to members or parishioners, ministers of religious orders have privilege.', ''),
(414, 34, 129, '<p><strong>&nbsp;Which kind of <em>working papers </em>may a client request, and have a right to receive from its auditor?</strong></p>', 'Analysis and comments on management’s strengths and weaknesses.', 'Papers that contain support for a client’s journal entries and that the client does not have a copy of.', 'Auditor’s comments and conclusions concerning materiality.', 'Both a & c.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Analyses of and comments on management’s strengths and weaknesses are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client.', 'Correct. Sole support for any part of the financial statements is the basis for the client having a right to the auditor’s working papers.', 'Incorrect. Auditor’s comments and conclusions concerning materiality are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client.', 'Incorrect. Analyses of and comments on management’s strengths and weaknesses are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client and auditor’s comments and conclusions concerning materiality are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client.', ''),
(415, 34, 129, '<p><strong>Which one of the following groups does NOT require disclosure of commissions or anticipated commissions?</strong></p>', 'To the AICPA Ethics Division.', 'To those members in public practice who do not perform an audit or review, examination of prospective statements, or compilation when independent.', 'To the client.', 'The State Board of the state in which the professional is practicing in.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. No disclosure is required to the AICPA.', 'Incorrect.  A member in public practice who do not perform an audit or review, examination of prospective statements, or compilation when independent is required and is not an exception to the rules.', 'Incorrect.  A professional is always required to disclose to their client.', 'Incorrect. A professional is not required to disclose commissions or anticipated commissions to the Board of the State in which they practice.', ''),
(416, 34, 129, '<p><strong>Which of the following is NOT an Exception to client confidentiality rules:</strong></p>', 'A member must comply with a valid subpoena of a court.', 'A member must allow review by an appropriate AICPA or state CPA society.', 'A member may initiate a complaint or respond to one of a recognized investigative body.', 'A client’s name is considered non-confidential information and therefore may be revealed.', '', '4', '', '', 'Deleted', 'Incorrect.  A CPA must comply with a valid court subpoena since they do not have privileged information protection.', 'Incorrect. In order for appropriate bodies to fulfill their functions, the CPA must allow them access to files.', 'Incorrect. Initiating a complaint is a right of the member and they must respond to any proper investigative body.', 'Correct. A client’s name IS confidential and may not be revealed without their consent.', ''),
(417, 34, 130, '<p><strong>A CPA borrows $12,000 from a client for the purchase of a car and makes a $4,000 down payment. The rate and terms are the same as those that other car buyers in a similar situation would receive. A loan from the client to the CPA would:</strong></p>', 'Produce a permitted loan.', 'Affect independence.', 'Not produce a permitted loan since the CPA would be independent.', 'Not produce a permitted loan since the CPA would not be independent.', '', '1', '', '', 'Deleted', 'Correct. This loan meets all the criteria for a permitted loan.', 'Incorrect. This loan would not affect independence since the terms are the same as those for other car buyers.', 'Incorrect. This loan has the same criteria applicable to the public.', 'Incorrect. Since the terms are the same as those for other car buyers, independence would not be impaired.', ''),
(418, 34, 130, '<p><strong>The attest engagement team includes all of the following, <u>EXCEPT</u>:</strong></p>', 'The proprietor who participates in the acceptance or performance of the attest engagement.', 'The partners who participate in the acceptance or performance of the attest engagement.', 'Full- or part-time professional staff in another office of the same firm in the same state who did not participate in the attest engagement.', 'The shareholders who participate in the acceptance or performance of the attest engagement.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The proprietor has to remain independent in order to participate in the performance of the attest engagement.', 'Incorrect. The partners have to remain independent in order to participate in the performance of the attest engagement.', 'Correct. These staff members would not be required to be independent since they had nothing to do with the attest engagement and were not in the same office.', 'Incorrect. The shareholders have to remain independent in order to participate in the performance of the attest engagement.', ''),
(419, 34, 130, '<p><strong>Upon determining that a supervisor&rsquo;s recommendation for treatment of financial information could result in a material misstatement, the first step in the CPA&rsquo;s ethical obligation is to:</strong></p>', 'Quit to avoid ethical violations.', 'Communicate concerns to the external accountant and all regulatory agencies that may be involved.', 'Report the disagreement to the supervisor’s supervisor.', 'Do sufficient research and consultation to determine if the supervisor is correct.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. This is the third step.', 'Incorrect. This is the fourth step.', 'Incorrect. This is the second step.', 'Correct. Determining if the supervisor is correct is the first step of a CPA’s ethical obligation in a matter of disagreement with a supervisor.', ''),
(420, 34, 130, '<p><strong>When is a contingent fee or commission deemed to be received?</strong></p>', 'When money for services is first received.', 'When services have been performed and the fee or commission is determined.', 'When a client agrees to have a member perform a service for the client.', 'When an initial sales contact is made with a client.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The receipt of money for the first time is not the first time the fee could be deemed received.', 'Correct. When the fee or commission can be determined is the time it is deemed received.', 'Incorrect. This is not the best time to consider a fee to be received.', 'Incorrect. A fee has not yet been earned.', ''),
(421, 34, 130, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements is FALSE? &nbsp;When an Attest Function CPA performs &ldquo;Other Services&rdquo; the client must be in a position to have an informed judgment on the results of the other services and that the client understands its responsibility to:</strong></p>', 'Designate a staff member to be responsible for overseeing the services being provided.', 'Evaluate the adequacy of the services performed and any findings that result.', 'Make management decisions, including accepting responsibility for the results of the other services.', 'Establish and maintain internal controls, including monitoring ongoing activities.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. The company must designate a Management-level individual to be responsible for overseeing the services being provided, not a staff person.', 'Incorrect. The client is responsible for evaluating the adequacy of the services performed and any findings that result.', 'Incorrect. The client is responsible for making management decisions, including accepting responsibility for the results of the other services.', 'Incorrect. The client is responsible for establishing and maintaining internal controls, including monitoring ongoing activities.', ''),
(422, 34, 130, '<p><strong>Which of the following new loans to be obtained from a financial institution client where independence is required is NOT an &ldquo;Other Permitted Loan&rdquo;?</strong></p>', 'Automobile loans and leases collateralized by the automobile.', 'Loans fully collateralized by the cash surrender value of an insurance policy.', 'Loans partially collateralized by cash deposits at the same financial institution.', 'Credit cards where the aggregate outstanding balance on the current statement is reduced to $5,000 or less by the payment due date.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Collateralized automobile loans are permitted.', 'Incorrect. Fully collateralized loans by an insurance policy are permitted.', 'Correct. Partially collateralized loans are not permitted, no matter the collateral.', 'Incorrect. Credit cards of $5,000 or less are permitted.', ''),
(423, 14, 53, '<p><strong>Which of the following is <u>not</u> a reason that it is difficult to identify duplicate invoices?</strong></p>', 'They are rarely identified as duplicate or copy', 'They are sent on different colored paper', 'Duplicate invoices look just like original invoices', 'You can print 100 copies of a PDF invoice and they all look like originals', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Since duplicate invoices are rarely identified as duplicate or copy, they are difficult to find.', 'Correct. If only invoices were sent on different colored paper, they’d be easy to find. Alas, they are not.', 'Incorrect. Duplicate invoices look just like original invoices making them difficult to identify.', 'Incorrect. You can print 100 copies of a PDF invoice and they all look like originals making it very hard to tell which was the original.', ''),
(424, 14, 53, '<p><strong>What is the best practice way to eliminate calls in accounts payable looking for payment status?</strong></p>', 'Refuse to accept such calls', 'Direct such calls to purchasing', 'Set up a vendor portal with this information', 'Pay all invoices as soon as you receive them', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. While refusing to accept such calls would eliminate the problem, it is not an acceptable practice.', 'Incorrect. Directing such calls to purchasing won’t work either.', 'Correct. Setting up a vendor portal with this information lets vendors get their own information with disrupting the accounts payable department.', 'Incorrect. Paying all invoices as soon as you receive them might reduce the number of phone calls but it is not an acceptable practice for other reasons.', ''),
(425, 14, 53, '<p><strong>What is the best practice associated with petty cash?</strong></p>', 'Limit the items that can be paid through petty cash', 'Eliminate petty cash completely', 'Allow employees to submit for petty cash reimbursements anything under $100', 'Reimburse petty cash any time of the day', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Limiting the items that can be paid through petty cash is a good start but not the best practice.', 'Correct. Eliminating petty cash completely is the best practice recommendation.', 'Incorrect. Allowing employees to submit for petty cash reimbursements anything under $100 is a really bad idea.', 'Incorrect. Reimbursing through petty cash anytime of the day is another really bad practice making accounts payable inefficient.', ''),
(426, 14, 53, '<p><strong>From a best practice standpoint, how often should vendor statements be requested and reviewed?</strong></p>', 'Never', 'Annually', 'Quarterly', 'Monthly', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Never is a worst practice.', 'Incorrect. Annually is better than nothing, but not ideal.', 'Correct. Quarterly is the recommended best practice.', 'Incorrect. Monthly is overkill.', ''),
(427, 14, 53, '<p><strong>What is the best practice regarding returning checks to requisitioners?</strong></p>', 'Always return them', 'Never return them', 'Only return them when asked', 'Only return checks for independent contractors', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Always returning them is a sign of weak internal controls.', 'Correct. Never returning them to requisitioners is the recommended best practice.', 'Incorrect. Only returning them when asked is a bad practice; they should never be returned.', 'Incorrect. Only returning checks for independent contractors is another bad practice.', ''),
(428, 14, 54, '<p><strong>Which of the following is <u>not</u>&nbsp;part of a best practice accounts payable processing function?</strong></p>', 'Sharing the organization’s personnel policy with all processors', 'Establishing detailed practices for all to use', 'Developing a rigid coding standard for data entry', 'Periodically checking to verify processors are using standards established', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. Sharing the organization’s personnel policy with all processors will not help achieve a best practice accounts payable processing function.', 'Incorrect. Establishing detailed practices for all to use is part of a best practice approach.', 'Incorrect. Developing a rigid coding standard for data entry is part of a best practice approach.', 'Incorrect. Periodically checking to verify processors are using standards established is part of a best practice approach.', ''),
(429, 14, 54, '<p><strong>Which of the following practices will help prevent making a duplicate payment?</strong></p>', 'Weak master vendor file controls', 'Timely payment of original invoices', 'Strict vacation policy', 'Mandatory overtime at year end', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Weak master vendor file controls does not prevent duplicate payments but facilitates their origination.', 'Correct. Timely payment of original invoices is one of the best ways to stop a second invoice and hence a duplicate payment.', 'Incorrect. A strict vacation policy will neither help or hurt the prevention of duplicate payments.', 'Incorrect. Mandatory overtime at year end will neither help or hurt the prevention of duplicate payments.', ''),
(430, 14, 54, '<p><strong>How should a best practice accounts payable operation direct its processors to handle invoices?</strong></p>', 'Be as creative as they like', 'Follow rigid standards set by the manager and used by others in the department', 'Use the standards they used at their prior company, especially if that organization was known for its best practices', 'Do whatever they like', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Allowing them to be as creative as they like will result in chaos.', 'Correct. Following rigid standards set by the manager and used by others in the department is the best way to ensure as few problems as possible.', 'Incorrect. Using the standards they used at their prior company, even if that organization was known for its best practices, is not a good idea. With everyone doing things differently, problems will increase', 'Incorrect. Allowing them to do whatever they like is likely to cause numerous problems.', ''),
(431, 14, 54, '<p><strong>Which of the following is <u>not</u> a recommended practice to stop duplicate payments?</strong></p>', 'Double check payments on high-dollar invoices', 'Double check payments to vendors known to submit duplicate invoices', 'Review payments looking for identical dollar amounts', 'Review payments looking for early payment discounts', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Double checking of payments on high-dollar invoices is a good way to locate strategic duplicates.', 'Incorrect. Double checking payments to vendors known to submit duplicate invoices is a smart strategy and a recommended best practice.', 'Incorrect. Reviewing payments looking for identical dollar amounts is a great way to find duplicates.', 'Correct. Reviewing payments looking for early payment discounts is a good idea but will not help with the duplicate payment issue.', ''),
(432, 14, 54, '<p><strong>Which of the following is a worst practice when it comes to rush checks?</strong></p>', 'Limiting the number of rush checks', 'Issuing a rush check to anyone who requests one', 'Making rush payments with ACH instead of paper checks', 'Requiring an approval from a senior level executive to issue a rush payment', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Limiting the number of rush checks is a best practice.', 'Correct. Issuing a rush check to anyone who requests one is the worst practice and will cause the number of such payments to skyrocket.', 'Incorrect. Making rush payments with ACH instead of paper checks is likely to discourage some employees from requesting rush payments.', 'Incorrect. Requiring an approval from a senior level executive to issue a rush payment is also likely to cause some to reconsider asking for a rush payment.', ''),
(433, 14, 55, '<p><strong>What is meant by segregation of duties in the accounts payable function?</strong></p>', 'No one person can handle more than one leg of the procure-to-pay function', 'No one in accounts payable can help out in personnel', 'The computer system for accounts payable must be separate from the computer system for the rest of the company', 'Employees cannot access their work computer from home', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. No one person can handle more than one leg of the procure-to-pay function is what segregation of duties means when it pertains to the accounts payable function.', 'Incorrect. Segregation of duties is not affected if someone in accounts payable helps out in personnel.', 'Incorrect. The computer system for accounts payable must NOT be separate from the computer system for the rest of the company in order to produce financial statements and for other accounting purposes.', 'Incorrect. Whether employees can or cannot access their work computer from home is not a segregation of duties issue.', ''),
(434, 14, 55, '<p><strong>When an employee is promoted to a new position what should be done with the system access in their new position?</strong></p>', 'Nothing', 'It should be closed off', 'It is not an issue', 'It should be expanded, after all they were promoted', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. If nothing is done you will eventually have a systems access nightmare.', 'Correct. It should be closed off to prevent a segregation of duties conflict.', 'Incorrect. Promotions are most definitely an issue. Unfortunately, they are often overlooked.', 'Incorrect. This will exacerbate segregation of duties issues.', ''),
(435, 14, 55, '<p><strong>Who should notify accounts payable about an employee&rsquo;s departure, so accounts payable can notify the bank to cancel credit cards and signing authority?</strong></p>', 'Controller', 'CFO', 'CIO', 'HR', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. It is unlikely the controller will be notified making it difficult for them to notify anyone else.', 'Incorrect. It is unlikely the CFO will be notified making it difficult for them to notify anyone else.', 'Incorrect. It is unlikely the CIO will be notified making it difficult for them to notify anyone else.', 'Correct. HR (human resources) is in the loop on employee departures and is in the best position to notify accounts payable.', ''),
(436, 14, 55, '<p><strong>Which of the following is <u>not</u> considered a weak control practice?</strong></p>', 'Using a petty cash box', 'Returning checks to the requisitioner', 'Using positive pay', 'Allowing an unlimited number of rush checks', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Using a petty cash box is considered a weak control practice as well as a poor practice.', 'Incorrect. Returning checks to the requisitioner is considered a weak control practice as well as a poor practice.', 'Correct. Using positive pay is a strong control practice.', 'Incorrect. Allowing an unlimited number of rush checks is considered a weak control practice as well as a poor practice.', ''),
(437, 14, 55, '<p><strong>It is critical that accounts payable keep current on all of the following issues except which one?</strong></p>', 'Best practices', 'Investment opportunities', 'New frauds', 'New regulatory requirements for 1099s', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. It is critical that accounts payable keep on top of Best practices as it directly affects the way their job is done.', 'Correct. Investment opportunities, while important, rarely fall under the accounts payable umbrella.', 'Incorrect. It is critical that accounts payable keep on top of new frauds as it directly affects the way their job is done.', 'Incorrect. It is critical that accounts payable keep on top of new regulatory requirements for 1099s as it directly affects the way their job is done.', ''),
(438, 14, 56, '<p><strong>All online banking activity should be conducted on whose computer?</strong></p>', 'Any computer, it doesn’t really matter', 'A separate computer used only for online banking', 'The CFO’s computer', 'The accounts payable manager’s computer', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. If online banking is conducted on any computer, the chances for an account takeover increase.', 'Correct. A separate computer used only for online banking is the best way to guard against a fraudulent takeover of your bank account.', 'Incorrect. The CFO’s computer is likely to be used for web browsing and e-mail and as such is at risk for an account takeover.', 'Incorrect. The accounts payable manager’s computer is likely to be used for web browsing and e-mail and as such is at risk for an account takeover.', ''),
(439, 14, 56, '<p><strong>When wire transfer information is requested via a phone call, what is the best practice?</strong></p>', 'Give it to the person calling', 'Ask the person for their e-mail address and e-mail it to them', 'Ask the person for their fax number and fax it to them', 'Don’t give it out over the phone at all', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Giving it to the person calling will ensure you give it to any crook who happens to be smart enough to call and ask. Thus it is not a good practice.', 'Incorrect. Asking the person for their e-mail address and e-mailing it to them will also ensure the information might end up in the wrong hands.', 'Incorrect. Asking the person for their fax number and faxing it to them will also ensure the information might end up in the wrong hands.', 'Correct. By not giving it out over the phone at all, you improve your chances of not having the information fall into the wrong hands.', ''),
(440, 14, 56, '<p><strong>What is the best policy for posting vendor information on the Internet?</strong></p>', 'Post all of it where everyone can view it', 'Don’t put it on the Internet', 'Put it on the internet if you have a password protected portal for your vendors', 'It doesn’t really matter; it’s not an issue', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Posting all vendor information where everyone can view it will make it easier for crooks looking to defraud your organization.', 'Incorrect. Not putting it on the Internet is overkill, if there is an alternative.', 'Correct. Putting it on the internet if you have a password protected portal for your vendors provides the protection your organization needs against fraud while providing your vendors with needed information.', 'Incorrect. It does really matter; it is definitely an issue.', ''),
(441, 14, 56, '<p><strong>In accounts payable, who should be required to take a mandatory vacation of at least five days?</strong></p>', 'Everyone who has anything to do with the payment function', 'No one', 'Only those in management or supervisory positions', 'Only those who process invoices', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. Everyone who has anything to do with the payment function should take at least five consecutive days off. If there is any ongoing fraud, it should unravel in that time period.', 'Incorrect. No one is wrong; there is always the risk of fraud', 'Incorrect. By only requiring those in management or supervisory positions to take mandatory vacations, you only address part of the issue.', 'Incorrect. By only requiring those who process invoices to take mandatory vacations, you only address part of the issue.', ''),
(442, 14, 56, '<p><strong>What is the <u>worst</u> practice when it comes to job rotation of invoice processors?</strong></p>', 'Require that they stay with the same accounts as long as they work for the organization', 'Leave it up to the individual processors to decide if and when they want to change', 'Require that they rotate every six months', 'Require that they rotate every five years', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. Requiring processors to stay with the same accounts as long as they work for the organization will increase the risk of collusion and fraud.', 'Incorrect. Leaving it up to the individual processors to decide if and when they want to change is not a great idea but not as bad as requiring that they stay.', 'Incorrect. Requiring that they rotate every six months is the best practice, so definitely not the worst.', 'Incorrect. Requiring that they rotate every five years is not a great idea but not as bad as requiring that they stay.', ''),
(443, 14, 56, '<p><strong>What is the best practice approach when a request for bank account change is made by a vendor currently being paid by ACH?</strong></p>', 'Go ahead and make the change as requested', 'Call the phone number provided in the e-mail to verify the request', 'Ignore the request', 'Call or email a contact using information currently on file', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. If you go ahead and make the change as requested, you will honor fraudulent requests.', 'Incorrect. If you call the phone number provided in the e-mail to verify the request, you will honor fraudulent requests.', 'Incorrect. If you ignore the request, you won’t be addressing the needs of legitimate requests.', 'Correct. Call or email a contact using information currently on file is the best way to ferret out fraudulent requests while honoring legitimate ones.', ''),
(444, 14, 57, '<p><strong>Which of the following represents a best practice when it comes to the use of positive pay?</strong></p>', 'It is not a best practice to use positive pay', 'Use payee name positive pay, if available', 'Use of positive pay is a worst practice', 'It is neither a good or a bad practice to use positive pay', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. It is absolutely incorrect to indicate that to use of positive pay is not a best practice. It is the best defense against check fraud.', 'Correct. Use payee name positive pay, if available is the best choice and the recommended best practice.', 'Incorrect. Of course, use of positive pay is not a worst practice.', 'Incorrect. To say use of positive is neither a good nor a bad practice is incorrect.', ''),
(445, 14, 57, '<p><strong>Which of the following represents a best practice when it comes to preprinted check stock?</strong></p>', 'There is no best practice related to use of preprinted check stock', 'Get rid of preprinted check stock', 'Use of preprinted check stock is a best practice', 'Preprinted check stock does not need special storage', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. That there is no best practice related to use of preprinted check stock is just not true.', 'Correct. Getting rid of preprinted check stock is the best alternative now that laser printing has made the process much safer and more efficient.', 'Incorrect. Use of preprinted check stock is NOT a best practice.', 'Incorrect. Preprinted check stock absolutely does need special storage considerations.', ''),
(446, 14, 57, '<p><strong>Preprinted check stock should be stored in which of the following manners?</strong></p>', 'In a secure, locked closet', 'In a file cabinet', 'In a desk drawer of an unlocked desk', 'Near the printer for ease of use', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. A secure, locked closet is the recommended way to store pre-printed check stock.', 'Incorrect. Putting check stock in a file cabinet makes it easy for anyone to steal and use for purposes not intended.', 'Incorrect. Putting check stock in a desk drawer of an unlocked desk makes it easy for a crook to steal.', 'Incorrect. Putting check stock near the printer for ease of use might make it operationally more efficient but increases the risk of check fraud exponentially.', ''),
(447, 14, 57, '<p><strong>Which of the following will help prevent check fraud?</strong></p>', 'Returning checks to requisitioners', 'Delivering checks to the mailroom early in the day', 'Using positive pay', 'Allowing as many rush checks as wanted', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Returning checks to requisitioners is a good way to increase the potential for internal check fraud.', 'Incorrect. Delivering checks to the mailroom early in the day will increase the time it spends there as well as the potential for someone to snatch a check made out to someone else.', 'Correct. Using positive pay is the best way to prevent check fraud.', 'Incorrect. Allowing as many rush checks as wanted will also increase the chance for check fraud.', ''),
(448, 14, 58, '<p><strong>How frequently should the travel and entertainment policy be updated?</strong></p>', 'It doesn’t need to be updated', 'Whenever there’s a change', 'Whenever the CFO indicates it should be updated', 'Whenever there is a change on the board of directors', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. If the policy isn’t updated it will become ineffective and useless.', 'Correct. Whenever there’s a change is when the policy should be updated. For most organizations, this will be several times a year.', 'Incorrect. Updating only when the CFO indicates it should be might result in the policy never being updated. This is not a good barometer for when it should be updated.', 'Incorrect. Whenever there is a change on the board of directors is not relevant. While it is an important event for the organization, it has little impact on the travel policy.', ''),
(449, 14, 58, '<p><strong>In an ideal situation, how are policy violations handled during the expense reporting process?</strong></p>', 'They are ignored', 'They are not an issue at most organizations', 'They are flagged for further review', 'They are flagged but no one reviews them', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Ignoring policy violations is an extremely poor practice and will result in violations growing.', 'Incorrect. Unfortunately, they are an issue for most organizations.', 'Correct. Flagging violations for further review is the best approach.', 'Incorrect. It is a waste of effort to flag violations if no one reviews them.', ''),
(450, 14, 58, '<p><strong>When it comes to checking details on expense reports, the recommended best practice is which of the following?</strong></p>', '100% of all returns be checked', 'Spot check 5-10%', 'Only check the expense reports of sales', 'No checking is necessary; managers should do that', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. If 100% of all returns are checked, the organization is wasting valuable resources that could be used elsewhere.', 'Correct. Spot check 5-10% is the best approach, especially for large organizations', 'Incorrect. Only check the expense reports of sales will result in potential abuse growing in other parts of the organization.', 'Incorrect. While in an ideal world no checking would be necessary as managers would have already done it, that approach does not work in the environment we live in.', ''),
(451, 14, 58, '<p><strong>The IRS requires organizations have receipts for all expenditures over what dollar limit?</strong></p>', '$10', '$25', '$75', '$1', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. $10 is not the correct response.', 'Incorrect. $25 is not the correct response, although many believe this is the right level.', 'Correct. $75 is the correct response, although few organizations have followed their lead.', 'Incorrect. $1 is not the correct response, although many feel this is the best level.', ''),
(452, 14, 58, '<p><strong>Why are a growing number of companies now considering getting the detailed meal receipts from employees putting in for expense reimbursements for those meals?</strong></p>', 'It is an IRS requirement', 'It is required by Sarbanes-Oxley', 'To determine if dessert was ordered', 'To determine if what was ordered conforms to the policy or if there was fraud', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. It is not an IRS requirement.', 'Incorrect. It is not required by Sarbanes-Oxley', 'Incorrect. Determining if dessert was ordered really won’t help much with policy compliance issues.', 'Correct. Determining if what was ordered conforms to the policy or if there was fraud is the correct response.', ''),
(453, 14, 59, '<p><strong>What is the best practice any organization can have regarding cash advances?</strong></p>', 'Give them to everyone', 'Eliminate them', 'Give them only to the sales staff', 'Give them only to those who request them', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Giving them to everyone will result in a massive and unnecessary tracking issue as well as encourage tardiness when submitting reports.', 'Correct. Eliminating cash advances is the recommended best practice.', 'Incorrect. Giving them only to the sales staff is not a good idea; no one should get them.', 'Incorrect. Giving them only to those who request them is likely to encourage everyone to ask.', ''),
(454, 14, 59, '<p><strong>Why are unused tickets a problem?</strong></p>', 'If not tracked, they will go unused and the organization will get no value for their expenditure', 'They are not a problem', 'Employees often use them to take their spouses along on a business trip', 'They take too much effort to track', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. If not tracked, they will go unused and the organization will get no value for their expenditure is the correct response.', 'Incorrect. They are a problem, especially when paper tickets are rarely used.', 'Incorrect. While a few employees might use them to take their spouses along on a business trip, that does not seem to be a big problem.', 'Incorrect. They take effort to track but that is fine given they represent value for the organization.', ''),
(455, 14, 59, '<p><strong>When an employee leaves the company, which of the following should <u>not</u> be recovered from the employee?</strong></p>', 'Excess cash advances', 'The travel card', 'Their last pay check', 'The key to the building', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Excess cash advances should definitely be recovered.', 'Incorrect. The travel card should definitely be recovered.', 'Correct. Their last pay check belongs to the employee and should NOT be returned to the organization.', 'Incorrect. The key to the building should definitely be recovered.', ''),
(456, 14, 59, '<p><strong>Which of the following is typically <u>not</u> part of a best practice travel reservation policy?</strong></p>', 'Requiring the employee get the best price, taking into account whether the trip might need to be canceled', 'Ensuring policy compliancy', 'Ensuring travel begins on a weekend day', 'Ensuring use of preferred providers, if preferred rates have been negotiated', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. This is part of a best practice reservation policy.', 'Incorrect. Ensuring policy compliancy is part of a best practice reservation policy.', 'Correct. Ensuring travel begins on a weekend day is not a good idea and is likely to lead to discontent among traveling employees.', 'Incorrect. Ensuring use of preferred providers, if preferred rates have been negotiated is part of a best practice reservation policy.', ''),
(457, 14, 59, '<p><strong>What is the best practice method for reimbursing employees for business travel?</strong></p>', 'Paper check mailed to the home', 'Paper check picked up in the accounts payable office', 'Including expenses in paychecks', 'ACH deposit separate from payroll', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Paper check mailed to the home is not the best practice recommendation.', 'Incorrect. Paper check picked up in the accounts payable office is a worst practice.', 'Incorrect. Including expenses in paychecks doesn’t provide employees who wish their expense reimbursements to go elsewhere any flexibility.', 'Correct. ACH deposit, separate from payroll, is the recommended best practice.', ''),
(458, 14, 60, '<p><strong>What is the best practice when it comes to requesting a W-9 for all vendors?</strong></p>', 'Require a W-9 before the first purchase order is written', 'Leave it to the vendor’s discretion as to whether they supply the W-9', 'Let vendors provide the information verbally instead of giving the W-9', 'Leave it up to the discretion of the processors', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. Requiring a W-9 before the first purchase order is written is the recommended best practice in this area.', 'Incorrect. Leaving it to the vendor’s discretion as to whether they supply the W-9 will result in very few W-9s being collected.', 'Incorrect. Letting vendors provide the information verbally instead of giving the W-9 will result in errors in the information due to misunderstandings, transpositions etc.', 'Incorrect. Leaving it up to the discretion of the processors will also result in very few W-9s being collected', ''),
(459, 14, 60, '<p><strong>When it comes to W-9s, a good collection policy includes all of the following <u>except</u> which item?</strong></p>', 'Send out requests to all new vendors', 'Track who returns completed W-9s', 'Make copies of W-9s sent in', 'Follow up with those who don’t return W-9s', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Sending out requests to all new vendors should be part of a best practice policy.', 'Incorrect. Track who returns completed W-9s should be part of a best practice policy.', 'Correct. Making copies of W-9s sent in is just make work and adds no value.', 'Incorrect. Following up with those who don’t return W-9s should be part of a best practice policy.', '');
INSERT INTO `chapter_review_questions` (`rev_ques_id`, `course_id`, `chapter_id`, `rev_ques_title`, `rev_ques_ans_1`, `rev_ques_ans_2`, `rev_ques_ans_3`, `rev_ques_ans_4`, `rev_ques_ans_5`, `rev_correct_ans_id`, `rev_correct_ans_text`, `rev_wronge_ans_text`, `rev_ques_status`, `ans1_text`, `ans2_text`, `ans3_text`, `ans4_text`, `ans5_text`) VALUES
(460, 14, 60, '<p><strong>Which of the following is the best reason to use the IRS TIN Matching system?</strong></p>', 'It is required by the IRS', 'It is easy', 'A reduction in the number of B-Notices', 'You won’t have to issue 1099s if you use it', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. It is not required by the IRS, at least at this time.', 'Incorrect. It is easy is not a good reason for doing something', 'Correct. A reduction in the number of B-Notices is the best reason to use TIN Matching.', 'Incorrect. You won’t have to issue 1099s if you use it is absolutely NOT true.', ''),
(461, 14, 61, '<p><strong>Which of the following practices will land you in hot water should unclaimed property auditors show up to audit your books?</strong></p>', 'Reporting and remitting all unclaimed property', 'Writing off un-cashed checks to miscellaneous income', 'Reporting un-cashed checks as unclaimed property', 'Trying to find the rightful owners of unclaimed property before reporting', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Reporting and remitting all unclaimed property is what you are supposed to do and won’t cause any problems.', 'Correct. Writing off un-cashed checks to miscellaneous income is a huge no-no. In fact, one of the first places auditors look to make sure you are doing what you are supposed to be doing is at your miscellaneous income account.', 'Incorrect. Reporting un-cashed checks as unclaimed property is what you are supposed to do and won’t cause any problems.', 'Incorrect. Trying to find the rightful owners of unclaimed property before reporting is what you are supposed to do and won’t cause any problems.', ''),
(462, 14, 61, '<p><strong>Organizations are expected by the states to perform which of the following actions regarding their unclaimed property?</strong></p>', 'Research items to see if they can find the rightful owner (due diligence)', 'Nothing', 'Take classes on unclaimed property', 'Study unclaimed property requirements in school', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. Researching items to see if they can find the rightful owner (due diligence) is what the states want done. They don’t want property turned over only to be immediately claimed by the rightful owners.', 'Incorrect. The states expect you to return the funds rather than turning them over to the states.', 'Incorrect. There is no requirement currently that you take classes on unclaimed property.', 'Incorrect. There is no requirement currently that you study unclaimed property requirements in school', ''),
(463, 14, 61, '<p><strong>Which of the following is now being used to locate rightful owners of unclaimed property by some organizations?</strong></p>', 'Twitter', 'Pinterest', 'YouTube', 'Facebook and LinkedIn', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Twitter is not appropriate for locating rightful owners of unclaimed property.', 'Incorrect. Pinterest is not appropriate for locating rightful owners of unclaimed property.', 'Incorrect. YouTube is not appropriate for locating rightful owners of unclaimed property.', 'Correct. Interestingly, Facebook and LinkedIn have turned out to be viable avenues for locating rightful owners of unclaimed property.', ''),
(464, 14, 62, '<p><strong>Which of the following is <u>not</u> a worst practice when it comes to proper handling of sales and use tax?</strong></p>', 'Accruing use tax on items where sales tax was owed but not collected', 'Paying all sales tax owed to one state', 'Not checking purchases made with p-cards to ensure the proper sales tax was collected', 'Adding sales tax to an invoice payment if the vendor forgot to include it', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. Accruing use tax on items where sales tax was owed but not collected is exactly what you are supposed to do, so clearly it is not a worst practice.', 'Incorrect. Paying all sales tax owed to one state will get you in trouble with all the states where taxes are owed except the one you paid.', 'Incorrect. Not checking purchases made with p-cards to ensure the proper sales tax was collected is likely to result in a few items being missed.', 'Incorrect. Adding sales tax to an invoice payment if the vendor forgot to include it will not get the tax paid; it will simply get you a credit with the vendor.', ''),
(465, 14, 62, '<p><strong>From a best practice standpoint, when should vendors be checked against the OFAC list?</strong></p>', 'Once a month', 'Only when the vendor is set up', 'Before each payment is made', 'Annually', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Once a month, while better than not doing it at all, is not sufficient.', 'Incorrect. Only when the vendor is set up, while better than not doing it at all, is not sufficient.', 'Correct. Before each payment is made is what is expected although not many organizations meet this directive.', 'Incorrect. Annually, while better than not doing it at all, is not sufficient.', ''),
(466, 14, 62, '<p><strong>The Foreign Corrupt Practices Act specifically forbids bribery to which of the following parties?</strong></p>', 'Anyone', 'Foreign officials', 'Foreign vendors', 'Foreign employees', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The Act is not that restrictive, and while it might not be good policy, there are people you can bribe and not be breaking the law.', 'Correct. Foreign officials are specifically mentioned in the Act.', 'Incorrect. Foreign vendors are not mentioned in the Act.', 'Incorrect. Foreign employees are not mentioned in the Act.', ''),
(467, 14, 63, '<p><strong>Which of the following describes a best practice technology plan for the accounts payable function?</strong></p>', 'It should be rigid and not change too much', 'It should be as flexible or rigid as the staff likes', 'It should always take advantage of the newest innovations', 'It should be flexible to adapt to whatever new innovations are developed', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. A policy that is rigid and doesn’t change much is not likely to service a best practice organization well.', 'Incorrect. A policy that is as flexible or rigid as the staff likes is not likely to provide the best direction.', 'Incorrect. A policy that always takes advantage of the newest innovations is not likely to distinguish between those innovations that are appropriate for the accounts payable function and those that are not.', 'Correct. Flexibility is the best practice.', ''),
(468, 14, 63, '<p><strong>Invoices accepted by e-mail should all be sent to which of the following?</strong></p>', 'One centralized e-mail address used specifically for this purpose', 'The purchasing person responsible for the transaction', 'The accounts payable managers personal e-mail address', 'Wherever the vendor wishes to send them', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. One centralized e-mail address used specifically to receive invoices and nothing else.', 'Incorrect. The purchasing person responsible for the transaction should not receive invoices as he or she may not forward them in a timely manner.', 'Incorrect. The accounts payable managers personal e-mail address should not be used as it will mix invoices with other e-mails and will not be addressed when the manager is out.', 'Incorrect. This is not a great way to centralize the receipt of invoices.', ''),
(469, 14, 63, '<p><strong>Which of the following is a good place to learn about invoice automation?</strong></p>', 'The newspaper', 'Popular magazines', 'Vendor webinars', 'The radio', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The newspaper is unlikely to have useful or accurate information.', 'Incorrect. Popular magazines are unlikely to have useful or accurate information.', 'Correct. Vendor webinars are a great source of information, especially about invoice automation capabilities.', 'Incorrect. The radio is unlikely to have useful or accurate information.', ''),
(470, 14, 63, '<p><strong>Why shouldn&rsquo;t employees use their own devices (Smartphones or tablets) to release ACH transactions and wires?</strong></p>', 'The company didn’t pay for the devices', 'The devices may not have the proper security protections', 'The devices aren’t capable', 'The devices make mistakes', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. While the company not paying for the devices might be true, it has no impact on their suitability for payment work.', 'Correct. The fact that the devices may not have the proper security protections is a legitimate concern.', 'Incorrect. The devices are very capable and that is why people are starting to use them for this purpose.', 'Incorrect. The devices don’t make mistakes so this is not a valid consideration.', ''),
(471, 14, 64, '<p><strong>Information can effectively be shared with vendors using all of the following <u>except</u> which one?&nbsp;</strong></p>', 'A welcome letter', 'The annual report', 'A vendor handbook', 'A password protected section of the website devoted to vendor issues', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. A welcome letter is a good start to sharing information with vendors.', 'Correct. The annual report does nothing to share vital information with vendors on topics of interest to them.', 'Incorrect. A vendor handbook is another good way to share information with vendors.', 'Incorrect. A password-protected section of the website devoted to vendor issues is an excellent way to share information with vendors.', ''),
(472, 14, 64, '<p><strong>All of the following <u>except</u> which tactic can be used to communicate accounts payable&rsquo;s requirements with the rest of the organization?</strong></p>', 'Sharing the AP Policy and Procedures manual with others', 'Periodically sending a short AP newsletter', 'Writing an article for a trade publication', 'Publishing cut off dates for T&E and vendor payments', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Sharing the AP Policy and Procedures manual with others is a good way for others to see what they need to do to get paid on time.', 'Incorrect. Periodically sending a short AP newsletter is a great way to share information with the rest of the company in a short interesting manner.', 'Correct. Writing an article for a trade publication will do little to communicate without your own organization.', 'Incorrect. Publishing cut off dates for T&E and vendor payments is another great way to share relevant information with the rest of the organization.', ''),
(473, 14, 64, '<p><strong>All of the following <u>except</u> which tactic are likely to improve relations between purchasing and accounts payable?</strong></p>', 'Looking at conflicts from the other''s point of view', 'Spending time performing the other’s work', 'Ignoring the problem when two staff are sniping at each other', 'Interdepartmental lunches', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Looking at conflicts from the others point of view is a good way to improve relations with any group, including purchasing.', 'Incorrect. Spending time performing the others work is a nifty way to understand the other side of the coin.', 'Correct. Ignoring the problem when the two staffs are sniping at each other will make the relations worse.', 'Incorrect. Interdepartmental lunches are a good way to get the two groups talking to each other.', ''),
(474, 14, 64, '<p><strong>All of the following <u>except</u> which tactic are likely to improve relations between purchasing and accounts payable?</strong></p>', 'Looking at conflicts from the other''s point of view', 'Spending time performing the other’s work', 'Ignoring the problem when two staff are sniping at each other', 'Interdepartmental lunches', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Looking at conflicts from the others point of view is a good way to improve relations with any group, including purchasing.', 'Incorrect. Spending time performing the others work is a nifty way to understand the other side of the coin.', 'Correct. Ignoring the problem when the two staffs are sniping at each other will make the relations worse.', 'Incorrect. Interdepartmental lunches are a good way to get the two groups talking to each other.', ''),
(475, 14, 64, '<p><strong>Which of the following is a worst practice when it comes to customer service in accounts payable?</strong></p>', 'Taking a ‘we’re the customer and always right’ approach', 'Looking for ways to bridge the gap when there are problems', 'Looking at the problem from the other’s perspective', 'Responding within a reasonable amount of time to all vendor inquiries', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. Taking a ‘we’re the customer and always right’ approach is likely to deteriorate a customer service attitude.', 'Incorrect. Looking for ways to bridge the gap when there are problems is a good practice, not a bad one.', 'Incorrect. Looking at the problem from the other’s perspective is a good practice, not a bad one.', 'Incorrect. Responding within a reasonable amount of time to all vendor inquiries is a good practice, not a bad one.', ''),
(476, 14, 65, '<p><strong>From a best practice standpoint, when should your organization take early payment discounts?</strong></p>', 'Whenever they are offered if you pay within 5 days of the early payment discount date', 'Whenever they are offered if you pay within 15 days of the early payment discount date', 'Whenever they are offered regardless of when you pay', 'Whenever they are offered if you pay within the early payment discount period', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. While this isn’t the worst practice we’ve ever seen, paying within 5 days of the early payment discount date is not the best practice.', 'Incorrect. Paying within 15 days of the early payment discount date is starting to push the envelope and is definitely not a best practice.', 'Incorrect. Taking the discount whenever they are offered regardless of when you pay is a worst practice and most vendors will no longer tolerate it.', 'Correct. Taking early payment discounts only if you pay within the early payment discount period is not only the recommended best practice, it is the fair practice.', ''),
(477, 14, 65, '<p><strong>What is the best practice regarding payment timing?</strong></p>', 'Pay the right amount at the right time', 'Stretch small vendors', 'Stretch all vendors for as long as you can', 'Stretch all vendors that don’t complain', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. Paying the right amount at the right time is the recommended best practice.', 'Incorrect. Stretching small vendors is an abhorrent practice and not recommended at all.', 'Incorrect. Stretching all vendors for as long as you can is likely to lead to extra work (and expense) along with an increase in duplicate payments.', 'Incorrect. Stretching all vendors that don’t complain is another less-than-desirable practice and should be avoided at all costs.', ''),
(478, 14, 65, '<p><strong>What is the very best way to reduce the number of &lsquo;where&rsquo;s my money calls?</strong></p>', 'Refuse to take the calls', 'Pay on time', 'Assign one person to handle all calls', 'Only take these calls one or two days a week', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Refusing to take the calls is likely to create havoc as vendors looking for their money will call other people within the organization.', 'Correct. Paying on time is the best way to eliminate these calls', 'Incorrect. Assigning one person to handle all calls will not impact the number of calls.', 'Incorrect. Only taking these calls one or two days a week will not limit the number and is likely to incense vendors.', ''),
(479, 37, 131, '<p><strong>Which of the following is a synonym for &ldquo;ethics&rdquo;?</strong></p>', 'Moral practice', 'Social values', 'Decency', 'All of the above', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Moral practice is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. Social values are not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. Decency is not the best answer.', 'Correct. All of the above answers are synonyms for “ethics.”', ''),
(480, 37, 131, '<p><strong>Which of the following best completes the sentence?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A member who departs from Rulings in similar circumstances:</strong></p>', 'Will be requested to justify the departure.', 'Is still ethical since these are not principles, but only rulings.', 'Is not considered ethical, but because of the circumstances does not have to justify it.', 'Is still ethical since rulings are only guidelines.', '', '1', '', '', 'Deleted', 'Correct.  A member that departs from a “Ruling” has to defend that position or be found guilty of violating the Code of Professional Ethics.', 'Incorrect.  Rulings are an official part of the Code of Professional Ethics.', 'Incorrect. Rulings summarize the application of Rules of Conduct.', 'Incorrect Interpretations to a particular set of factual circumstances.', ''),
(481, 37, 131, '<p><strong>A member of the AICPA is responsible to which of the following groups?</strong></p>', 'The state society to which the member belongs.', 'The appropriate state board of accountancy.', 'The AICPA ethics division.', 'All of the above.', '', '4', '', '', 'Deleted', 'Incorrect. The state society to which the member belongs is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. The appropriate state board of accountancy is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. The AICPA ethics division is not the best answer.', 'Correct. All of the answers above are appropriate.', ''),
(482, 37, 131, '<p><strong>Which of the following words is <u>NOT</u> a synonym of &ldquo;ethical&rdquo;?</strong></p>', 'Honest', 'Conscientious', 'Moral', 'Humane', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Honest is being ethical.', 'Incorrect. Being Conscientious is being ethical.', 'Correct. Moral may or may not be ethical. The Mafia has their “moral code” which society does not consider ethical.', 'Incorrect. Being Humane is being ethical.', ''),
(483, 37, 131, '<p><strong>The sections of the Code consist of _________ and _________:</strong></p>', 'Principles and Standards.', 'Rules and Standards.', 'Principles and Rules.', 'Rules, Principles, and Standards.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Standards are not one of the sections.', 'Incorrect.  Principles must be one of the sections.', 'Correct. The two sections are Principles and Rules.', 'Incorrect. Standards are a subset of the Rules, not one of the sections.', ''),
(484, 37, 131, '<p><strong>Which of the following is NOT considered a Covered Member? </strong></p>', 'An individual on the attest engagement team.', 'A Partner in an office in the same state.', 'An individual in a position to influence the attest engagement.', 'The firm, including the firm''s employee benefit plans.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. An individual on the attest engagement team is a Covered Member.', 'Correct. A Partner in an office in the same state is not necessarily a covered member.  Other attributes must be present.', 'Incorrect. An individual in a position to influence the attest engagement is a Covered Member.', 'Incorrect. The firm, including the firm''s employee benefit plans, is a Covered Member.', ''),
(485, 37, 131, '<p><strong>A member should consult, in addition to the Code of Professional Ethics, if applicable, the ethical standards of:</strong></p>', 'The state society to which the member belongs.', 'The appropriate state board of accountancy.', 'The AICPA ethics division.', 'All of the above.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The state society to which the member belongs is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. The appropriate state board of accountancy is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. The AICPA ethics division is not the best answer.', 'Correct. All of the above answers are appropriate.', ''),
(486, 37, 132, '<p><strong>Which one of the following definitions is NOT correct?</strong></p>', 'Council: the Council of the AICPA', 'Member: a member, associate member, or international associate of the AICPA.', 'Professional services: all services performed by a member while performing public accounting services.', 'Institute: the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Council is properly defined as “The Council of the AICPA.” The Council is the governing body of the AICPA and is comprised of approximately 265 members and representatives from every state and U.S. Territory. Council meets twice a year, in May and October, and Regional Council meetings are held every year in March.', 'Incorrect.  Member is properly defined as “A member, associate member, or international associate of the AICPA.”', 'Correct. Professional services include all services performed by a member while holding out as a CPA, not just while performing public accounting services.', 'Incorrect. Institute is properly defined as “The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants.”', ''),
(487, 37, 132, '<p><strong>Which of the following items completes the following sentence?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Independence in Fact:</strong></p>', 'involves impartiality.', 'indicates that the member has abstained from relationships that appear to prevent objectivity.', 'is a state of mind.', 'involves freedom from conflicts of interest.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Impartiality is connected with objectivity.', 'Incorrect. Independence in appearance, not fact, involves actions such as abstaining from relationships.', 'Correct. Independence is attitudinal - a state of mind. Independence in appearance involves actions.', 'Incorrect. Objectivity involves actions such as freedom from conflicts of interest.', ''),
(488, 37, 132, '<p><strong>The unique characteristics of the accounting profession that set it apart from the rest of society is its acceptance of its responsibility to:</strong></p>', 'Its clients', 'The government and its agencies', 'The public', 'Investors', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. A profession is responsible to its clients, but this is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. A profession is responsible to certain government agencies at times, but this is not the best answer.', 'Correct.  A profession is responsible to its public, which is unique.', 'Incorrect. A profession is responsible to investors sometimes, but this is not the best answer.', ''),
(489, 37, 132, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements is NOT correct? </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A Key position is a position in which an individual: </strong></p>', 'Has primary responsibility for significant accounting functions that support material components of the financial statements.', 'Has responsibility for the sales force.', 'Has primary responsibility for the preparation of the financial statements.', 'Has the ability to exercise influence over the contents of the financial statements, including when the individual is a member of the board of directors.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Having primary responsibility for significant accounting functions that support material components of the financial statements gives the possibility of adversely affecting the financial statements and they are therefore in a key position.', 'Correct. Having responsibility for the sales force does NOT allow the person to impact adversely the financial statements.', 'Incorrect.  Primary responsibility for the preparation of the financial statements allows the individual to adversely impact the financial statements and makes them in a key position.', 'Incorrect. The ability to exercise influence over the contents of the financial statements in any capacity is a key position.', ''),
(490, 37, 132, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements is the BEST answer? &nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>All sections of society are recipients &hellip; of the work of the profession. Society includes:</strong></p>', 'Clients & credit grantors', 'Governments', 'Employers & investors', 'All of the above', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Clients & credit grantors are most definitely a part of society; however, this is not the BEST answer.', 'Incorrect.  Governments are most definitely a part of society; however, this is not the BEST answer.', 'Incorrect. Employers & investors are most definitely a part of society; however, this is not the BEST answer.', 'Correct. All of the above are a part of Society.', ''),
(491, 37, 133, '<p><strong>In which of the following situations would a CPA be considered independent?</strong></p>', 'The CPA was the temporary staff training instructor during the initial portion 		of the period.', 'The CPA had or was committed to acquire a small direct interest in the client.', 'The CPA had or was committed to acquire a large but indirect interest in the client.', 'The CPA was the controller for the firm during the initial portion of the period.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. The position of staff training instructor does not require decision making or indicate financial interest, which would cause the CPA to not be independent.', 'Incorrect. Acquisition of a small direct interest is specifically stated as one of the situations where the CPA is not considered to be independent.', 'Incorrect. Acquisition of a large but indirect interest in the client is specifically stated as one of the situations where the CPA is not considered to be independent.', 'Incorrect. The position of controller involves decision-making, which is specifically prohibited and affects independence.', ''),
(492, 37, 133, '<p><strong>A member who performs auditing, review, compilation, consulting, tax, or other professional services shall comply with only:</strong></p>', 'All applicable standards promulgated by bodies designated by Council.', 'The Code of Professional Ethics.', 'Generally Accepted Accounting Principles.', 'Internal Auditing Standards.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. Members have to comply with the standards set for the particular service performed.', 'Incorrect. Members have to comply with more than the Code.', 'Incorrect. Members have to comply with more than Generally Accepted Accounting Principles.', 'Incorrect. Internal Auditors are the only ones required to comply with Internal Auditing Standards.', ''),
(493, 37, 133, '<p><strong>Which one of the following professionals does NOT have a privileged information status with their client? </strong></p>', 'Medical doctors', 'Certified public accountants', 'Attorneys', 'Religious ministers', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. A medical doctor has the privilege under our laws so that they may treat patients psychologically as well as physically.', 'Correct. For the most part, CPAs cannot disclose confidential information, but they are not protected by law or given privileged information status exempting them from being required to do so.', 'Incorrect. In order to be an advocate for their client, attorneys have the right to not disclose communications with them.', 'Incorrect. In order to minister adequately and appropriately to members or parishioners, ministers of religious orders have privilege.', ''),
(494, 37, 133, '<p><strong>What kind of working papers may a client request, and have a right to receive from its auditor?</strong></p>', 'Analysis and comments on management’s strengths and weaknesses.', 'Papers that contain support for a client’s journal entries and that the client does not have a copy of.', 'Auditor’s comments and conclusions concerning materiality.', 'Both a & c.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Analyses of and comments on management’s strengths and weaknesses are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client.', 'Correct. Sole support for any part of the financial statements is the basis for the client having a right to the auditor’s working papers.', 'Incorrect. Auditor’s comments and conclusions concerning materiality are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client.', 'Incorrect. Analyses of and comments on management’s strengths and weaknesses are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client. Auditor’s comments and conclusions concerning materiality are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client.', ''),
(495, 37, 133, '<p><strong>Which one of the following groups does NOT require disclosure of commissions or anticipated commissions?</strong></p>', 'The AICPA Ethics Division', 'Those members in public practice who do not perform an audit or review, examination of prospective statements, or compilation when independent.', 'The client.', 'The State Board of the state in which the professional is practicing in.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. No disclosure is required to the AICPA.', 'Incorrect.  A member in public practice who do not perform an audit or review, examination of prospective statements, or compilation when independent is required and is not an exception to the rules.', 'Incorrect.  A professional is always required to disclose to their client.', 'Incorrect. A professional is not required to disclose commissions or anticipated commissions to the Board of the State in which they practice.', ''),
(496, 37, 133, '<p><strong>Which of the following is NOT an exception to client confidentiality rules:</strong></p>', 'A member must comply with a valid subpoena of a court.', 'A member must allow review by an appropriate AICPA or state CPA society.', 'A member may initiate a complaint or respond to one of a recognized investigative body.', 'A client’s name is considered non-confidential information and therefore may be revealed.', '', '4', '', '', 'Deleted', 'Incorrect.  A CPA must comply with a valid court subpoena since they do not have privileged information protection.', 'Incorrect. In order for appropriate bodies to fulfill their functions, the CPA must allow them access to files.', 'Incorrect. Initiating a complaint is a right of the member and they must respond to any proper investigative body.', 'Correct. A client’s name IS confidential and may not be revealed without their consent.', ''),
(497, 37, 134, '<p><strong>A CPA borrows $12,000 from a client for the purchase of a car and makes a $4,000 down payment. The rate and terms are the same as those that other car buyers in a similar situation would receive. A loan from the client to the CPA would:</strong></p>', 'Produce a permitted loan.', 'Affect independence.', 'Not produce a permitted loan since the CPA would be independent.', 'Not produce a permitted loan since the CPA would not be independent.', '', '1', '', '', 'Deleted', 'Correct. This loan meets all the criteria for a permitted loan.', 'Incorrect. This loan would not affect independence since the terms are the same as those for other car buyers.', 'Incorrect. This loan has the same criteria applicable to the public.', 'Incorrect. Since the terms are the same as those for other car buyers, independence would not be impaired.', ''),
(498, 37, 134, '<p><strong>The attest engagement team includes all of the following, EXCEPT:</strong></p>', 'The proprietor who participates in the acceptance or performance of the attest engagement.', 'The partners who participate in the acceptance or performance of the attest engagement.', 'Full- or part-time professional staff in another office of the same firm in the same state who did not participate in the attest engagement.', 'The shareholders who participate in the acceptance or performance of the attest engagement.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The proprietor has to remain independent in order to participate in the performance of the attest engagement.', 'Incorrect. The partners have to remain independent in order to participate in the performance of the attest engagement.', 'Correct. These staff members would not be required to be independent since they had nothing to do with the attest engagement and were not in the same office.', 'Incorrect. The shareholders have to remain independent in order to participate in the performance of the attest engagement.', ''),
(499, 37, 134, '<p><strong>Upon determining that a supervisor&rsquo;s recommendation for treatment of financial information could result in a material misstatement, the first step in the CPA&rsquo;s ethical obligation is to:</strong></p>', 'Quit to avoid ethical violations.', 'Communicate concerns to the external accountant and all regulatory agencies that may be involved.', 'Report the disagreement to the supervisor’s supervisor.', 'Do sufficient research and consultation to determine if the supervisor is correct.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. This is the third step.', 'Incorrect. This is the fourth step.', 'Incorrect. This is the second step.', 'Correct. Determining if the supervisor is correct is the first step of a CPA’s ethical obligation in a matter of disagreement with a supervisor.', ''),
(500, 37, 134, '<p><strong>When is a contingent fee or commission deemed to be received?</strong></p>', 'When money for services is first received.', 'When services have been performed and the fee or commission is determined.', 'When a client agrees to have a member perform a service for the client.', 'When an initial sales contact is made with a client.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The receipt of money for the first time is not the first time the fee could be deemed received.', 'Correct. When the fee or commission can be determined is the time it is deemed received.', 'Incorrect. This is not the best time to consider a fee to be received.', 'Incorrect. A fee has not yet been earned.', ''),
(501, 37, 134, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements is FALSE? &nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>When an Attest Function CPA performs &ldquo;Other Services&rdquo; the client must be in a position to have an informed judgment on the results of the other services and understand its responsibility to:</strong></p>', 'Designate a staff member to be responsible for overseeing the services being provided.', 'Evaluate the adequacy of the services performed and any findings that result.', 'Make management decisions, including accepting responsibility for the results of the other services.', 'Establish and maintain internal controls, including monitoring ongoing activities.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. The company must designate a Management-level individual to be responsible for overseeing the services being provided, not a staff person.', 'Incorrect. The client is responsible for evaluating the adequacy of the services performed and any findings that result.', 'Incorrect. The client is responsible for making management decisions, including accepting responsibility for the results of the other services.', 'Incorrect. The client is responsible for establishing and maintaining internal controls, including monitoring ongoing activities.', ''),
(502, 37, 134, '<p><strong>Which of the following new loans to be obtained from a financial institution client where independence is required is NOT an &ldquo;Other Permitted Loan&rdquo;?</strong></p>', 'Automobile loans and leases collateralized by the automobile.', 'Loans fully collateralized by the cash surrender value of an insurance policy.', 'Loans partially collateralized by cash deposits at the same financial institution.', 'Credit cards where the aggregate outstanding balance on the current statement is reduced to $5,000 or less by the payment due date.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Collateralized automobile loans are permitted.', 'Incorrect. Fully collateralized loans by an insurance policy are permitted.', 'Correct. Partially collateralized loans are not permitted, no matter the collateral.', 'Incorrect. Credit cards of $5,000 or less are permitted.', ''),
