(636, 44, 161, '<p><strong>A member who performs auditing, review, compilation, consulting, tax, or other professional services shall comply with only:</strong></p>', 'All applicable standards promulgated by bodies designated by Council.', 'The Code of Professional Ethics.', 'Generally Accepted Accounting Principles.', 'Internal Auditing Standards.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. Members have to comply with the standards set for the particular service performed.', 'Incorrect. Members have to comply with more than the Code.', 'Incorrect. Members have to comply with more than Generally Accepted Accounting Principles.', 'Incorrect. Internal Auditors are the only ones required to comply with Internal Auditing Standards.', ''),
(637, 44, 161, '<p><strong>Which one of the following professionals does NOT have a privileged information status with their client? </strong></p>', 'Medical doctors.', 'Certified public accountants.', 'Attorneys.', 'Religious ministers.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. A medical doctor has the privilege under our laws so that they may treat patients psychologically as well as physically.', 'Correct. For the most part, CPAs cannot disclose confidential information, but they are not protected by law or given privileged information status exempting them from being required to do so.', 'Incorrect. In order to be an advocate for their client, attorneys have the right to not disclose communications with them.', 'Incorrect. In order to minister adequately and appropriately to members or parishioners, ministers of religious orders have privilege.', ''),
(638, 44, 161, '<p><strong>What kind of working papers may a client request, and have a right to receive from its auditor?</strong></p>', 'Analyses and comments on management’s strengths and weaknesses.', 'Papers that contain support for a client’s journal entries and that the client does not have a copy of.', 'Auditor’s comments and conclusions concerning materiality.', 'Both a & c.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Analyses of and comments on management’s strengths and weaknesses are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client.', 'Correct. Sole support for any part of the financial statements is the basis for the client having a right to the auditor’s working papers.', 'Incorrect. Auditor’s comments and conclusions concerning materiality are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client.', 'Incorrect. Analyses of and comments on management’s strengths and weaknesses are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client. Auditor’s comments and conclusions concerning materiality are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client.', ''),
(639, 44, 161, '<p><strong>Which one of the following groups does NOT require disclosure of commissions or anticipated commissions?</strong></p>', 'The AICPA Ethics Division.', 'Those members in public practice who do not perform an audit or review, examination of prospective statements, or compilation when independent.', 'The client.', 'The State Board of the state in which the professional is practicing in.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. No disclosure is required to the AICPA.', 'Incorrect.  A member in public practice who do not perform an audit or review, examination of prospective statements, or compilation when independent is required and is not an exception to the rules.', 'Incorrect.  A professional is always required to disclose to their client.', 'Incorrect. A professional is not required to disclose commissions or anticipated commissions to the Board of the State in which they practice.', ''),
(640, 44, 162, '<p><strong>The attest engagement team includes all of the following, EXCEPT:</strong></p>', 'The proprietor who participates in the acceptance or performance of the attest engagement.', 'The partners who participate in the acceptance or performance of the attest engagement.', 'Full- or part-time professional staff in another office of the same firm in the same state who did not participate in the attest engagement.', 'The shareholders who participate in the acceptance or performance of the attest engagement.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The proprietor has to remain independent in order to participate in the performance of the attest engagement.', 'Incorrect. The partners have to remain independent in order to participate in the performance of the attest engagement.', 'Correct. These staff members would not be required to be independent since they had nothing to do with the attest engagement and were not in the same office.', 'Incorrect. The shareholders have to remain independent in order to participate in the performance of the attest engagement.', ''),
(641, 44, 162, '<p><strong>Upon determining that a supervisor&rsquo;s recommendation for treatment of financial information could result in a material misstatement, the first step in the CPA&rsquo;s ethical obligation is to:</strong></p>', 'Quit to avoid ethical violations.', 'Communicate concerns to the external accountant and all regulatory agencies that may be involved.', 'Report the disagreement to the supervisor’s supervisor.', 'Do sufficient research and consultation to determine if the supervisor is correct.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. This is the third step.', 'Incorrect. This is the fourth step.', 'Incorrect. This is the second step.', 'Correct. Determining if the supervisor is correct is the first step of a CPA’s ethical obligation in a matter of disagreement with a supervisor.', ''),
(642, 44, 162, '<p><strong>When is a contingent fee or commission deemed to be received?</strong></p>', 'When money for services is first received.', 'When services have been performed and the fee or commission is determined.', 'When a client agrees to have a member perform a service for the client.', 'When an initial sales contact is made with a client.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The receipt of money for the first time is not the first time the fee could be deemed received.', 'Correct. When the fee or commission can be determined is the time it is deemed received.', 'Incorrect. This is not the best time to consider a fee to be received.', 'Incorrect. A fee has not yet been earned.', ''),
(643, 44, 162, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements is FALSE? &nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>When an Attest Function CPA performs &ldquo;Other Services&rdquo; the client must be in a position to have an informed judgment on the results of the other services and understand its responsibility to:</strong></p>', 'Designate a staff member to be responsible for overseeing the services being provided.', 'Evaluate the adequacy of the services performed and any findings that result.', 'Make management decisions, including accepting responsibility for the results of the other services.', 'Establish and maintain internal controls, including monitoring ongoing activities.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. The company must designate a Management-level individual to be responsible for overseeing the services being provided, not a staff person.', 'Incorrect. The client is responsible for evaluating the adequacy of the services performed and any findings that result.', 'Incorrect. The client is responsible for making management decisions, including accepting responsibility for the results of the other services.', 'Incorrect. The client is responsible for establishing and maintaining internal controls, including monitoring ongoing activities.', ''),
(644, 44, 162, '<p><strong>Which of the following new loans to be obtained from a financial institution client where independence is required is NOT an &ldquo;Other Permitted Loan&rdquo;?</strong></p>', 'Automobile loans and leases collateralized by the automobile.', 'Loans fully collateralized by the cash surrender value of an insurance policy.', 'Loans partially collateralized by cash deposits at the same financial institution.', 'Credit cards where the aggregate outstanding balance on the current statement is reduced to $5,000 or less by the payment due date.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Collateralized automobile loans are permitted.', 'Incorrect. Fully collateralized loans by an insurance policy are permitted.', 'Correct. Partially collateralized loans are not permitted, no matter the collateral.', 'Incorrect. Credit cards of $5,000 or less are permitted.', ''),
(645, 35, 163, '<p><strong>Francona Financial owns a portfolio of debt securities that it accounts for under the historical cost accounting method. In accordance with U.S. GAAP, these financial assets should be measured on the Balance Sheet at: </strong></p>', 'The price at which Francona could sell the asset in the current market.', 'The price paid for the asset at the time of acquisition (less cumulative amortization).', 'The price paid to replace them if the assets were sold today.', 'The price at which other market participants could sell the asset in the current market .', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. A security accounted for under the fair value accounting method (not historical cost) would be presented at the value in which it could sell in the current market by the entity.', 'Answer B is correct. Historical cost accounting is a method that presents an asset/liability on the balance sheet at the price paid/received at the time of its acquisition. In this example, the debt securities portfolio would be presented at the price paid for the asset at the time of acquisition (less cumulative amortization, if any).', 'Answer C is incorrect. This describes the concept of ‘replacement cost’, which is a method of measuring the fair value (not the historical cost) of an asset.', 'Answer D is incorrect. A security accounted for under the fair value accounting method (not historical cost) would be presented at the value in which it could sell in the current market by the entity (or another market participant).', ''),
(646, 35, 163, '<p><strong>Which of the following accounting practices is the most consistent with the concept of historical cost accounting under U.S. GAAP?</strong></p>', 'Company A excludes installation costs and delivery fees from its historical cost calculations.', 'Company B periodically adjusts the historical cost of its assets to reflect changes in market conditions.', 'Company C immediately expenses purchase premiums paid for their financial assets.', 'Company D systematically reduces the balance sheet value of its construction equipment to reflect wear and tear.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Installation costs and delivery fees should be included (not excluded) from the calculation of an asset’s historical cost.', 'Answer B is incorrect. The carrying value of an asset measured at historical cost would not be adjusted for changes in its market value.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Purchase premiums must be amortized over the lives of financial assets under historical cost accounting.', 'Answer D is correct. The balance sheet carrying value of the historical cost of the equipment would be reduced to reflect depreciation, which represents the systematic reduction in the value of the asset due to usage, passage of time, wear and tear, etc.', ''),
(647, 35, 163, '<p><strong>A research analyst is preparing a report on the pros and cons of historical cost accounting. Which of the following statements would most likely appear in the analyst&rsquo;s report to describe the impact that this method had on the Savings and Loan scandal in the mid-to-late 1980&rsquo;s? </strong></p>', 'The use of historical cost accounting assisted in hiding the S&L industry’s true financial condition at the time.', 'The use of historical cost accounting would have prevented the S&L crisis from occurring.', 'The historical cost method would have properly reflected the S&L industry’s assets and liabilities at their current values.', 'The fraudulent application of the historical cost method of accounting is what ultimately caused the crisis.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. Many critics believed that the use of historical cost accounting failed to expose the industry''s true financial condition.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Historical cost accounting was considered a cause of the S&L Crisis.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Fair value accounting (not historical cost accounting) recognizes assets and liabilities on the balance sheet at their current values.', 'Answer D is incorrect. The S&L’s were not criticized for fraudulently applying historical cost accounting. Rather, the historical cost basis itself was criticized as inherently flawed.', ''),
(648, 35, 163, '<p><strong>Which of the following accounting practices is the most consistent with the concept of fair value accounting under U.S. GAAP?</strong></p>', 'Company A reports fixed assets on the balance sheet at their amortized cost.', 'Company B amortizes purchase premiums paid for their debt securities over the estimated lives of the assets.', 'Company C reports its equity investments on the balance sheet at their current value.', 'Company D deducts the salvage value from the original cost of its auto fleet when performing their depreciation calculations.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The concepts of historical cost and amortized cost pertain to the presentation of assets and liabilities on the balance sheet at their original cost. They are not synonymous with (or related to) the concept of fair value, which pertains to the presentation of assets and liabilities on the balance sheet at their current value.', 'Answer B is incorrect. The concepts of depreciation and amortization are related to the concept of historical cost (not fair value).', 'Answer C is correct. The concept of ‘fair value’ is synonymous with ‘current value’. Therefore this accounting practice of measuring investments on the balance sheet at their current value is the most consistent with the concept of fair value accounting.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Measuring assets on the balance sheet at their depreciated value is an example of historical cost accounting (not fair value accounting).', ''),
(649, 35, 163, '<p><strong>Which of the following accounting practices is the most consistent with the disclosure requirements of ASC 825-50 (formerly SFAS 107)? </strong></p>', 'Company A discloses its revenue recognition policies in the notes to their financial statements.', 'Company B measures financial instruments on their balance sheet at fair value (as required).', 'Company C supplements their historical cost financial statements with disclosures about the fair values of financial instruments.', 'Company D uses the retrospective method when amortizing the purchase premiums associated with their investment securities.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. ASC 825-50 includes fair value disclosure requirements for financial instruments. It does not include revenue recognition disclosure requirements.', 'Answer B is incorrect. ASC 825-50 requires certain fair value disclosures for financial instruments measured at historical cost on the balance sheet. The Standard does not require those instruments to be measured at fair value on the balance sheet.', 'Answer C is correct. ASC 825-50 requires entities to supplement their historical cost financial statements with disclosures about the fair values of financial instruments reported in those statements.', 'Answer D is incorrect. ASC 825-50 does not include guidance addressing the amortization of premiums & discounts on investment securities. Rather, it would require the fair value of those securities to be provided in the notes to the financial statements.', ''),
(650, 35, 163, '<p><strong>A research analyst is preparing a report on the Enron scandal of the early 2000&rsquo;s. Which of the following GAAP-related issues would the analyst most likely cite as enabling the fraud perpetrated by The Enron Corporation? </strong></p>', 'The vague definition of ‘historical cost’.', 'The permitted use of the cash method of accounting.', 'The inconsistent guidance on the accrual method of accounting.', 'The lack of specific guidance on the concept of fair value.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The lack of formal accounting guidance on the definition of “fair value” (not historical cost) has been blamed (in part) for enabling the Enron accounting scandal in 2001.', 'Answer B is incorrect. The cash method is not permitted under U.S. GAAP, and it was not considered a primary factor in the Enron fraud.', 'Answer C is incorrect. The accrual method of accounting was not considered a factor in the Enron scandal. Rather, the lack of guidance defining ‘fair value’ led to management fraud.', 'Answer D is correct. Many critics believed that fair value accounting enabled Enron to commit fraud on a massive scale in the early 2000’s. Enron executives frequently measured their assets at massively inflated fair values. This fraud was facilitated by the lack of formal fair value accounting guidance in U.S. GAAP.', ''),
(651, 35, 163, '<p><strong>Ellsbury Corp. is planning to apply the U.S. GAAP concepts of fair value to their year-end financial statements. Under the guidance of ASC 820, the definition of fair value and its application should be: </strong></p>', 'Unique for each individual class of assets and liabilities', 'The same for all assets and liabilities', 'The same for all assets, but unique for each individual liability class', 'The same for all liabilities, but unique for each individual asset class', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The FASB did not determine that the definition of fair value and its application in GAAP should be unique to various classes of assets and liabilities. Rather, ASC 820 was issued to provide a single definition that could be applied when measuring all assets and liabilities at fair value.', 'Answer B is correct. The FASB determined that the definition of fair value and its application in GAAP should be the same for all assets and liabilities. This concept is a significant aspect of ASC 820.', 'Answer C is incorrect. The FASB determined that the definition of fair value should be the same for all liabilities. The FASB did not determine that the definition should be unique to various classes of liabilities.', 'Answer D is incorrect. The key concept of ASC 820 is that all assets (and liabilities) measured at fair value should be measured consistently using a single definition of fair value.', ''),
(652, 35, 163, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements accurately summarizes the FASB&rsquo;s reasoning for issuing ASC 820 Fair Value Measurements and Disclosures?</strong></p>', 'This FASB wished to prohibit the use of historical cost accounting', 'The FASB wanted to reduce the required disclosures about fair value measurements', 'The FASB wanted to require several new fair value measurements that were previously not included in existing FASB literature', 'This FASB wished to define fair value and establish a framework for measuring fair value', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The FASB issued ASC 820 to provide a single definition of ‘fair value’ for those assets and liabilities to which the measurement basis applies. The Standard does not prohibit the use of historical cost accounting.', 'Answer B is incorrect. ASC 820 expands (not reduces) disclosures about fair value measurements.', 'Answer C is incorrect. ASC 820 does not require several new fair value measurements that were previously not included in existing FASB literature. Rather, the Standard provides a single definition of ‘fair value’ for those assets and liabilities to which the measurement basis applies.', 'Answer D is correct. The Financial Accounting Standards Board (FASB) issued ASC 820 Fair Value Measurements and Disclosures in order to define fair value, establish a framework for measuring fair value, expand disclosures about fair value measurements, simplify and codify the related guidance that currently exists for developing fair value measurements and eliminate differences that have added to the complexity in GAAP.', ''),
(653, 35, 164, '<p><strong>Which of the following accounting policies is compliant with ASC 820&rsquo;s definition of &lsquo;fair value&rsquo;? </strong></p>', 'Company A values its fair value assets at the historical price paid for each asset.', 'Company B values its fair value assets at the price paid for the asset in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date.', 'Company C does not apply the ASC 820 definition of fair value to its derivative instruments.', 'Company D applies the ASC 820 definition of fair value only to stand-alone assets.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The historical purchase price paid for an asset is referred to as its historical cost (not fair value). The fair value of an asset is the current price paid for the asset in an orderly transaction between market participants. Therefore Company A’s accounting policy is not compliant with the fair value accounting requirements of ASC 820.', 'Answer B is correct. Company B’s accounting policy is compliant with ASC 820, which  defines fair value as the price paid for an asset or liability in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date.', 'Answer C is incorrect. ASC 820 must be applied to most assets & liabilities accounted for at fair value, including derivative instruments. Therefore Company C’s accounting policy is not compliant with the fair value accounting requirements of ASC 820.', 'Answer D is incorrect. ASC 820 is not limited to stand-alone assets, but instead applies to most assets and liabilities measured at fair value. Therefore Company D’s accounting policy is not compliant with the fair value accounting requirements of ASC 820.', ''),
(654, 35, 164, '<p><strong>Which of the following prices would most likely be consistent with the definition of fair value under ASC 820? </strong></p>', 'A market-based price to purchase equipment.', 'A market-based price to sell an investment.', 'An entity-specific price to purchase equipment.', 'An entity-specific price to sell an investment.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. A market-based price to purchase equipment is consistent with the concept of an “entry price”; under ASC 820, fair value represents an exit price, not an entry price.', 'Answer B is correct. Under ASC 820, the objective of a fair value measurement is to determine the price that would be received to sell an asset or paid to transfer a liability at the measurement date (i.e. an “exit” price). A market-based exit price to sell an investment would be consistent with the ASC 820 definition of fair value.', 'Answer C is incorrect. ASC 820 states that fair value is a market-based measurement, not an entity-specific measurement. Also, this description is consistent with the concept of an “entry price”; fair value represents an exit price, not an entry price.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Fair value must be a market-based measurement, not an entity-specific measurement (under ASC 820).', ''),
(655, 35, 164, '<p><strong>Which of the following scenarios depicts the appropriate application of the concept of &lsquo;exit price&rsquo; as it is defined in ASC 820?</strong></p>', 'Company A values its machinery at its acquisition cost.', 'Company B adjusts the fair value of its investments for trading costs.', 'Company C uses hypothetical transactions to estimate the value that its assets would sell for in its principal market.', 'Company D bases its fair value calculations on its intent to hold or sell the asset.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Valuing machinery at its acquisition cost is consistent with the concept of entry price, not exit price.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Under ASC 820, the exit price of an asset should not be adjusted for transaction costs.', 'Answer C is correct. An exit price generally represents a hypothetical transaction price to sell an asset or transfer a liability in the item’s principal market.', 'Answer D is incorrect. The exit price objective of a fair value measurement applies regardless of the reporting entity’s intent and/or ability to sell the asset or transfer the liability at the measurement.', ''),
(656, 35, 164, '<p><strong>Which of the following would most likely be considered an &lsquo;orderly transaction&rsquo; under the guidance provided in ASC 820? &nbsp;</strong></p>', 'A machinery sale made as part of bankruptcy proceedings.', 'The distressed sale of an auto fleet.', 'A hypothetical equipment sale that assumes exposure to the market for a customary period.', 'An investment sale that occurs in an illiquid market.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. A sale made as part of bankruptcy proceedings would generally be considered a ‘forced transaction’ under ASC 820. Forced transactions are not considered ‘orderly’ under ASC 820.', 'Answer B is incorrect. A distressed sale would not generally be considered an ‘orderly transaction’ under ASC 820, as the seller is being forced to sell the auto fleet (likely for prices lower than fair value).', 'Answer C is correct. An orderly transaction is a transaction that assumes exposure to the market for a period prior to the measurement date to allow for marketing activities that are usual and customary for transactions involving such assets and liabilities.', 'Answer D is incorrect. A transaction to buy or sell a financial instrument that takes place in an illiquid (or inactive) market is not generally considered an ‘orderly transaction’ under ASC 820.', ''),
(657, 35, 164, '<p><strong>For the following 4 questions, please refer to this information:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Brady Bank offers several types of loan products to its customers and frequently purchases and sells all types of financial instruments in many different markets. Brady accounts for its financial instruments at fair value.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Under ASC 820, the principal market of Brady&rsquo;s financial instruments is:</strong></p>', 'The market in which Brady would purchase or sell each product with the greatest volume and level of activity.', 'Not considered if a more advantageous prices are available in other markets.', 'Always considered to be the retail market for each product, regardless of the actual market from which the entity transacts.', 'The same for all identical assets, regardless of an entity’s access to other markets.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. The principal market is the market in which the reporting entity would sell the asset or transfer the liability with the greatest volume and level of activity for the asset or liability.', 'Answer B is incorrect. ASC 820 specifies that if there is a principal market for the asset or liability being measured, the fair value for that asset or liability should represent the price in that market, even if the price in a different market is more advantageous at the measurement date.', 'Answer C is incorrect. The determination of the principal (or most advantageous) market is made from the perspective of the reporting entity. Different reporting entities may sell assets or transfer liabilities in different markets depending on their activities.', 'Answer D is incorrect. The principal market for identical assets may differ for different reporting entities, as certain entities may lack access to markets that other’s have.', ''),
(658, 35, 164, '<p><strong>Which of the following entities would Brady most likely consider a &lsquo;market participant&rsquo; for their financial instruments under the guidance of ASC 820? </strong></p>', 'Company A, a wholly-owned subsidiary of Brady Corp.', 'Company B, a hedge fund who has recently sold their open positions as a result of bankruptcy.', 'Company C, a commercial bank that is independent of Brady Corp.', 'Company D, a credit union that is prohibited from purchasing Brady’s financial products.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. A ‘market participant’ should not be a related party to the reporting entity under ASC 820 guidelines. Therefore a subsidiary of Brady Corp. would not be considered a ‘market participant’.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Under ASC 820, a ‘market participant’ should not be forced into a purchase or sale transaction. Therefore a bankrupt financial institution would not be considered a market participant in this example.', 'Answer C is correct. Under ASC 820, market participants must be independent of the reporting entity. Therefore an independent financial institution would likely be considered a participant in the market for Brady Corp.’s products.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Under ASC 820, an entity must be able to transact for the asset or liability in order to be considered a ‘market participant’.', ''),
(659, 35, 164, '<p><strong>The risk that Brady&rsquo;s customers may default on the terms of their loans is known as:</strong></p>', 'Interest rate risk.', 'An entity’s own credit risk.', 'Prepayment risk.', 'Counterparty credit risk.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Interest rate risk is the risk that an investment''s value will change due to a change in the absolute level of interest rates.', 'Answer B is incorrect. An entity’s own credit risk (which is generally assumed by a reporting entity’s counterparty) is the risk that the reporting entity becomes insolvent and/or is unable to meet the terms of the agreement.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Prepayment risk is the risk associated with the early unscheduled return of principal on a fixed-income security.', 'Answer D is correct. The risk that Brady’s customers may default on the terms of their loans is known as counterparty credit risk (a form of nonperformance risk). Nonperformance risk is often an important attribute when valuing loans (and similar types of financial instruments).', ''),
(660, 35, 164, '<p><strong>The risk that Brady Corp may become default on the terms of their outstanding derivative contracts is known as:</strong></p>', 'Interest rate risk.', 'An entity’s own credit risk.', 'Prepayment risk.', 'Counterparty credit risk.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Interest rate risk is the risk that an investment''s value will change due to a change in the absolute level of interest rates. Interest rate derivatives are generally transacted to hedge interest rate risk.', 'Answer B is correct. The risk that Brady Corp may become default on the terms of their open derivative contracts is known as an entity’s own credit risk. This is a form of nonperformance risk that is generally assumed by a reporting entity’s counterparty.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Prepayment risk is the risk associated with the early unscheduled return of principal on a fixed-income security.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Counterparty credit risk (which is generally assumed by the reporting entity) is the risk that the counterparty becomes insolvent and/or is unable to meet the terms of the agreement.', ''),
(661, 35, 164, '<p><strong>For the following 4 questions, please refer to this information:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Kraft Auto, Inc. is attempting to value its car dealership (the building and land) and its car inventory in accordance with ASC 820. </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Based on preliminary market research, Kraft determines that the land provides maximum benefit when used in combination with the dealership building. Under ASC 820, the _________ valuation premise would likely be required in this circumstance.</strong></p>', 'In-combination.', 'In-use.', 'In-exchange.', 'In-benefit.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. “In-combination” is not a valid valuation premise under ASC 820.', 'Answer B is correct. The highest and best use of the asset is in-use if the asset would provide maximum value to market participants principally through its use in combination with other assets as a group. This valuation premise would be required under this circumstance.', 'Answer C is incorrect. The highest and best use is in-exchange if the asset would provide maximum value to market participants principally on a stand-alone basis. It is not applicable in this case.', 'Answer D is incorrect. “In-benefit” is not a valid valuation premise under ASC 820.', ''),
(662, 35, 164, '<p><strong>The basis at which Kraft accounts for its car inventory (i.e. a car-by-car basis vs. an aggregated basis) under other U.S. GAAP standards:</strong></p>', 'Will likely determine the level at which the assets are valued under ASC 820.', 'Is pre-determined for all asset & liability types within the scope of ASC 820.', 'Is not a fundamental component in the determination of fair value.', 'Is a valuation concept that determines how the asset or liability is measured.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. The unit of account is an accounting concept that determines the level at which an asset or liability is aggregated or disaggregated for purposes of applying ASC 820, as well as other accounting pronouncements. Therefore the unit of account used by Kraft to account for its assets under other U.S. GAAP standards Will likely determine the level at which the assets are valued under ASC 820.', 'Answer B is incorrect. ASC 820 does not prescribe the unit of account to be used for assets and liabilities required (or permitted) to be measured at fair value.', 'Answer C is incorrect. The unit of account represents exactly what asset or liability is being measured, which is fundamental in determining its fair value.', 'Answer D is incorrect. The valuation premise determines how the asset or liability is measured (not the unit of account).', ''),
(663, 35, 164, '<p><strong>Which of the following transactions has most likely been executed at a transaction price that equals the asset&rsquo;s fair value at the time of purchase?</strong></p>', 'Company A purchases several equity investments on the New York Stock Exchange.', 'Company B purchases equipment from its subsidiary.', 'Company C purchases machinery from a company that has filed bankruptcy.', 'Company D purchases a securities portfolio at a price that includes transaction fees.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. An asset’s transaction price (or ‘entry price’) generally equals its fair value (or ‘exit price’) if the transaction takes place in an active market for that asset and does not involve related parties or forced sales. The NYSE is commonly considered an active market for equity investments.', 'Answer B is incorrect. A transaction price might not represent the fair value of an asset or liability if the transaction is between related parties. Therefore the purchase and sale of equipment between a company and its subsidiary would likely be disregarded when determining the equipment’s “fair value” under ASC 820.', 'Answer C is incorrect. A transaction price might not represent the fair value of an asset or liability if the transaction occurs under duress (due to bankruptcy or other circumstances). Therefore the price paid by Company C for the machinery would not likely be considered the asset’s fair value.', 'Answer D is incorrect. An exit price should not include transaction fees; therefore, in this case, Company D’s transaction price would not equal fair value.', ''),
(664, 35, 164, '<p><strong>An analyst is researching an income statement line item labeled &ldquo;Day 1 Gains &amp; Losses.&rdquo; Within the scope of ASC 820, these gains and losses most likely resulted as a result of the dissimilar definitions of ________ in the Standard: </strong></p>', 'Transaction price & entry price.', 'Entry price & exit price.', 'Market price & current price.', 'Amortized cost & market price.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Under ASC 820, the concepts of transaction & entry price are identical and do not result in the potential recognition of Day 1 Gains & Losses.', 'Answer B is correct. Under ASC 820, ‘day one gains & losses’ often result from differences in the ‘entry price’ and ‘exit price’ of a transaction when it is executed.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Market prices & current prices are substantially the same under ASC 820 and do not result in the potential recognition of Day 1 Gains & Losses.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Although the concepts of amortized cost & market price are different, they do not result in the potential recognition of Day 1 Gains & Losses as described in ASC 820.', ''),
(665, 35, 165, '<p><strong>Company A uses a valuation model that incorporates present value techniques to measure the fair value of a reporting unit for goodwill impairment testing purposes. Under ASC 820, this valuation technique would be considered consistent with the: </strong></p>', 'Market approach.', 'Income approach.', 'Cost approach.', 'Fixed approach.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The focus of the market approach is on prices and other relevant information generated by actual market transactions, not values derived from cash flow models.', 'Answer B is correct. Company A’s methodology would fall under the income approach, as described in ASC 820. The income approach uses valuation techniques to convert future amounts (i.e. future cash flows or earnings) to a single discounted amount.', 'Answer C is incorrect. The cost approach is based on the replacement cost of the asset being valued, not on cash flow projections.', 'Answer D is incorrect. The “fixed approach” is not a valid valuation technique within the scope of ASC 820.', ''),
(666, 35, 165, '<p><strong>Company B uses a pricing matrix to price its portfolio of floating rate investment securities. Under ASC 820, this valuation technique would be considered consistent with the: </strong></p>', 'Market approach.', 'Income approach.', 'Cost approach.', 'Floating approach.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. Company B’s pricing matrix methodology would fall under the market approach, as described in ASC 820. The market approach uses prices and other relevant information generated by market transactions involving identical or comparable assets or liabilities.', 'Answer B is incorrect. The income approach generally applies to valuations derived from cash flow models rather than market price of identical or similar assets.', 'Answer C is incorrect. The cost approach is based on the replacement cost of the asset being valued, not on market prices of identical or similar assets.', 'Answer D is incorrect. The “floating approach” is not a valid valuation technique within the scope of ASC 820.', ''),
(667, 35, 165, '<p><strong>Company C values its machinery at its current replacement cost on the Balance Sheet. Under ASC 820, this valuation technique would be considered consistent with the: </strong></p>', 'Market approach.', 'Income approach.', 'Cost approach.', 'Machine approach.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The focus of the market approach is on prices and other relevant information generated by actual market transactions, not the replacement cost of the asset.', 'Answer B is incorrect. The income approach generally applies to valuations derived from cash flow models rather than the replacement cost of the asset.', 'Answer C is correct. Company C’s valuation technique would fall under the cost approach, as described in ASC 820. The cost approach is based on the amount that currently would be required to replace the service capacity of an asset.', 'Answer D is incorrect. The “machine approach” is not a valid valuation technique within the scope of ASC 820.', ''),
(668, 35, 165, '<p><strong>Which of the following valuation policies would most likely be considered consistent with the guidance of ASC 820? &nbsp;</strong></p>', 'Company A prohibits the use of only one valuation technique when valuing an asset or liability.', 'Company B prohibits the use of more than one valuation technique when valuing an asset or liability.', 'Company C requires consistent application of valuation techniques among similar assets.', 'Company D requires the use of the market approach is all cases.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Under ASC 820, Company A would not be prohibited from using only one valuation technique may be appropriate to measure the fair value of an asset or liability (in certain cases).', 'Answer B is incorrect. Under ASC 820, Company B would not be prohibited from measuring fair value using one or more valuation techniques (where appropriate).', 'Answer C is correct. The FASB has emphasized that the application of valuation techniques be applied on a consistent basis, among similar assets, as well as across reporting periods. Company C’s consistent application would therefore be consistent with the requirements of ASC 820.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Company D would not be required to use the market approach to measure fair value in all cases. ASC 820 does not prioritize the valuation techniques to be applied, as all three approaches may not be applicable to all assets or liabilities.', ''),
(669, 35, 165, '<p><strong>Daisuke Corp. utilizes a valuation model to estimate the fair value of its debt securities. The model uses two primary inputs when calculating this value: interest rate data published in independent financial journals and loan prepayment assumptions that have been developed internally by Daisuke management. Based on the guidance provided in ASC 820, the interest rate data would most likely be considered an _______ input and the internally developed prepayment assumptions would most likely be considered an _______ input.</strong></p>', 'Observable; observable.', 'Unobservable; observable.', 'Unobservable; unobservable.', 'Observable; unobservable.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Internally developed valuation assumptions  (such as the Company’s prepayment assumptions) would not be considered an observable input in this example.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Publicly-available information (such as interest rate data) are generally considered to be observable inputs. The internally developed prepayment assumptions would not be considered an observable input in this example.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Publicly-available information (such as interest rate data) are generally considered to be observable inputs.', 'Answer D is correct. An interest rate or index value would be considered an ‘observable input’ because it is independently determined and widely published. Management assumptions that have been developed internally would be considered an unobservable input as it is not widely observable in the market.', ''),
(670, 35, 165, '<p><strong>Which of the following policies would most likely ensure compliance with the requirements for fair value techniques outlined in ASC 820? &nbsp;</strong></p>', 'Company A maximizes the use of observable inputs and minimizes the use of unobservable inputs.', 'Company B maximizes the use of unobservable inputs and minimizes the use of observable inputs.', 'Company C makes equal use of observable and unobservable inputs.', 'Company D prohibits the changing of their valuation methodologies once they have been approved by their board of directors.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. Under, ASC 820, valuation techniques used to measure fair value must maximize the use of observable inputs and minimize the use of unobservable inputs. Company A’s accounting policy complies with this requirement.', 'Answer B is incorrect. ASC 820 places a higher priority on observable inputs over unobservable inputs. Company B’s policy of maximizing the use of unobservable inputs and minimizing the use of observable inputs would therefore not comply with ASC 820.', 'Answer C is incorrect. ASC 820, Company C would be required to place a higher priority on observable inputs over unobservable inputs. It would not be permitted to place an equal priority on both types of inputs.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Under ASC 820, Company D would be permitted to change its valuation techniques. Such a change would be accounted for as a change in accounting estimate in most cases.', ''),
(671, 35, 165, '<p><strong>Quoted prices for similar assets or liabilities used in a pricing matrix would generally be considered a _______ input under ASC 820. &nbsp;</strong></p>', 'Level 1.', 'Level 2.', 'Level 3.', 'Level 4.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Under ASC 820, Level 1 valuation inputs generally include only prices of identical assets that are traded in active markets.', 'Answer B is correct. Observable prices for similar assets or liabilities (such as those included in a pricing matrix) would be considered a Level 2 input according to the ASC 820 fair value hierarchy.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Under ASC 820, quoted prices would generally not fall into the Level 3 category unless significant adjustments were made based on unobservable information.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Level 4 is not a valid classification under the ASC 820 fair value hierarchy.', ''),
(672, 35, 165, '<p><strong>Valuation assumptions which cannot be corroborated with observable market data would generally be considered a _______ input under ASC 820.</strong></p>', 'Level 1.', 'Level 2.', 'Level 3.', 'Level 4.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The Level 1 classification generally applies only to prices of identical assets that are observable in active markets.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Management assumptions may fall into the Level 2 category only if they can be corroborated by observable market data.', 'Answer C is correct. Unobservable valuation assumptions (such as those based solely on management’s internal data) would be considered a Level 3 input according to the ASC 820 fair value hierarchy.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Level 4 is not a valid classification under the ASC 820 fair value hierarchy.', ''),
(673, 35, 165, '<p><strong>Quoted prices of identical assets available on the New York Stock Exchange would generally be considered a _______ input under ASC 820. &nbsp;</strong></p>', 'Level 1.', 'Level 2.', 'Level 3.', 'Level 4.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. Under ASC 820, Level 1 valuation inputs include quoted prices of identical assets, such as those available on the New York Stock Exchange.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Quoted prices of similar assets generally fall within the Level 2 classification, while quoted prices of identical assets fall within the Level 1 classification.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Quoted prices would generally not fall into the Level 3 category unless significant adjustments were made based on unobservable information.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Level 4 is not a valid classification under the ASC 820 fair value hierarchy.', ''),
(674, 35, 165, '<p><strong>Ortiz Inc. is preparing their fair value disclosures for the year ending 20X9. Which of the following parties would most likely bear the responsibility of determining the appropriateness of Ortiz&rsquo;s fair value measurements, as well as their classification within the fair value hierarchy? &nbsp;</strong></p>', 'Ortiz’s external auditors.', 'Ortiz’s internal auditors.', 'Ortiz’s shareholders.', 'Ortiz’s management.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. External auditors assess the appropriateness of an entity’s fair value measurements and their classification in the fair value hierarchy as part of the audit process. However management bears the ultimate responsibilities for its fair value measurements and disclosures.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Internal auditors may review their entity’s fair value measurements and disclosures, but (in most cases) an entity’s management will bear the responsibility for ensuring compliance with ASC 820.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Shareholders are not primarily responsible for determining the appropriateness of an entity’s fair value measurements and their classification in the fair value hierarchy.', 'Answer D is correct. Ultimately, it is management’s responsibility to determine the appropriateness of its fair value measurements and their classification in the fair value hierarchy.', '');
INSERT INTO `chapter_review_questions` (`rev_ques_id`, `course_id`, `chapter_id`, `rev_ques_title`, `rev_ques_ans_1`, `rev_ques_ans_2`, `rev_ques_ans_3`, `rev_ques_ans_4`, `rev_ques_ans_5`, `rev_correct_ans_id`, `rev_correct_ans_text`, `rev_wronge_ans_text`, `rev_ques_status`, `ans1_text`, `ans2_text`, `ans3_text`, `ans4_text`, `ans5_text`) VALUES
(675, 35, 165, '<p><strong>Youkilis Bank relies on a pricing service to provide the fair value of its investments portfolio. Which of the following statements accurately reflect the fair value accounting requirements for broker quotes received from an outside pricing service? &nbsp;</strong></p>', 'Such inputs must be classified as a Level 3 input in all circumstances.', 'Such inputs may be classified as a Level 2 input if it can be corroborated by market evidence.', 'Such inputs be classified as a Level 2 input even if it cannot be corroborated by market evidence.', 'Such inputs must be classified as a Level 2 input in all circumstances.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. ASC 820 does not require broker quotes or valuations received from an outside pricing service to automatically be classified as Level 3 inputs.', 'Answer B is correct. A broker quote or valuation received from an outside pricing service may be classified as a Level 2 input if the entity performs the due diligence necessary to corroborate the valuation with market observable information.', 'Answer C is incorrect. A broker quote or valuation received from an outside pricing service may only be classified as a Level 2 input if the entity performs the due diligence necessary to corroborate the valuation with market observable information.', 'Answer D is incorrect. ASC 820 does not require broker quotes or valuations received from an outside pricing service to automatically be classified as Level 2 inputs.', ''),
(676, 35, 166, '<p><strong>A financial reporting manager at ABC Inc. is researching the disclosure requirements included in ASC 820. Which of the following statements is most consistent with these requirements? </strong></p>', 'All of ABC’s financial assets & liabilities should be presented at fair value on the Balance Sheet.', 'Fair value amounts reported in ABC’s financial statements should be reconciled to the amounts reported on their corporate tax returns.', 'ABC’s financial instrument disclosures (under ASC 825-50) should be replaced with their ASC 820 disclosures.', 'ABC Inc. should provide financial statement users with additional insight into the relative reliability of fair value measures.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. ASC 820 does not require assets or liabilities to be measured at fair value. Rather, it provides a standard definition of fair value to be used when measuring items at fair value in accordance with other Standards.', 'Answer B is incorrect. A corporate tax return reconciliation is not part of the disclosure requirements of ASC 820.', 'Answer C is incorrect. The disclosures required by ASC 820 do not replace those required by ASC 825-50. Rather, ASC 820 encourages reporting entities to combine the fair value measurement disclosures with the fair value disclosures required under other accounting standards (including ASC 825-50), if practicable.', 'Answer D is correct. ASC 820’s disclosure requirements are intended to provide financial statement users with additional insight into the relative reliability of the various fair value measures, thus enhancing their ability to broadly assess the quality of earnings.', ''),
(677, 35, 166, '<p><strong>Which of the following ASC 820 disclosures is required for a Level 1 asset that is measured at fair value on a recurring basis? </strong></p>', 'Company A disclosed the impact that economic conditions had on the asset’s fair value.', 'Company B disclosed the inputs used in the asset’s fair value measurements.', 'Company C disclosed the valuation technique used to estimate the asset’s fair value.', 'Company D disclosed the asset’s fair value amortization methodology.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The impact that economic conditions had on an asset’s fair value may be useful information for investors in certain circumstances, but it is not explicitly required by ASC 820.', 'Answer B is correct. Reporting entities are required to disclose the inputs used to develop the asset’s fair value measurements.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Disclosing the valuation technique used to estimate an asset’s fair value is required for Level 2 & Level 3 assets, but not Level 1 assets. This is because Level 1 assets are valued using unadjusted market prices (not financial models or other valuation techniques).', 'Answer D is incorrect. Fair value adjustments are not amortized under U.S. GAAP. Therefore such a disclosure would not be appropriate.', ''),
(678, 35, 166, '<p><strong>Which of the following disclosures for assets and liabilities that are measured at fair value on a recurring basis is required under the requirements of ASC 820? </strong></p>', 'Company A disclosed the effect that Level 1 fair value measurements had on equity for the period.', 'Company B provided a reconciliation of beginning and ending balances for Level 3 assets or liabilities.', 'Company C disclosed the impact that their Level 2 fair value gains & losses had on their earnings-per-share for the period.', 'Company D provided a reconciliation of fair values used for U.S. GAAP and tax reporting purposes.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. ASC 820 does not include a requirement to disclose the effect that level 1 fair value measurements had on equity for a reporting period.', 'Answer B is correct. A reconciliation of beginning and ending balances is required for Level 3 assets or liabilities measured on a recurring basis.', 'Answer C is incorrect. The disclosures required for assets and liabilities that are measured at fair value on a recurring basis do not include the impact that fair value gains & loss on EPS.', 'Answer D is incorrect.  Reconciliations of fair values used for U.S. GAAP and tax purposes are not required under ASC 820.', ''),
(679, 35, 166, '<p><strong>Which of the following processes would normally be considered appropriate for an auditor to perform under the standards of fieldwork included in SAS No. 101?</strong></p>', 'Auditor A establishes an accounting and financial reporting process for determining fair value measurements.', 'Auditor B disregards the role that information technology has in the fair value measurement process.', 'Auditor C obtains an understanding of the client’s process for determining fair value measurements and the related disclosures.', 'Auditor D does not consider the expertise and experience of those persons determining the fair value measurements.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Under SAS No. 101, management is responsible for establishing an accounting and financial reporting process for determining fair value measurements. Auditor A should obtain an understanding of this process and the related disclosures, as well as the relevant controls sufficient to develop an effective audit approach.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Under SAS No. 101, Auditor B should consider the role that information technology has in the fair value measurement process.', 'Answer C is correct. Auditor C correctly obtains an understanding of the client’s process for determining fair value measurements and the related disclosures (in accordance with SAS No. 101).', 'Answer D is incorrect. Under SAS No. 101, Auditor C should consider the expertise and experience of those persons determining the fair value measurements.', ''),
(680, 35, 166, '<p><strong>Which of the following processes would normally fall within the scope of responsibility for management to perform under the standards of fieldwork included in SAS No. 101? </strong></p>', 'Company A’s management evaluates their intent and ability to carry out specific courses of action where they are relevant to the use of fair value measurements.', 'Company B’s management prepares fair value measurements and the related disclosures included in the financial statements.', 'Company C’s management evaluates whether the entity’s method for determining fair value measurements is applied consistently.', 'Company D’s management obtains sufficient appropriate audit evidence to provide reasonable assurance that fair value measurements and disclosures are in conformity with GAAP.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Under SAS 101, an auditor is responsible for evaluating management’s intent and ability to carry out specific courses of action where they are relevant to the use of fair value measurements.', 'Answer B is correct. Under SAS 101, management is responsible for making the fair value measurements and disclosures included in the financial statements. As part of fulfilling its responsibility, management needs to establish an accounting and financial reporting process for determining the fair value measurements and disclosures, select appropriate valuation methods, identify and adequately support any significant assumptions used, prepare the valuation, and ensure that the presentation and disclosure of the fair value measurements are in accordance with GAAP.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Under SAS 101, an auditor is responsible for evaluating whether an entity’s method for determining fair value measurements is applied consistently.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Under SAS 101, an auditor is responsible for obtaining sufficient appropriate audit evidence to provide reasonable assurance that fair value measurements and disclosures are in conformity with GAAP.', ''),
(681, 35, 166, '<p><strong>An auditor is preparing to perform substantive tests of his client&rsquo;s fair value measurements. Such tests would generally involve: </strong></p>', 'Developing independent fair value estimates for corroborative purposes.', 'Requiring the entity to measure its assets or liabilities using valuation models under all circumstances.', 'Preparing the fair value measurements and related disclosures included in the financial statements.', 'Ignoring subsequent events and transactions due to engagement time constraints.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. Substantive tests of the fair value measurements may involve (a) testing management''s significant assumptions, the valuation model, and the underlying data, (b) developing independent fair value estimates for corroborative purposes or (c) reviewing subsequent events and transactions.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Requiring a reporting entity to measure its assets or liabilities using valuation models under all circumstances would not be considered appropriate under SAS 101.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Under SAS 101, management (not the auditor) is responsible for preparing the fair value measurements and related disclosures.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Under SAS 101, an auditor should review subsequent events and transactions as part of the substantive tests.', ''),
(682, 35, 166, '<p><strong>For the following 4 questions, please refer to this information: </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A partner at Timlin &amp; Foulke, LLC is reviewing the work papers of the audit team assigned to Wakefield Bank. The audit papers show that Wakefield owns several investments for which there are no observable market prices. Wakefield used a valuation model to provide the fair values of those investments.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Which of the following actions should be taken by the audit firm regarding their client&rsquo;s failure to use observable market prices when estimating the fair values of these assets? </strong></p>', 'Issue a qualified opinion.', 'Withdraw from the engagement.', 'Accept the fair value measurement as provided, without further corroboration.', 'Evaluate whether the entity’s method of measurement is appropriate in the circumstances.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. ASC 820 permits the use of valuation models and their use alone is normally not cause for an auditor to issue a qualified opinion.', 'Answer B is incorrect. The use of valuation models is permitted under ASC 820, and therefore their use alone is normally not cause for an auditor to withdraw from an engagement.', 'Answer C is incorrect. An auditor should apply procedures to evaluate whether the assumptions included in a valuation model provide a reasonable basis for measuring fair values in the context of an audit of the financial statements taken as a whole.', 'Answer D is correct. When there are no observable market prices and the entity estimates fair value using a valuation method, the auditor should evaluate whether the entity''s method of measurement is appropriate in the circumstances. That evaluation requires the use of professional judgment. It also involves obtaining an understanding of management''s rationale for selecting a particular method by discussing with management its reasons for selecting the valuation method.', ''),
(683, 35, 166, '<p><strong>Which of the following procedures would the auditors at Timlin &amp; Foulke LLC most likely perform for assets valued using a valuation model?</strong></p>', 'Function as an appraiser and re-value the items using his or her own judgment.', 'Discourage management from using techniques such as sensitivity analysis to help identify particularly sensitive assumptions.', 'Review the model and evaluate whether the assumptions used are reasonable and appropriate.', 'Obtain sufficient appropriate audit evidence to provide an opinion on specific fair value assumptions included in the model.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Under SAS 101, an auditor is not required to not serve as an appraiser and is not expected to substitute his or her judgment for that of the entity''s management.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Under SAS 101, an auditor should encourage management to use techniques such as sensitivity analysis to help identify particularly sensitive assumptions.', 'Answer C is correct. Under SAS 101, for items valued by the entity using a valuation model, the auditor does not function as an appraiser and is not expected to substitute his or her judgment for that of the entity''s management. Rather, the auditor reviews the model and evaluates whether the assumptions used are reasonable and the model is appropriate considering the entity''s circumstances.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Under SAS 101, audit procedures dealing with management''s assumptions are performed in the context of the audit of the entity''s financial statements. The objective of the audit procedures is therefore not intended to obtain sufficient appropriate audit evidence to provide an opinion on the assumptions themselves.', ''),
(684, 35, 166, '<p><strong>When testing Wakefield&rsquo;s fair value measurements and disclosures, the T&amp;F auditors should:</strong></p>', 'Obtain sufficient appropriate audit evidence to provide an opinion on specific fair value assumptions.', 'Evaluate whether or not management’s assumptions are reasonable and reflect market information.', 'Prepare the fair value disclosures for Wakefield in accordance with GAAP.', 'Disregard the sensitivity of the valuation to changes in significant assumptions that may affect the value.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Audit procedures dealing with management''s assumptions are performed in the context of the audit of the entity''s financial statements. The objective of the audit procedures is therefore not intended to obtain sufficient appropriate audit evidence to provide an opinion on the assumptions themselves. Rather, the auditor performs procedures to evaluate whether the assumptions provide a reasonable basis for measuring fair values in the context of an audit of the financial statements taken as a whole.', 'Answer B is correct. The auditor does not function as an appraiser and is not expected to substitute his or her judgment for that of the entity''s management.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Management is responsible for preparing fair value disclosures in accordance with GAAP.', 'Answer D is incorrect. When testing an entity’s fair value measurements and disclosures, an auditor should consider the sensitivity of the valuation to changes in significant assumptions that may affect the value.', ''),
(685, 35, 166, '<p><strong>When auditing Wakefield&rsquo;s disclosures about fair values included in the notes to the financial statements, the T&amp;F auditors: </strong></p>', 'Should generally perform essentially the same types of audit procedures as those employed in auditing a fair value measurement recognized in the financial statements.', 'Are required to perform separate audit procedures to confirm that the disclosures are in conformity with GAAP.', 'Must always issue a qualified opinion if the disclosures are not in conformity with GAAP.', 'Should disregard sections related to the methods of estimation and significant assumptions made by management.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. When auditing fair value measurements and related disclosures included in the notes to the financial statements, whether required by GAAP or disclosed voluntarily, the auditor ordinarily performs essentially the same types of audit procedures as those employed in auditing a fair value measurement recognized in the financial statements. The auditor obtains sufficient appropriate audit evidence that the valuation principles are appropriate under GAAP and are being consistently applied, and that the method of estimation and significant assumptions used are adequately disclosed in accordance with GAAP.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Separate audit procedures to confirm that the disclosures are in conformity with GAAP are not required under SAS 101.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Under SAS 101, if the entity has not appropriately disclosed fair value information required by GAAP, the auditor evaluates whether the financial statements are materially misstated.', 'Answer D is incorrect. An auditor should not disregard procedures to confirm that the disclosures are in conformity with GAAP under SAS 101.', ''),
(686, 35, 167, '<p><strong>For the following 4 questions, please refer to this information:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Beantown Enterprises frequently (1) issues debt instruments to fund its operations and (2) purchases investment securities that is classifies as &ldquo;Trading&rdquo;. The Trading securities are measured at fair value on the balance sheet, with changes in fair value recognized in earnings. The debt issued to fund its operations is measured at amortized cost. The CFO of Beantown Enterprises is concerned about the resulting accounting mismatch that has been impacting Beantown&rsquo;s earnings for the year. The CFO would like to apply the &ldquo;fair value option&rdquo; to eliminate this mismatch, as well as other similar mismatches that exist on their balance sheet.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The use of the fair value option in the case of Beantown Enterprises would:</strong></p>', 'Provide them the option of measuring their Trading securities at amortized cost on the balance sheet.', 'Require all of their financial instruments to be measured at fair value on the balance sheet.', 'Expands their ability to select the basis of measurement for their debt.', 'Limits their ability to select the basis of measurement for their debt.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The fair value option provides the ability to measure certain financial instruments at fair value on the balance sheet. It does not provide for the ability to measure financial instruments at amortized cost.', 'Answer B is incorrect. The fair value option is an optional election to measure financial instruments on the balance sheet at fair value. It does not require such measurement.', 'Answer C is correct. The fair value option provides the ability to measure certain financial instruments at fair value on the balance sheet. It considerably expands the ability of a reporting entity to select the basis of measurement for certain assets and liabilities.', 'Answer D is incorrect. The fair value option expands (not limits) the ability of a reporting entity to select the basis of measurement for certain assets and liabilities.', ''),
(687, 35, 167, '<p><strong>One of the benefits of the fair value option is that it would allow Beantown to:</strong></p>', 'Offset changes in the fair values of their derivative instruments and the related hedged items while avoiding complex hedge accounting.', 'Apply fair value accounting to investments in subsidiaries that Beantown is required to consolidate.', 'Revoke the election at any point in the future.', 'Reduce the comparability of their financial statements, as similar assets or liabilities could be reported under different measurement attributes.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. Both ASC 815-15-25 and ASC 825-10 allow entities to offset changes in the fair values of a derivative instrument and the related hedged item by selecting the FVO for the hedged item. This means entities can avoid application of complex hedge accounting provisions.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Investments in subsidiaries that require consolidation are excluded from the scope of ASC 825-10.', 'Answer C is incorrect. The election of the fair value option is irrevocable.', 'Answer D is incorrect. The fair value option can reduce the comparability of financial statements, as similar assets or liabilities could be reported under different measurement attributes. However, this reduced comparability is not considered to be a benefit of the fair value option.', ''),
(688, 35, 167, '<p><strong>Once Beantown has elected the fair value option, the election is:</strong></p>', 'Revocable at any point in the future.', 'Revocable in the current reporting period only.', 'Revocable only when hedge accounting is subsequently applied.', 'Irrevocable.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Under U.S. GAAP, election of the fair value option may not revocable at any point in the future.', 'Answer B is incorrect. The fair value option is not revocable in the current reporting period.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Once this fair value option is elected, it is irrevocable.', 'Answer D is correct. In accordance with the requirements of U.S. GAAP, once the FVO election is made it is irrevocable. Reporting entities must continue to measure applicable assets or liabilities at fair value going forward.', ''),
(689, 35, 167, '<p><strong>Items currently on Beantown&rsquo;s balance sheet that are eligible for the fair value option include the company&rsquo;s:</strong></p>', 'Consolidated subsidiaries.', 'Fixed rate demand deposits.', 'Loan commitments.', 'Consolidated variable interest entities.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Under ASC 825-10, the fair value option may not be applied to investments in subsidiaries that the entity is required to consolidate.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Under ASC 825-10, the fair value option may not be applied to demand deposit liabilities.', 'Answer C is correct. ASC 825-10 allows entities to elect the fair value option for specified financial assets and financial liabilities, including written loan commitments.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Under ASC 825-10, the fair value option may not be applied to interests in variable interest entities that the reporting entity is required to consolidate.', ''),
(690, 35, 167, '<p><strong>Which of the following accounting practices represents an application of the fair value option that is consistent with the requirements of ASC 825-10?</strong></p>', 'Company A elected the option in 2008 for a group of assets and subsequently revoked the option in 2009.', 'Company B elects the option on an instrument-by-instrument basis.', 'Company C elects the option at any point during the life cycle of a financial asset or liability.', 'Company D elected the option for its interests in variable interest entities that the company is required to consolidate.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Under ASC 825-10, the election of the fair value option is irrevocable. Therefore Company A would be required to apply the fair value option in 2008, 2009, and beyond.', 'Answer B is correct. ASC 825-10 permits reporting entities to apply the FVO on an instrument-by-instrument basis. Therefore, Company B is permitted to elect the FVO for certain instruments but not others within a group of similar items (e.g., for some debt securities but not for others).', 'Answer C is incorrect. Under ASC 825-10, Company C must generally elect the fair value option when an asset or liability is initially recognized in the financial statements (with limited exceptions).', 'Answer D is incorrect. Under ASC 825-10, Company D would not be able to elect the fair value option for variable interest entities that the company is required to consolidate. These items are specifically excluded from the scope of the Standard.', ''),
(691, 35, 167, '<p><strong>For the following 4 questions, please refer to this information:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Lowe Bank elected the fair value option to account for financial assets held in one of their portfolios. Lowe chose to elect the option only for certain instruments held in that portfolio; the remaining instruments continued to be recognized at amortized cost. Lowe generally pays upfront fees whenever purchasing these assets.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Subsequent to the fair value option election, the changes in fair value associated with Lowe&rsquo;s FVO assets should be reflected:</strong></p>', 'In other comprehensive income.', 'As a direct adjustment to retained earnings.', 'In earnings.', 'On the balance sheet as a contra-asset or contra-liability.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The changes in fair value must be reflected in earnings (not in other comprehensive income, which is a component of equity).', 'Answer B is incorrect. The changes in fair value must be reflected in current period earnings. It should not be recognized as a direct adjustment to retained earnings.', 'Answer C is correct. Once the fair value option is elected for a financial asset or liability, the changes in fair value for that item going forward are reflected in earnings.', 'Answer D is incorrect. The changes in fair value must be reflected in earnings (not on the balance sheet as a contra-asset or contra-liability).', ''),
(692, 35, 167, '<p><strong>The upfront fees paid by Lowe to purchase their assets accounted for using the fair value option should be ________; the upfront fees paid by Lowe to purchase their assets accounted for at amortized cost should be ________.</strong></p>', 'Deferred; expensed.', 'Deferred; deferred.', 'Expensed; expensed.', 'Expensed; deferred.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Under ASC 825-10, upfront fees associated with assets that are accounted for under the fair value option should be recognized as an expense in the income statement (not deferred on the balance sheet).', 'Answer B is incorrect. Under U.S. GAAP, upfront fees associated with financial assets that are measured at amortized cost are deferred on the balance sheet and amortized into earnings over time. However those same fees would be immediately expensed if the fair value option is elected.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Upfront fees associated with assets that are accounted for at amortized cost should not be expensed immediately.', 'Answer D is correct. Upfront fees associated with assets that are accounted for under the fair value option should be expensed as incurred; upfront fees associated with assets that are accounted for at amortized cost should be deferred and amortized.', ''),
(693, 35, 167, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements correctly summarizes Lowe&rsquo;s ability to elect the fair value option on an instrument-by-instrument basis?</strong></p>', 'Such election is strictly prohibited.', 'Such election is permitted, but only for “hybrid” financial instruments.', 'Such election would require additional disclosures in this case.', 'Such election requires no additional disclosures.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. ASC 825-10 would permit Lowe to apply the fair value option on an instrument-by-instrument basis.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Lowe would be permitted to elect the fair value option for its financial assets on an instrument-by-instrument basis. Such election is not limited to hybrid instruments.', 'Answer C is correct. ASC 825-10 permits entities to apply the FVO on an instrument-by-instrument basis; however, it requires additional disclosures if the FVO is elected for only some of the eligible items within a group of similar eligible items (e.g., a description of those similar items and reasons for partial election).', 'Answer D is incorrect. ASC 825-10 requires additional disclosures when the fair value option is elected.', ''),
(694, 35, 167, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements correctly summarizes the ASC 825-10 presentation requirements for the interest income earned on Lowe&rsquo;s FVO assets?</strong></p>', 'Lowe is prohibited from presenting any items associated with its FVO assets in interest income.', 'Lowe may use judgment when determining how to report the interest income.', 'Lowe must present all fair value changes in non-interest income.', 'Lowe must present the amortization of the upfront fees paid on their FVO assets in interest income.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. Lowe is not prohibited from presenting items (such as interest accruals, fair value gains & losses) in interest income under ASC 825-10.', 'Answer B is correct. ASC 825-10 allows for significant policy discretion in how to report interest income and expense for items under the FVO. The Standard does not include specific presentation requirements.', 'Answer C is incorrect. Lowe is not specifically required to present fair value changes in non-interest income by ASC 825-10.', 'Answer D is incorrect. Upfront fees associated with assets that are accounted for under the fair value option should not be deferred and amortized.', ''),
(695, 35, 168, '<p><strong>An author is writing a book on the pros and cons of fair value accounting. Which of the following arguments is generally considered one of the principal criticisms of fair value?</strong></p>', 'Fair value accounting is pro-cyclical.', 'Fair value accounting is counter-cyclical.', 'Fair value accounting creates an upward bias on asset values during periods of illiquid market conditions.', 'Fair value accounting failed to expose the financial industry''s ailing financial condition during the global credit crisis.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is correct. Fair value is believed by some to be very “pro-cyclical” (in economic terms). In other words, it tends to magnify current financial trends, whatever they are.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Fair value is believed by some to be very pro-cyclical, not counter-cyclical.', 'Answer C is incorrect. A common criticism of fair value accounting is that it creates a downward (not upward) bias on asset values during periods of illiquid market conditions.', 'Answer D is incorrect. This criticism applied to historical cost accounting during the S&L Crisis. It does not apply to fair value accounting.', ''),
(696, 35, 168, '<p><strong>Which of the following asset valuation approaches is considered the most appropriate according to the CAQ white paper &ldquo;Measurements of Fair Value in Illiquid (or Less Liquid Markets)&rdquo;?</strong></p>', 'Company A estimates the price that would be received under optimal market conditions.', 'Company B estimates the price that would be received under existing market conditions.', 'Company C estimates the price that would be received under illiquid market conditions.', 'Company D estimates the price that would be received under expected (future) market conditions.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. The objective of a valuation is to estimate the price that would be received under existing (not optimal) market conditions. Existing market conditions may be illiquid or inactive due to various economic factors.', 'Answer B is correct. According to the white paper, the objective of a valuation is to estimate the price that would be received under existing market conditions. Therefore, the assumptions used in a valuation model must be consistent with assumptions that market participants would use to price an asset at the measurement date.', 'Answer C is incorrect. The CAQ white paper does not present an argument that assets should be valued at a hypothetical price under illiquid market conditions. Rather, the paper argues that assets should be valued based on a price that would be received under existing market conditions.', 'Answer D is incorrect. The objective of a valuation is to estimate the price that would be received under existing (not expected) market conditions.', ''),
(697, 35, 168, '<p><strong>Which of the following valuation methodologies has garnered significant criticism from FASB constituents for creating a &ldquo;downward bias&rdquo; on asset fair values?</strong></p>', 'Company A uses a valuation model with significant unobservable inputs.', 'Company B adjusts the market price to remove the effect of abnormal liquidity risk premiums.', 'Company C uses an unadjusted last transaction price.', 'Company D uses the income approach described in ASC 820.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. A valuation model that uses significant unobservable inputs has not been criticized for creating a downward bias on asset values.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Adjusting a market price to remove the effect of abnormal liquidity risk premiums would likely increase (not decrease) the fair value of the asset.', 'Answer C is correct. Many believe that the fair value hierarchy within ASC 820 creates a downward bias on asset values by favoring observable market transactions (i.e. the last transaction prices) even when those transactions may be “distressed” or the market for those transactions may not be active.', 'Answer D is incorrect. The income approach has not been criticized for creating a downward bias on asset values.', ''),
(698, 35, 168, '<p><strong>Williams Co. is attempting to estimate the fair value of a financial asset that is associated with a market that is currently inactive. According to the FASB amendment to ASC 820 issued in March 2009, factors that indicate that a market is inactive would include:</strong></p>', 'Many recent market transactions.', 'Many recent market transactions.', 'Normal liquidity risk premiums.', 'Indexes that are not highly correlated with the fair values of the asset.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Answer A is incorrect. As discussed in the ASC 820 amendment, few recent market transactions are an indicator that a market is inactive. Many market transactions are indicative of an active market.', 'Answer B is incorrect. Price quotations that vary substantially among market makers are an indicator that a market is inactive.', 'Answer C is incorrect. A liquidity risk premium is a premium that investors will demand when any given security cannot be easily converted into cash, and converted at the fair value. When the liquidity premium is high, then the asset is said to be illiquid. Abnormal liquidity risk premiums are an indicator that a market is inactive.', 'Answer D is correct. Indexes that previously were highly correlated with the fair values of the asset are demonstrably uncorrelated with recent fair values would be considered an indication that an inactive market exists. This is an indicator of an inactive market', ''),
(699, 46, 169, '<p><strong>When shipping merchandise directly from its home state warehouse to a customer in a different destination state, an out-of-state business may be required to collect:</strong></p>', 'The destination state’s sales tax.', 'The destination state’s use tax.', 'Its home state’s sales or use tax.', 'Neither state’s tax can be asserted against the business, since the purchaser is the primary taxpayer.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Pursuant to the “dormant” commerce clause of the U.S. Constitution, a state may not impose its sales tax on a sale that occurs outside its borders.', 'Correct.  If the seller is regarded as doing business in the destination state, it is required to collect that state’s use tax on sales of merchandise shipped to consumers within the state’s borders, unless some other exemption applies.', 'Incorrect.  Since the buyer does not take possession or make use of the property in the seller’s state, that state’s sales or use tax does not apply.', 'Incorrect.  Although the purchaser is considered the primary taxpayer for use tax purposes, under some circumstances a state may pursue either the buyer or the seller for the tax.', ''),
(700, 46, 169, '<p><strong>In order to be regarded as &ldquo;doing business&rdquo; in a state, an enterprise must:</strong></p>', 'Be registered with the Secretary of State.', 'Have established an economic presence within the state.', 'Have established a de minimus physical presence within the state.', 'Have established a substantial nexus within the state.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Unless the enterprise has established a physical presence sufficient to establish substantial nexus, it will not be regarded as doing business in the state.', 'Incorrect.  An economic presence does not in itself create nexus for sales and use tax purposes.  To be regarded as doing business (having nexus) in the state, the enterprise must have a physical presence that rises beyond a de minimus (slightest presence) level.', 'Incorrect.  Under the criterion articulated in the Quill case, a de minimus physical presence will not be sufficient to create substantial nexus, which is the threshold for being regarded as doing business in the state.', 'Correct.  Substantial nexus is the criterion reaffirmed by Quill as being sufficient to overcome the dormant commerce clause and establish a company as “doing business” within a state.', ''),
(701, 46, 169, '<p><strong>Which case or legislation provides the best general guideline for determining sales and use tax nexus?</strong></p>', 'Complete Auto, Inc. v. Brady', 'Scripto, Inc. v. Carson', 'Quill Corporation v. North Dakota', 'The Marketplace Fairness Act', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.   Complete Auto, Inc. v. Brady established that a business must have a substantial nexus with the taxing state to overcome the dormant commerce clause, but the case did not provide criteria for determining when the “substantial” threshold would be reached.', 'Incorrect.  Scripto, Inc. v. Carson the Court ruled that substantial nexus was created under a specific fact pattern (the presence of ten independent contractors soliciting sales in the state) but did not propose a general rule.', 'Correct.  Quill Corporation v. North Dakota reaffirmed the physical presence requirement as the appropriate criterion for establishing “substantial nexus” and provided the best available guidance for determining the threshold for such presence.', 'Incorrect.  The Marketplace Fairness Act is proposed legislation that has not been enacted.', ''),
(702, 46, 169, '<p><strong>Once a firm is determined to be doing business in a state, it must:</strong></p>', 'Register as a seller and remit the state’s sales or use tax on all of its taxable sales of goods shipped to customers in the state.', 'Register as a seller and remit sales or use tax on all of its sales of taxable merchandise regardless of destination.', 'Register as a seller and remit sales or use tax on all sales of goods shipped to customers in the state except for sales made over the Internet, which are exempt under the Internet Tax Freedom Act.', 'Register as a seller and remit sales or use tax on all sales of goods to residents of the state, regardless of where the goods are shipped.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct.  The seller will be responsible for remitting sales or use tax on all taxable sales of merchandise that it ships to recipients in the state.', 'Incorrect.  The seller will be responsible for remitting sales or use tax on taxable sales of merchandise that it ships to recipients in the state; it will not be responsible for remitting tax on sales of items shipped to customers in other states unless it has nexus in those states as well.', 'Incorrect.  There are no specific sales or use tax exemptions for sales made over the Internet.', 'Incorrect.  Goods shipped to a buyer at a location outside the buyer’s home state cannot be subjected to the home state’s use tax unless the goods were actually bought for use in that state and, after receiving the items, the purchaser in fact transports them to the home state for use therein.', ''),
(703, 46, 170, '<p><strong>The following in-state presence of merchandise owned by an out-of-state company would not justify an assertion of nexus, assuming no other form of in-state presence existed:</strong></p>', 'Recurring deliveries of the out-of-state company’s products are made into the state by common carrier.', 'Property owned by the out-of-state company is stored by an independent contractor inside the state pending shipment to in-state customers.', 'The out-of-state company ships merchandise to third party assemblers within the destination state, which put the property together before forwarding it to in-state customers.', 'The out-of-state company sometimes uses its own vans to deliver merchandise to customers in the destination state.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct.  The courts have repeatedly held that deliveries of an out-of-state company’s products by common carrier do not create nexus.', 'Incorrect.  In-state storage of property owned by an out-of-state company will generally be construed as establishing a physical presence sufficient to justify a finding of nexus.', 'Incorrect.  The out-of-state company’s contracting for in-state assembly of its merchandise constitutes an in-state exercise of ownership as well as a step in the process of manufacturing its own products.  Such activities performed on the company’s property would establish substantial nexus.', 'Incorrect.  When an out-of-state seller delivers its merchandise to customers in its own vehicles, nexus is very likely to be asserted by the destination state.', ''),
(704, 46, 170, '<p><strong>Nexus probably could not be successfully asserted against an out-of-state company based on the presence of an in-state employee under the following circumstances:</strong></p>', 'An employee of the out-of-state company makes periodic visits to in-state customers to inspect and calibrate equipment that the customers bought from the company.', 'The in-state employee works remotely from her home in the destination state and is responsible for maintaining and periodically updating the advertising language and graphics on the company’s website.', 'The out-of-state company hires an in-house internal auditor who lives in the destination state and often works from his home.  Under the destination state’s statute, “doing business in the state” includes maintaining resident employees provided that such employees are engaged in sales activities on behalf of their employers.', 'The out-of-state company periodically sends an employee into the state to follow up on sales leads and take orders for merchandise.  The orders must be forwarded to the out-of-state company’s headquarters, which has the sole authority for approving and authorizing the sales.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Remote sellers with one or more employees regularly travelling to the state for purposes related to the sellers’ business activities generally will be found to be doing business in the state.', 'Incorrect.  Maintaining a permanent employee in the state will almost always be regarded as establishing nexus.', 'Correct.  The state’s statute specifies that maintaining resident employees will be regarded as “doing business” provided that the employees are engaged in sales activities.  Since the internal auditor would not be engaged in sales activities, his presence should not create nexus.', 'Incorrect.  Virtually any regular in-state sales activity by a remote seller’s employees will be regarded as establishing nexus.', ''),
(705, 46, 170, '<p><strong>An out-of-state company&rsquo;s use of in-state independent contractors probably will not create nexus under the following circumstances:</strong></p>', 'The out-of-state company engages a contractor to make in-state warranty repairs on products it has sold.', 'The company hires an in-state independent consultant to provide advice on personnel matters.', 'A resident independent manufacturer’s representative makes periodic visits to potential or existing customers in the state to explain the uses of the company’s products or deal with troubleshooting issues.', 'The company engages independent in-state telemarketers to solicit sales throughout the country.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  A contractor’s performance of in-state warranty repair services for an out-of-state company will create nexus for the out-of-state seller.', 'Correct.  The use of an in-state independent consultant that does not make sales, develop an in-state market for the out-of-state retailer, or interact with the retailer’s customers generally will not rise to the level of “doing business” in the state.', 'Incorrect.  The representative’s explanations of the uses of the out-of-state company’s products and its assistance with troubleshooting issues would be regarded as promoting sales and enhancing the retailer’s in-state market.', 'Incorrect.  An out-of-state company’s engagement of an in-state telemarketing company has been found to constitute sales activities sufficient to be regarded as “doing business” in the state.', ''),
(706, 46, 171, '<p><strong>The following was an outcome of New York&rsquo;s Orvis Co., Inc. case:</strong></p>', 'The case significantly helped to clarify the bright line established by the U.S. Supreme Court in its definition of “substantial nexus.”', 'Every other state has now accepted Orvis Co., Inc. as binding legal precedent.', 'The conclusions of the justices in both the Orvis case and the related case involving Vermont Information Processing, Inc. were unanimous.', 'A different state’s Supreme Court explicitly rejected the standard applied by the New York appeals court in the Orvis case.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  As demonstrated by the dissenting opinion in the case, Orvis highlights the confusion created by the U.S. Supreme Court’s “bright line.”  To date, nobody has clearly established the point at which “the slightest physical presence” ends and substantial nexus begins.', 'Incorrect.  Nexus rulings are often inconsistent from state to state.  Kansas has specifically declined to follow the Orvis court’s reasoning.', 'Incorrect.  A similar dissent was issued in both cases. The dissenting justice believed that neither company’s activities were sufficient to establish substantial nexus.', 'Correct.  The Supreme Court of Kansas has specifically stated that it would not apply the criteria used by the New York Court of Appeals in Orvis.', '');
INSERT INTO `chapter_review_questions` (`rev_ques_id`, `course_id`, `chapter_id`, `rev_ques_title`, `rev_ques_ans_1`, `rev_ques_ans_2`, `rev_ques_ans_3`, `rev_ques_ans_4`, `rev_ques_ans_5`, `rev_correct_ans_id`, `rev_correct_ans_text`, `rev_wronge_ans_text`, `rev_ques_status`, `ans1_text`, `ans2_text`, `ans3_text`, `ans4_text`, `ans5_text`) VALUES
(707, 46, 171, '<p><strong>Which of the following fact patterns would probably <u>not </u>result in an assertion of nexus? </strong></p>', 'An appliance company has no permanent physical presence within State A.  Approximately twelve times per year, the company dispatches resident (State A) independent contractors to perform warranty and repair work for customers within State A.', 'Company B sells software online.  The software is delivered to its customers in state C electronically, via download from a remote server located in state X.  The company’s lead software developer attends an annual one-day conference in state C where entrepreneurs present new software products and ideas to a variety of attendees.  The developer does not solicit sales at the conference.', 'A garage door manufacturer produces all of its doors at facilities in China.  The doors are delivered to the manufacturer’s home state of Louisiana, where it maintains its administrative offices and warehousing facilities.  The doors are sold directly to homeowners throughout the nation, and all shipments are made by common carrier from Louisiana.  The sales are solicited over the Internet and through the mail by catalog.  Last year, the company sent technicians to Texas on twenty separate occasions to install doors for its customers.', 'A home electronics store located in New Jersey only markets to local residents through radio and print ads.  The store is, however, also known to residents of New York for providing great deals on televisions.  If a television is too large for a customer’s vehicle, the store will deliver it for a small charge using one of its own trucks, retaining title prior to delivery.  It makes approximately twenty deliveries into New York each year.  On some of those occasions, the delivery driver will help the customer set up the television.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Under the US Supreme Court ruling in Scripto, it makes no difference whether a company uses regular employees or independent contractors. It generally will not matter that the contractors are performing repair work and not making sales.  State A would probably assert nexus under the theory that the warranty and repair work helps to develop and maintain a market in the state.', 'Correct.  The software developer attends the conference to learn about new products and ideas; does not solicit sales; and only visits the state one day annually.  This activity probably would not be sufficient to motivate state C to assert substantial nexus.', 'Incorrect.  The installation of a garage door is generally regarded as a construction contract.  Fulfilling such contracts within a state approximately twenty times in one year will be regarded as doing business in the state and create an assertion of nexus.', 'Incorrect.  The company uses its own trucks to deliver televisions into New York approximately twenty times each year, and it retains title to the televisions prior to delivery.  Because title transfers inside New York upon delivery, the sale occurs within the state.  An average of twenty annual sales within a state would establish sales and use tax nexus in New York or any other state with a sales tax program.  (Note that when merchandise is delivered in company vehicles, title will usually be regarded as transferring at the point of delivery in the absence of a specific contractual clause to the contrary.)', ''),
(708, 46, 171, '<p><strong>Company A, a New York accounting software vendor, is seeking to expand its market to various other states. &nbsp;To aid in that effort, it plans to attend and/or participate in a variety of trade shows within its target states. &nbsp;Under which of the following fact patterns would nexus probably be asserted?</strong></p>', 'To learn what a typical accounting trade show in New Jersey would entail, the company sends one of its sales managers to a three-day show in Newark.  While at the show, the manager attends several continuing education seminars and otherwise mingles with a variety of participants.', 'Because the company considers California a primary target for its growth plans, it purchases space at four different five-day trade shows to be held in the following year.  The company plans to send four sales representatives and numerous copies of its software with the intention of making as many sales as possible at the shows.  It hopes to maintain this level of participation indefinitely.', 'The company will participate in three trade shows in Utah, each lasting two days, in an effort to establish relationships with accounting professionals.  It does not intend to send sales personnel or otherwise make sales at these shows.', 'The company will participate in the largest annual accounting show in Kansas, which will last five days.  It will send five employees, including three sales representatives, along with several copies of its software, with the intention of making as many sales as possible.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  States typically make a distinction between merely attending a trade show and actually participating in presentations.  If an employee merely attends the trade show, even if he signs up for seminars and actively engages in discussions with its participants/presenters, nexus will not be asserted.', 'Correct.  Although many states, including California, provide a safe harbor for attending trade shows, most states would assert nexus under the circumstances presented here.  California permits up to 15 days of participation at trade shows within a 12 month period, but it would assert nexus following the fifteenth day.  Further, even if a state did not assert nexus based on participation in the show, it would probably require the company to apply for a temporary permit and report any sales that occurred at the show.', 'Incorrect.  Utah provides a safe harbor for companies attending trade shows for less than a two-week period.  Although attendance is planned at three separate shows, the company will only be present for a total of six days, which accordingly should not trigger nexus.  Further, no sales will be made at the shows; the purpose of attendance is merely to establish relationships.', 'Incorrect.  Kansas allows trade show activities without limitation only if the company’s employees or representatives do not negotiate or take orders for sales at the shows.', ''),
(709, 46, 172, '<p><strong>A state is likely to successfully assert affiliate (related entity) nexus against an out-of-state remote seller if:</strong></p>', 'An in-state independent third-party contractor performs warranty repairs on behalf of the out-of-state seller.', 'A related in-state entity accepts returned merchandise and makes exchanges on behalf of the remote seller.', 'An out-of-state remote seller is a corporate subsidiary of an in-state company; the subsidiary and its in-state parent operate as separate entities, do not act as agents for one another, and are in different lines of business.', 'An in-state corporate subsidiary distributes discount coupons that are redeemable on purchases from its parent corporation, an out-of-state remote seller.  The companies otherwise maintain complete separation with respect to their operations, personnel, property, management, and information systems.  The in-state subsidiary does not provide preferential treatment to the online seller’s customers, nor does it accept returns of products bought by those customers.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Warranty repairs by an independent contractor would create agency nexus but not affiliate nexus.  The contractor is regarded as acting as the seller’s agent but is not a related entity.', 'Correct.  An in-state company that accepts returns of an out-of-state affiliate’s merchandise will establish nexus for the out-of-state seller.', 'Incorrect.  Nexus is unlikely to be upheld if the out-of-state seller and in-state parent have no common activities and maintain complete separation.', 'Incorrect.  If complete separation is otherwise maintained and no other intercompany activities are involved, any presence created by the in-state subsidiary’s distribution of the out-of-state company’s discount coupons would probably be regarded as insignificant.', ''),
(710, 46, 172, '<p><strong>Each of the following fact patterns involves an out-of-state remote seller and a commonly owned in-state business that is a separate legal entity. &nbsp;The great majority of states probably would not assert nexus under the following circumstances:</strong></p>', 'For a monthly fee, a division of the out-of-state company provides accounting and administrative services for the in-state affiliate.  The division provides similar services at comparable rates for unrelated businesses.  Otherwise, the affiliates maintain complete separation.', 'The instate company sells gift cards that are redeemable by the online company and include the online affiliate’s website address.  The in-state company also offers preferential treatment to returns of items bought from the online company.  The two companies engage in cross-advertising, sell memberships under which customers can receive discounts on purchases from either entity, and share common trademarks and logos.', 'The in-state affiliate and the out-of-state seller offer similar products, operate under similar business names, and use similar trademarks.', 'The in-state affiliate and the out-of-state seller maintain common legal, accounting, marketing, and human resources departments and share a common business plan.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct.  The services provided by the out-of-state affiliate are unrelated to sales activities and are transacted at arm’s length, since they’re provided to outside companies at similar rates.  Most states would not even try to assert nexus in these circumstances.', 'Incorrect.  This level of intercompany sales-related activities would probably result in an assertion of nexus.', 'Incorrect.  Many states have enacted legislation that either specifically states or strongly implies that nexus will be presumed when an out-of-state seller and a commonly owned in-state affiliate offer similar products, operate under similar business names, and use similar trademarks.', 'Incorrect.  The affiliates are commingling their activities to an extent that their legal status as separate entities could be jeopardized.  Most, if not all, state agencies would assert nexus in this situation.', ''),
(711, 46, 173, '<p><strong>The usual guidelines applied by &ldquo;click-through&rdquo; states when asserting nexus for out-of-state companies do not include the following:</strong></p>', 'An in-state business maintains a link on its website that enables customers to access the website of an out-of-state seller, where the customers can make purchases from the out-of-state seller.', 'In most of the click-through states, the out-of-state company’s sales resulting from sources within the state must exceed a specified minimum dollar amount.', 'Once the out-of-state seller’s activities are determined to meet the state’s click-through guidelines, the presumption of nexus is no longer rebuttable.', 'The in-state business must “solicit” on behalf of the out-of-state seller in a way that significantly enhances the seller’s ability to establish or maintain an in-state market.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Maintenance of a link on an in-state company’s website is the first prerequisite for asserting click-through nexus.', 'Incorrect.  Most (although not all) of the click-through states have established a minimum level of sales that must be made from in-state sources within the prior twelve months before nexus will be asserted.', 'Correct.  The presumption of nexus may generally be rebutted by evidence that the activities of the in-state sources did not significantly enhance the out-of-state company’s ability to create or maintain a market within the state.', 'Incorrect. “Solicitation” (as defined by each individual state) by the in-state source(s) on behalf of the out-of-state seller generally must be present in order for a state to assert click-through nexus.', ''),
(712, 46, 173, '<p><strong>In order for a state&rsquo;s assertion of click-through nexus to be upheld by most courts, the following factor must be present:</strong></p>', 'The in-state web host must be compensated by the out-of-state seller based on the number of clicks on the host’s link to the seller’s website.', 'The out-of-state company’s sales resulting from the in-state sources must exceed $10,000 for the preceding year.', 'The seller must have an explicit provision in its contract with the in-state web host requiring the host to solicit customers on behalf of the seller.', 'The in-state web host must solicit on behalf of the out-of-state seller in a manner that can be significantly associated with the seller’s ability to establish or maintain an in-state market.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  The out-of state seller must compensate the in-state sources through commissions or other methods based on sales.  Payment based on the number of clicks on the seller’s link would not constitute “compensation” for this purpose.', 'Incorrect.  The $10,000 threshold is common but not a required element.  No minimum in-state sales figure has been stipulated by case law as a requirement for assertion of nexus, even though most click-through states have established such a minimum', 'Incorrect.  If the in-state affiliate is actually determined to be soliciting customers on behalf of the seller (and the other “doing business” prerequisites are present), nexus will be asserted whether or not a clause in the contract requires solicitation.', 'Correct.  For nexus to be successfully asserted, the in-state web host not only must solicit on behalf of the out-of-state seller; the manner of solicitation must be found to significantly enhance the seller’s ability to establish or maintain an in-state market.', ''),
(713, 46, 175, '<p><strong>When a state requires a vendor that otherwise lacks nexus to register and report for sales and use tax purposes as a condition of doing business with one of its state agencies, the following stipulation will apply:</strong></p>', 'The vendor will have to report its sales to all state and local government agencies but will not have to report sales to private individuals or companies.', 'In most cases both the vendor and its affiliates will be required to register, collect, and remit the states’ sales and use taxes.', 'The vendor will be required to collect and remit all applicable state taxes on its sales within the state but will not be held responsible for collecting and reporting local sales taxes.', 'In all of the applicable states, vendors will be required to register and report for sales and use tax purposes if they enter into contracts with either state or local government agencies.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  The vendor will have to report all of its in-state sales and collect and remit the applicable sales and use taxes, regardless of the nature of the customers.', 'Correct.   The applicable states are generally prohibited from buying or leasing tangible personal property from vendors and their affiliates unless the vendors and affiliates register, collect, and remit the states’ sales and use taxes.', 'Incorrect.  The vendor will be required to collect and remit both state and local sales and use taxes arising from sales to customers in the state.', 'Incorrect.  In most of the applicable states, the requirement to register only arises in connection with contracts with state agencies.', ''),
(714, 46, 175, '<p><strong>Incorporation, obtaining a certificate of authority to transact business, or voluntary registration for sales and use tax purposes will generally have the following effect with respect to the applicable state:</strong></p>', 'The company will have established nexus for sales and use tax purposes.', 'No presumption of nexus will be created by these actions.', 'Either obtaining a certificate of authority to transact business or voluntary registration will create a presumption of sales and use tax nexus; merely incorporating in the state will not.', 'Voluntary registration for sales and use tax purposes will create a presumption that the registrant is accepting responsibility for the state’s collecting and reporting requirements.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Absent additional indicators, incorporation or obtaining a certificate of authority to transact business in a state will usually be insufficient for an assertion of nexus.', 'Incorrect.  Voluntary registration for sales and use tax purposes will generally create a presumption of nexus.', 'Incorrect.  Neither obtaining a certificate of authority to transact business nor incorporating in the state will create a presumption of sales and use tax nexus in the great majority of cases.', 'Correct.  Once a business registers for a sales and use tax permit, it should assume that it will be treated no differently than any other registered taxpayer, whether or not it actually has a physical presence in the state.', ''),
(715, 46, 174, '<p><strong>When a business learns that it unknowingly established nexus several years ago in states where it has been making a significant volume of remote sales, it should:</strong></p>', 'Immediately cease making sales into the applicable states.', 'Register for a seller’s permit in each of the states and start collecting and reporting tax from the date of registration forward.', 'Review the available options for voluntarily disclosing its prior sales, select the most favorable alternative, make the disclosure, pay any agreed-upon back taxes, and register, collect and report going forward.', 'Go back to its customers, bill them for the taxes that should have been charged, turn any amounts collected over to the states, and register, collect and report going forward.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Ceasing all sales will not extinguish the liability for past activities, nor will it shorten the statute of limitations for the liability.', 'Incorrect.  Reporting on a “going forward” basis will not extinguish the liability for past activities, nor will it shorten the statute of limitations for the liability.', 'Correct.  Voluntary disclosure will result in the most favorable possible resolution of past liabilities, and collecting and reporting on a “going forward” basis will minimize subsequent exposure.', 'Incorrect.  The business is responsible for all taxes due on its previous transactions.  Unless the business bills every prior customer for the taxes that should have been charged and every customer actually remits the taxes billed, the business will not have extinguished its entire liability by turning the amounts collected over to the state.', ''),
(716, 46, 174, '<p><strong>The Multistate Tax Commission&rsquo;s Voluntary Disclosure Program does not include the following provision(s):</strong></p>', 'Member states will limit their look-back periods to approximately three to four years for qualifying taxpayers.', 'The identity of a taxpayer applying for the program will remain confidential until an agreement with the applicable state has been finalized; upon finalization, the taxpayer’s identity will be disclosed only to the state that is party to the agreement.', 'The taxpayer may apply for voluntary disclosure to as many or as few participating states as it wishes.', 'The participating states will generally waive interest and penalties on all back taxes due.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  The MTC’s voluntary disclosure program does provide that its member states will limit their look-back periods to approximately three to four years for qualifying taxpayers.', 'Incorrect.  The MTC’s voluntary disclosure program does provide that the taxpayer’s identity will be disclosed only to the state that is party to the agreement, and only after the agreement is finalized.', 'Incorrect.  Under the MTC’s program, a taxpayer may in fact apply for voluntary disclosure to only one state or to as many participating states as it wishes.', 'Correct.  Participating states will generally waive penalties on all back taxes due, but they will assess interest.', ''),
(717, 46, 174, '<p><strong>Under the Streamlined Sales Tax Agreement, participating businesses will receive the following benefit(s):</strong></p>', 'An amnesty relieving taxpayers in the member states from all uncollected and unpaid sales or use taxes (including penalties and interest) on sales made before their dates of registration.', 'One identification number that can be used for all member states, plus the ability to register and update information for all member states in one place.', 'Reimbursement for amounts paid to Certified Service Providers for handling most of the sales and use tax filing, collecting, and remitting requirements resulting from registration in all member states, regardless of the registrant’s nexus with each state.', 'The ability to register with as many or as few member states as it wishes.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  The Streamlined Sales Tax amnesty is currently available in only one full member state (Ohio) and the associate member state (Tennessee).', 'Correct.  A single identification number, centralized registration, and centralized information update capabilities are provided for all member states under the Streamlined Sales Tax Agreement.', 'Incorrect.   Reimbursement for amounts paid to Certified Service Providers is only available to sellers who collect voluntarily in states where they lack nexus.', 'Incorrect.   Businesses participating in the Streamlined Sales Tax Agreement must register in all full member states.', ''),
(718, 45, 176, '<p>You are at your client&rsquo;s place of business and they are using QuickBooks Pro 2016. To be able to use the Batch Delete/Void Transactions feature which condition must apply?</p>', 'Log into the file as the Admin user.', 'Make sure your user login has permissions to the Batch Delete/Void feature.', 'Log into the file as the External Accountant user.', 'None of the above.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect – the Admin user does not have access to the Batch Delete/Void feature in QuickBooks Pro.', 'Incorrect – There are no permissions specific to the Batch Delete/Void feature.', 'Correct – Request that the Admin user for the file create a user for you and assign the External Accountant permissions.', 'Incorrect – To access the Batch Delete/Void feature in this scenario you need to have External Accountant permissions.', ''),
(719, 45, 177, '<p>With the release of QuickBooks Desktop in 2016, reports can now be efficiently generated for what newly defined date range?</p>', 'This Fiscal Year to Last Month.', 'This Fiscal Year to Date.', 'This Fiscal Year Compared to Last Fiscal Year', 'This Fiscal Year to Last Quarter.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct – The date selection of This Fiscal Year-to-Last Month when creating reports is a newly defined date range.', 'Incorrect – The date selection of This Fiscal Year-to-Date is not a newly defined date range when creating reports.', 'Incorrect – The date selection of This Fiscal Year Compared-to-Last Fiscal Year is not a newly defined date range when creating reports.', 'Incorrect – The date selection of This Fiscal Year-to-Last Quarter is not a newly defined date range when creating reports.', ''),
(720, 45, 178, '<p><strong>Controlling the font size on the displayed report, without having to open a customize report window was a feature improvement unique to which version of QuickBooks Desktop in 2016?</strong></p>', 'QuickBooks Enterprise.', 'QuickBooks Mac Desktop.', 'QuickBooks Pro Desktop.', 'QuickBooks Premier Desktop.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect – Controlling the font size on a displayed report was not a feature improvement for QuickBooks Enterprise.', 'Correct – Controlling the font size on the displayed report, without having to open a customize report window was a feature improvement for the QuickBooks Mac.', 'Incorrect – Controlling the font size on a displayed report was not a feature improvement for QuickBooks Pro Desktop.', 'Incorrect – Controlling the font size on a displayed report was not a feature improvement for QuickBooks Premier Desktop.', ''),
(721, 48, 179, '<p><strong>Which of the following is a synonym for &ldquo;ethics&rdquo;?</strong></p>', 'Moral practice.', 'Social values.', 'Decency.', 'All of the above.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Moral practice is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. Social values is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. Decency is not the best answer.', 'Correct. All of the above answers are synonyms for “ethics.”', ''),
(722, 48, 179, '<p><strong>Which of the following words is NOT a synonym of &ldquo;ethical&rdquo;?</strong></p>', 'Honest', 'Conscientious', 'Moral', 'Humane', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Honest is being ethical.', 'Incorrect. Being Conscientious is being ethical.', 'Correct. Moral may be ethical or not.  The Mafia has their “moral code” which society does not consider ethical.', 'Incorrect. Being Humane is being ethical.', ''),
(723, 48, 179, '<p><strong>The sections of the Code of Ethics consist of _________ and _________:</strong></p>', 'Principles and Standards.', 'Rules and Standards.', 'Principles and Rules.', 'Rules, Principles and Standards.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Standards are not one of the sections.', 'Incorrect.  Principles must to be one of the sections.', 'Correct. The two sections are Principles and Rules.', 'Incorrect. Standards are a subset of the Rules, not one of the sections.', ''),
(724, 48, 179, '<p><strong>Which of the following is NOT considered a &ldquo;Covered Member&rdquo; is:</strong></p>', 'An individual on the attest engagement team.', 'A Partner in an office in the same state.', 'An individual in a position to influence the attest engagement.', 'The firm, including the firm''s employee benefit plans.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. An individual on the attest engagement team is a Covered Member.', 'Correct.  A Partner in an office in the same state is not necessarily a covered member.  Other attributes must be present.', 'Incorrect.  An individual in a position to influence the attest engagement is a Covered Member.', 'Incorrect. The firm, including the firm''s employee benefit plans, is a Covered Member.', ''),
(725, 48, 179, '<p><strong>A member should consult, in addition to the Code of Professional Ethics, if applicable, the ethical standards of:</strong>&nbsp;</p>', 'The state society to which the member belongs.', 'The appropriate state board of accountancy.', 'The AICPA ethics division.', 'All of the above.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The state society to which the member belongs is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. The appropriate state board of accountancy is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. The AICPA ethics division is not the best answer.', 'Correct.  All of the above answers are appropriate.', ''),
(726, 48, 179, '<p><strong>Which of the following people is <u>NOT</u> engaged in the practice of public accounting?</strong></p>', 'A person who is an independent contractor and contracts with organizations for the purpose of making trial balances or statements as a part of bookkeeping operations and does not sign as a CPA or PA.', 'A person who uses the CPA designation and prepares personal financial plans 	for a fee.', 'A person who offers to prospective clients to perform for compensation, professional services that involve a review of financial transactions and accounting records.', 'A person who maintains an office for the transaction of business as a public accountant.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct.  A person involved as an independent contractor to do bookkeeping work and does not sign as a CPA or PA is NOT in the practice of public accountancy.', 'Incorrect. A person who uses the CPA designation and prepares personal financial plans is in the practice of public accountancy.', 'Incorrect. A person who performs for compensation, professional services that involve a review of financial transactions and accounting records is in the practice of public accountancy.', 'Incorrect. A person who maintains an office for the transaction of business as a public accountant is obviously in the practice of public accountancy.', ''),
(727, 48, 180, '<p><strong>Which one of the following definitions is NOT correct?</strong></p>', 'Council: the Council of the AICPA.', 'Member: a member, associate member, or international associate of the AICPA.', 'Professional services: all services performed by a member while performing public accounting services.', 'Institute: the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Council is properly defined as “The Council of the AICPA.”  The Council is the governing body of the AICPA and is comprised of approximately 265 members and representatives from every state and U.S. Territory. Council meets twice a year, in May and October, and Regional Council meetings are held every year in March.', 'Incorrect.  Member is properly defined as “A member, associate member, or international associate of the AICPA.”', 'Correct. Professional services include all services performed by a member while holding out as a CPA, not just while performing public accounting services.', 'Incorrect. Institute is properly defined as “The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants.”', ''),
(728, 48, 180, '<p><strong>Which of the following items completes the following sentence? Independence in Fact:</strong></p>', 'involves impartiality.', 'indicates that the member has abstained from relationships that appear to prevent objectivity.', 'is a state of mind.', 'involves freedom from conflicts of interest.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Impartiality is connected with objectivity.', 'Incorrect. Independence in appearance, not fact, involves actions such as abstaining from relationships.', 'Correct. Independence in fact, is attitudinal, that is, a state of mind. Independence in  appearance involves actions.', 'Incorrect. Objectivity involves actions such as freedom from conflicts of interest.', ''),
(729, 48, 180, '<p><strong>The unique characteristics of the accounting profession that set it apart from the rest of society is its acceptance of its responsibility to:</strong></p>', 'Its clients.', 'The government and its agencies.', 'The public.', 'Investors.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. A profession is responsible to its clients, but this is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. A profession is responsible to certain government agencies at times, but this is not the best answer.', 'Correct.  A profession is responsible to its public, which is unique.', 'Incorrect. A profession is responsible to investors sometimes, but this is not the best answer  Its clients.', ''),
(730, 48, 180, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements is</strong><strong> <u>NOT</u> </strong><strong>correct?&nbsp; A Key position is a position in which an individual:&nbsp;</strong></p>', 'Has primary responsibility for significant accounting functions that support material components of the financial statements.', 'Has responsibility for the sales force.', 'Has primary responsibility for the preparation of the financial statements.', 'Has the ability to exercise influence over the contents of the financial statements, including when the individual is a member of the board of directors.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Having primary responsibility for significant accounting functions that support material components of the financial statements gives the possibility of adversely affecting the financial statements and they are therefore in a key position.', 'Correct. Having responsibility for the sales force does NOT allow the person to impact adversely the financial statements.', 'Incorrect.  Primary responsibility for the preparation of the financial statements allows the individual to adversely impact the financial statements and makes them in a key position.', 'Incorrect. The ability to exercise influence over the contents of the financial statements in any capacity is a key position.', ''),
(731, 48, 180, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements is the BEST answer?&nbsp; &ldquo;All groups of society are recipients of the work of the accounting profession.&nbsp; Society includes which of the following _____.</strong></p>', 'Clients & credit grantors', 'Governments', 'Employers & investors', 'All of the above', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Clients & credit grantors are most definitely a part of society; however, this is not the BEST answer.', 'Incorrect.  Governments are most definitely a part of society; however, this is not the BEST answer.', 'Incorrect. Employers & investors are most definitely a part of society; however, this is not the BEST answer.', 'Correct. All of the above are a part of Society', ''),
(732, 48, 180, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements concerning responding to an inquiry by the board is </strong><u><strong>FALSE</strong></u><strong>?</strong></p>', 'A licensee shall respond to any inquiry by the Board.', 'The response shall include making available all files and other documents requested.', 'Any inquiry by the Board requiring a response pursuant to this section shall be in person.', 'Failure to respond to the inquiry within 30 days constitutes a violation of the Accountancy Act.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  A licensee must respond to any inquiry by the Board.', 'Incorrect. The response must include making available all files and any other documents requested by the Board.', 'Correct.  Any inquiry by the Board requiring a response pursuant to this section must be in writing, not in person.', 'Incorrect.  Failure to respond to the inquiry within 30 days constitutes a violation of section 51.00(f) the Accountancy Act.', ''),
(733, 48, 182, '<p><strong>In which of the following situations would a CPA be considered independent?</strong></p>', 'The CPA was the temporary staff training instructor during the initial portion of the period.', 'The CPA had or was committed to acquire a small direct interest in the client.', 'The CPA had or was committed to acquire a large but indirect interest in the client.', 'The CPA was the controller for the firm during the initial portion of the period.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. The position of staff training instructor does not require decision making or indicate financial interest, which would cause the CPA to not be independent.', 'Incorrect. Acquisition of a small direct interest is specifically stated as one of the situations where the CPA is not considered to be independent.', 'Incorrect. Acquisition of a large but indirect interest in the client is specifically stated as one of the situations where the CPA is not considered to be independent.', 'Incorrect. The position of controller involves decision-making, which is specifically prohibited and affects independence.', ''),
(734, 48, 182, '<p><strong>A member who performs auditing, review, compilation, consulting, tax, or other professional services shall comply with only:</strong></p>', 'All applicable standards promulgated by bodies designated by Council.', 'The Code of Professional Ethics.', 'Generally Accepted Accounting Principles.', 'Internal Auditing Standards.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. Members have to comply with the standards set for the particular service performed.', 'Incorrect. Members have to comply with more than the Code.', 'Incorrect. Members have to comply with more than Generally Accepted Accounting Principles.', 'Incorrect. Internal Auditors are the only ones required to comply with Internal Auditing Standards.', ''),
(735, 48, 182, '<p><strong>Which one of the following professionals does </strong><u><strong>NOT</strong></u><strong> have a privileged information status with their client?&nbsp;</strong></p>', 'Medical doctors.', 'Certified public accountants.', 'Attorneys.', 'Religious ministers.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. A medical doctor has the privilege under our laws so that they may treat patients psychologically as well as physically.', 'Correct. For the most part, CPAs cannot disclose confidential information, but they are not protected by law or given privileged information status exempting them from being required to do so.', 'Incorrect. In order to be an advocate for their client, attorneys have the right to not disclose communications with them.', 'Incorrect. In order to  minister adequately and appropriately to members or parishioners, ministers of religious orders have privilege.', ''),
(736, 48, 182, '<p><strong>Which kind of <em>working papers </em>may a client request, and have a right to receive from its auditor?</strong></p>', 'Analysis and comments on management’s strengths and weaknesses.', 'Papers that contain support for a client’s journal entries and that the client does not have a copy of.', 'Auditor’s comments and conclusions concerning materiality.', 'Both a & c.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Analyses of and comments on management’s strengths and weaknesses are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client.', 'Correct.  Sole support for any part of the financial statements is the basis for the client having a right to the auditor’s working papers.', 'Incorrect. Auditor’s comments and conclusions concerning materiality are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client.', 'Incorrect. Analyses of and comments on management’s strengths and weaknesses are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client and auditor’s comments and conclusions concerning materiality are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client.', ''),
(737, 48, 182, '<p><strong>Which one of the following groups does <u>NOT</u> require disclosure of commissions or anticipated commissions?</strong></p>', 'To the AICPA Ethics Division.', 'To those members in public practice who do not perform an audit or review, examination of prospective statements, or compilation when independent.', 'To the client.', 'The State Board of the state in which the professional is practicing in.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. No disclosure is required to the AICPA.', 'Incorrect.  A member in public practice who do not perform an audit or review, examination of prospective statements, or compilation when independent is required and is not an exception to the rules.', 'Incorrect.  A professional is always required to disclose to their client.', 'Incorrect. A professional is not required to disclose commissions or anticipated commissions to the Board of the State in which they practice.', ''),
(738, 48, 183, '<p><strong>The attest engagement team includes all of the following </strong><u><strong>EXCEPT</strong></u><strong>:</strong></p>', 'The proprietor who participates in the acceptance or performance of the attest engagement.', 'The partners who participate in the acceptance or performance of the attest engagement.', 'Full- or part-time professional staff in another office of the same firm in the same state who did not participate in the attest engagement.', 'The shareholders who participate in the acceptance or performance of the attest engagement.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The proprietor has to remain independent in order to participate in the performance of the attest engagement.', 'Incorrect. The partners have to remain independent in order to participate in the performance of the attest engagement.', 'Correct. These staff members would not be required to be independent since they had nothing to do with the attest engagement and were not in the same office.', 'Incorrect. The shareholders have to remain independent in order to participate in the performance of the attest engagement.', ''),
(739, 48, 183, '<p><strong>The attest engagement team includes all of the following </strong><u><strong>EXCEPT</strong></u><strong>:</strong></p>', 'The proprietor who participates in the acceptance or performance of the attest engagement.', 'The partners who participate in the acceptance or performance of the attest engagement.', 'Full- or part-time professional staff in another office of the same firm in the same state who did not participate in the attest engagement.', 'The shareholders who participate in the acceptance or performance of the attest engagement.', '', '3', '', '', 'Deleted', 'Incorrect. The proprietor has to remain independent in order to participate in the performance of the attest engagement.', 'Incorrect. The partners have to remain independent in order to participate in the performance of the attest engagement.', 'Correct. These staff members would not be required to be independent since they had nothing to do with the attest engagement and were not in the same office.', 'Incorrect. The shareholders have to remain independent in order to participate in the performance of the attest engagement.', ''),
(740, 48, 183, '<p><strong>Upon determining that a supervisor&rsquo;s recommendation for treatment of financial information could result in a material misstatement, the first step in the CPA&rsquo;s ethical obligation is to:</strong></p>', 'Quit to avoid ethical violations.', 'Communicate concerns to the external accountant and all regulatory agencies that may be involved.', 'Report the disagreement to the supervisor’s supervisor.', 'Do sufficient research and consultation to determine if the supervisor is correct.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. This is the third step.', 'Incorrect. This is the fourth step.', 'Incorrect. This is the second step.', 'Correct. Determining if the supervisor is correct is the first step of a CPA’s ethical obligation in a matter of disagreement with a supervisor.', ''),
(741, 48, 183, '<p><strong>When is a contingent fee or commission deemed to be received?</strong></p>', 'When money for services is first received.', 'When services have been performed and the fee or commission is determined.', 'When a client agrees to have a member perform a service for the client.', 'When an initial sales contact is made with a client.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The receipt of money for the first time is not the first time the fee could be deemed received.', 'Correct. When the fee or commission can be determined is the time it is deemed received.', 'Incorrect. This is not the best time to consider a fee to be received.', 'Incorrect. A fee has not yet been earned.', ''),
(742, 48, 183, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements is FALSE?&nbsp; When an Attest Function CPA performs &ldquo;Other Services&rdquo; the client must be in a position to have an informed judgment on the results of the other services and that the client understands its responsibility to:</strong></p>', 'Designate a staff member to be responsible for overseeing the services being provided.', 'Evaluate the adequacy of the services performed and any findings that result.', 'Make management decisions, including accepting responsibility for the results of the other services.', 'Establish and maintain internal controls, including monitoring ongoing activities.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. The company must designate a Management-level individual to be responsible for overseeing the services being provided, not a staff person.', 'Incorrect. The client is responsible for evaluating the adequacy of the services performed and any findings that result.', 'Incorrect. The client is responsible for making management decisions, including accepting responsibility for the results of the other services.', 'Incorrect. The client is responsible for establishing and maintaining internal controls, including monitoring ongoing activities.', ''),
(743, 48, 183, '<p><strong>Which of the following new loans to be obtained from a financial institution client where independence is required is NOT an &ldquo;Other Permitted Loan&rdquo;?</strong></p>', 'Automobile loans and leases collateralized by the automobile.', 'Loans fully collateralized by the cash surrender value of an insurance policy.', 'Loans partially collateralized by cash deposits at the same financial institution.', 'Credit cards where the aggregate outstanding balance on the current statement is reduced to $5,000 or less by the payment due date.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Collateralized automobile loans are permitted.', 'Incorrect. Fully collateralized loans by an insurance policy are permitted.', 'Correct. Partially collateralized loans are not permitted, regardless of the collateral.', 'Incorrect. Credit cards of $5,000 or less are permitted.', ''),
(744, 49, 184, '<p><strong>Which of the following is a synonym for &ldquo;ethics&rdquo;?</strong></p>', 'Moral practice.', 'Social values.', 'Decency.', 'All of the above.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Moral practice is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. Social values are not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. Decency is not the best answer.', 'Correct. All of the above answers are synonyms for “ethics.”', ''),
(745, 49, 184, '<p><strong>Which of the following words is NOT a synonym of &ldquo;ethical&rdquo;?</strong></p>', 'Honest', 'Conscientious', 'Moral', 'Humane', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Honest is being ethical.', 'Incorrect. Being Conscientious is being ethical.', 'Correct. Moral may or may not be ethical. The Mafia has their “moral code” which society does not consider ethical.', 'Incorrect. Being Humane is being ethical.', ''),
(746, 49, 184, '<p><strong>The sections of the Code of Ethics consist of _________ and _________:</strong></p>', 'Principles and Standards.', 'Rules and Standards.', 'Principles and Rules.', 'Rules, Principles, and Standards.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Standards are not one of the sections.', 'Incorrect.  Principles must be one of the sections.', 'Correct. The two sections are Principles and Rules.', 'Incorrect. Standards are a subset of the Rules, not one of the sections.', ''),
(747, 49, 184, '<p><strong>Which of the following is NOT considered a <em>Covered Member</em>? </strong></p>', 'An individual on the attest engagement team.', 'A Partner in an office in the same state.', 'An individual in a position to influence the attest engagement.', 'The firm, including the firm''s employee benefit plans.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. An individual on the attest engagement team is a Covered Member.', 'Correct. A Partner in an office in the same state is not necessarily a covered member.  Other attributes must be present.', 'Incorrect. An individual in a position to influence the attest engagement is a Covered Member.', 'Incorrect. The firm, including the firm''s employee benefit plans, is a Covered Member.', ''),
(748, 49, 184, '<p><strong>A member should consult, in addition to the Code of Professional Ethics, if applicable, the ethical standards of:</strong></p>', 'The state society to which the member belongs.', 'The appropriate state board of accountancy.', 'The AICPA ethics division.', 'All of the above.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The state society to which the member belongs is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. The appropriate state board of accountancy is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect. The AICPA ethics division is not the best answer.', 'Correct. All of the above answers are appropriate.', ''),
(749, 49, 185, '<p><strong>Which one of the following definitions is <u>NOT </u>correct?</strong></p>', 'Council: the Council of the AICPA.', 'Member: a member, associate member, or international associate of the AICPA.', 'Professional services: all services performed by a member while performing public accounting services.', 'Institute: the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Council is properly defined as “The Council of the AICPA.” The Council is the governing body of the AICPA and is comprised of approximately 265 members and representatives from every state and U.S. Territory. Council meets twice a year, in May and October, and Regional Council meetings are held every year in March.', 'Incorrect.  Member is properly defined as “A member, associate member, or international associate of the AICPA.”', 'Correct. Professional services include all services performed by a member while holding out as a CPA, not just while performing public accounting services.', 'Incorrect. Institute is properly defined as “The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants.”', '');
INSERT INTO `chapter_review_questions` (`rev_ques_id`, `course_id`, `chapter_id`, `rev_ques_title`, `rev_ques_ans_1`, `rev_ques_ans_2`, `rev_ques_ans_3`, `rev_ques_ans_4`, `rev_ques_ans_5`, `rev_correct_ans_id`, `rev_correct_ans_text`, `rev_wronge_ans_text`, `rev_ques_status`, `ans1_text`, `ans2_text`, `ans3_text`, `ans4_text`, `ans5_text`) VALUES
(750, 49, 185, '<p><strong>Which of the following items completes the following sentence?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Independence in Fact:</strong></p>', 'involves impartiality.', 'indicates that the member has abstained from relationships that appear to prevent objectivity.', 'is a state of mind.', 'involves freedom from conflicts of interest.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Impartiality is connected with objectivity.', 'Incorrect. Independence in appearance, not fact, involves actions such as abstaining from relationships.', 'Correct. Independence is attitudinal - a state of mind. Independence in appearance involves actions.', 'Incorrect. Objectivity involves actions such as freedom from conflicts of interest.', ''),
(751, 49, 185, '<p><strong>The unique characteristics of the accounting profession that set it apart from the rest of society is its acceptance of its responsibility to:</strong></p>', 'Its clients.', 'The government and its agencies.', 'The public.', 'Investors.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. A profession is responsible to its clients, but this is not the best answer.', 'Incorrect.  A profession is responsible to certain government agencies at times, but this is not the best answer.', 'Correct.  A profession is responsible to its public, which is unique.', 'Incorrect. A profession is responsible to investors sometimes, but this is not the best answer.', ''),
(752, 49, 185, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements is NOT correct? </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A Key position is a position in which an individual: </strong></p>', 'Has primary responsibility for significant accounting functions that support material components of the financial statements.', 'Has responsibility for the sales force.', 'Has primary responsibility for the preparation of the financial statements.', 'Has the ability to exercise influence over the contents of the financial statements, including when the individual is a member of the board of directors.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Having primary responsibility for significant accounting functions that support material components of the financial statements gives the possibility of adversely affecting the financial statements and they are therefore in a key position.', 'Correct. Having responsibility for the sales force does NOT allow the person to impact adversely the financial statements.', 'Incorrect.  Primary responsibility for the preparation of the financial statements allows the individual to adversely impact the financial statements and makes them in a key position.', 'Incorrect. The ability to exercise influence over the contents of the financial statements in any capacity is a key position.', ''),
(753, 49, 185, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements is the BEST answer? &nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&ldquo;All groups of society are recipients of the work of the accounting profession. &nbsp;Society includes which of the following _____.</strong></p>', 'Clients & credit grantors', 'Governments', 'Employers & investors', 'All of the above', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Clients & credit grantors are most definitely a part of society; however, this is not the BEST answer.', 'Incorrect.  Governments are most definitely a part of society; however, this is not the BEST answer.', 'Incorrect. Employers & investors are most definitely a part of society; however, this is not the BEST answer.', 'Correct. All of the above are a part of Society.', ''),
(754, 49, 187, '<p><strong>In which of the following situations would a CPA be considered independent?</strong></p>', 'The CPA was the temporary staff training instructor during the initial portion of the period.', 'The CPA had or was committed to acquire a small direct interest in the client.', 'The CPA had or was committed to acquire a large but indirect interest in the client.', 'The CPA was the controller for the firm during the initial portion of the period.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct.  The position of staff training instructor does not require decision making or indicate financial interest, which would cause the CPA to not be independent.', 'Incorrect.  Acquisition of a small direct interest is specifically stated as one of the situations where the CPA is not considered to be independent.', 'Incorrect.  Acquisition of a large but indirect interest in the client is specifically stated as one of the situations where the CPA is not considered to be independent.', 'Incorrect. The position of controller involves decision-making, which is specifically prohibited and affects independence.', ''),
(755, 49, 187, '<p><strong>A member who performs auditing, review, compilation, consulting, tax, or other professional services shall comply with <em>only</em>:</strong></p>', 'All applicable standards promulgated by bodies designated by Council.', 'The Code of Professional Ethics.', 'Generally Accepted Accounting Principles.', 'Internal Auditing Standards.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. Members have to comply with the standards set for the particular service performed.', 'Incorrect. Members have to comply with more than the Code.', 'Incorrect.  Members have to comply with more than Generally Accepted Accounting Principles.', 'Incorrect.  Internal Auditors are the only ones required to comply with Internal Auditing Standards.', ''),
(756, 49, 187, '<p><strong>Which one of the following professionals does <u>NOT</u> have a privileged information status with their client? </strong></p>', 'Medical doctors.', 'Certified public accountants.', 'Attorneys.', 'Religious ministers.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. A medical doctor has the privilege under our laws so that they may treat patients psychologically as well as physically.', 'Correct. For the most part, CPAs cannot disclose confidential information, but they are not protected by law or given privileged information status exempting them from being required to do so.', 'Incorrect. In order to be an advocate for their client, attorneys have the right to not disclose communications with them.', 'Incorrect. In order to minister adequately and appropriately to members or parishioners, ministers of religious orders have privilege.', ''),
(757, 49, 187, '<p><strong>Which kind of <em>working papers</em> may a client request, and have a right to receive from its auditor?</strong></p>', 'Analyses and comments on management’s strengths and weaknesses.', 'Papers that contain support for a client’s journal entries and that the client does not have a copy of.', 'The Auditor’s comments and conclusions concerning materiality.', 'Both a & c.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect.  Analyses of and comments on management’s strengths and weaknesses are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client.', 'Correct. Sole support for any part of the financial statements is the basis for the client having a right to the auditor’s working papers.', 'Incorrect. Auditor’s comments and conclusions concerning materiality are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client.', 'Incorrect. Analyses of and comments on management’s strengths and weaknesses are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client. Auditor’s comments and conclusions concerning materiality are made to determine future work and do not have to be given to the client.', ''),
(758, 49, 187, '<p><strong>Which one of the following groups does <u>NOT</u> require disclosure of commissions or anticipated commissions?</strong></p>', 'The AICPA Ethics Division.', 'Those members in public practice who do not perform an audit or review, examination of prospective statements, or compilation when independent.', 'The client.', 'The State Board of the state in which the professional is practicing in.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. No disclosure is required to the AICPA.', 'Incorrect.  A member in public practice who do not perform an audit or review, examination of prospective statements, or compilation when independent is required and is not an exception to the rules.', 'Incorrect.  A professional is always required to disclose to their client.', 'Incorrect. A professional is not required to disclose commissions or anticipated commissions to the Board of the State in which they practice.', ''),
(759, 49, 188, '<p><strong>The attest engagement team includes all of the following, <u>EXCEPT</u>:</strong></p>', 'The proprietor who participates in the acceptance or performance of the attest engagement.', 'The partners who participate in the acceptance or performance of the attest engagement.', 'Full- or part-time professional staff in another office of the same firm in the same state who did not participate in the attest engagement.', 'The shareholders who participate in the acceptance or performance of the attest engagement.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The proprietor has to remain independent in order to participate in the performance of the attest engagement.', 'Incorrect.  The partners have to remain independent in order to participate in the performance of the attest engagement.', 'Correct.  These staff members would not be required to be independent since they had nothing to do with the attest engagement and were not in the same office.', 'Incorrect. The shareholders have to remain independent in order to participate in the performance of the attest engagement.', ''),
(760, 49, 188, '<p><strong>Upon determining that a supervisor&rsquo;s recommendation for treatment of financial information could result in a material misstatement, the first step in the CPA&rsquo;s ethical obligation is to:</strong></p>', 'Quit to avoid ethical violations.', 'Communicate concerns to the external accountant and all regulatory agencies that may be involved.', 'Report the disagreement to the supervisor’s supervisor.', 'Complete sufficient research and consultation to determine if the supervisor is correct.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. This is the third step.', 'Incorrect. This is the fourth step.', 'Incorrect. This is the second step.', 'Correct.  Determining if the supervisor is correct is the first step of a CPA’s ethical obligation in a matter of disagreement with a supervisor.', ''),
(761, 49, 188, '<p><strong>When is a contingent fee or commission deemed to be received?</strong></p>', 'When money for services is first received.', 'When services have been performed and the fee or commission is determined.', 'When a client agrees to have a member perform a service for the client.', 'When an initial sales contact is made with a client.', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The receipt of money for the first time is not the first time the fee could be deemed received.', 'Correct.  When the fee or commission can be determined is the time it is deemed received.', 'Incorrect. This is not the best time to consider a fee to be received.', 'Incorrect.  A fee has not yet been earned.', ''),
(762, 49, 188, '<p><strong>Which of the following statements is FALSE? &nbsp;</strong><strong>When an Attest Function CPA performs &ldquo;Other Services&rdquo; the client must be in a position to have an informed judgment on the results of the other services and understand its responsibility to:</strong></p>', 'Designate a staff member to be responsible for overseeing the services being provided.', 'Evaluate the adequacy of the services performed and any findings that result.', 'Make management decisions, including accepting responsibility for the results of the other services.', 'Establish and maintain internal controls, including monitoring ongoing activities.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct.  The company must designate a Management-level individual to be responsible for overseeing the services being provided, not a staff person.', 'Incorrect.  The client is responsible for evaluating the adequacy of the services performed and any findings that result.', 'Incorrect. The client is responsible for making management decisions, including accepting responsibility for the results of the other services.', 'Incorrect.  The client is responsible for establishing and maintaining internal controls, including monitoring ongoing activities.', ''),
(763, 49, 188, '<p><strong>Which of the following new loans to be obtained from a financial institution client where independence is required is NOT an &ldquo;Other Permitted Loan&rdquo;?</strong></p>', 'Automobile loans and leases collateralized by the automobile.', 'Loans fully collateralized by the cash surrender value of an insurance policy.', 'Loans partially collateralized by cash deposits at the same financial institution.', 'Credit cards where the aggregate outstanding balance on the current statement is reduced to $5,000 or less by the payment due date.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Collateralized automobile loans are permitted.', 'Incorrect. Fully collateralized loans by an insurance policy are permitted.', 'Correct. Partially collateralized loans are not permitted, no matter the collateral.', 'Incorrect.  Credit cards of $5,000 or less are permitted.', ''),
(764, 50, 189, '<p><strong>The <em>Tell Me</em> feature in Excel 2016:</strong></p>', 'Instantly creates a chart based on data within a worksheet.', 'Automates repetitive data entry work.', 'Displays alternate pivot table arrangements based on your data.', 'Enables users to quickly discover features and formulas.', '', '4', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. This describes Excel''s Recommended Charts feature, which was introduced in Excel 2013 and is also available in Excel 2016.', 'Incorrect. The Flash Fill Feature in Excel 2013 and later offers to automate repetitive data entry, or can be accessed by pressing Ctrl-E.', 'Incorrect. The Recommended Pivot Tables feature in Excel 2013 and later gives you a jump start on creating pivot tables based on data that you specify.', 'Correct. This feature appears at the top of the Excel screen to the right of the last menu tab, which is typically View, but can vary based on additional features or options enabled within Excel.', ''),
(765, 50, 190, '<p><strong>In Excel 2013 and later by default the Ctrl-O keyboard shortcut displays:</strong></p>', 'The Open dialog box', 'The Open menu', 'The Object dialog box', 'The Orientation dialog box', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Ctrl-O does display the Open window in Excel 2010 and earlier, but not in Excel 2013 and later.', 'Correct. You must then click Browse to get to the Open window unless you turn on the Don''t Show Backstage When Opening or Saving Files option.', 'Incorrect. This feature is accessed by way of the Insert Object command on Excel''s Insert menu.', 'Incorrect. Excel does not have an Orientation dialog box, but you can change the orientation by way of the Print menu, the Page Layout menu, or the Page Setup dialog box.', ''),
(766, 50, 191, '<p><strong>Treemap charts:</strong></p>', 'Display both numbers and text labels.', 'Can be displayed in Excel 2013 and earlier.', 'Display data spatially in rectangular form.', 'Display data spatially in circular form.', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. Treemap charts only display text-based labels and cannot show numeric values.', 'Incorrect. Treemap charts are destroyed when a workbook is open and saved in Excel 2013 and earlier.', 'Correct. It''s important to ensure that your data is summarized before creating the chart; otherwise, the chart will be highly fragmented.', 'Incorrect. The Sunburst chart in Excel 2016 presents data in a doughnut style format.', ''),
(767, 50, 192, '<p><strong>What functionality does the Flash Fill feature offer?</strong></p>', 'Flash Fill offers to automatically populate other adjacent cells with text based on the pattern that Excel perceives.', 'Flash Fill copies the contents of the current cell down the current column until a blank is encountered in the previous cell.', 'Flash Fill instantly creates a pivot table from the range of data that you have selected.', 'Flash Fill instantly creates a chart from the range of data that you have selected.', '', '1', '', '', 'Active', 'Correct. The Flash Fill feature is an artificial intelligence feature in Excel that can eliminate repetitive keystrokes or formulas when working with lists of data.', 'Incorrect. Double-click on the fill handle of a given cell to copy cell contents in this fashion.', 'Incorrect. The Recommended Pivot Tables feature in Excel 2013 performs this functionality.', 'Incorrect. The Recommended Charts feature in Excel 2013 performs this functionality.', ''),
(768, 50, 193, '<p><strong>Which Excel feature does Timeline complement?</strong></p>', 'Any range of cells containing a list.', 'Pivot Tables', 'Tables', 'Charts', '', '2', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. The Timeline feature allows you to filter pivot table data based on selecting dates from a continuum interface.', 'Correct. The Timeline feature allows you to filter pivot table data based on selecting dates from a continuum interface.', 'Incorrect. The Timeline feature allows you to filter pivot table data based on selecting dates from a continuum interface.', 'Incorrect. The Timeline feature allows you to filter pivot table data based on selecting dates from a continuum interface.', ''),
(769, 50, 194, '<p><strong>What will IFNA display in Excel 2010 and earlier?</strong></p>', 'Either calculation results or an alternate value', '#N/A', '#NAME?', '#REF!', '', '3', '', '', 'Active', 'Incorrect. IFNA does return this in Excel 2013 and later, but would not return this in Excel 2010 and earlier.', 'Incorrect. The IFNA function is specifically designed to display an alternate value or text in situations where a formula returns #N/A.', 'Correct. The #NAME? function identifies worksheet function names that are either misspelled or not available in a given Excel versions, as well as invalid range names.', 'Incorrect. IFNA does return all # sign errors other than #N/A in Excel 2013 and later, but would not return this error in Excel 2010 and earlier.', '');
